<SLUG> BC-BKC-CONN-SYRACUSE-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN DOMINATES SYACUSE TO REACH BIG EAST FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wh is Souleymane Wane and why is Khalid El-Amin
leaping as high as his shoes can fly to chest-bump what little
chest Connecticut's backup center has? And Rashamel Jones, pumping
his fist after once more knifing through the lane finishing yet
another fast break? Who is he?
</P>
<P>
   Until Connecticut thoroughly crushed Syracuse, 71-50, in the
semifinals of the Big East tournament, only the most devoted of
Husky fans could have answered those questions. No more.
</P>
<P>
   They are talented members of a team that, when it feels like
showing up, can be as dominating as any outside of the Duke Blue
Devils. And against Syracuse they not only showed up, but gave a
sold out, partisan Connecticut crowd at Madison Square Garden a
night to remember.
</P>
<P>
   While Wane and Jones sparked a first-half rally that demoralized
the Orangemen, such Connecticut stalwarts as Kevin Freeman and
Richard Hamilton downright embarrassed them. After teaming up for a
nifty bit of ball handling finished by Freeman's reverse layup _
shades of Michael Jordan _ the two stopped at the free-throw line
and bowed to each other.
</P>
<P>
   The two led Connecticut, as Freeman scored 21 points and
Hamilton 17. But it was the contributions from down the bench that
transformed the Huskies from a sluggish squad that barely outlasted
Seton Hall, 57-56, in the quarterfinal. In a suffocating display of
team defense, Connecticut held Syracuse to 38 percent shooting,
forced 15 turnovers and so bottled up Etan Thomas that he had to be
separated from Connecticut center Jake Voskuhl after a hard foul.
</P>
<P>
   UConn shot 45 percent, had only 10 turnovers and scored 16
points off turnovers. By contract, Syracuse scored just two points
off turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen led off a rough February for Connecticut, a month
in which the Huskies struggled as they lost the No. 1 ranking in
the country. At the Hartford Civic Center, Syracuse upset UConn,
top ranked at the time, as Hamilton and Voskuhl sat out with
injuries. The Huskies had their lowest point total of the year that
day as they lost, 59-42.
</P>
<P>
   But last Sunday, UConn went to the Carrier Dome to return the
favor. The Huskies' 70-58 rout in the regular-season finale was
most notable for perhaps their best half since their streak of 10
weeks as the top-ranked team. They wiped out the Orangemen's
two-point halftime lead when their transition game showed up with
the second-half tipoff. And in 10 nearly perfect minutes of
basketball, Connecticut went 10 for 10 from the field and scored 15
points on the fast break on their way to burying Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after last night's tipoff, it was apparent that this rubber
match mattered to both teams. Voskuhl, who has not practiced in two
weeks to minimize the wear and tear on an injured left foot, went
elbow to elbow, chest to chest with Thomas, Syracuse's 6-foot-9
shot blocker.
</P>
<P>
   The Orangemen's strategy was clear: turn the game into a
deliberate shoving match played within three feet of the basket.
Thomas tried to do that the hardest. He finished with 11 points, 10
rebounds and six blocked shots, but had little help as the
Orangemen shot just 30 percent in the first half.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In fact, early in the first half, when Syracuse guard Allen
Griffin ignored Jim Boeheim's game plan to pound the ball inside to
Thomas, the coach berated him so passionately that Griffin's
backcourt mate, Jason Hart, asked Boeheim to back off.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeheim had more than hard-headed players to contend with as
the Huskies came out determined to follow up last Sunday's perfect
half with an equally dazzling one to open the game. They intended
to stretch the court and make Syracuse chase them baseline to
baseline. They were successful.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Hamilton hit a 3-pointer to end the half and fired
an imaginary six-shooter at the Syracuse players, Connecticut had a
20-point lead and was on its way to proving they still are the
biggest team in the East.
</P>
</TEXT>
