<HEADLINE>
WITH VISITORS CENTER, NEW YORK PUTS ON A HOSPITABLE FACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This city has often had a love-hate relationship with
its tourists. Sure, their money fuels the economy, but they also
crowd Manhattan streets and make it even tougher to get restaurant
reservations. And while locals do offer directions to
out-of-towners, albeit reluctantly, the city continues to be a
daunting place for visitors to master.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the city took a step toward greater hospitality with the
opening of a computerized visitor information center in midtown
that is designed to help tourists navigate a maze of cultural
offerings using state-of-the-art technology. It will let visitors
purchase tickets to a multitude of events and get up-to-the-minute
information on many of the city's cultural and recreational
offerings. Its operator, the New York Convention and Visitors
Bureau, calls it the most technologically advanced center of its
kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the welcome mat is being rolled out only so far: In true New
York fashion, the center will not have public restrooms. Nell
Barrett, a spokeswoman for the Convention and Visitors Bureau, said
space constraints would not allow anything but a single toilet for
use by the staff members.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its lack of comfort facilities, the center, at 810
Seventh Ave. at 53rd Street, signifies that New York has finally
caught up with other cities in trying to cater to its tourists,
said Fran Reiter, president of the Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``Previously, we have not served visitors as well as we might,''
she said. ``We were so big and so exciting that we assumed we
didn't have to sell the city so hard.''
</P>
<P>
   New York has good reason to be accommodating to tourists. An
estimated 35 million visitors will come to the city this year,
representing an increase of 53 percent since 1991, according to the
Convention and Visitors Bureau. These visitors will pump $14.5
billion into the city's economy, the bureau estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which cost $400,000 to set up, will be open 365 days
a year and will be staffed from 8:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. on weekdays
and from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. on weekends by four clerks who speak a
multitude of languages. It was built in partnership with American
Express, Eastman Kodak and an Internet company, CitySearch.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
