<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T COUNT WILLIAMS AMONG THE LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It could have been the crushing blow in
a flurry of haymakers that sent the New Jersey Nets reeling like a
battered prizefighter. But instead of being floored by the loss of
another key starter, the Nets received good news Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams, who was taken to Hackensack Medical Center for
X-rays on his left thumb during halftime Thursday night of the
Nets' 96-82 loss to the Charlotte Hornets, is not likely to miss a
game.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the club's heart and soul, has played the entire
season with ligament damage in his thumb, and after the X-rays
proved negative Friday, Dr. Charlie Melone said that the Nets'
center only aggravated the injury against the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   Melone, a hand specialist who has worked with Williams in the
past, fit him for a soft splint Friday, and Williams is expected to
be in the lineup Sunday against the New York Knicks at Madison
Square Garden. As soon as the season is completed, Williams will
undergo corrective surgery. He insisted that the surgery will take
place ``the day after the Nets are knocked out of the playoffs.''
But a trip to the post-season does not appear to be likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, with their 3-12 record, are about to embark on a long
and potentially ugly road trip. Eight of their next nine games are
on the road, and whatever faint hopes they have of making the
playoffs could be dead when that stretch ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a big deal because we haven't played any
better at home than we have on the road,'' Keith Van Horn said of a
team that is 2-6 at home and 1-6 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the optimist, coach John Calipari talked Friday about his
team being only four and a half games out of the eighth and final
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nets are on pace to win only seven more games this
season and finish with a 10-40 record. Thus, there is no reason to
be upbeat about this team making a turnaround, despite the air of
confidence Calipari and his players are trying to portray.
</P>
<P>
   Since training camp, the coaches and the players have said that
Calipari has mellowed in practice. But in an attempt to spark some
fire in this club, Calipari said he would return to his louder,
more grating persona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have backed off and not been as hard on the guys this year
and some of them aren't playing well because I have backed off,''
Calipari said. ``I'm not saying it's time for me to get in a guy's
face, but in practice, I've got to turn it on and stop being so
general in my criticism. I have to point out specific guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is because of Calipari's mellower demeanor during
practice or something else, the Nets are not paying attention to
details.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Evans, who as the last player on the Nets' bench has had
plenty of time to study his teammates, said the Nets' terrible
execution and shooting percentage (.391) were because of the team's
refusal to do the little things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the little details that make a difference, like
jumping out strong on pick-and-rolls and making the defense adjust
to the way we're playing, like blocking out underneath the basket
every time,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And offensively, it's the same deal. When we come off a
pick-and-roll, we don't come off tight enough. When we run off a
screen, we don't run off shoulder to shoulder and make sure we get
rid of our man. Then the other team comes down and pays attention
to detail and it looks kind of easy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   With the worst record in the Eastern Conference, with the
second-worst shooting percentage in the league, and with eight of
their next nine games on the road, nothing is going to be easy for
the Nets. Even with Williams on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   Reports that the Nets could trade KENDALL GILL and CHRIS GATLING
to San Antonio for the All-Star center DAVID ROBINSON are
preposterous, according to team officials. One said that the Nets
would make that trade in a heartbeat, but that San Antonio ``would
never entertain'' the thought. The same report had the Nets
thinking about trading JAYSON WILLIAMS for Robinson, but that is
impossible because under the new collective bargaining agreement,
Williams cannot be traded this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
