<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Political Infighting
</P>
<P>
   In a barb at President Ernesto Zedillo, Manuel Bartlett Diaz,
who has announced that he will seek the governing party's
nomination for president in 2000, called on the party's other
candidates to declare their intentions and resign from public
office. Zedillo is believed to back his interior minister,
Francisco Labastida Ochoa, to be the candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Canada: Nanavut Premier Picked
</P>
<P>
   Paul Okalik, a 34-year-old Inuit lawyer, has been chosen the
first premier of the new territory of Nunavut when it comes into
existence on April 1. Okalik, of Iqaluit, was one of 19 legislators
elected last month to the first Nunavut legislature.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Switzerland: Emergency Trade Meeting
</P>
<P>
   The European Union called for a special meeting of the World
Trade Organization in Geneva on Monday to denounce Washington's
preparations for sanctions on $520 million worth of European goods.
The American move, protesting Europe's preference for importing
bananas grown in the Caribbean, was described as ``irresponsible
unilateral action.''
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Basque Mediation Rejected
</P>
<P>
   MADRID _ Spain said it would not accept a foreign mediator to
help start peace talks with the Basque guerrilla group ETA, which
has observed a cease-fire since September. The government said any
talks must be direct, and denied a Basque newspaper report that the
rebels had proposed a foreign mediator.
</P>
</TEXT>
