<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL STILL CAGEY ABOUT L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARSON _ National Football League commissioner Paul Tagliabue
paid the city of Carson and wanna-be NFL owner Michael Ovitz
hundreds of compliments Friday after taking a helicopter ride over
the city and proposed site for a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't say the two words Ovitz and Carson wanted to hear
most: play ball.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner and other league officials were cagey as usual
about the fate of a proposed 32nd franchise and the three groups
bidding for it. He said the league will likely choose between
Houston and Los Angeles at its annual meetings March 14-17 in
Phoenix, but won't go any farther in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The Ovitz/Carson group is competing for now with proposals from
the New Coliseum, headed by Kings owner Ed Roski, and a Houston
group fronted by businessman Robert McNair. A chance exists the
league will open up the bidding anew once it selects a city.
</P>
<P>
   It will be tough enough, Tagliabue said, to get 24 of 32 owners
to vote to expand. ``At best, we'll be making a choice on a city,''
he said. ``The where, who and how much remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Producing a consensus (on those issues) won't be easy. There
are three strong groups bidding for a team and we have a lot of
strong-minded, individualistic owners. We need a consensus of 24,
and different factors are weighed differently by different
owners.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that clinical example of obsfucation, Tagliabue lauded
Ovitz and Carson. He said the flyover eased concerns about road
access, and called the size of 200-acre lot ``a strong positive.''
He said the NFL's legal staff has done its own thorough examination
of environmental reports and scheduled remedies, and he is
satisfied with it. ``It (building on a landfill) is not a unique
situation, so we're comfortable on that score.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times, he said the league will eventually select a
stadium and an owner that has the best ``vision.'' He diverted a
question about the possible franchise fee -- speculation puts it
between $500 million and $1 billion depending on who's speculating
-- by talking about what the league wants in a new partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Far more important is the quality of ownership,'' Tagliabue
said. ``The two owners we selected in Carolina (Richardson) and
Jacksonville (Wayne Weaver) have already made terrific
contributions to the league. One of the reasons Michael Ovitz is
attractive is because he has a track record in entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's flyover was sort of a show, too, when you realize Ovitz
got Tagliabue excited by showing him a landfill.
</P>
<P>
   The former Hollywood agent felt the visit was important to give
the league a view of the site and ``reinforce my point of view that
this is an extraordinary opportunity and city,'' he said. Carson
officials like Mayor Peter Fajardo and Councilman Daryl Sweeney
felt the commissioner's visit was a serious step in the process of
being accepted.
</P>
<P>
   On at least one competitive issue related to the New Coliseum
proposal, Tagliabue clearly sided with Carson/Ovitz. He said
Carson's public investment -- $180 million in cashbonds -- ``is
much more substantial (than the Coliseum).
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one area we're still addressing (with the New Coliseum
group). There are some variables and terms we need to define.
There's more uncertainty up there regarding ... how much (public
money) is really there.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the New Coliseum's public investment is in the form of
already completed infrastructure -- the value of the land, better
freeway and road access, and earthquake retrofitting of the
Coliseum. New Coliseum officials say a dime is a dime no matter
when it was spent.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue also deflated the notion that the league will build a
stadium itself. It may assist in funding construction and include
that expense into the franchise fee, which it did in Cleveland, but
that's the extent of the league's role. He also said Raiders owner
Al Davis' legal claim that he owns the rights in L.A. ``is not a
factor at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz once wanted a quick decision, but he said he's willing to
play at the league's pace. As far as the franchise fee, he has an
open mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a point where we're not going to go,'' he said.
``Every deal has that point, and I think NFL owners understand
that. The 31 owners did not get there by accident. They're good
business people and they know how to make a deal work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
