<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-DORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELS DECIDES NOT TO TAKE A BREAK AND FINDS HIMSELF IN CONTENTION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Many of the world's top players took a break this week,
but Ernie Els did not.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a 66, six under par, with six birdies and no bogeys,
Els soared into a second-place tie after Friday's second round of
the Doral-Ryder Open. Els is seven under par for the tournament
(137), two strokes behind Greg Kraft, who shot a 67 to take the
lead &UR; . &LR;  Greg Chalmers (66) is tied with Els for second place.
</P>
<P>
   The top three players in the world golf ranking _ Tiger Woods,
David Duval and Mark O'Meara _ decided to skip Doral, as did 11 of
the world's top 15. But after losing in the first round of last
week's Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship, Els, ranked
fourth in the world, changed his mind and entered Doral.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I missed the cut last week, so I decided to come
down here,'' Els said. ``I felt like I was playing well, and if I
took this week off, I might lose that bit of magic.''
</P>
<P>
   If Els wins Doral, he will join Duval as a two-time winner on
the PGA Tour this year. Els won the Nissan Open last month.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much talk this year about a budding rivalry
between Woods and Duval for No. 1 player in the world, but Els
cannot be overlooked. He has won 28 tournaments worldwide since
1992, including the United States Open in both 1994 and 1997. While
Els will not have the chance to outplay Woods or Duval this
weekend, a victory would certainly get their attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are still seven, eight wins ahead of me, especially
David,'' said Els, who is 29 years old. ``He's not playing this
week; Tiger's not playing. You can't really get into an argument
that I'm playing as good as they are, because they are not playing.
I'm just trying to do well in this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Doral is the first of four tournaments on the tour's Florida
swing, and Els plans to play them all.
</P>
<P>
   The day started with Tommy Armour III, Bob Burns, Scott Dunlap
and Franklin Langham locked in a four-way tie for first place at
five under par. But they were all overtaken Friday, as Armour shot
71, Burns and Dunlap both shot 72, and Langham shot 76.
</P>
<P>
   That opened the door for Kraft, Els and Chalmers. Els will be
the favorite, but he was taking nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are used to seeing superstars on the leader boards, and now
we've got new names,'' Els said. ``You don't know quite what to
expect. You've got to be on your toes.''
</P>
<P>
   CHIP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   Charles Raulerson &UR;  &LR; had a double-eagle on the par-5, 529-yard
first hole Friday, holing a 6-iron shot from 202 yards. It was the
third double-eagle on the PGA Tour this year. . . . Justin Leonard
and Nick Price are still in contention at three under par, while
Greg Norman is even (144), barely making the 144 cut. . . . Nick
Faldo (two over par), Mark Brooks (five over par) and Vijay Singh
(six over par) missed the cut. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
