<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITMAN-PROFILING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN SEEKS DELAY FOR RACIAL PROFILING APPEAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ After denying for years that black and Latino
drivers are targeted by state troopers searching for drugs, the
Whitman administration said Friday that it was considering dropping
its appeal of a 1996 court ruling that found troopers had a ``de
facto policy of racial profiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Paul Zoubek filed an affidavit Friday
asking for a four-month delay in the appeal hearing, scheduled for
March 12, saying the attorney general's office would like to
complete the first portion of an investigation into profiling
ordered by Gov. Christie Whitman last month before deciding whether
to continue the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   An official in the attorney general's office, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity, said the state may eventually drop its
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should these investigations turn up a lot, it's possible we
could drop the case,'' the official said. ``We don't want to paint
ourselves into a corner, but we want to be in a position to take
the appropriate reaction to whatever evidence the investigation may
uncover.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistants to Attorney General Peter G. Verniero have been
preparing an Appellate Court appeal to challenge a Gloucester
County judge's ruling in 1996 that troopers routinely attempt to
catch drug traffickers by stopping and searching law-abiding
motorists based on the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general's position in the case _ that there is no
widespread practice of racial profiling _ has infuriated many civil
rights leaders, who say it symbolizes the Whitman administration's
racial insensitivity and ignores state police statistics,
complaints from minority drivers and lawsuits filed by troopers who
say state police colleagues told them to target blacks and Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, when Ms. Whitman tapped Verniero's office to begin
the profiling investigation, members of the Black Ministers Council
of New Jersey were outraged that the attorney general would
investigate the profiling allegations while his office was busily
denying the existence of a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Legislative Minority Caucus, who have scheduled
public hearings on the profiling charges, have vowed to use the
issue to oppose Verniero's bid to join the state Supreme Court. Ms.
Whitman nominated Verniero last month to the state's highest court,
and the state Senate is expected to hold confirmation hearings this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Zoubek's affidavit also disclosed for the first time that the
attorney general's office has been investigating profiling
allegations against troopers from the Cranbury and Moorestown
barracks since April, when troopers from those barracks shot three
unarmed minority men during a traffic stop on the New Jersey
Turnpike. A grand jury has not yet decided whether the two troopers
who fired at the men, wounding them 11 times, should face criminal
charges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
