u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-BUCKS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-BUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL PROVIDES SOME SPARK BUT KNICKS STILL GO DOWN IN FLAMES TO
BUCKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ Latrell Sprewell popped off the bench Friday night
and came onto the scene like a siren in the rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   He was clapping his hands for the ball and unnerving the
Milwaukee Bucks. After missing almost a month with a stress
fracture in his right heel, Sprewell was a welcome arrival that
kept the New York Knicks alive in this game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But once again, the Knicks showed their inability to win a
tough road game when Patrick Ewing _ for the second time in two
games _ missed a 13-foot jumper at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing's miss allowed the Bucks to exhale and exit the Bradley
Center with an 88-87 victory. Ewing led the Knicks with 24 points,
while Sprewell added 18.
</P>
<P>
   Just like in the Knicks' one-point loss to Miami in overtime
Tuesday night, Ewing was the one taking and missing the last shot.
But this defeat was not Ewing's burden to bear. The slumping Allan
Houston had a dreadful night, hitting just 2 of 12 shots as the
Knicks (9-7) fell to 2-6 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucks were led by Glenn Robinson (19 points) and Terrell
Brandon (16 points), who hit two free throws to give the Bucks an
88-87 lead with 8 seconds left in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a nine-point third quarter lead, the Knicks began
to fray mentally and physically. A 3-pointer by Brandon, who came
off the bench after missing two games with a thigh contusion, with
6 minutes 34 seconds left in the game gave the Bucks a 75-73 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Houston tried to redeem his horrid night of shooting by nailing
a 3-pointer to bring the Knicks to within, 82-81, with 2:35 left.
The back-and-forth game went the Bucks way until 50 second
remained. A missed 3-pointer by Chris Childs was kept alive and
deflected off the Bucks by Sprewell with 26.8 seconds left in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   That play allowed the Knicks the chance to go ahead, which they
did on a 10-foot jumper by Ewing. He was fouled, but failed to hit
the free throw, leaving the Knicks with a tenuous, 87-86 lead, with
16.8 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Brandon took the inbounds and, trying to break down the defense,
drove into Larry Johnson and picked up the foul. Brandon coolly hit
both free throws to give the Bucks an 88-87 lead with 8 seconds to
go. Sprewell may have been listed as a reserve, but he made his
entrance back onto the league's stage like a leading man. There was
nothing tentative about him as he stepped onto the floor with 3
minutes 38 seconds left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell stepped onto the court with 3:38 remaining in the first
quarter. One minute and one errant 3-pointer later, an undaunted
Sprewell unveiled a vicious, two-handed dunk as he drove right by a
helpless Dell Curry with 2 minutes left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of confidence and the kind of unbridled
aggression the Knicks have been missing on offense, particularly on
the road. In a scoring sprint, Sprewell hit 5 of 11 shots for 14
first-half points. He did not come up for air until he was taken
out of the game with 2:06 to go in the first half. He had helped
turn a tie game into a five-point Knicks lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
