<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTHY FOX IS ON TARGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A five-game winning streak noted for Dennis Rodman's
rebounding and Kurt Rambis' coaching needs a footnote appended to
it for Rick Fox's 3-point shooting spree.
</P>
<P>
   His shot ailing as much as his injured feet, Fox started the
season in a 1-for-18 slump from 3-point range. But he's hit 14 of
his last 26 attempts (53.8 percent), all during the Lakers'
five-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so much better physically than I had for the first
month of the season,'' Fox said. ``Coming out of training camp, I
couldn't even run. . . . Thanks to (Lakers trainer) Gary Vitti for
getting me healthy and working on strengthening the ankle area, I
feel like I did last year when I was healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox opened training camp with new athletic insoles, which
unfortunately turned out to be a bad fit. He suffered sore ankles
and knees and later was diagnosed with bone spurs in his right foot
_ an ailment he'll wait until summer to rectify with surgery.
</P>
<P>
   But after weeks of treatment and therapy, Fox is playing
pain-free, and his shooting rhythm has returned. It started with a
4-for-6 3-point shooting night against the Clippers last Thursday,
followed by a 5-for-5 performance behind the arc against Houston
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The shortened training camp after the lockout also had an effect
on Fox's game, he said. ``A month and a half into the season is
about the stretch you usually get in preseason to get into a
rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Rambis did the rest. Though not a shooter by any stretch of the
imagination, Rambis had noticed a few hitches in Fox's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was playing passively, he was hesitating. That's not his
game,'' Rambis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's watched me shoot a lot, he notices the difference when I
get into a really good rhythm when I've swayed a little bit,'' Fox
said. ``It's helpful to know someone's watching you and knows what
the key points and the key words to remind you are.''
</P>
<P>
   No power shortage: A week into Rodman's tenure, Rambis is
finding it difficult to distribute minutes at the power and small
forward positions.
</P>
<P>
   The glut of available bodies is so bad, former starter Robert
Horry played just three minutes against Phoenix earlier this week,
and he's now coming in primarily at small forward _ stuck behind
Kobe Bryant and former starter Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Corie Blount _ previously the first option off the bench at
power forward _ went three games without playing a minute, as
Rodman and starter Travis Knight dominated the playing time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get Robert as much time as possible. . . . It's just
hard to find the minutes,'' Rambis said. ``It comes down to a
big-time numbers game with Corie. He's played well, his attitude is
great, he practices hard. Everything about Corie, I love. There's
no easy way to say it, he's getting screwed. He deserves more
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
