A9984 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-SKI-$ADV07-A     03-06 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-SKI-$ADV07-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CLIMBING SO MANY MOUNTAINS, A SKI RESORT GIANT STUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Vt., Maine, N.H., Md., Calif., British Columbia)  (For Release Sunday, March 7) 
(ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a bold strategy: Buy like mad, build like mad, pay for it
with an initial stock offering and a lot of borrowed money, and
pray that the snow _ and the customers _ would keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   For almost five years it was an exhilarating ride, as the
American Skiing Co. grew from a single Maine resort in 1994 to nine
in New England and the Rockies. Hotels bought, condos built, new
snow machines and gondolas installed: The company was pumping
millions into its strategy of rapidly building itself into a giant
in winter recreation.
</P>
<P>
   Then the juggernaut crashed into the season that wouldn't start.
Unusually warm weather in the East combined with a dry spell in the
West in the first few months of the 1998-99 season to keep trails
bare and cash registers empty. The cracks that soon appeared in
American Skiing's financial results call into question the wisdom
of barreling ahead so fast in an industry that depends so
profoundly on Mother Nature's fickle graces.
</P>
<P>
   The snows last week in New England came too late to rescue the
company's second quarter, which ended Jan. 24. On Monday, American
Skiing announced a net loss of $10.8 million, even worse than it
had forecast in January, on revenue of $109.5 million. Resort
revenue fell $3.7 million from the corresponding period the
previous year, while real estate revenue declined $1.6 million.
During what was supposed to be the company's most active quarter,
30 employees, mostly in middle management, were laid off at three
of the resorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one can say that they are happy about having the kind of
weather that we've had,'' said Leslie B. Otten, the company's
founder, chairman and chief executive. ``Long term, I don't think
this is going to have any detrimental effect to the company. In the
short term, it is something that we understand and expect will
happen from time to time.''
</P>
<P>
   With two prominent banks, Fleet and BankBoston, in the company's
corner as lenders, analysts had high hopes for American Skiing when
it went public at $18 a share in November 1997. But within a year,
the stock had slid to $5 a share; it closed last week at $3.75
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Noll, a ski industry analyst with the Chapman Co. in
Baltimore, called American Skiing the most highly leveraged in the
winter recreation industry and the most aggressive in real estate
development. When the company found that it had to defer some
projects, ``they disappointed the analysts on Wall Street, and
that's just been a big penalty for them,'' Noll said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The question now is how much of the company's aggressive
building schedule can be sustained, and how much must be scrapped
to conserve cash and service the company's debt of more than $400
million.
</P>
<P>
   American Skiing already has shelved its planned $30 million
Grand Summit Resort Hotel at the Sugarbush resort in Vermont,
because of poor advance sales, as well as a related land exchange
agreement the company had painfully worked out with the U. S.
Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the company also backed off from a planned $300
million offering of secured notes. Instead, it placed $58 million
in secured notes with high financing costs and will use the
proceeds to complete projects at its two Western resorts, Steamboat
in Colorado and The Canyons in Utah, in time for next season. The
switch led Standard &AMP; Poor's to downgrade the company's corporate
credit and debt ratings, saying it hurt the company's ``financial
flexibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the company sought to play down its bad earnings
report by announcing that it had renegotiated the terms of its debt
with its bank lenders. The deal will put about $20 million for
capital improvements into American Skiing's coffers during the
coming season. Though that is less than the $35 million the company
originally planned to borrow, it ``gives us more than enough
flexibility for the coming year,'' said Mark Miller, the chief
financial officer. ``We don't want anyone to get the impression
that the banks crimped us.''
</P>
<P>
   The new agreement also will allow Otten to keep pursuing his
vision of ski resorts that go beyond winter sports to become luxury
vacation destinations with all the trimmings. With much of the
basic infrastructure in place at the company's resorts, he added,
it is ``not a bad thing to be taking a break from that expenditure
pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Bullish analysts say the company's real estate ventures could
have more staying power than its lift-ticket sales.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Frick, an economist with BBC Consulting in Denver, said
that aging baby boomers who no longer frequented the slopes were an
attractive demographic group for second-home ownership, including
resort condos. ``The real estate industry has really grown to
eclipse the skiing industry'' in the West, he said, and he sees a
similar trend, though not as advanced, in New England.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hammerle, an industry consultant in Littleton, N.H.,
said American Skiing should not have much trouble filling its
properties. ``Across North America, resort real estate is in fairly
high demand, particularly in the Rocky Mountain region,'' Hammerle
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of time-share ownerships at American Skiing's hotels,
which come with amenities like the use of ski lockers, lounges and
libraries, have been brisk and highly profitable, Noll said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts find encouragement in Otten's track record turning
around resorts like his flagship property, Sunday River in Maine,
and hope the company can do the same with Steamboat. The Colorado
resort looked like a good bet after a 1.1-million-visit season in
1997. But skier visits have slid sharply this season, off 16
percent through January, and the resort's managing director
resigned.
</P>
<P>
   American Skiing continues to put much of its energy into
developing The Canyons, which it wants to transform into one of the
largest ski resorts in North America in time for the 2002 Winter
Olympics in Salt Lake City. More than 1,300 acres of skiable
terrain have been added; a hotel and condominiums, many of them
already sold, are under construction. Frick, the economist at BBC
Consulting, called it ``a make it or break it project'' for the
company.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the fate of The Canyons, it remains unclear how
America Skiing and the three other big, aggressive group owners _
Intrawest of Vancouver, British Columbia; Vail Resorts of Vail,
Colo., and Booth Creek Ski Holdings of Truckee, Calif. _ can keep
growing, given that the number of skiers has stayed fairly flat for
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's clear is that those four companies are spending
hundreds of millions of dollars to put in high-speed chair lifts
and grooming, and they're all building a lot of housing,'' Noll
said. ``If they don't get some kind of growth, unless those four
companies take all of the market, you're going to have some of them
changing their lifestyle.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 0040EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
