<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9985 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      03-06 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FINALLY BEAT THE DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This time there was no coming from
behind three times, grabbing a tie, and being thankful for a point.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Bruins didn't have to play catch-up. This time,
they led from wire to wire.
</P>
<P>
   They grabbed a 3-0 first-period lead, then turned things over to
goalie Byron Dafoe, who was brilliant again, and whipped the New
Jersey Devils, 4-1, Friday night at Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The first-period snipers were defensemen Kyle McLaren and Grant
Ledyard, and Sergei Samsonov, who finished off a textbook
two-on-one breakaway with Joe Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   After surging to the 3-0 lead, the Bruins turned things over to
Dafoe. He had 24 saves and was denied his seventh shutout of the
season when Jason Arnott beat him on the power play at 17:52 of the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter scored the other Bruin goal into an empty net in
the waning seconds.
</P>
<P>
   So, was this big, Pat Burns?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, definitely,'' said the Bruins coach. ``We played with
emotion. The Devils were frustrated and that was the most
frustrated I've ever seen a New Jersey Devils team play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get the early lead and we did. We wanted to get
in low behind them, move our legs, and make them chase us. The only
intimidation we have against them is our speed and we did that very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The win gave the Bruins some breathing room in the race for the
eighth and final playoff spot, opening up a 4-point bulge on both
the Florida Panthers and the New York Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The last time these two teams met, eight days ago at the
FleetCenter, the Bruins came from behind three times and escaped
with a 3-3 overtime tie. Friday night they hit the Devils early and
often, determined to end a 10-game winless streak (0-7-3) against
the Atlantic Division leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins started a bit on the sluggish side and lapses forced
Dafoe to make sparkling saves on shots from Petr Sykora and Brian
Rolston in the first 90 seconds. But then the Bruins got moving and
when they did, they shifted into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   McLaren lit the lamp at 2:39 with a blast from the point that
whistled past Devils goaltender Martin Brodeur. Carter started the
play by picking up a loose puck inside the circle and passing it
out to Jason Allison just inside the blue line. Allison slid it to
McLaren, who let fly a bullet that Brodeur never saw.
</P>
<P>
   At 15:12, Ledyard boosted the lead to 2-0 when he slapped in a
rebound from 20 feet. Thornton had a big part in the goal. He kept
possession behind the net, brought it out front, and swiped it at
Brodeur, who kicked it right back to Ledyard.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton was the centerpiece of the third goal, too.
</P>
<P>
   Landon Wilson poke-checked the puck free just inside the Bruins
blue line to Thornton, who skated down the right wing two-on-one
with Samsonov to his left. Just before skating in on Brodeur, he
shoveled the puck across the crease to Samsonov, who put it behind
Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, I wanted to settle down the puck on the stick and then
I saw Sergei,'' said Thornton. ``Then I said, `let me get it to him
and he can put it in.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Burns was impressed with Thornton's overall play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is still young and still has things to learn,'' said Burns,
``but he's coming along. The expectations of a first-round draft
pick are always high. Last year he had to learn a lot of things.
Now he is coming into his own. He knows what the NHL is all about.
He knows what it is like to go into the corner and get put down on
the seat of your pants. Kids have to learn that, we can't expect
them to know that. Remember, he was just 18 years old last year.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Bruins on top after the first 20 minutes, they
basically plugged the middle and played sound defense in front of
Dafoe. But there were some cracks, and more than once Dafoe came up
big.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey's a team that likes to play with the lead and when
they're down, 3-0, they can't stick to their game plan,'' said
Dafoe. ``Fortunately, I was able to make a few stops early and then
we got going. A win like this was probably impossible a few weeks
ago, but the confidence level on this team is so much bigger right
now. This is the way we know we can play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
