<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABRES' SUB GOALIE SUBDUES STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. _ Bring back Dominik Hasek, already.
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Dominator'' might be the best player on the planet,
as superstar Wayne Gretzky called him last year, the Stars have to
believe Hasek is no Martin Biron.
</P>
<P>
   Biron, the 21-year-old rookie who was called up from the
American Hockey League, came up with 27 saves last night in a 2-1
Buffalo Sabres' victory that stopped the Stars' franchise-record
10-game road unbeaten streak. It was Biron's first NHL victory in
six appearances and also stopped the Stars' three-game winning
streak against the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek was in the net for those three games and had abominable
numbers, including a 5.71 goals-against average and an .823 save
percentage _ shocking for a man who has been chosen the NHL's
regular-season most valuable player two consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But with Hasek out with a nagging groin injury, Biron was called
into duty and responded well. Mix that with a monster game from
Sabres captain Michael Peca and the Stars were staring at their
first loss in their past five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid played well,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``We
had a lot of chances, but we couldn't convert.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss drops the Stars to 39-12-10, 10 points better than the
Ottawa Senators, the next closest team in the NHL standings. The
Sabres move to 29-21-12 and continue to jockey for playoff seeding
in the tight Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ends a three-game Stars' road trip in New York state
that finished 1-1-1 and was ``sporadic,'' defenseman Richard
Matvichuk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not as consistent as we have been,'' Matvichuk
said. ``It's not that we're playing a bad game, it's just that
we've got to bear down and play better. We have to play our style
of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   In the three road games, the Stars have yielded 26, 30 and 28
shots _ they average 23 a game. What's more, they're making
uncharacteristic puck-handling errors _ something they can't blame
on the condition of the Reunion Arena ice.
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk made the biggest mistake of the game, turning over the
puck to the Sabres' Wayne Primeau at the 11:26 mark of the first
period. Matvichuk was trying to make a cross-ice pass off the
boards at the Stars' defensive blue line and sent the puck directly
to Primeau, who wristed it past a surprised Ed Belfour for a 1-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars then tied the game seven minutes later when Joe
Nieuwendyk made a strong play to end a strong shift started by his
linemates Pat Verbeek and Jere Lehtinen. Nieuwendyk sent a 30-foot
wrister through a crowd for his 16th goal of the season and fourth
goal in the past four games. Nieuwendyk has a six-game
point-scoring streak going.
</P>
<P>
   The score stayed that way for the next 20 minutes until Peca
struck with 13.5 seconds remaining in the second period. The Sabres
were on a power play after Verbeek received a controversial
roughing penalty. Sabres defenseman Alexei Zhitnik fired a shot on
net and Vaclav Varada deflected it while camping out inches in
front of Belfour. Belfour made the save, but Matvichuk knocked
Varada on top of Belfour and Peca easily lifted the rebound in from
the left side of the net over the pile.
</P>
<P>
   A video replay was checked to see if Varada was in the crease,
and he was. But replay judges determined he had been pushed in by
Matvichuk and Peca's 25th goal of the season stood up as the
game-winner.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
