<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-JAZZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS FALL TO 0-19 AT JAZZ HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ This time, the Utah Jazz fans got their money's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   One week after the Mavericks played four starters 12 minutes or
less here against the Jazz, all hands were on deck last night for
the rematch. Unfortunately for the Mavericks, the outcome was
basically the same as they suffered another loss in their
least-favorite arena, 106-95.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are 0-19 at the Delta Center and have dropped the
past 24 games they have played in Utah. The Mavericks carry a 6-12
record into Sacramento, where they complete this two-game road trip
at 8 p.m. tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Utah, which has an NBA-best record of 13-3, was in control for
much of the game, and a Howard Eisley 3-pointer pushed its lead to
84-63 with 1:37 left in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   After that, either the Jazz lost interest or the Mavericks
decided it was time to play ball.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by Michael Finley, Hubert Davis, Shawn Bradley and rookie
Dirk Nowitzki, the Mavericks had enough energy down the wire to
keep the Jazz regulars in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We zone-trapped them a lot of the game, and it was successful
sometimes, and other times it wasn't,'' Mavericks coach Don Nelson
said. ``But we stayed with it and got back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis hit a 3-pointer with 2:55 left as the Mavericks drew
within 94-87, capping a 13-2 run over a two-minute span.
</P>
<P>
   But John Stockton connected on two free throws, Nowitzki missed
a long shot, and Jeff Hornacek's 18-footer bumped the Utah lead to
98-87.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Malone led Utah with 30 points and nine rebounds, and
Hornacek finished with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   Finley paced the Mavericks with 29 points on 11-of-19 shooting
and collected eight rebounds. Bradley and Nowitzki scored 10 points
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 26 at the Delta Center, Nelson decided to raise the
white flag after the first period against the Jazz. The Mavericks
had played the previous night at home against Denver, and were
following the Jazz game with a home game against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   With three games in three days, Nelson decided to play the odds
and rest the majority of his starters against the Jazz. The
strategy didn't go over well in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very tough game for us because of the way they
didn't compete against us the last time we played,'' said Phil
Johnson, who coached in Jerry Sloan's absence. ``And we were
concerned about it _ at least as a coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Sloan missed the game while recovering from a knee operation.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Mavericks nearly pushed the Jazz to the final
minute, but they couldn't overcome their slow start. For more than
three quarters, the Jazz used precision passing to pick apart the
Mavericks. In the first half, all 16 of Utah's field goals came on
assists, and 32 of their 35 field goals overall were off assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team executes better than anybody in the league,'' Nelson
said. ``I think they are the best but look out for the Lakers
now.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
