<HEADER>
A9998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-STJOHNS-MIAMI-NYT     03-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHNS-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAL BY BARKLEYPUTS STORM IN FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The St. John's basketball players had lusted for this rematch,
had said all week that the only interest the Big East tournament
held for them was the chance at one more meeting with Miami. They
wanted, quite simply, revenge against the only team that had beaten
them twice this season and surged past them in the national polls
in the final week of the regular season. They owed them, Coach Mike
Jarvis said.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff finally came Friday night when, in the waning seconds
of a game full of brutal defense and extraordinary intensity, point
guard Erick Barkley, who had promised that Miami had another thing
coming if it thought this third game would be a cakewalk, stripped
Johnny Hemsley of the ball as the clock wound down to single
digits, securing a 62-59 victory over the ninth-ranked Hurricanes
and St. John's first trip to the Big East final since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The 10th-ranked Red Storm (25-7) will play fourth-ranked and
top-seeded Connecticut (27-2) in Saturday's game, and has a chance
to vanquish another opponent that defeated it this season.
Connecticut came back from a 12-point deficit to beat St. John's in
their only meeting this season, 78-74. The Red Storm's victory
Friday night was its first over a top-10 opponent this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game should have been played in the old Madison Square
Garden,'' Jarvis said, ``because it reminded me of a Rocky Marciano
fight where you punch each other for 15 rounds and the guy that was
standing at the end won. Thank God we were the last team standing.
Tonight was a little reward for many of the other very, very
disappointing games that we didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's, which used a small lineup because center Tyrone
Grant was hampered by an infected cut on his right hand, slowed the
pace considerably, mixing defenses on Miami (22-6) and causing the
play to turn ugly quickly. Neither team shot over 40 percent and
the teams combined for 30 turnovers. Bodies banged, arms flew and
the whistles were plentiful. But the strategy worked, throwing
Miami's offensive timing off early in the game. St. John's had a
7-point lead midway through the first half, but the Hurricanes
finally found their rhythm to pull even at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected this to be a typical St. John's game where they
try to score 80 points,'' Miami Coach Leonard Hamilton said. ``To
their credit, they really slowed the tempo and did a nice job of
executing. It made us work an awful lot on defense. Any time a team
can make that adjustment and play like that, it is to their
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had built a 10-point lead with 4 minutes 30 seconds
remaining _ forward Ron Artest led St. John's with 18 points and
Bootsy Thornton, who had been struggling, regained his
aggressiveness and had 14 points _ but Miami scored 8 straight
points, 4 by the co-player of the year Tim James (25 points) to
close the lead to 56-54. But Barkley, who had just 9 points but
added 5 assists, lofted a 3-pointer with 1:59 left to stop the run
and allow St. John's to exhale.
</P>
<P>
   The score was 59-54, and after James hit one of two free throws
and then another layup with 57.9 seconds left, the score was 59-57.
On the next possession, St. John's Lavor Postell (17 points) got
smacked in the face by Miami's Vernon Jennings as he drove to the
basket. He made both free throws to make it 61-57 with 31.9 seconds
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After Miami let :15 seconds elapse, James hit another layup with
:16.8 left and the St. John's lead was back down to two 2 points,
at to 61-59. But as Miami tried to get in position for a
game-ending- shot, the ball hit Vernon Jennings in the leg and he
fell to the floor. With no timeouts left, Jennings tossed the ball
desperately to Johnny Hemsley. Barkley pulled it out of his arms,
and seconds later was dancing joyously around the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good players will make great plays,'' Hamilton said. ``He did
a tremendous job of running the offense _ the best I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The bluster before this game _ the start of what will likely be
a heated tango for years to come _ had been great and the game was
even greater. The founding fathers of the Big East _ the seven
athletic directors who founded the league 20 years ago and who were
honored during the evening _ must have felt as if they were in a
time warp, brought back to the glorious, bruising heyday of the
league with plenty of hard fouls and little offensive showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   That Miami is the only team to beat St. John's twice in one
season, that they have surged ahead of the Red Storm in the
national polls, that the Hurricanes, according to St. John's
players, pointed and laughed at them after the first win victory in
Miami, has made the Hurricanes the unlikely foil in St. John's
drive for revenge. Even the normally polished Mike Jarvis needled
his adversary to the south this week, when he said that getting
Miami in the tournament was the only thing that mattered for the
Red Storm. After the game, as the ice packs were applied, the ill
will and bumps that define so many of the Big East's great
rivalries lingered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just wanted to win real bad,'' James said. ``But they
were still scared. So I don't know what they're all happy about.''
</P>
<P>
   Because payback is sweet for St. John's. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
