<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BAYLOR-MILLER-HNS     03-06 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BAYLOR-MILLER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baylor
</P>
<P>
   Miller
</P>
<P>
   Miller resigns &QL; 
as Baylor coach &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Five seasons after taking over a team in turmoil from NCAA
violations, Baylor basketball coach Harry Miller resigned Friday
night on the heels of a 6-24 season that included a winless
conference record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for 25 years,'' said Miller, who was
56-87 at Baylor. ``I think the time is right for a change. I have
no regrets except for our record this year. We got caught in a
tornado and just couldn't get out. That's the hardest part about
leaving now. I've always wanted to be the very best and be on top
in everything I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor athletic director Tom Stanton said an advisory committee
will be formed to find a successor to Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any names in mind as a replacement, and we don't
have a timetable,'' Stanton said at a news conference in Waco.
``Harry and I had some very cordial conversations the last few
weeks. We talked about the program and shared ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not a forced situation. It was something where we
mutually agreed that the program needed to go another direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources say possible candidates for the job include Oklahoma
State assistant coach Paul Graham, Southwest Missouri State coach
Steve Alford and Tulsa coach Bill Self.
</P>
<P>
   Sources also say Jim Turner, the CEO of Dr Pepper Texas and a
prominent Baylor alumnus, plans to provide additional financial
support to help the school get the best possible successor.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears this season suffered the most losses in school history
and became the first Big 12 team to go through the conference
schedule without a victory. The Bears were 0-16 in league play
before losing to Oklahoma State 83-57 on Thursday in the opening
round of the Big 12 tournament at Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not as bad as our record would indicate,'' said
Miller, who was in the last year of his contract. ``I hope the fans
will be patient with whoever takes over the program, but I think
they can bounce back quickly because we've built a solid
foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor's 1998-99 record was a drastic downturn from the previous
two seasons when Miller led the Bears to a 14-14 record last year
and an 18-12 mark in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor failed to make postseason play in either season, but it
was a major improvement from Miller's first two years when the team
was 9-19 in 1994-95 and 9-18 in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was named interim head coach in November 1994 after head
coach Darrel Johnson and three of his assistants were fired in the
wake of NCAA violations involving academic fraud. Miller was given
the full title Jan. 25, 1995, but the Bears were on probation until
the 1997-98 season _ the first in which Miller had a full allotment
of scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Miller came to Baylor as an assistant to Johnson in the summer
of 1994 after building Temple High School into one of the top
basketball programs in the state. Two of his players _ center Brian
Skinner and guard Roddrick Miller, his son _ signed with Baylor in
1994 and played four seasons for Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who is a rookie for the Los Angeles Clippers, became
one of the best players is Baylor history, and Miller was a
starting guard his last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Along with point guard Patrick Hunter, Baylor had three talented
senior starters last season and started league play 5-0, but the
Bears ended Big 12 play a disappointing 8-8.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of three senior starters caused Baylor to be picked
near the bottom of the Big 12 entering this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears were 6-7 when conference play began but did not win
another game after a 102-85 victory over Texas-Pan American on Dec.
30. Miller's team was last in the Big 12 in shooting (37.9 percent)
and last in field-goal defense (42.6 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 47, said he has several options about what he will do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know for sure, but I've been looking into some
franchise businesses,'' Miller said. ``There's nothing concrete,
but if I do it, it will take me out of Waco. Even when Roddrick
graduated from high school, I started thinking about how much
longer I wanted to be in coaching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
