<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHN'S-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED STORM SWEEPS PAST MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Finally, St. John's got some satisfaction. After a
regular season of ``almosts'' and ``could have beens'' against
ranked teams, the Red Storm came away with a quality win against a
quality team Friday night at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   That the victim was No. 2 seed Miami in the semifinals of the
Big East tournament made it all the more satisfying for St. John's,
which pulled out a tough 62-59 victory over the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   The victory will send No. 3 seed St. John's (25-7) into Saturday
night's championship game against top seed Connecticut. It will be
the Red Storm's first appearance in the final since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Storm had lost to Miami twice during the regular season
and vowed it wouldn't happen a third time.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, although not without a monumental struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give them credit,'' said Miami coach Leonard
Hamilton. ``We expected them to come out with their quick-tempo
game the way they had played before. But they slowed it down and
controlled the tempo of the game. They showed a tremendous amount
of discipline and that's to their credit.''
</P>
<P>
   The first half was played at that slow pace ended tied, 26-26.
The pace picked up in the second half and the Red Storm seemed to
gain control when they built a 56-46 lead with 4:38 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Hurricanes (22-6) streaked back again, scoring the next
8 points and closing the gap to 56-54 with three minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was gutcheck time. St. John's Erick Barkley spoke first,
popping in a rainbow 3-pointer from the left side with 2:19 left to
extend the St. John's lead to 59-54.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Tim James (game-high 25 points) countered by making 1 of
2 free throws to make it 59-55, but the Hurricanes were running out
of time.
</P>
<P>
   James, the Big East co-Player of the Year, wasn't about to give
up as he put in a layup with 57.9 seconds left to cut the St.
John's lead to 59-57.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's tried to work the clock and get a good shot. They
split the difference when Miami's Vernon Jennings fouled Lavor
Postell with 31.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Postell, who keyed a St. John's surge in the first half, made
both foul shots to extend the Red Storm lead to 61-57.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes gave it their best shot, again led by James, who
put in a follow with 16.8 seconds left. The Hurricanes used their
last timeout to plot strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Miami quickly fouled Bootsie Thornton with 15.4 seconds left and
Thornton missed the first end of a one-and-one.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes rebounded but Barkley stole the ball from Johnny
Hemsley with five seconds left. All the 'Canes could do was foul
with 1.8 seconds left. Barkley's final free throw sealed the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game probably should have been played in the old Madison
Square Garden,'' said St. John's coach Mike Jarvis. ``It was like
an old-time heavyweight fight. It came down to the last man
standing and that was us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis said his team didn't feel any added pressure after a
string of disappointments that included losses to Miami, UConn,
Duke, and Stanford. ``We never felt we had to get over the hump,''
said Jarvis. ``The courageousness of this team came out. We
deserved to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The players felt the same way. Ron Artest, who scored a
team-high 18 points and was one of three St. John's players in
double figures, was asked what the difference was this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept going, we were full of energy, we didn't slack off,''
he said. ``You don't want to go down, 0-3, against a club. They're
not that much better than us.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, they weren't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
