r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     03-06 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BEAT SONICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ No string of victories, no number of Dennis Rodman
scissor-kick rebounds and no scientifically sound hypotheses about
the Lakers' quick turnaround could dispel the theory, however
quietly spoken, that just maybe this sudden success was a mirage.
</P>
<P>
   Five wins in five games sounded good, but with two against the
winless Clippers and two against the inconsistent Phoenix Suns, it
has been all too easy to brush off this streak as the product of
scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   But legitimizing the streak was only as far away as a game
against a Seattle or a Utah, and the Lakers draw both in a
three-day span. Legitimacy may have come Friday night, as the
Lakers won a close battle with the Sonics 103-100 in front of a
packed house at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good test,'' coach Kurt Rambis said before tipoff
Friday. ``The players have to know exactly where they stand....
It's a barometer of where they are and where they have to be. Win
or lose, it just helps them understand what they've gotta do.''
</P>
<P>
   For certain the winning streak has masked some deficiencies,
from sporadic defensive lapses to bad shot selection. And Rambis
said it's not gone unnoticed, or unspoken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a point of telling them everything is not OK,'' Rambis
said. ``We still have a long way to go. We want to be playing much
better basketball at the end of the season than we're playing
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Minute for minute, Friday's game against the Sonics ranked with
the best the Lakers have played this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it's always about improving,'' Rambis said. ``We don't
have time to kill in practice to get the necessary hard work. We're
going to have to improve in games throughout the season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers entered the fourth quarter with a 74-73 lead, with
neither team able to mount a pull-away rally. The final period
turned into the Gary Payton show, as the Sonics' crafty guard
scored Seattle's first 15 points of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the most Seattle could muster was a four-point lead, and it
quickly vanished with a Shaquille O'Neal jam and Derek Harper
fast-break layup. With 1:58 remaining, the score was knotted at 94.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper and Dale Ellis then turned it into a personal
rivalry. The longtime friends, who came into the league together 16
years ago, began trading clutch 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   First Harper, then Ellis. Then an O'Neal baseline jumper to make
it 99-97 Lakers. Then another Ellis 3-pointer, followed immediately
by a Harper 3-pointer to give the Lakers the 102-100 edge.
</P>
<P>
   An O'Neal free throw made it 103-100 with 18.1 seconds left,
leaving it up to a wide-open Vin Baker to nail the 3-pointer ...
which clanged off the front of the rim. Hersey Hawkins' 3-point try
at the buzzer also missed to seal the Lakers victory.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal led the Lakers with 31 points, and Payton led Seattle
with 34.
</P>
<P>
   A hard-fought first half ended with a 50-48 Lakers lead. Kobe
Bryant, picking up where he left off two nights earlier, came out
blazing with 10 points in the first quarter, and Shaquille O'Neal
scored 15 in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers outshot the Sonics, 48.8 percent to 39.5 percent, but
the Sonics' flurry of 3-pointers _ five on nine attempts _ kept the
score close.
</P>
<P>
   With Rodman getting the majority of power forward minutes,
Travis Knight spent the first half justifying Rambis' confidence in
him as the starter. Knight stayed out of the early foul trouble
that has plagued him this season and ended the half with nine
rebounds and eight points in 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Knight also played solid defense against Olden Polynice, who
hurt the Lakers with 15 points and 17 rebounds in their meeting two
weeks ago. Rambis put Knight on Polynice, leaving O'Neal to cover
Vin Baker, and the move paid off.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice ended the half with four points and six rebounds, and
Baker made just 2 of 12 field goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
