<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS FIND NEW SCORING SOURCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Last season Teemu Selanne scored 52 goals as he did
his best to carry a Mighty Ducks team that was much too heavy for
even his sturdy back.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's load is much lighter this year and both he and the
Ducks are enjoying themselves much more -- and that means
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Selanne extended his point-scoring streak to 15 games
and his goal-scoring streak to eight, but it was little-known Jeff
Nielsen who scored twice as the Ducks defeated Nashville 3-2 before
15,839 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, who had only one goal coming into the game, helped the
Ducks (29-25-9) equal a team record with their sixth consecutive
victory and move them four games over the .500 mark for the first
time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   The win also moves them to within three points of fourth-place
Phoenix in the Western Conference standings.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, who has only seven career goals, put the Ducks in front
early and then scored a much needed insurance goal midway through
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between Nielsen's goals was Selanne's 36th goal of
the season. It was a goal that helped him match a season-high
streak of eight set by Buffalo's Miroslav Satan. His 15-game point
streak is the second longest in the league this year (Eric Lindros
had an 18-game streak). It also ties his own team record.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks took a 1-0 lead at 7:06 of the first period when
Nashville's Kimmo Timonen fell down on the job.
</P>
<P>
   There was nobody within 10 feet of the defensemen when he lost
an edge and fell on his backside at the Predators' blue line.
Neilsen jumped on the puck, broke down the right wing and his
25-footer from the right circle bounced in off Nashville goalie
Mike Dunham's glove for his second goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's Denny Lambert, a former Duck, hit the post midway
through the period, before the Ducks' mighty power play struck
again.
</P>
<P>
   With 26.2 seconds left in the period, Selanne took a pass from
Marty McInnis and ripped a shot from the top of the left circle,
beating Dunham high on the stick side.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Ducks' NHL-leading 66th power play goal, six more
than they have scored in any previous season. Anaheim has scored at
least one power play goal in 29 of 32 games at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The second period saw both teams generate some good scoring
chances. Dunham made a great glove save on Selanne to prevent
another power play goal and he stopped a deflection by Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Roussel thwarted Sebastien Bordeleau's shorthanded bid
from point-blank range 2 1/2 minutes into the period. He also
knocked the puck off Cliff Ronning's stick as the Nashville center
appeared ready to score on backhander with 5 1/2 minutes left in
the period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Anaheim backup goalie was unable to stop Tom
Fitzgerald's seemingly harmless 45-footer at 11:50, a shot that cut
the Ducks' lead to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had three splendid chances to get that goal back early
in the final period when Selanne and Kariya buzzed in and around
the Nashville defense.
</P>
<P>
   Dunham, however, was equally brilliant stopping a breakaway by
Selanne, a hard backhander by Kariya and a point-blank deflection
by Selanne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
