<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-COLORADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS OVERCOMES FOUL WOES, INJURY TO STOP COLORADO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Texas coach Rick Barnes has often called Ivan
Wagner his team's unsung hero.
</P>
<P>
   When Wagner sat with his fourth foul yesterday and 11 1/2
minutes remaining in Texas' 82-76 Big 12 quarterfinal victory over
Colorado, the Longhorns lost the momentum of what had been their
most efficient offensive performance of the season.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, Texas had forged a reasonably comfortable margin
between itself and Colorado's dangerous offensive attack, led by
shooting ace Kenny Price.
</P>
<P>
   But the top-seeded Longhorns pulled off a series of late clutch
plays to hold off the Buffaloes, surviving Wagner's six-minute
absence and Kris Clack's bruised buttock that limited him in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Refreshed after a loss to Missouri a week ago, Texas (19-11)
advanced to face Oklahoma State (21-9) in today's 1 p.m. semifinal
at Kemper Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm very pleased with the way we did what we had to
do down the stretch,'' Texas coach Rick Barnes said. ``We got into
some trouble when Ivan was in foul trouble, which proves how
valuable he is to our team. But this time of year, players have to
make plays, and we had players who did that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading 61-47 shortly after Wagner's departure with 11:37 left,
Texas watched its lead gradually shrink to 75-72 with 1:40 to play.
The Longhorns then seized the moment.
</P>
<P>
   First, backup guard Will Clay hit a one-dribble, pull-up,
14-foot jumper from the left side of the lane with 1:06 to play and
four seconds left on the shot clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``A one-dribble move I work on every day,'' Clay said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after a Colorado free throw, Clack rebounded Gabe
Muoneke's errant 16-footer and laid it in off the glass for a 79-73
cushion with 19.5 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to jump, but I didn't have to jump that high,''
Clack said. ``I was in the right spot and was able to get \Rthe
rebound\S, throw it off the glass and it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally, Muoneke answered the call to seal the victory after
Jaquay Walls nailed Colorado's 14th 3-point shot of the day with
14.7 seconds left. After Clay netted a free throw at 12.3, Muoneke
stole the rebound when Clay missed his second shot. Muoneke kicked
it out and got a return pass for a dunk that slammed the door with
two seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I might get inside my man and tip the ball out and
that would seal the game,'' Muoneke said. ``But he got control and
I tipped it out of his hands, picked it up, and then threw it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do anything to let this one slip away, though it
could have gone either way. We kept our composure to get this
victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Mihm led with a season's 17th double-double of 24 points
and 14 rebounds. Muoneke contributed 18 points and nine rebounds
and tied a career-high with six assists _ all to Mihm. Clack added
14 points and Wagner had five assists.
</P>
<P>
   Price hit a tournament-record nine 3-pointers in 11 attempts on
his way to a game-high 31 points. But Texas outscored Colorado
52-18 in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a really good Texas team,'' Colorado coach Ricardo
Patton said. ``They pounded the ball inside a lot and for the most
part _ especially in the first half \RTexas led 44-34\S _ we didn't
have any answers. It's a shame Kenny plays his best game of the
season and we come up short.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
