r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-COW     03-06 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE-AGENT ADDITIONS WOULD PUT GLINT BACK IN GAILEY'S EYES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chan Gailey's face was pale, his eyes dark and sunken that late
January afternoon just over two months ago. He searched for the
right words, looking for a way to say what needed to be said
without pointing fingers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' head coach started to talk, then stopped. He
answered questions with a nod. He asked, a couple of times, for
those gathered around him to draw their conclusions based on their
own observations.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey and a sold-out Texas Stadium had just seen the Cowboys'
offense shut down by dropped passes and poorly run routes.
Quarterback Troy Aikman had been sacked four times and threw three
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone paying attention in the home team's locker room after the
Arizona Cardinals upset the Cowboys, 20-7, in the first round of
the playoffs knew what was coming this off-season, knew that Gailey
would target two areas that had to be improved before next season:
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver and the middle of his offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The answers to both those problems paid visits to Valley Ranch
over the last 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Conclusion drawn: Owner Jerry Jones will somehow find a way to
put a smile back on his coach's face by signing free-agent wide
receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail and center Mark Stepnoski within
the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Gailey was already smiling yesterday, or
perhaps it was because he had just spent the afternoon playing golf
with Pat Summerall and a couple of other friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did was sit down at the end of the season and evaluate
where we were as a team,'' Gailey said. ``As we looked at the
players available, it just so happened that two of the better
players available fit what we were looking for in free agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Just so happened? If Jimmy Johnson were still here, someone
would call that Cowboy luck.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Cowboys have cap problems. But since when has Jones not
been able to slither his way around, over, under and through that
red tape? He'll take money out of one pocket, drop it in another,
you watch and see.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a situation, when you're either tight under the cap,
you have to be smart about how you spend your money,'' Gailey said.
``We don't want to get to the point where we're dismantling the
team just to sign a couple of free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Dismantling, no. Rearranging, sure.
</P>
<P>
   Stepnoski is still one of the best in the NFL at center. His
presence alone would immediately upgrade the Cowboys' offensive
line and lift Aikman's spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the guy we've spent most of our time on and with to
this point,'' said Gailey, who hinted that the Cowboys and
Stepnoski might be close to striking a deal. ``We wouldn't be
posturing ourselves and neither would he if we didn't see that
there was a light at the end of the tunnel. Anytime you visit,
you've got a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great knowledge of our team and a lot of people in
our organization have a great knowledge of him. He's a sharp guy.
Very sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Stepnoski and the return of Everett McIver would
improve the depth in the middle of the line immensely. The Cowboys
could consider keeping Flozell Adams at tackle, where he's better
suited.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail would be the No. 2 receiver the Cowboys have needed so
badly to help stretch the field and take some of the pressure off
Michael Irvin. ``Rocket'' is coming off a career year in which he
caught 69 passes for 1,024 yards and eight touchdowns for the
Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an excellent year this year, obviously the best year
he's had,'' Gailey said. ``He's a guy who has a lot of potential, a
great deal of speed. He would fit our offense pretty well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely need to be able to complement the other side of
Michael. I don't think anybody would argue with that. We did that
early in the year. We did not do that later in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   When wideout Ernie Mills and tight end David LaFleur went down
with injuries, the Cowboys discovered that Billy Davis was not
going to be the answer as the No. 2 receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had just been one injury, we might have overcome it,''
Gailey said. ``But then all of a sudden to get Ernie hurt and David
LaFleur hurt, those things just started to mount up. That got to us
in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made strides this year on offense and I think as much as
anything, us being in the second year of the offense will help,
along with Troy being comfortable in all the calls. But more good
players never hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are closing in on two more, which comes as no real
surprise to those who looked into Gailey's eyes that sickening
Sunday afternoon two months ago.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
