<SLUG> BC-BKC-BAYLOR-RESIGNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAYLOR COACH RESIGNS UNDER PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Baylor basketball coach Harry Miller resigned
last night, little more than 24 hours after his team finished the
worst season in school history.
</P>
<P>
   He said he made his decision after consulting with athletic
director Tom Stanton yesterday, the latest in a series of
discussions that Miller said had gone on for the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a point in time now for me to turn another page in my
life,'' Miller said from Waco. ``I'm going to explore some business
opportunities outside athletics. I've done some preliminary looking
at some franchise opportunities that I was considering five years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't rule out coaching again, but it's not in my immediate
plans. I've put five years into this program ... and I think I've
bridged the gap and borne the brunt of the most difficult part of
it. Now it's up to someone else to take it to another level.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller came to Baylor in the summer of 1994 from Temple High
School, the last stop in a distinguished career of Texas high
school coaching. He was appointed interim coach in November 1994
after Darrel Johnson was dismissed near the end of a two-year NCAA
investigation into academic fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was given a five-year contract on Jan. 25, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took over at a difficult time and has been a model of
integrity and class for our players, the athletic department and
the entire university,'' Stanton said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's record was 56-87. His best season was 18-12 in 1997,
though last season's 14-14 team improved from 6-10 to 8-8 and a tie
for fifth place in the Big 12. He lost the core of his program when
former Temple star center Brian Skinner and junior college transfer
guard Patrick Hunter graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Miller said, ``There is life after Brian
Skinner.''
</P>
<P>
   His optimism was unfounded. Baylor stumbled to a 6-7 start, then
lost 17 consecutive Big 12 games _ including Thursday's 83-57 loss
to Oklahoma State in the opening round of the Big 12 tournament. No
Baylor team had gone winless in conference play since 1945.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
