<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-A10-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
URI, TEMPLE TO MEET FOR A10 CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The storylines suggested a compelling game. The
University of Rhode Island featured sophomore sensation Lamar Odom,
the Atlantic 10 rookie of the year and future NBA lottery pick.
George Washington featured Shawnta Rogers, the 5-foot-4-inch A-10
player of the year. Moreover, GWU is coached by former URI mentor
Tom Penders.
</P>
<P>
   And if that wasn't enough, URI was so steamed it lost a
regular-season battle to GWU Jan. 23 that on Thursday night, Odom
declared, ``Don't be surprised to see blood on the floor'' the
second time around.
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, there was no blood. There wasn't much suspense
either. URI used a balanced scoring attack and a defense that held
GWU to 21 percent shooting in the first half to post a 94-78
victory and advance to its second Atlantic 10 tournament
championship game in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Reynolds-Dean had 21 points and nine rebounds, Odom had
17 points and 11 assists, and Preston Murphy had 14 points and
blocked three shots by Rogers (four total) for URI (19-12), which
beat only its fourth opponent with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defense was outstanding, and Murphy set the tone,'' said
URI coach Jim Harrick, whose team will meet Temple, a 76-64 winner
over defending A-10 tournament champ Xavier Friday &UR;  &LR; night, in
Saturday's 6 p.m. championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Rasheed Brokenborough had a game-high 22 points and Mark Karcher
added 19 points for Temple (21-9), which advanced to the
championship game for the league-leading 10th time, the first time
since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the second time the teams have met in the title game;
Temple beat the Penders-coached Rams 68-63 in the 1988
championship, URI's first championship game appearance. The Owls
have won four titles, their last coming in 1990. Since then,
they've reached the finals four times, losing to the University of
Massachusetts each time.
</P>
<P>
   URI, which lost to St. Joseph's in the 1998 championship game,
struggled in two lopsided losses to Temple in the regular season.
It was one of the reasons URI players said Thursday night they
preferred playing Xavier should they reach the final. After Friday
night's win, however, the Rams changed their tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who we play now. I don't care if we play
Duke,'' said Reynolds-Dean, who helped URI outrebound the Colonials
in the first half, 28-18.
</P>
<P>
   But GWU assisted its own demise, with poor shot selection. The
Colonials (20-8) mustered just two field goals over the last 11:17
of the first half and trailed at halftime, 45-24.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers finished with a team-high 22 points but was 6 of 20 from
the floor. Odom, on the other hand, spent much of the evening
getting his teammates involved in the offense. With 14:57 left, he
threaded the GWU defense for a nifty halfcourt pass to Murphy, who
scored on a layup to give the Rams a 57-32 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the other game, Karcher scored 17 second-half points,
including three treys and four free throws over the last 7:26, to
help the Owls pull away.
</P>
<P>
   Temple trailed, 30-28, at halftime. Karcher hit consecutive
treys, the former with 7:26 left, to give the Owls a 57-53 lead. A
trey by Gary Lumpkin with 5:20 left, cut the deficit to 57-56, but
Karcher hit another trey and Lamont Barnes scored on a putback dunk
of a Kevin Lyde miss to give the Owls a 62-57 edge with 3:53 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Karcher sank a pullup trey, with 3:05 to go, to give the Owls a
65-59 edge. Two more Karcher free throws with 1:03 left gave the
Owls a 73-61 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
