<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORM HAS US ALL HOOKED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ A week after the one-man, Rodman circus came to
town, his impact can be summed up this way: The Lakers are not
distracted _ but you are.
</P>
<P>
   Admit it, you're hopelessly, happily distracted by the freak
with the hair. You and 17,504 friends at the Forum have never
watched basketball this way before, with eyes riveted to the one
player least likely to sink a shot, tracking his every move even
when he's sitting on the bench, the hair and the pierced ears
hooded by a towel.
</P>
<P>
   I'm with you. I sat down to write the Lakers haven't been so
much fun to watch since they took ``Showtime'' off the marquee.
</P>
<P>
   But this sounds more precise: (begin ital)No Laker(end ital) has
ever been as fun to watch as Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team? I couldn't really say. I don't watch them
anymore. Is Eddie Jones still a Laker? How about Kobe Bryant?
</P>
<P>
   I know Shaquille O'Neal is still here _ he's the one who's
always spoiling my view of Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   Like you, I don't want to miss a second of him.
</P>
<P>
   It might be the second when he air-balls a free throw, then
walks to the rim with his index finger in the air, as if to gauge a
tricky breeze, as he did in the Lakers' victory over Phoenix the
other night.
</P>
<P>
   Or the second when he asks a referee for the ball between
somebody else's free throws, squeezes it as if to check for
ripeness, and quietly hands it back.
</P>
<P>
   Or the second when he fumbles a rebound out of bounds, and takes
out his frustration by pulling himself up on the net.
</P>
<P>
   Or the second when he grabs a rebound right-handed because his
left arm is locked up with one of the Suns', and manages to hurl an
outlet without bothering to disentangle the other arm.
</P>
<P>
   Or the second when he locks arms with the Suns' Tom Gugliotta _
how (begin ital)do(end ital) these things always happen to Dennis?
_ both go tumbling and Gugliotta receives a technical foul for
complaining.
</P>
<P>
   Or the second when he plants a playful pat on the butt of the
Suns' Joe Kleine, who's on a rant after being whistled for hacking
Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   Or the second when he quickly positions himself to get run over
by a cutting opponent, causing an offensive foul with a move so
clever it draws laughs from the (begin ital)Phoenix(end ital)
bench.
</P>
<P>
   All the things you booed when Rodman wore Detroit blue, San
Antonio black or Chicago red, you love now that he's in purple and
gold for your town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is an entertainer,'' Derek Harper said, which is what
Dennis has always maintained.
</P>
<P>
   During the weeks-long contract negotiations, the Lakers were
warned of the Rodman tradeoff: On the plus side, he'd give them
13.2 rebounds a game, nettling defense and infectious intensity; on
the negative, he'd be a goof-off _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But until or unless the ``or worse'' kicks in, the cold, hard
production and the clown act go together like skin and ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would say it's not the glamorous way to play,'' Laker Rick
Fox said of Rodman's emphasis on the game's menial tasks. ``But he
makes it glamorous.'' If he played baseball, Rodman would win
notoriety not by hitting 70 home runs but by breaking up 70 double
plays.
</P>
<P>
   You would also say Dennis Rodman is the last guy anybody would
hold up as a role model for the kids. But think about this.
</P>
<P>
   He has fun playing defense, the basketball equivalent of
homework. He has fun boxing out for rebounds, the basketball
equivalent of cleaning up your room. He even makes amusement out of
sitting on the bench, the basketball equivalent of keeping quiet at
your sister's flute recital.
</P>
<P>
   This could be the NBA's next public-service announcement:
``Kids, I'm Dennis Rodman, living proof that doing the chores with
panache will make you a star. So why don't you get off your
(bleep)?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to see a guy with the ability to play defense and
rebound as well as he does,'' Laker Derek Fisher said, ``and give
it flair.''
</P>
<P>
   The joke being that sometimes, Rodman appears to be not much
more than a kid himself. When he mused during the already-legendary
Planet Hollywood press conference that he wasn't sure he wanted to
rejoin the NBA and ``go back and be 22 again,'' the unasked
follow-up question was, When did you ever act as old as 22 before?
</P>
<P>
   As bitter as he sounded that tearful day in Beverly Hills, as
sour as much of his past has been, that's how sweet his basketball
has been for the first week in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The 13.2 rebounds aren't even half of it.
</P>
<P>
   The Wormaphobics' buzzword was ``distraction.'' Remember? Rodman
would be a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they were right. The Lakers might be all right, but I'm
hopelessly, happily distracted. And if you'd quit grinning long
enough to admit it, you are too. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
