<HEADER>
A0018 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-LINEUP-HNS     03-06 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-LINEUP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros
</P>
<P>
   Juggling process &QL; 
ahead for Dierker &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alou's injury means new lineup roles
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ For any manager, there are two must-have items
once the exhibition season begins: a pencil and an eraser.
</P>
<P>
   During the next four weeks, Astros manager Larry Dierker will
fill in, scratch off and erase a number of potential batting
lineups. The only two spots on which it is safe to use ink are
leadoff (Craig Biggio) and No. 9 (the pitcher).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to look at a lot of different ways,'' Dierker said
after the Astros' 7-4 victory over Atlanta in their exhibition
opener Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to spring training, the batting order appeared to be the
least pressing issue, with the National League's most potent
offense from a year ago returning intact. The knee injury that
sidelined Moises Alou has forced some experimenting, if not
shuffling, in parts of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The search will concentrate on the Nos. 2 and 5 spots. The
latter was occupied last season by Alou.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker is inclined to move Derek Bell into Alou's former spot,
but he could be met with some resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Bell repeatedly says he has no desire to move from the No. 2
spot, one protected by Biggio and Jeff Bagwell, but the Astros must
find some way to compensate for the loss of Alou's power _ 38 home
runs and 124 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we have to replace his RBIs, and the most veteran guy
we have to do that is Derek,'' Dierker said. ``But he doesn't feel
as comfortable hitting fifth as he does second. Maybe if we put him
in there a few times, that will change.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bell shifts to the middle of the lineup, Carl Everett and
Ricky Gutierrez become the leading candidates to bat second.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a 1-through-8 look at possible scenarios:
</P>
<P>
   1) Biggio is one of the best leadoff hitters in the game. End of
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   His blend of power, speed and smarts makes Biggio perfect for
this role. He had a club-record 210 hits last season and batted a
career-high .325, meaning he is always a threat to get on base.
Biggio managed 20 home runs and 88 RBIs _ figures usually reserved
for a No. 3 or No. 5 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   2) Perhaps the biggest lineup question: Do you move Bell from
his current comfort zone and run the risk of having his production
drop off? It's hard to disagree with Bell's argument that he remain
in the same lineup spot after he produced career-best numbers in
almost every category while hitting second in more than one-third
of the games.
</P>
<P>
   An ideal No. 2 hitter can hit line drives, is needed to move
runners from second to third and is usually a good bunter; this
last is not one of Bell's strong traits.
</P>
<P>
   One possible alternative could be Everett, who never has hit
second. Everett, a switch-hitter, is quick and makes contact
regularly. Another plus: set to begin his first full-time gig in
the major leagues Everett is willing to bat anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play,'' said Everett, who batted sixth in 91 of his
113 starts last season. ``For some guys it may bother them (to bat
in certain spots), but for someone like me that has never really
gotten to play you don't care where you hit. Some guys need
protection in the lineup. Some guys may have their superstitions,
or just feel comfortable, being in a certain spot. I couldn't care
less.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker also plans to look at Gutierrez (27 games at No. 2 in
1998); utility player Bill Spiers (57 games); and Alou's outfield
replacement, Richard Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   3) Bagwell, who can be counted on 30-plus homers and 100 or more
RBIs, can bat third or cleanup. With the addition of Ken Caminiti,
he likely will see most of his time at No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   4) Caminiti gives the Astros the potential to have four of the
top five spots produce 20 or more home runs. When healthy, he can
add another dimension to a club's lineup (40 homers, 130 RBIs in
1996), but Dierker will closely monitor how much playing time the
'96 Most Valuable Player gets after missing 32 games last season
with an assortment of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   On days he rests, Dierker probably will bat Bagwell fourth, a
spot he occupied in 99 games last year.
</P>
<P>
   5) Alou was a mainstay in the fifth spot, batting there in all
but 27 games in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing his offensive numbers seems unlikely; the Astros' goal
is to come close. The problem is determining whether Bell will
adapt to a new role.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker hopes that if uses Bell enough in this spot during the
spring, Bell will adjust.
</P>
<P>
   6) An ideal sixth hitter has decent power. Hidalgo and Everett,
who combined for 22 home runs and 111 RBIs last year, are logical
fits. Dierker was able to use them in a platoon. Hidalgo would get
the role if Everett moves to the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   7) Catcher Tony Eusebio likely will likely bat here. If
Gutierrez hits in the second spot, the Astros catchers could move
to No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   8) Whoever bats in this spot will be called on to do a lot of
things. Pitchers usually pitch the bottom of the order tough, so
the No. 8 hitter will have to be mentally tough.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros like Gutierrez in this spot because he is a
fast-enough runner to advance on bunts and infield outs _ often hit
softly _ by the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's too early to set a lineup,'' said Gutierrez, who
batted eighth 21 times in 1998, when catcher Brad Ausmus normally
occupied the No. 8 spot. ``There are a lot of options. All managers
wish they had a lineup like we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
