<HEADER>
A0019 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALDEZ-OIL-SPILL-1STL     03-06 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALDEZ-OIL-SPILL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10 YEARS LATER, DISAGREEMENT PERSISTS ON EFFECTS OF VALDEZ OIL
SPILL
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS lede to clarify and move up date of accident; 6th graf to add
date federal law was passed; grafs 13, 14 for clarification and to
refine prose; editorial refinements throughout.)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(fe) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TATITLEK, Alaska _ It was a few minutes after midnight on March
24, 1989, when the big tanker ran aground on Bligh Reef in the icy
waters of Prince William Sound. ``Evidently, we're leaking some
oil, and we're going to be here for quite a while,'' the captain
radioed to the Coast Guard. Even now, as the 10th anniversary of
one of the nation's worst environmental disasters approaches, the
Exxon Valdez is in many ways still here.
</P>
<P>
   In environmental terms, the sound is still recovering, according
to a report issued recently by the joint federal and state council
that monitors the continuing effects of the tanker accident, which
dumped at least 10.8 million gallons of North Slope crude into the
sound and blackened 1,500 miles of the magnificent Gulf of Alaska
coastline.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 28 species listed in the report, only two _ the bald
eagle and the river otter _ are considered to be ``fully
recovered'' a decade later. For the ecosystem in general and for
most other species, substantial progress has been made toward
recovery but ``there is a long way yet to go,'' according to the
council's director.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, the Valdez case drags on. Five years after a federal
jury ordered Exxon to pay a record $5 billion in punitive fines to
the thousands of villagers and commercial fishermen hurt by the
spill, the company has yet to pay any of the judgment, challenging
it in an appeals process that may continue for years. Exxon, which
spent an estimated $2.3 billion on cleanup activities and another
$1 billion in a federal settlement, says the award sends a
``perverse message'' after all the company did to mitigate the
spill's effects.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another continuing reminder of the spill, the tanker's
skipper, Joseph J. Hazelwood, is also still a presence here in
Alaska. After years of fighting his state conviction on the
misdemeanor charge of negligent discharge of oil, the former
captain, who lives on Long Island, N.Y., will at last return this
summer to begin a court-ordered community service program. He has
been assigned to pick up trash on the streets of Anchorage.
</P>
<P>
   And even the ship itself remains in the news. It has long since
been repaired and renamed the SeaRiver Mediterranean, and the Exxon
subsidiary that owns it, challenging the 1990 federal law that in
the animus of the moment prohibited her from ever returning to
Alaska, has been seeking permission in both Congress and the courts
for her once again to work the waters of Prince William Sound.
</P>
<P>
   But for many people who live here, the idea of the tanker's
returning is ``just too much,'' in the words of Gary P. Kompkoff,
president of the village council here in Tatitlek, a small Aleut
community just three miles from where the Exxon Valdez went
aground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still struggling with what happened here,'' Kompkoff
said. ``Eleven million gallons of oil, from the bottom of the food
chain to the top. I'm not sure I understand how we could ever
totally recover from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of the spill, Exxon and most of the people who live
in the area around the sound here were in disagreement over just
how bad its effects would be, and 10 years later, they still are.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon says the area has ``essentially recovered'' by any
reasonable measure, and the company's vice president for
environment and safety, Frank B. Sprow, said that while any oil
spill is an unfortunate event, exhaustive studies by the company
and independent scientists have found no long-term harm.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you find is acute short-term impacts,'' Sprow said, ``but
the environment &UR;  &LR; _ Mother Nature, if you will _ has remarkable
powers of recovery, whether aided by man or not, and the natural
order does re-establish itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to tourists who pass by in cruise ships or to a visitor
flying over the snowy tundra and vast blue glacial fields in a bush
plane, the sound looks as clean and spectacular as it ever did. And
some steps taken because of the spill may protect it all the more.
For instance, some of the money from Exxon's federal settlement has
been used for conservation programs protecting about 650,000 acres
of land, including sensitive habitat along 61 salmon and trout
streams.
</P>
<P>
   And while there can be no guarantee that a disastrous spill will
not happen again, steps undertaken since the accident have, it is
widely agreed, made shipping here less prone to a recurrence. In
addition to enactment of a federal law that phases in a requirement
that all tankers be double-hulled, an elaborate escort program with
tugboats, on-board harbor pilots, radar tracking and other measures
is in place for the tankers that routinely pass in and out of the
port of Valdez, ferrying oil from the trans-Alaska pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   But the Exxon Valdez spill killed 250,000 seabirds, 2,800 sea
otters, 300 harbor seals, 250 bald eagles and up to 22 killer
whales, according to the Exxon Valdez Oil Spill Trustee Council,
the federal-state monitoring agency. And the notion that the sound
has recovered from the kind of devastation that such a toll implies
is bitterly disputed by many of the 20,000 people who live in the
areas that were most directly affected by the spill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not back to what it was _ no way at all,'' said Gail
Evanoff, the council president in tiny Chenega Bay, a village that
lay directly in the the path of the westward flow of the oil.
``There's life there, but not what you saw before.'' Ms. Evanoff,
as well as officials of the trustee council, said there were still
small pockets along the beaches and in rock crevices where small
pools of oil and tar balls can be found _ and smelled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 0205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0021 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALDEZ-OIL-SPILL-ART-     03-06 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALDEZ-OIL-SPILL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TATITLEK, Alaska: and smelled.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Cordova, a fishing village with a postcard harbor nestled up
against the Chugach Mountains, there is still visceral anger at
Exxon, and many people blame the oil company for a downturn in
their fortunes _ declining Pacific herring runs and a sharp falloff
in the value of commercial fishing permits, particularly for
herring. ``The fabric of this community was pulled apart, ripped,
torn, shredded, kicked,'' said a former mayor, Kelley Weaverling.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Lange, 46, who comes from a longtime fishing family and
with her husband has been struggling to maintain a fish-processing
plant in Cordova, said she believed the damage to the sound and the
people who make their living from it could be compared in many ways
to the trauma of a rape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say with utmost certainty that there is no such thing as
a true `cleanup' here,'' Mrs. Lange said. ``You can put on makeup
and make a show of it and say, `Oh, it must be better again.' But
it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Exxon vigorously disputes such claims and notes that many of the
people who are still complaining about the spill received
compensatory payments in 1989 and 1990 that amounted to several
times their normal annual income.
</P>
<P>
   Herring spawning has indeed sharply declined since 1989 _ from
100,000 metric tons to 16,000 by 1993 and now around 30,000, said
Stan Senner, science coordinator of the trustee council. But Exxon
says that such declines are part of normal fluctuations in the
ocean and cannot be attributed to the spill. Runs of salmon, which
make vast migrations and were much less directly affected by the
spill, have remained strong.
</P>
<P>
   A comprehensive look at the spill's continuing environmental
effects is not easy to come by, in part, scientists point out,
because there is not a lot of detailed ``baseline data''
quantifying exactly what the sound was like before the Exxon Valdez
hit the jagged shoals of Bligh Reef.
</P>
<P>
   But the trustee council, which was financed with money from the
government's settlement, did reach several conclusions in the
recent report. The good news was that bald eagles, which can be
seen all around here and which were enumerated in surveys before
the spill, are flourishing and are thus considered ``recovered.''
River otters no longer indicate elevated levels of the blood
chemicals that indicate oil exposure, and so they too were declared
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   But several bird species and marine mammals _ including common
loons, three species of cormorants, harbor seals, harlequin ducks
and the killer whales of Prince William Sound _ have shown no
significant recovery, according to the report. The stellar sea lion
remains an endangered species, though its numbers had been entering
into a serious decline in the northern Gulf of Alaska even before
1989, meaning that the spill's responsibility for the continued
decline remains a subject of fierce contention.
</P>
<P>
   Many villagers rely on the fish, mammals and wild plants for a
subsistence diet here, and the report found that their gathering
methods had changed after the spill, with many vital foods being
much harder to find in abundance.
</P>
<P>
   And just as the ecological conditions remain under debate, the
legal terrain of the case remains a battlefield as well, and
recently, plaintiffs have been pressing Congress to intervene by
holding up the proposed $80 billion merger of Exxon and Mobil until
the case gets resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given Exxon's arrogance in refusing to pay us what it owes us,
the government should not let Exxon amass any more power or
arrogance,'' said Patience Andersen Faulkner, a Cordova resident,
showing a visitor a letter she sent recently to her senators on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 federal jury award to about 33,000 fishermen, villagers
and other Alaskans was the largest pollution award in history, but
it remains unpaid.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is currently under appeal, and it might wind up
before the Supreme Court, though the plaintiffs' lead lawyer, Brian
O'Neill, says there is no reason for it to do so.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's basically a big drunk-driving case,'' said O'Neill, who
is based in Minneapolis. ``There are no big constitutional issues
involved. We don't need the Supreme Court _ Exxon should pay up.''
(The ship's captain was seen having drinks in the hours before the
Valdez left port and failed an initial blood-alcohol test by the
Coast Guard, but he has steadfastly denied being drunk when the
tanker hit the reef, and the state jury acquitted him of
intoxication charges.)
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plaintiffs in Cordova and Tatitlek seem prepared to
fight on in the courts for years or longer, while other shrug off
the whole case and say they doubt they will ever see any money from
the judgment. A few say Exxon tried to make amends and no longer
deserves to be the object of communal wrath. And still others say
that in the most important way, the case will never be resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter has fished with me since she was a toddler, and
one thing I know we've lost is my ability to tell her, `Oh, it'll
be OK, the sound will always be OK,''' said Steve Riedel, a
42-year-old fisherman who notes ruefully that his fishing boat,
Lucky Lady, was so named before the spill.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Diana, is 16 now, and she has a collection of
rocks, including some oil-covered ones she pulled from the beaches
just last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just isn't the same,'' Riedel said, ``and she knows it. And
so when she's deciding what she's going to do with her life, I
think I'm probably going to tell her, keep your fond memories, but
find something to do other than fishing in Prince William Sound.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
