<HEADER>
A0023 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-BIGSKY-LADN     03-06 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-BIGSKY-LADN </SLUG>
 
NORTHRIDGE WOMEN ONE WIN FROM NCAAs 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Edniesha Curry couldn't find her shot, Lynda
Amari was there.
</P>
<P>
   When Amari ran into foul trouble in the second half, Curry was
there.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they put the Cal State Northridge women's basketball
team one step closer to the school's first date with 63 other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Curry scored 18 of her 24 points in the second half, and Amari
added 11 of her 16 points in the second half to lead the top-seeded
Matadors to an 83-68 victory over No.6 Northern Arizona in front of
a season-high 905 at Northridge on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The win was its sixth in a row and put Northridge (20-7) into
tonight's 5 p.m. final against second-seeded Portland State. To the
winner goes as the conference's automatic NCAA Tournament
representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be one game away from the NCAAs is so exciting, it's almost
beyond words,'' Northridge coach Frozena Jerro said.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona, which had won four in a row to get to the
tournament, then knocked off No.3 Montana State on Thursday,
finished 14-14.
</P>
<P>
   As it has been throughout the season, Curry and Amari have been
the inside-outside combination for the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do it on purpose,'' Amari said. ``We have a
connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night was no different.
</P>
<P>
   Curry was just 1 of 5 from the field in the first half, and
Amari played just eight minutes because of foul trouble. Both had
five points.
</P>
<P>
   What a different a half makes.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 34-32 to start the second half, Amari 11 of her team's
first 15 points. That keyed a 13-4 Northridge run and gave the
Matadors a 45-38 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona, which lost both games against Northridge this
season, fought back to tie the score at 51-51 with 11:30 to play.
Eight seconds later, Amari left with four fouls.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Curry awakened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat down (at halftime) and relaxed,'' Curry said. ``My
teammates told me to let the game come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   She drove the land for a layup. She drained two 3-pointers. Then
two more outside jumpers. Then she stole the ball and made a layup,
followed by another 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen points in five minutes and seven seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Curry, in the postgame interview, couldn't believe it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa!'' she exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Explosive, huh?'' Jerro said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Northridge had a 72-58 lead with about six
minutes to play, and that was the end of the Lumberjacks' bid to
become the first sixth-seeded team to reach the women's tournament
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took it to us in the second half,'' said NAU forward
RaeAnn West, who led the Lumberjacks with 20 points. ``Curry and
Amari came out, started hitting their. They were hot. We were in
their faces and they were hitting them.''
</P>
<P>
   One other piece of motivation guided the Matadors: Northern
Arizona had defeated them three times last year, the third time
coming in the conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had forgotten,'' Jerro said. ``A player mentioned it. Tina
(Greer) said, `It's payback time.'''
</P>
<P>
   Keisha Harris added 11 points for Northridge, and Jamilah Jones
added 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona got 15 points from Kristi Forman, 11 points
from Anna Sturing and 10 points from Jess LeBlanc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
