<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0028 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-L     03-06 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WIN 3-2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Last season Teemu Selanne scored 52 goals as he did
his best to carry a Mighty Ducks team that was much too heavy for
even his sturdy back.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's load is much lighter this year and both he and the
Ducks are enjoying themselves much more -- and that means
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Selanne extended his point-scoring streak to 15 games
and his goal-scoring streak to eight, but it was little-known Jeff
Nielsen who scored twice as the Ducks defeated Nashville 3-2 before
15,839 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, who had only one goal coming into the game, helped the
Ducks (29-25-9) equal a team record with their sixth consecutive
victory and move them four games over the .500 mark for the first
time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not often I score one goal, so then to score two ...,''
said Nielsen, who had a shot at a hat trick when he was rewarded
with some power play time late in the game. ``I held my breath for
a minute, but maybe three is a little too much to ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's 12th victory in its last 15 games moved it within
three points of fourth-place Phoenix in the Western Conference
standings.
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Kariya still wants to see more from his team,
especially with Detroit coming to town on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to play a lot better,'' said Kariya of the Ducks,
who outshot Nashville, 34-24. ``If we get the same kind of effort
against Detroit we're going to get killed, but I'm sure our team
will respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen, who has only seven career goals, put the Ducks in front
early and then scored a much needed insurance goal midway through
the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't scored a lot of goal, but we feel real good about
our role,'' said Nielsen, who plays on a checking line with Ted
Drury and Jim McKenzie. ``We are going to play a real simple game,
try to create some energy and get the crowd going.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who was held scoreless despite seven shots on goal, was
happy for Nielsen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played extremely well,'' said Kariya. ``It's nice to see
him get rewarded. He has a great shot, he just needs to be more
confident in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Players like Nielsen scoring certainly take the pressure off the
Ducks' top line and that's very much appreciated by team's captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to get offense from other guys,'' Kariya
said. ``It's a huge confidence booster.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between Nielsen's goals was Selanne's 36th goal of
the season. It was a goal that helped him match a season-high
streak of eight set by Buffalo's Miroslav Satan. His 15-game point
streak is the second longest in the league this year (Eric Lindros
had an 18-game streak). It also ties his own team record.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks took a 1-0 lead at 7:06 of the first period when
Nashville's Kimmo Timonen fell down on the job.
</P>
<P>
   There was nobody within 10 feet of the defensemen when he lost
an edge at the Predators' blue line. Neilsen jumped on the puck,
broke down the right wing and his 25-footer from the right circle
bounced in off Nashville goalie Mike Dunham's glove.
</P>
<P>
   With 26.2 seconds left in the period and the Ducks on the power
play, Selanne took a pass from Marty McInnis and ripped a shot from
the top of the left circle, beating Dunham high on the stick side.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Ducks' NHL-leading 66th power play goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The second period saw both teams generate some good scoring
chances, but the only goal came on a harmless looking 45-footer at
11:50 that eluded Dominic Roussel, who was making a rare start in
place of Guy Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville, however, didn't scored again until there were only
11.8 seconds left in the game when Cliff Ronning beat Roussel on
the short side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
