<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, March 6.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EXCLUSIVE-NUKE-SECURITY (Washington) _ Working with nuclear
secrets stolen from a U.S. government laboratory, China has made a
leap in the development of nuclear weapons: the miniaturization of
its bombs, according to administration officials. Until recently,
Beijing was unable to produce small warheads that could be launched
from a single missile at multiple targets and form the backbone of
a modern nuclear force. But by the mid-1990s, China had built and
tested such small bombs, a breakthrough that officials say was
accelerated by the theft of U.S. nuclear secrets from Los Alamos
National Laboratory in New Mexico. By James Risen and Jeff Gerth.
With graphic and photos.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-U.S. (Washington) _ In an unusual display of frustration
between close allies, the Italian prime minister told President
Clinton on Friday that he was shocked at the acquittal of a U.S.
pilot in the deaths of 20 tourists in Italy and said he would not
be satisfied until someone was punished. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Western envoys flew into the Balkans on
Friday to pressure the warring sides in Kosovo to agree to a peace
accord as the province suffered another day of shelling and
casualties. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-REFORMS (Beijing) _ Senior Chinese officials reaffirmed
their determination to squeeze dead wood and red ink out of bloated
state-owned enterprises, vowing to make nearly all of them
competitive and profitable by the end of next year. By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   BERLIN-REICHSTAG (Berlin) _ Sixty-six years after a fire at the
Reichstag summed up Hitler's view of parliamentary democracy, the
historic building will reopen next month as the seat of the German
Parliament. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-KILLINGS (Undated) _ Three Americans who were kidnapped
last week in the Colombian rain forest were found slain Thursday
just across the border in Venezuela, the authorities said Friday.
Initial reports suggested that the three had been abducted by
leftist guerrillas in Colombia. By Andrew Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-CIVILRIGHTS (Washington) _ The federal government
stepped into the heated issue of police treatment of black and
Hispanic people in New York City on Friday when the Civil Rights
Commission voted to conduct a hearing into the city's police
practices. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-SHOOTING (New York) _ In a sign of how deeply the
fatal shooting of Amadou Diallo has pierced New York City, Cardinal
John O'Connor agreed to mediate a meeting in his midtown office
this week between two groups who are sharply divided over what the
tragedy represents: the police union and black business executives.
As they left the meeting on Thursday, the two groups agreed to
sponsor a joint prayer service for racial peace. By Kevin Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   VALDEZ-OILSPILL (Tatitlek, Alaska) _ In environmental terms,
Prince William Sound is still recovering 10 years after one of the
nation's worst environmental disasters, according to a report
issued recently by the joint federal and state council that
monitors the continuing effects of the Exxon Valdez tanker
accident, which dumped at least 10.8 million gallons of North Slope
crude into the sound and blackened 1,500 miles of the magnificent
Gulf of Alaska coastline. By Sam Howe Verhovek. With graphic and
map.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-GAY-ATTACK (Sylacauga, Ala.) _ The closets that gay people
build in small, severe towns like this one are thick and difficult
to penetrate, and Billy Jack Gaither's was locked tighter than
most. Until the day two weeks ago when he was beaten to death and
burned, Gaither, 39, lived with his disabled parents in their white
clapboard house, tending to their needs, cooking dinner and
cleaning up, singing in the choir of his Baptist church. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CANDIDACY (San Francisco) _ Vice President Al Gore has only
one declared rival for the Democratic presidential nomination in
2000, and his party is delighting in its newfound popularity after
impeachment. Why, then, is Gore performing so feebly in the polls?
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-ASSESS (Washington) _ A news analysis: Republicans,
learning from the president, start using early budget proposals as
purely political documents that no one expects to become law
intact. Even so, they face internal pressures because their plan
requires domestic cuts that House moderates who voted for
impeachment may find unacceptable. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The unemployment rate unexpectedly rose
in February, to 4.4 percent from 4.3 percent in January, even as
companies added jobs. Payrolls expanded by 275,000 jobs in
February, about 25,000 jobs more than expected. Workers' average
hourly earnings rose only 0.1 percent during February, to $13.04,
slower than January's increase of 0.4 percent. The data indicated
that inflation remained well under control _ but the report also
showed that the manufacturing industries, which have taken a
beating from the economic problems elsewhere in the world, had not
recovered. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ Japan's central bank pushed overnight
interest rates to the unprecedented level of zero this week in one
of its boldest attempts yet to invigorate the economy _ basically
allowing Japanese banks to borrow for free. The hope is that such a
move will stimulate spending and generate some momentum in the
world's second-largest economy, which is languishing in the worst
recession since World War II. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-INVEST (Plymouth, Mass.) _ Looking for a bargain in nuclear
power plants? It's a buyer's market. By Agis Salpukas. With
graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MERRILL-CEO (New York) _ NEW YORK _ The rising tide of executive
pay did not lift all boats on Wall Street last year, with the top
bosses at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. taking a pay cut to reflect the
firm's profit slump. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Boston) _ BOSTON _ ``I saw things this past
year,'' Monica Lewinsky told Barbara Walters, ``that I didn't know
happened in this country.'' What happened was that an
out-of-control prosecutor and his thuggish deputies threatened and
grossly abused Ms. Lewinsky, her family and her friends. And the
purpose was not to fight crime of any serious kind but to destroy
the president of the United States. By Anthony Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TABOOS (Undated) _ How do democratic, pluralistic societies like
the United States, based on religious and cultural tolerance,
respond to customs and rituals that may be repellent to the
majority? As new groups of immigrants from Asia and Africa are
added to the demographic mix in the United States, Canada and
Europe, balancing cultural variety with mainstream values is
becoming more and more tricky. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   FERGUSON-HISTORY (Windsor, England) _ Niall Ferguson is a Fellow
of Jesus College, Oxford, and author of an appropriately learned
tome, ``Paper and Iron: Hamburg Business and German Politics in the
Era of Inflation, 1897-1927,'' published by Cambridge University
Press. But he is also the most talked-about British historian of
his generation, thanks to frequent newspaper articles and
interviews on television and radio, along with two new books aimed
at nonacademic readers. A profile by Alan Riding. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SEMICOLONS (Undated) _ These days the semicolon, one of the
least loved, least understood punctuation marks, barely ekes out a
living between the period and the comma. It was not always that
way. By Sara Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN (New York) _ NEW YORK _ For the last 10
seasons, Dermon Player has watched March Madness from the outside.
As the boys' basketball coach and athletic director of the
Riverside Church Hawks, Player's real season was in the summer,
when he took some of New York City's best high school players and
barnstormed the country. Three years ago Player coached the
Riverside team that was 67-1 in summer-league competition. The team
included the St. John's players Ron Artest, Erick Barkley and
Reggie Jessie. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-DEVILS-BRUINS (East Rutherford, N.J.) _ With 20 games to
play in the regular season, the Boston Bruins are clinging to the
eighth and last playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. Their grip
hardened a bit Friday night when Boston made three first-period
goals stand up in a 4-1 victory over the Devils at Continental
Arena. By Alex Yannis.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-KNICKS-BUCKS (Milwaukee) _ Once again, the Knicks showed
their inability to win a tough road game when Patrick Ewing _ for
the second time in two games _ missed a 13-foot jumper at the
buzzer. Ewing's miss allowed the Bucks to exhale and exit the
Bradley Center with an 88-87 victory. Ewing led the Knicks with 24
points, while Sprewell added 18. By Selena Roberts.
</P>
