<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 02:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0031 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      03-06 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS FALTER IN CLUTCH, LOSE TO LAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Kobe Bryant performed all the fancy moves.
Shaquille O'Neal punished with power. And in the end, veteran Derek
Harper delivered the clutch baskets to prove Sonics coach Paul
Westphal's point.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers seem to have it all.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sonics are attempting to contend with Gary
Payton, a mystery sidekick from game to game, and strong signs that
one day soon they will piece it all together.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Sonics failed to hold a late lead and fell to the
Lakers 103-100 at the Great Western Forum. It was the Lakers' sixth
straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics dropped their second straight and fourth in their
last six games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're up and down. We're not on the same page, but we'll get
there,'' Payton said. ``At some point, we're going to put it
together. I've played with these guys too long. We've just go to be
patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, the Lakers were the most diligent team in crunch
time.
</P>
<P>
   They withstood Payton scoring 15 of his game-high 34 points in
the fourth quarter. And with the game tied 94-94, the Lakers passed
the ball around the Sonics' trapping defense until they found an
open shot.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it was Harper with the open looks, and he made the
Sonics pay. Harper hit a 3-pointer with 1:26 to put the Lakers
ahead. Then, after Dale Ellis responded for the Sonics, Harper
struck again.
</P>
<P>
   His last 3-pointer with 37.8 seconds left to play put the Lakers
ahead 102-100. After O'Neal split two free throws, the Sonics had a
couple of chances to force overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers were just 1-for-12 from the 3-point line before
Harper's barrage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Sonics had two chances to force overtime. But when
the Lakers forced the ball out of Payton's hands with a double
team, the ball went to Vin Baker, whose 3-pointer fell short with
2.8 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle got the ball back and Hersey Hawkins fired a desperation
3-pointer that bounced off the back of the rim at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just so happened that it was Vinnie,'' Payton said. ``If it
was Dale (Ellis), he might have made the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Payton, the Sonics only got major offensive
contributions from Ellis. The reserve guard scored 20 points off
the bench, which included 5-of-5 3-pointers. Ellis sank two
3-pointers in the game's final minutes to keep the Sonics afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary and Dale were sensational,'' Westphal said. ``We couldn't
find much offense from anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Westphal stayed with his revamped lineup. Hersey Hawkins started
at shooting guard with Billy Owens at small forward. Detlef
Schrempf came off the bench for the second straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal used just eight players until late in the third
quarter, when Aaron Williams made a brief appearance. Otherwise,
only Drew Barry came off the bench to spell Payton and occasionally
allow him to play shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   Payton wasted little time rebounding from Thursday's poor
performance. After making just 3 of 16 shots in a home loss to
Phoenix, Payton connected on four of his first seven shots against
the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   He made both 3-pointers he attempted in the opening period, and
scored inside with Harper and Derek Fisher taking turns guarding
him. Payton finished with 10 points in the first quarter _ one more
than the nine points he totaled in Thursday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary Payton is amazing,'' Lakers coach Kurt Rambis said. ``I
thought he would get tired, but he just got better.''
</P>
<P>
   Things seem to get worse for the other starters.
</P>
<P>
   Baker missed 10 of his first 11 shot attempts, surprisingly
scoring six of his 10 first-half points from the free throw line.
Owens missed the two shots he attempted. Polynice went 2-for-5, and
Hawkins was 1-for-3 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Owens finished the game 1-for-4 from the field. Baker finished
with 16 points but shot 4-of-20 from the floor _ mostly jump shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can make that shot, but he's our primary low-post threat,''
Westphal said of Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Said Baker: ``I had good looks. Maybe I rushed them a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles dominated the glass even though Dennis Rodman was
ineffective with a season-low six rebounds. The Lakers beat the
Sonics on the boards, 46-36. O'Neal just methodically worked the
paint. The Laker center scored a team-high 31 points and grabbed 11
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Another killer for the Sonics was their inability to get back on
defense, which cost them several easy baskets down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't go by our schemes,'' Payton said. `` . . . We got
cherry-picked about six times. That's just not paying attention. We
were up four points with the ball (late in the fourth quarter).
We're not a ballclub that pays attention. When we didn't pay
attention and didn't do what we were supposed to, it cost us the
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
