<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0051 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOURISTS-DANGER-REVIE     03-06 0393
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOURISTS-DANGER-REVIEW-ART-DTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 JOHANNESBURG: was dicey. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the meeting's agenda illustrated the problem: Yemen was
discussed only after the fact; Uganda was not discussed. Foreign
travel dangers often get noticed only after the worst has happened.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, if any group of globetrotters should have been able
to live with some risk, gorilla tourists should have. There are
fewer than 600 mountain gorillas left on earth, and seeing them is
one of the coveted experiences in the growing field of adventure
tourism. The Uganda trek is expensive and hard, but ``everyone who
does it comes back saying they felt privileged,'' Ms. Ockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure tourists are expected to know they are taking
potentially fatal chances. No one imagines he or she will die at
the hands of terrorists, of course. And even factoring in
terrorism, the statistical risks are usually lower than those of
driving to work every day. Until the odds get stacked ridiculously
high against them, adventure tourists will keep signing up.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure tourism is a big industry here in southern Africa,
where even rental houseboats are advertised with swimming cages
that ward off crocodiles.
</P>
<P>
   Drifters Adventours, which sends small groups off with guides to
drive as far as Kenya _ camping out, driving through elephant herds
and going whitewater-rafting and bungee jumping on the way _ has
lost only 2 clients in 17 years. One was gored by a buffalo, one
got blood poisoning after a spider bite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients come from European countries where the worst thing
that happens to you is your trash can gets knocked over,'' said
Andrew Dott, the managing director. ``But they live in little gray
boxes and go to work in tubes. They could pop over to Spain and lie
on the beach, but they want a freak-out holiday that will blow
their minds. We sit them down and tell them: `Be careful. This
isn't Disneyland. You may get malaria. You could get chomped by a
hippo.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he added, ``I couldn't offer this in the States,
where you have all that litigation. But people are strange. You
read about someone drowning in a rafting accident, and the rafting
company's bookings pick up the next week. You read about a game
lodge where someone is chewed on by a lion, and the bookings pick
up. People know it's the real thing, and they want it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
