<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 10:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0054 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CREDITCARD-RE     03-06 0313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CREDITCARD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR CLINTON, ANOTHER CHARGE DISMISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The definition of ``high crimes and misdemeanors'' is subject to
interpretation by the Senate. But a charge card's expiration date
is etched in plastic.
</P>
<P>
   On March 1, President Clinton ducked into Dolly's Books in Park
City, Utah, where he was spending a long weekend with first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and their daughter, Chelsea. He picked out
two thrillers and two volumes about India and laid down his
American Express gold card to pay the $62.66. But the card had
expired the day before and was rejected by the American Express
computer.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Sosnik, the president's ubiquitous senior adviser, slipped
the boss $50 and Clinton sheepishly paid cash for the books.
</P>
<P>
   An American Express spokeswoman, Gail Wasserman, said the
company sends out new cards three to four weeks before a card
expires. The cardholder is required to acknowledge receipt of the
new card by calling a toll-free number. Clinton apparently never
saw the new card.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people like you and me _ as opposed to dignitaries _ open
our own mail,'' Ms. Wasserman said. ``Some others get a lot more
mail and have people who do that for them.''
</P>
<P>
   A presidential spokesman said Clinton's new gold card was
waiting for him when he returned to the White House on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   But Sosnik is still waiting for his 50 bucks. ``He usually pays
back quickly,'' Sosnik said, ``but he hasn't yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
