<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0055 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     03-06 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hello. Must You Leave So Soon? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, the armed religious movement that runs Afghanistan,
has a problem, and his name is Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile and
suspected terrorist with a $5 million bounty on his head.
</P>
<P>
   The Afghans, citing culture and custom, have said publicly that
they cannot expel a guest like bin Laden from their country, as the
United States has demanded. On the other hand, a senior Taliban
official said last week ``his presence is not a benefit to the
people of Afghanistan.'' The Taliban will never get international
recognition or foreign aid as long as they harbor him.
</P>
<P>
   Now it appears that ``there is friction between him and the
Taliban,'' senior U.S. officials say _ so much friction that bin
Laden is being held under Taliban control, moving from village to
village, deprived of his satellite telephone, while the Taliban's
leaders try to figure out how do deal with him without being seen
to cooperate with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ By TIM WEINER
</P>
<P>
   A New Leader Is Elected in Nigeria
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria chose a former military ruler, Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo,
to lead its first civilian government in 16 years, hoping to put an
end to one of the darkest periods in Africa's most populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   The election of Obasanjo, still the only soldier in his country
to have stepped down voluntarily from power, was blemished by
serious fraud and the refusal by his rival, Olu Falae, to concede
defeat. But most international observers said the cheating had not
been significant enough to alter the outcome, given the margin.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of leader the general will be remains unclear. He is
respected internationally for his diplomacy, but remembered at home
for his strong hand during his tenure from 1976 to 1979. And while
he is often seen in the West as someone who has defended democracy,
he also has close ties with corrupt, retired generals who clung to
power under previous military regimes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NORIMITSU ONISHI
</P>
<P>
   A Deal to Save Privately Owned Redwoods
</P>
<P>
   In a $480 million deal officials called as historically
significant as the creation of Yosemite National Park, the federal
and California governments have bought 10,000 acres of ancient
redwoods from Pacific Lumber Co., including the largest privately
owned stand of ancient redwoods in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the decade-long saga leading to the Headwaters forest deal,
which was completed minutes before a March 1 midnight deadline, is
not over.
</P>
<P>
   While plans to provide public access to the primordial rain
forest are already underway, environmentalists say they will
continue to protest on Pacific Lumber property and file lawsuits
against the company and the government.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a 50-year habitat conservation plan that will govern
Pacific Lumber's logging operations. Opponents say the plan is
riddled with loopholes that undermine its purpose of protecting the
endangered spotted owl, coho salmon and marbled murrelet, a sea
bird that nests on the tops of old redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   _ By EVELYN NIEVES
</P>
<P>
   High-Tech Purchase Brings Arrest of 2 Chinese
</P>
<P>
   To hear the Chinese tell it, two men arrested in the United
States in recent weeks were seeking high-tech gyroscopes for a
railroad project.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the U.S. Customs Service, and the men were violating export
control laws that bar the export of the gyros, which can be used to
hone missile guidance systems.
</P>
<P>
   The two suspects, Collin Xu and Yao Yi, are accused of
attempting to buy strategic goods from a a Boston-area military
contractor.
</P>
<P>
   In their quest, officials say, they were referred to a dummy
company established by Customs. Now investigators are trying to
find out where in China the gyroscopes were headed.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID E. SANGER
</P>
<P>
   A State Police Chief Resigns After Comments About Race
</P>
<P>
   Police departments in a wide variety of communities nationwide
have been accused of routinely using racial stereotypes as a tool
with which to target people for suspicion of involvement in crime.
</P>
<P>
   With that controversy as a backdrop, and accusations that the
New Jersey State Police in particular had unfairly singled out
black drivers to be stopped on state highways, Gov. Christie
Whitman swiftly dismissed the head of the State Police after he was
quoted as saying it was naive to think race was not an issue in
drug crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's issue of The Star-Ledger of Newark quoted Col. Carl
Williams as saying, in a wide-ranging interview: ``Two weeks ago,
the president of the United States went to Mexico to talk to the
president of Mexico about drugs. He didn't go to Ireland. He didn't
go to England. Today, with this drug problem, the drug problem is
cocaine or marijuana. It is most likely a minority group that's
involved with that.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the day was out, Whitman had a reply of her own: ``I
have valued Williams' service, and his career record is an
honorable one. However, his comments today are inconsistent with
our efforts to enhance public confidence in the State Police. I
have therefore asked for his immediate resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   Marine Pilot Exonerated In Italian Alps Collision
</P>
<P>
   A jury of eight Marine officers took just over seven hours to
conclude that when an Marine jet in the Italian alps hit the cables
of a gondola system 13 months ago, killing all 20 aboard the
skiers' transport, it was an accident, not a crime.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot's lawyer, Frank Spinner, said that the purpose of the
court martial was to discover truth, and that ``we believe their
finding displays an act of courage and true integrity.'' But
relatives of German victims, who would have been called to the
stand to testify on the impact of the deaths if there had been a
conviction, were bitter, as were people in Italy when they received
the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot understand how it will ever get into my mind that a
system like this calls itself just,'' said Emmi Aurich, through a
translator, after the trial. Her son and daughter-in-law were among
the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Of the pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, she said, ``I hope and I pray
that he will get punished for what he did one day but not as
vengeance, just as reconciliation for our dead people.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Ashby could have brought a prison term of
more than 200 years if he had been convicted. He could still get up
to a year for obstruction of justice, as could his navigator, if
prosecutors have better luck with the next jury and show that the
reason the two took a videotape out of the jet's cockpit after the
accident is that they had something to hide.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
