<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-SEXHARASSMENT-     03-06 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-SEXHARASSMENT-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARITY'S UNWELCOME FALLOUT: SEXUAL HARASSMENT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., S.C., Va., Ohio, N.J.)   By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before the public hugs of congratulation after games escalated
to private embraces in a school room, Amanda Henderson said, she
found it flattering that a veteran high school football coach would
take such an uncommon interest in her, a sophomore basketball
player.
</P>
<P>
   In what became a ritual, Henderson recalled, the coach, Joe
Sutton, refused to let anyone else tape her ankles before her games
for Indian Land High School in South Carolina and, to the vexation
of her female basketball coach, did not want anyone else around
when he taped them. He never missed Henderson's games, chose
Henderson as his student aide and showered her with gifts like the
basketball T-shirts she collected. During softball season, when he
served as an assistant coach, he parked himself at third base, her
position, and supervised her every move. Henderson thought he
wanted her to be a winner. But, she said, he gradually began to
demand a dividend for his devotion.
</P>
<P>
   The hugs and compliments were followed by invitations to spend
time with Sutton away from school. Henderson's parents became
suspicious and eventually mobilized a school board investigation
that resulted in Sutton's resignation in January 1998. Amanda
Henderson's name was added to a growing list of female athletes who
say they have been sexually harassed by their male coaches.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd twist, the rise in reports of harassment by male
coaches is acknowledged to be an unanticipated byproduct of a
landmark victory for women: Title IX, the 1972 law barring sexual
discrimination at schools that receive federal money. As
participation in organized women's athletics has rocketed from
300,000 to 3 million student-athletes in the wake of Title IX,
creating a need for thousands of new coaches, the share of those
coaches who are women has dropped dramatically: at the college
level, the percentage of female head coaches of women's teams has
fallen to 47.4 percent, from 90 percent in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics on sexual harassment in women's sport are minimal.
Researchers in the field say that schools have been reluctant to
pool data for a national survey, partly from a fear of creating a
general atmosphere of guilt. They say that the numbers would be
misleading anyway, because athletes, afraid of losing their spots
on teams, rarely report their coaches. But interviews with about 50
athletes, parents, coaches, administrators and researchers around
the country indicate that reports of harassment are on the rise,
and two current lawsuits against high-profile coaches _ Anson
Dorrance, the women's soccer coach at the University of North
Carolina, and Jesse Dwire, the women's tennis coach at Syracuse
University _ have put the issue in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big problem out there,'' said Don Sabo, a sociology
professor at D'Youville College in Buffalo who has developed
harassment workshops for coaches. Describing the special nature of
the relationship between athlete and coach, Sabo adds, ``It's all
about emotions, about trust, and about the body.'' When
scholarships come into play, it's about money, too.
</P>
<P>
   A lack of certainty over what constitutes an improper
relationship, or improper contact, between coach and athlete, as
well as vague school policies, have made sexual harassment on the
playing fields difficult to police, say experts like Dr. Joel Fish,
director of the Center for Sport Psychology in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole issue of sexual harassment within athletics, of
coaches trying to understand the boundaries of what's right and
wrong, of when to yell and when to pat her on the back, of whether
or not to hug, is still being defined,'' Dr. Fish said. ``There's
more opportunity for female athletes than ever before, but the flip
side is that there's more risk to those athletes because we haven't
developed policies, legislation, and screening processes to keep up
with the social progress made by Title IX.''
</P>
<P>
   Educators attribute the predominance of male coaches in the wake
of Title IX to various factors, including an upswing in male
applicants for jobs that did not previously exist or did not pay as
well as they do now, and a bias by some male athletic directors
against recruiting and hiring female candidates. (Men direct 80
percent of university athletic departments.)
</P>
<P>
   What is not disputed is that the men who now coach a majority of
women's teams are sometimes _ perhaps through no fault of their own
_ insensitive when it comes to dealing with female athletes.
</P>
<P>
   While female coaches are also accused of harassing female
athletes, such reports are far less prevalent, Sabo said. One
reason could simply be the numbers: in women's college track, for
example, just 18 percent of head coaches are women. In women's
swimming, the figure is 33 percent. Swimming, track, volleyball and
gymnastics are, according to Marie Tuite, the University of
Washington's senior associate athletic director, ``hot points''
when it comes to sexual harassment claims.
</P>
<P>
   Fish said, ``When you put a male in a position of power where he
can manipulate something of real meaning to an athlete, such as
playing time or a scholarship, then add in the possibility of a
young girl who may have a crush, you've got an extremely dangerous
mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it never became more physical than hugs, Sutton's
connection to Henderson had destructive consequences for both.
Henderson, accused of exaggerating Sutton's overtures, was
ostracized by her teammates. The school board's investigation of
Sutton turned up complaints that he had committed similar or worse
indiscretions with at least four other students. Sutton was
suspended in September 1997, resigned the following January and now
faces a charge of criminal sexual misconduct, based on allegations
of fondling made by a 1995 Indian Land graduate who came forward
during the Henderson investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried my whole junior year,'' said Henderson, now a freshman
at Gardner-Webb University in Boiling Springs, N.C. ``In my mind,
Coach Sutton went from being a nice guy to a pervert who lusts
after young girls and knows how to manipulate them.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's mother, Alana, said, ``It's like one big playground
out there for these con artists.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The university landscape was jolted last summer by the filing of
two sexual harassment lawsuits against established coaches and the
Division I athletic programs that employ them.
</P>
<P>
   At North Carolina, Dorrance, 47, whose teams have won 15
national titles, is the focus of a suit filed by two players.
Debbie Keller, a leading scorer on the U.S. national team and a
former college player of the year, has accused Dorrance of
inappropriate behavior that included uninvited sexual comments.
Melissa Jennings has accused Dorrance of creating a hostile
environment for her before cutting her from the team.
</P>
<P>
   Dorrance has denied the allegations, and Michael Hooker, the
North Carolina chancellor, has defended the university's handling
of Keller's and Jennings' complaints, saying they were ``thoroughly
investigated and appropriately responded to.'' The case is on hold
while a dispute over venue is settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suit has been a catastrophe for us in women's soccer
because of the bad publicity,'' said April Heinrich, head soccer
coach at the University of Virginia. Still, Heinrich _ who played
for Dorrance at North Carolina and said she ``had no complaints''
with him then _ says the lawsuit could have positive ramifications.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it takes something like this before people's
consciousness gets raised and policies get enforced,'' Heinrich
said. ``I think institutions have a responsibility to educate their
coaches. We all assume a teacher is a professional at 23, but that
isn't really the case, and the line is a little bit gray about what
is and isn't acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither Dorrance nor Dwire is 23. The lawsuit against Dwire,
a 20-year veteran at Syracuse, is scheduled to begin March 29 in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan. The suit alleges that Dwire
massaged, fondled and propositioned two scholarship tennis players,
Kirsten Ericson and Dacia Kornechuk, and that Dwire and the
university retaliated against the players after they pursued a
complaint through the school's grievance system. After a university
panel recommended a two-year ban of Dwire in 1997, finding that he
had violated sexual harassment and discrimination policies, the
punishment was reduced to a three-month suspension.
</P>
<P>
   William Dealy, the lawyer for Ericson and Kornechuk, said
Syracuse officials, aware that the National Collegiate Athletic
Association has no policy on sexual harassment, had ignored
complaints about Dwire's sexual improprieties for years. Kevin
Morrow, a Syracuse spokesman, said neither Dwire nor any of the
dozen university administrators named in the suit would comment.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Varchetto, the lawyer for Keller and Jennings, echoed
Dealy's complaint. ``The whole university mentality is hide your
head in the sand,'' Varchetto said. ``There's probably a higher
duty placed on the coach than a teacher because of the intimacy
athletics generates, but when it comes to appropriate behavior, I
don't think there's a fine line at all: conduct that would not be
approved of in the classroom shouldn't go on in the gym, either.''
</P>
<P>
   As administrators take notice of the rise in harassment
complaints, an awareness is increasing of the necessity of
re-educating coaches, both male and female, about what constitutes
acceptable contact on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to sit down with my coaches and make them aware that
what previously may have been acceptable, like patting a player on
the bottom, is not acceptable now,'' said Christine Grant, athletic
director at the University of Iowa. ``One on ones are risky; closed
doors are risky.'' At Stanford, where men coach 9 of the 15 women's
teams, the two athletic directors have asked university lawyers to
put a no-touching clause into their policy by next fall.
</P>
<P>
   But most athletic directors and coaches alike describe such a
policy, advocated by the Women's Sports Foundation, as unrealistic.
Laurie Priest, athletic director at Mount Holyoke, said: ``The
coach-athlete relationship is based on trust, and to cut off all
physical contact sterilizes the experience. I tell every coach I
hire that I have a no-tolerance policy when it comes to being
sexually involved with an athlete; that said, you've got to
continue to have your antennae up.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is only too obvious when the line has been crossed.
The parents of a young New Jersey tennis player will never forget
the outrage they felt the night in December 1997 when their
daughter told them the real reason she wanted a new coach: her
coach at the time, Stuart Gerechoff of Nutley, N.J., had begun
fondling her when she was 12 and had coerced her into having
intercourse when she was 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told us he'd been touching her and having sexual
intercourse with her,'' recalled the mother of the player, a county
champion who is now a junior in high school. ``She was shaking and
crying, and she said she hadn't wanted anyone to know because she
felt so terrible about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother said she should have seen the signals that Gerechoff
was too involved with her daughter: incessant telephone calls, a
barrage of gifts, an insistence that no one else coach her daughter
when the family went to the shore for summer vacations. ``And he
didn't want me around the courts at all,'' she said. ``When I told
him I didn't like all the hugging that went on after practices, he
jumped down my throat and said there was nothing wrong with it,
that he hugged everybody. He used to tell me how lucky I was that I
didn't have to worry about boys molesting her, that tennis was her
boyfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   Through three years of trysts at Gerechoff's tennis club, the
player never let on that her relationship with her coach had
entered a forbidden dimension.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought it would be the end of her tennis career if she
told anybody,'' the mother said. ``He always told her she'd never
make it without him.''
</P>
<P>
   The player's parents initially welcomed Gerechoff, who ran the
Randolph Hills Tennis Club, into their home and, mistaking his
obsession for genuine interest in her tennis, gave him free rein.
After their daughter told them what was happening, they notified
the police immediately, and Gerechoff was arrested three days
later. He pleaded guilty to aggravated sexual assault in March 1998
and was sentenced last summer to eight years at the Adult
Diagnostic and Treatment Center in Avenel, N.J., a facility for sex
offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really kind of lost it,'' said John McDonald, Gerechoff's
lawyer. ``He was smitten, but the fact that he loved her is no
defense to statutory rape.''
</P>
<P>
   At his sentencing, the 44-year-old Gerechoff apologized to his
wife and family, then offered an eerie apology to the player: he
said he loved her and wanted to hug her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a child loses her innocence this way, nothing can ever be
the same as it was,'' the player's mother said. ``These men are
monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that she is away at Division II Gardner-Webb, where she
earned a basketball scholarship and plays for a male coach, Amanda
Henderson remains vulnerable to disturbing memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I see a male coach, I'm cautious; I'm wondering if
he's in it for the same reason Coach Sutton was, if he's another
manipulator,'' she said. ``I know my coach isn't like Coach Sutton,
but when I look around, I see plenty of them out there. I know what
they're up to; I know how easy it is to fall for it. In the
beginning, you just think he's being nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said she saw no reason to be suspicious of Sutton at
first, and she dismissed it when several boys from his football
team warned her about him. She said she began to heed the warnings
the summer before her junior year, when Sutton began calling her
when he knew she was home alone. ``I was starting to be afraid of
him by then,'' she said. ``Everybody hugged after games, but it was
happening with him all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, her parents had talked to the school principal and
requested that Sutton stay away from their daughter. When Sutton's
presence on the softball coaching staff that spring caused
Henderson so much discomfort that she quit in the middle of a
championship season, her parents went to the county's
superintendent of Schools. After that failed to produce action,
they went to the state board of education.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shouldn't back down just because the door slams in
their face at the local level,'' said Joe Henderson, Amanda's
father.
</P>
<P>
   With a lawyer's help and guidance from Sesame, a national
victim-assistance group, the Hendersons got an investigation.
Sutton was suspended, and in a closed-door session with the school
board in January 1998 his resignation was accepted with the proviso
that he not seek teaching or coaching positions in South Carolina
that put him in contact with girls under the age of 18. Those
conditions became public last fall when Sutton ran unsuccessfully
for a seat on the same school board that suspended him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found a pattern of inappropriate behavior that warranted
his suspension,'' said John Taylor, the Lancaster County school
superintendent. ``In some sense, I think the system worked here.
It's hard to investigate these complaints because it's tough for
the kids to come forward, but I don't see how we can beef up our
harassment policy without putting our schools into some sort of
terror state.''
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Henderson felt that she was living in such a state after
she made her accusations. ``Somebody sent anonymous letters to the
colleges that were recruiting me, warning them I was a
troublemaker,'' Henderson said. This year her parents have
transferred her younger brother to a different high school; they
say it is because of the continuing backlash from his sister's
case. Henderson says she is reluctant go home for visits.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton is free on bail while awaiting trial on the criminal
sexual misconduct charge that grew out of the Henderson
investigation. Neither he nor his lawyer, W. Allan Nickles,
returned repeated telephone calls requesting comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0065 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-SEXHARASSMENT-     03-06 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-SEX </SLUG>
 HARASSMENT-4THTAKE-NYT 
UNDATED: requesting comment.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cases of Amanda Henderson and of the New Jersey teen-ager
molested by her coach have, after significant pain and struggle,
reached some form of resolution. But other disputes can dissolve
into ``he said/she said'' battles that leave both sides feeling
damaged and frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   The court documents recounting the sexual harassment complaint
of Denise Klemencic, a former distance runner at Ohio State
University, against Ed Crawford, an assistant track coach, read
like scenes from ``Rashomon.'' The way Klemencic sees it, the
actions of Crawford and Ohio State have wrecked her life. ``My
whole athletic career backfired because I wouldn't sleep with my
coach,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, now head coach of women's track at the University of
New Mexico, says that Klemencic's misinterpretation of a friendly
dinner invitation has blighted his reputation and exacted a mental
toll during five years of litigation. ``It's a nightmare when
somebody accuses you of this, because you're almost automatically
considered guilty,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Klemencic, now 29, says that after she rejected an attempt by
Crawford to date her in June 1992, he reneged on an agreement to
let her stay on as a volunteer coach at Ohio State and train for
the Olympic trials after her college eligibility expired. Ohio
State contends that she was not of Olympic caliber, and Elizabeth
Stanton, a lawyer who represented the university, said the school
offered to let Klemencic train with the team in 1992 but was turned
down. According to Klemencic, Crawford had ``poisoned the team''
against her.
</P>
<P>
   After Klemencic turned down a settlement offer from Ohio State
in December 1997, she sued Crawford in U.S. District Court in
Columbus, Ohio, last summer and lost. Her lawyer, Seymour Brown,
has requested a new trial. Klemencic also has an appeal pending in
the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit in Cincinnati,
protesting a court decision that excused Ohio State from liability.
Ohio State argued that its response to Klemencic's complaints was
sufficient. It issued a written reprimand stating that Crawford had
inappropriately pursued a personal relationship with her and a
warning against his continuing to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted the coach fired,'' Stanton said, ``but it was the
university's position that this was not the type of activity that
would justify removing someone from their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Justus, who directs the NCAA's education department, has
acknowledged that the association's lack of a policy on sexual
harassment of athletes needs to be addressed. ``I've heard some of
the horror stories out there,'' she said. ``It's astonishing what
people get by with. The policy was in the plan to look at down the
road, but maybe we need to look at it sooner. For now, the final
recourse for athletes is litigation: the issue of harassment is so
complex, so laden with people's own biases and blind spots, that
the law and liability may be the only way to catch their
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Klemencic feels that every system of redress has failed her, and
she said she was $22,000 poorer for her efforts so far. ``But I
don't regret turning the settlement down,'' she said. ``That would
have been letting the school off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, 43, said that the possibility that the case could be
retried kept him on tenterhooks. He insisted his intentions toward
Klemencic were never romantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely hard to defend yourself against something that
didn't happen,'' he said. ``And it's a scenario that since then
scares the hell out of me whenever I'm alone with an athlete,
because it seems like half our job, as a coach, is being a
psychologist. Kids can be vindictive: tell a kid you're pulling
their scholarship and they're liable to turn around and accuse you
of anything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As draining as it can be, litigation may prove to be the most
effective tool in redefining the boundaries of proper behavior on
the playing field, just as it has been in the workplace. ``Let's
face it: folks don't want to get sued,'' said Dr. Fish of the
Center for Sport Psychology.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Carpenter and Vivian Acosta of Brooklyn College have
completed a study that documents the decline of female coaches and
administrators in college sports in the wake of Title IX. As sexual
harassment disputes threaten to become a legacy of the expansion of
women's sports, the researchers have their own suggestion for
curtailing them.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you never set the line as an institution, it becomes
impossible to police it,'' Carpenter said. ``Bite the bullet, get a
policy that says amorous relations with students are verboten and
if you cross the line, you're out. The rule needs to be in writing
at the bottom of every coach's contract. There's no such thing as
consensual anything when one person has that much control over
another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
