<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Beijing bookends.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration came to power far from convinced that
Bosnia was a central interest of the United States, then decided
that the Balkans (along with Somalia and Haiti) must be, as the
horror of it all unfolded on television. But the reality is that
while Americans are perfectly happy to see the secretary of state
jetting around the world to strike peace agreements, their
willingness to put lives at risk for such causes is limited.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, though, both the public and Congress have come to
recognize a second type of national interest: averting economic
implosions that could affect U.S. prosperity. Congress screamed
when the administration bailed out Mexico, a move that most now
believe avoided a long, ugly recession on America's border. By the
time the Asian crisis hit, the objections began to dissipate, and
there was barely a peep when the Treasury helped organize the
rescues of South Korea and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But the administration's luck ran out when it came to Russia.
Ever since the $17 billion IMF package failed last summer, both the
Russian economy and Moscow's relationship with Washington have been
in a downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes China, the most complex case. No one doubts that
Chinese are enjoying greater economic freedom. Or that China is
cracking down on political organizers, reverting to elements of a
state-run economy and adding to the missiles facing Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   So Washington has reverted to a mixed message, encouraging moves
to get China into the World Trade Organization _ part of that web
of economic engagement _ while talking about building a regional
missile defense that drives the Chinese up the wall. The Chinese
say they recognize America's real strategy and it is both old and
familiar: containment. They may be wrong, but at least it's a
coherent theory.
</P>
