<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PHXOPEN-CHANGES-A     03-06 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHXOPEN-CHANGES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSING OFF THE OPEN  
 SAFETY CONCERNS MAY SPUR ALCOHOL, CROWD CAPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -Sweeping changes to cut crowds at the Phoenix Open,
perhaps by limiting daily tickets or relying on expensive weekly
badges, are under consideration after a security incident this year
involving PGA Tour star Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Measures being discussed could significantly reduce attendance,
limit alcohol consumption and tone down the tournament's raucous
party atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Thunderbirds, who organize the tournament, and the
PGA Tour will work out specific solutions in the next three months.
</P>
<P>
   One idea, kicked back indirectly to the Thunderbirds from the
PGA, would raise the minimum cost of admission to the tournament to
$150 or more for the week.
</P>
<P>
   Some think such a plan would slash the total crowds from this
year's 422,650 to around 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Matteucci, who recently was promoted to tournament
chairman for next year's Phoenix Open, said new policies will be in
effect by June 1. He said the proposed changes were prompted by the
nationally reported incident involving the gun-carrying fan, Brian
K. Murphy, during the final round of the tournament on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Murphy thing really caught people's attention,'' Matteucci
said of the scuffle that broke out between Murphy, a north Phoenix
resident, and Scottsdale police Officer Robert Rucker. Murphy, who
was found to have a pistol in his fanny pack, was arrested on
suspicion of felony assault on a police officer and disorderly
conduct. The case remains under investigation by the Maricopa
County Attorney's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Still, changes will not be popular with all tour pros, or with
rowdy fans who routinely pack the 16th hole of the course.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Magee of Paradise Valley, the runner-up in last week's
prestigious World Golf Championship Match Play tournament, said he
had heard the rumblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I heard (the PGA Tour) said to cool it, to get things
under control,'' Magee said. ``But I think the tour should leave
the Phoenix Open alone. Yeah, there's nothing like it in golf, but
what's wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Phoenix Open is a very unique event, and the tour wants to
make it just like every other tournament. If it's about the gun
deal, well, that's a really random thing. Besides, that guy wasn't
going to use a gun. And if it's about the 16th hole, you just get
over it. You suck it up for that one shot and then go on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it, maybe (the Phoenix Open) is the wave of
the future. Maybe our crowds in Phoenix are just getting the
players ready for the next generation of golf fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Other local pros, such as Billy Mayfair and Tom Purtzer, have
said frequently that they thought the tournament needed to tone
down its act. They could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After this year's incident, tournament organizers reacted by
banning guns at the TPC of Scottsdale, which is on federal
property. A special task force made up of Thunderbirds also has
been formed to address the issues of gallery control and security
in general, as well as traffic and parking concerns, Matteucci
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wrote to (PGA Tour Commissioner) Tim Finchem and proposed
the task force to deal with our growing crowd challenges,''
Matteucci said. ``We're looking at a whole host of things that
would make for a more balanced environment for the players and the
fans.''
</P>
<P>
   At this year's Open, the Thunderbirds eliminated beer sales
around the infamous 16th tee, where partygoers, mostly of college
age, tend to congregate. But beer was brought in from other
concession stands, and the 16th-hole gang still was able to scream,
sometimes with slurred speech, ``Get in the hole!'' after every tee
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci said that the Thunderbirds ``are definitely looking at
alcohol consumption issues.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the crowd behavior issues and alcohol are
intertwined,'' he said. ``It's just a little early to address any
solutions specifically, like when or where it's going to be served.
</P>
<P>
   Although Matteucci said the idea for the task force originated
with the Thunderbirds, he said he had heard reports out of Miami on
Tuesday that the PGA Tour Policy Board was told by Finchem's office
to ``do something about Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that, yeah,'' Matteucci said. ``But we don't think
there's any Band-Aid for this. That's why we formed the task force
to study a lot of factors.''
</P>
<P>
   The liaison from Finchem's office told the PGA Tour Policy board
at its meeting in Miami that the only way to control the Phoenix
Open was ``to reduce the size of the crowds significantly, like
they did in Dallas (at the Byron Nelson GTE Classic),'' according
to a source within the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be done by limiting daily tickets, or eliminating
them entirely with a weekly badge that would cost, say, $150, or
twice as much as a daily ticket ($20)'' the source told ``The
Arizona Republic'' on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci said that, essentially, that was the same rumor he'd
heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that breaking attendance records is no longer a
top priority,'' Matteucci said. ``I think we've reached _ even
exceeded _ our capacity. And with more and more development going
on out there around the TPC (of Scottsdale), the tournament is
really getting squeezed to the point where we need some new
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Open annually tops the PGA Tour in attendance,
attracting 400,000 to 500,000 for the week. The Greater Hartford
Open and Byron Nelson rank second and third among other tour
events, although the PGA Tour does not keep track of attendance
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Butler, the vice president of business affairs for the PGA
Tour, said, ``The Phoenix Open is certainly a unique tournament
because of its large attendance.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the size of those crowds is a detriment or
not. That's why we're only in the early stages of studying possible
changes,'' said Butler, who plans to meet with four members of the
Thunderbirds _ Matteucci, Tim Grant, Ray Artigue and Peter Callihan
_ during the week of March 22-28 at the PLAYERS Championship in
Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we are deferring everything to the
Thunderbirds, who are going to give us their operational review of
the tournament, then we'll go from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily the size of the crowd that is the
problem, although it's a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler cited the Byron Nelson as a tournament that effectively
handled large crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Salesmanship Club of Dallas, which is the host
organization for the Nelson like the Thunderbirds are for the
Phoenix Open, decided to cap the number of tickets sold before they
ran into any real problems,'' Butler said. ``Plus, the laws
instituted by the Texas Alcohol and Beverage Commission also cause
greater restraint than you have (in Arizona). At the Nelson, you
can only consume beer in certain, gardenlike areas. You can't just
walk around the tournament with a beer in your hand like (in
Phoenix).''
</P>
<P>
   Matteucci said the Thunderbirds hope to walk a fine line between
keeping the Phoenix Open's ``unique fabric'' and addressing and
effectively dealing with the security concerns of the tour and its
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, we create a city out there, and with it come all
the inherent issues and problems you have with a real city,'' he
said. ``At the same time, the tournament brings so many good things
to the community, such as $3 million in charitable contributions.''
</P>
<P>
   But like it or not, there's a new Phoenix Open on the way in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there definitely will be some changes for next year's
tournament, because we want the players to know we're interested in
their safety,'' Matteucci said. ``But, hopefully, they won't be so
dramatic as to take away from the tournament's uniqueness.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
