<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0089 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGIOUS-RIGHT-ART-2     03-06 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGIOUS-RIGHT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS RIGHT UNABLE TO UNITE FOR RACE IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Mich., S.C., Fla., Pa., N.H.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR and RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years after the Rev. Jerry Falwell's Moral Majority Inc.
propelled religious conservatives into a heavyweight force in U.S.
politics, the movement is struggling without a clear strategy, and
for the first time a debate has erupted among leading figures over
whether they should radically scale back their political efforts.
</P>
<P>
   As the 2000 presidential campaign gets under way, religious
conservative groups are fractured and unable to coalesce around a
single candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, some influential leaders are saying that the best
way to change America is not through politics but by building a
conservative base through the schooling of children at home or by
working to change the hearts and minds of people through Christian
preaching and the example of biblically inspired good works.
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to a sense of exasperation, prominent religious
conservatives complain, is that they are not getting enough
attention from Republican leaders on Capitol Hill. That is because
many in the party, trying to erase the low popularity ratings for
Republicans in the wake of President Clinton's impeachment, are
seeking to shift the agenda from moral issues to practical ones
like education and tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton's acquittal in the impeachment trial last month,
Paul Weyrich, president of the Free Congress Foundation, a
conservative organization in Washington, wrote a widely circulated
letter declaring that attempts to restore morality ``through the
political process have failed'' and suggesting that conservatives
build up ``parallel institutions,'' like home schools and religious
radio.
</P>
<P>
   While no one argues that religious conservatives should stop
voting or caring about issues, Weyrich is by no means the only
religious conservative to question what is gained from pouring time
and money into highly organized political efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The cover article in the Feb. 27 issue of the conservative
magazine World was devoted to three Republican senators who had
left politics to focus on business or religion. One, Dan Coates of
Indiana, was quoted as saying, ``The political process is very
limited in what it can do for our spiritual and moral problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar idea forms a theme of ``Blinded by Might,'' a book by
two former Moral Majority officials, the syndicated columnist Cal
Thomas and the Rev. Ed Dobson, a pastor in Grand Rapids, Mich., to
be published later this month by Zondervan Publishing House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who are looking in whole or in part to government to
correct the problems of America are looking in the wrong place,''
Thomas said in an interview. Instead, he said, Christians should
work to change the culture by following Jesus' commands to love
their enemies, feed the hungry, clothe the naked and visit the
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a call to retreat or surrender,'' he added. ``It
is a call for re-enlistment in a better army that provides better
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   His co-author, Ed Dobson, a native of Northern Ireland, said
that ``moral transformation will come one person at a time, one
family at a time, one street at a time, one community at a time.''
He added, ``It will not come from the government.''
</P>
<P>
   But such talk has led some religious conservatives to see a
white flag. Speaking before about 1,700 people at a Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., conference on Feb. 26, Gary Bauer, president of
the Family Research Council, declared, ``Words like `I give up'
should not be in our vocabulary.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who is considering a bid for the Republican presidential
nomination, was followed to the podium by the Rev. James Kennedy,
whose Coral Ridge Ministries sponsored the gathering. Kennedy
paraphrased some of Churchill's wartime remarks, saying, ``Never
give up, never give up, never give up!''
</P>
<P>
   Power Diluted by Divisions
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, in the aftermath of Clinton's acquittal, some
religious conservatives have sounded discouraged. James Dobson,
president of Focus on the Family, told a magazine interviewer
recently that although he believed that social conservatives
represented a slight majority of the American public, they were
less politically active than liberals and often did not vote.
</P>
<P>
   For years many religious conservative leaders fashioned
themselves as power brokers in the Republican presidential
primaries, in which their followers were usually among the most
politically active, with influence far beyond their numbers.
</P>
<P>
   John Green, a political scientist who is director of the Ray C.
Bliss Institute of Applied Politics at the University of Akron,
said he did not believe that voting by religious conservatives
declined last year from the elections in 1994 and 1996. ``I expect
them to be fully energized next year,'' Green added.
</P>
<P>
   But as the 2000 campaigns gear up, religious conservatives are
balkanized among as many as a half-dozen candidates. The contender
who was emerging as a favorite, Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri,
decided recently not to make the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ashcroft's departure and the lack of a consensus around a
single candidate, it's going to be very hard to put Humpty Dumpty
back together,'' said Ralph Reed, the political strategist and
former executive director of the Christian Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of religious conservative groups to deliver a block
of voters has probably long been overstated. But the perception
that they are unable to rally behind a single candidate could lead
candidates to be even less eager to romance the groups.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Robertson, the religious broadcaster who founded the
Christian Coalition and who had supported Ashcroft, told reporters
in a recent interview, ``He would have been the favorite of some of
the people of the Christian Coalition.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whom he supported now, Robertson did not express
enthusiasm for any prospect. Robertson, in fact, was perhaps the
last presidential candidate who truly energized religious
conservatives when he ran for president in 1988. His huge number of
devoted loyalists, particularly in Iowa, were called ``the
invisible army.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, the frustration of overly high hopes has
contributed to a sense of disillusionment for some. ``There were
expectations that the religious right, monolithically thinking, was
expecting certain results from a Republican-controlled Congress and
it felt like Congress didn't deliver,'' said former Gov. David
Beasley of South Carolina, who played an important role in uniting
religious conservatives in his state behind Bob Dole in the 1996
presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many in the Christian community expect that through the
political arena we can solve America's problems,'' Beasley said,
``and I do not agree with that. But I think the Christian community
has an obligation to be involved in the political process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some Even Question If They Have Power
</P>
<P>
   While many religious conservatives would agree with that, some
are not very optimistic about their political influence.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Paige Patterson, president of the Southern Baptist
Convention, said that ``there is a lot of cynicism in evangelical
circles and in Baptist circles'' about politicians not fulfilling
their promises to support social conservative causes. ``Apparently,
once you go to work inside the Beltway, your radar collapses,''
Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   But others struck an optimistic note. Richard Land, president of
the Southern Baptist Convention's Ethics and Religious Liberty
Commission, said he believed that there would be ``a profound
discussion in the year 2000 about the kind of society we're going
to have,'' a debate that would work to the advantage of
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Falwell predicted in a recent interview that Vice President Al
Gore, because of his unstinting defense of Clinton, would not be
elected next year. ``I think you'll find activism at an all-time
high in the year 2000 among religious conservatives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, the senior pastor of Coral Ridge Presbyterian Church in
Fort Lauderdale, said that a century-long rise in the number of
conversions to Christianity worldwide should inspire religious
conservatives. ``If you're running a marathon, and you get to
within 20 yards of the finish line, you don't quit while you're
ahead,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy noted that evangelical Protestants largely separated
themselves from American culture earlier this century. In the
1920s, after enduring ridicule in the Scopes trial for their
support of efforts to block the teaching of evolution,
fundamentalists withdrew from attempts to influence society.
</P>
<P>
   Forsaking Image of Irrelevancy
</P>
<P>
   But since the late 1970s, religious conservatives have said
separatism is a thing of the past, particularly when it comes to
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Democracy is hard work,'' said Randy Tate, executive director
of the Christian Coalition. ``To go back to the days when we were
on the irrelevant sidelines is not a formula to change the
culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Random interviews among those at the Fort Lauderdale conference
indicated that many shared Tate's views. Barbara Harris, a pastor's
wife from Orlando, Fla., paraphrased a statement attributed to the
political philosopher Edmund Burke by saying, ``Evil triumphs when
good men do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Robinson, 61, a school administrator from Beaver Falls,
Pa., said, ``Rather than pulling back, Christians ought to go full
speed ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   A major challenge for religious conservatives in politics,
however, is the numbers they can field in major presidential
primary states. While the Christian Coalition has never been as
influential in New Hampshire as in Iowa, Steve Duprey, the
Republican state chairman in New Hampshire, was almost dismissive
of the group. ``They're one of 10 or 15 constituent groups,'' he
said. ``They're not a dominant block.''
</P>
<P>
   And nationally, voters in that block appear more fractured than
ever. Richard Bond, a former chairman of the Republican National
Committee, said: ``It's going to be very difficult for Christian
conservatives, much less the conservative wing of the party, to
reach critical mass. There's just no one perfect candidate for them
out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
