<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, March 7, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scheduled for the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   TOURISTS-DANGER-REVIEW (Johannesburg) _ The killing of tourists
by rebels in Uganda raises the questions of why weren't the
tourists warned that they were in a potentially dangerous region,
and were they crazy to be there in the first place? But the reality
is simple, and particularly relevant at a time of rising and
increasingly exotic global travel: Predicting danger for tourists
is a crap shoot, tour operators and foreign service officials say.
By Donald G. McNeil Jr. (`i' category). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-CRIME-REVIEW (Undated) _ The U.S. crime rate is
plunging, but its prison population is exploding. No matter how
much crime drops, the U.S. will still have to add the equivalent of
one new jail or prison every week for perhaps another decade,
federal officials say. Some even believe the prison boom could be
permanent, at least for another generation. A big the reason is
that so many of the new inmates are drug offenders. By Timothy
Egan. (`a' category). WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-POWER-REVIEW (Undated) _ Twenty years after the meltdown
at Three Mile Island, the nuclear industry has succeeded in ways
that were hard to imagine as Pennsylvania cowered in fear in March
1979 and plants around the country subsequently lost their luster
and scores of projects to build reactors were abandoned. The
industry is doing better now, ironically, because it is marching
ever faster toward extinction. By Matthew L. Wald. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   PBS-TV-REVIEW (Undated) _ The recent flap over proposed format
changes in `Washington Week in Review' revived a nagging question:
What is the mission of public television these days, and who needs
it? The profusion of cable stations, some of which are doing the
sort of programming that Public Broadcasting could once call its
own, has sent the so-called noncommercial broadcasters into
something of an identity crisis. By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-TIME-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Internet encompasses all
the world's time zones, making for a considerable amount of
incompatibility in transactions and other online activities. A
watch-manufacturing company, Swatch, is trying to introduce a
standard Internet time system. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   COUNSEL-TEXT-REVIEW (Washington) _ Last week the Clinton
administration completed a remarkable turnaround in its thinking
about the independent counsel law, which President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno persuaded Congress to renew nearly five
years ago. Excerpts from congressional testimony and other
statements illustrate the history of flipflops on the statute.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-NEWSPAPERS-TEXT-REVIEW (Toronto) _ It's not easy being in
the news business in Canada. You stare at juicy American stories
nearly every day while your own pages fill with curling scores and
wheat quotas. Oh, for a big, page one blockbuster! In February, a
Canadian newspaper thought it had a real scoop when it reported:
`U.S. believes North Korea would target Montreal for a nuclear
strike.' Excerpts on how the story played out.
</P>
<P>
   NONSTORIES-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ With the end of the century
approaching, Americans are making lists. Lots of lists. The Top 100
Films. The Top 100 Books. Now, a list of the top 100 most
unimportant news events of the century.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CREDITCARD-REVIEW (Undated) _ For Clinton, another
charge dismissed. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FOREIGNPOLICY-REVIEW (Washington) _ For six years, the
Clinton administration and its critics have flailed about for some
grand Unified Field Theory of Foreign Relations _ something as neat
as the Cold War concept of containment to define priorities. Recent
U.S. actions on Kosovo and China have something odd in common: they
have come to mark the two extremes of the the administration's
struggle to bring coherence to U.S. foreign policy at a time that
often seems incoherent itself. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-CHINA-REVIEW (Tokyo) _ Japan seemed resentful and envious
as it watched China's economy boom last year. Japan was suffering
its worst slowdown in more than half a century, and China was the
only Asian country to survive the regional economic crisis
enhanced. But now that China's economy is showing signs of frailty,
Japanese executives and economists are viewing that situation with
apprehension. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-WARCRIMES-REVIEW (Undated) _ While German scientists
conducted hideous experiments on concentration camp prisoners,
their lesser-known Japanese counterparts were waging full-scale
biological warfare and subjecting human beings to ghastly
experiments of their own _ on a far greater scale than the Germans.
Taking decades to emerge, the Japanese record of atrocities is
still producing revelations. The delay illustrates striking
differences in the willingness of the two former Axis allies to
come to terms with their past. It has also thrown a harsh light on
Cold War rivalries. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-U.S.-REVIEW (Undated) _ When a Guatemalan truth
commission implicated the U.S. in the creation of a killing machine
that ravaged Mayan villages in the 1980s, it raised troubling
questions. How could a country that calls itself a beacon of
democracy link its military and intelligence agencies so intimately
to Guatemala's darkest reactionary forces? Some answers, or at
least clues, can be found in scores of declassified documents the
Clinton administration released to the National Security Archive.
By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
