<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Sunday, March 7. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (212) 556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOP: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Lead story: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RELIGIOUS-RIGHT (Undated) _ Twenty years after the Rev. Jerry
Falwell's Moral Majority Inc. propelled religious conservatives
into a heavyweight force in American politics, the movement is
struggling without a clear political strategy and, for the first
time, a debate has even erupted among leading figures over whether
they should radically scale back their political efforts. By
Richard L. Berke and Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Top center: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-FUTURE (New York) _ In recent weeks, leaders of both the
New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq, the nation's over-the-counter
market, have confirmed that they are considering a wide range of
new alliances that they hope will transform their institutions into
the stock markets of the future. Their initiatives are driven by a
frenzied competition for America's stock-trading business. While it
is too soon to predict which design will triumph, individual
Americans have a big stake in the outcome. If the transformation
works as its advocates hope, it could provide investors, big and
small, with better service at lower prices. But if it goes awry, it
could damage a national treasure: a stock market whose strength and
fairness have attracted foreign capital, fostered the growth of new
businesses, and provided investment opportunities for an
unprecedented number of people. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 2 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ALGERIA-UNREST (Algiers) _ The savage war between Algeria's
military rulers and Islamic guerrilla groups has taken at least
80,000 lives since it began in 1992. The vicious civil strife
erupted after the shadowy group of generals who hold real power in
this nation of 28 million people canceled a second round of
elections that were on the verge of securing a parliamentary
majority for a militant Islamic party. But now, to the surprise of
many Algerians, the situation has eased. A presidential election,
scheduled for April 15, has come alive, with 11 candidates
representing an array of political opinions, and a promise from the
army not to rig the ballot, as it has in the past. By John F.
Burns.
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   1-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `i' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LATEX-ALLERGY (New York) _ Over 10 percent of the country's
health-care workers suffer from latex allergy, an illness that was
almost unheard of just a decade ago. And experts said that the
numbers are probably higher _ as high as 17 percent _ among those
who work almost exclusively in hospitals and with patients' fluids,
such as nurses in emergency and operating rooms, since allergies to
latex get much worse from heavy exposure to the material over time.
The illness affects roughly three percent of the general population
and since the late 1980s, nearly 30 people have died from
latex-related illnesses, according to Food and Drug Administration
figures. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOTTOM: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-SEXHARASSMENT (Undated) _ In an odd twist, the rise in
reports of harassment by male coaches is acknowledged to be an
unanticipated byproduct of a landmark victory for women: Title IX,
the 1972 law barring sexual discrimination at schools that receive
federal money. As participation in organized women's athletics has
greatly increased, creating a need for thousands of new coaches,
the share of those coaches who are women has dropped: at the
college level, the percentage of female head coaches of women's
teams has fallen to 47.4 percent, from 90 percent in 1972.
Statistics on sexual harassment in women's sport are minimal.
Researchers in the field say that schools have been reluctant to
pool data for a national survey. And they add that the numbers
would be misleading anyway, because athletes, afraid of losing
their spots on teams, rarely report their coaches. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   2-column photo with story.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `s' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-CLASSICS (South Bend, Ind.) _ It may seem quaint, if
not useless, to bring philosophical literature to the homeless, an
idea conceived in some pristine ivory tower. But that is not how
some students view it. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved; `a' category.)
</P>
<P>
   CENTAM-U.S. (San Salvador) _ When President Clinton visits
Central America, he will witness a region forged by one tragedy or
another over the last several decades, and more often than not,
forgotten in its intervals of renewal. The president is to open a
four-day visit to El Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras and Guatemala on
Monday, the day after Salvadorans vote on a new president and
further cement a remarkable democratic transformation after 12
years of civil war that left more than 70,000 people dead. By
Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 2 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RDP (London) _ The Clinton administration's hope of
moving the Kosovo peace plan much closer to completion was
frustrated again on Saturday when its special emissary to the
ethnic Albanians, former Sen. Bob Dole, told Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright here that he had failed to clinch a deal with
the separatists. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 2 p.m. ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-REASSESS (Charlottesville, Va.) _ In a room just
across the road from Monticello, the hilltop mansion of Thomas
Jefferson, a group of scholars struggled this weekend to understand
the character of the third president now that it has taken on a
dimension that historians almost unanimously denied for two
centuries. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 2 p.m. ET in `a' news file.)
