<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RDP-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE IS UNSURE IF REBELS WILL SIGN KOSOVO PEACE ACCORD
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds., see also KOSOVO-REBELS)  
(fb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The Clinton administration's hope of moving the Kosovo
peace plan much closer to completion was frustrated again Saturday
when its special emissary to the ethnic Albanians, former Sen. Bob
Dole, told Secretary of State Madeleine Albright here that he had
failed to clinch a deal with the separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, speaking after consulting with Albright, who arrived here
after a trip to Asia, was relatively upbeat, saying that he had
been promised an agreement by the ethnic Albanians by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the outlook for agreement from what the administration had
viewed as the most pliant side in the Kosovo conflict remained
uncertain. A key ethnic Albanian guerrilla leader, Hashim Thaci,
skipped the Albanians' meeting with Dole in Skopje, Macedonia, on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most embarrassing, Thaci, a 29-year-old commander of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, could not be found, even after what an
administration official called a scouting party was sent to look
for him in Tirana, Albania, where he was believed to be. Instead,
Dole said he had two telephone conversations with another senior
guerrilla leader, Jakup Krasniqi. ``I told them every day they
waited was a respite for Slobodan Milosevic, who caused the problem
in the first place,'' Dole said in reference to the Yugoslav leader
whose forces have been fighting the ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Peace talks on Kosovo are due to resume in Paris on March 15. By
then, the administration would like to have the ethnic Albanians
signed on to a peace deal and have offered Milosevic a
take-it-or-leave-it proposition.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by press criticism in the United States and Europe of
Albright's handling of the Kosovo peace effort, her closest aide,
James P. Rubin, volunteered a series of statements defending
Albright to reporters traveling with her from Indonesia to London.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin acknowledged that the administration had ``misjudged'' how
easy it would be to win the approval of the ethnic Albanians at
Rambouillet, France, where peace talks were suspended without an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He insisted that Albright was right to push ahead despite what
he called the ``hard work'' and plethora of players. ``The fact
that the secretary of state is not able to fully obtain an
agreement in a relatively short number of days for the people
who've been fighting _ violently for many months and politically
for many years _ shouldn't be considered a mistake by the United
States,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the criticisms in the European press were charges that
Albright, by threatening airstrikes against Milosevic without
following through, had diluted the credibility of NATO. Some
administration officials have essentially agreed, acknowledging
that the threat of airstrikes against Milosevic as a way of getting
him to sign the peace deal had considerably weakened in the past
week.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The administration was likely to send an American envoy,
probably Richard Holbrooke, to see Milosevic in the coming week,
officials said. The timing, and defined purpose, of such a trip
remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
   In the usual tangled pattern of joint American-European
diplomacy toward Milosevic, the European nations of the Contact
Group _ Britain, France, Italy and Germany _ were unhappy about the
prospect of Holbrooke visiting Milosevic, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Ambassador Wolfgang Petritsch of Austria, one of
three negotiators at the Kosovo peace talks, said the Europeans
thought that Holbrooke ``could complicate things if he started open
negotiations'' with Milosevic on the peace plan. Petritsch worked
for months with the American envoy Christopher Hill to draft the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans, the spokesman said, would prefer that Holbrooke
concentrate on the Yugoslav leader's violations of the agreement of
last October. Holbrooke personally negotiated that agreement, which
called for a substantial reduction of Milosevic's security forces
in Kosovo, a province of southern Serbia whose population is 90
percent ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   The German foreign minister, Joschka Fischer, and a senior
European Union envoy, Hans van den Broek, are due to see the
Yugoslav leader on Monday in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Several Washington officials said it was likely that the
administration would let the Europeans troop in to see Milosovic
and that Holbrooke would be kept as a trump card.
</P>
<P>
   With the ethnic Albanians' refusal to sign a peace deal taking
the pressure off him, Milosevic has been building up troop strength
in southern Serbia, on the borders of Kosovo. In the province
itself, Serbian police and Yugoslav soldiers have been taken out of
their garrisons.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say these additional troops may be poised for an
offensive against the ethnic Albanians, or in preparation for NATO
airstrikes against the Serbs. They violate troop levels set by
Holbrooke last October, but for Milosevic are a useful way of
signaling his own strength. Serbia and Montenegro together make up
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic stripped Kosovo's Albanians of broad autonomy in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement with the ethnic Albanians, whose rebel army has
been fighting the Serbs for the past year, has been a linchpin of
the administration's strategy in Kosovo. Without the ethnic
Albanians' signatures on the plan for 28,000 NATO-led troops to
oversee a three-year period of autonomy for Kosovo, the
administration remains in a weak position to pressure Milosevic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
