<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REBELS REVISIT SCENE OF CALL TO ARMS
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds., see also KOSOVO-RDP)  
(fb) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PREKAZ, Yugoslavia _ Several thousand villagers swarmed across a
hillside in north Kosovo on Saturday to watch parades of the Kosovo
Liberation Army on the first anniversary of its open battles with
the security forces of the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 rebel Albanian soldiers, in combat fatigues and
berets, rifles across their chests, marched behind the red Albanian
flag, emblazoned with a two-headed eagle. Flanked by black-clad
special security troops, the senior guerrilla commanders who
watched included one of the most elusive, Suleyman Selimi, known as
Sultan, who was appointed chief of staff of the rebel army last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic Albanians of Kosovo were commemorating the massacre a
year ago by Serbian security forces of a top rebel, Adem Jashari,
and his clan at their compound in this northern Kosovo village.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre precipitated a full-blown conflict between the
rebel army and the Serbian security forces who had kept a tight lid
on Kosovo since 1989, when Milosevic stripped the region of broad
autonomy. Ninety percent of Kosovo's 2 million people are ethnic
Albanians, but the province is dear to Serbs as the cradle of their
medieval empire.
</P>
<P>
   The police stormed this village at dawn a year ago, and battled
with armed fighters for two days. Jashari became an instant martyr,
and events here did more than anything to galvanize Kosovo's
Albanians into widespread revolt.
</P>
<P>
   In the week before the Prekaz clash, ethnic Albanians and the
Serbian police had battled in two nearby villages after rebels
assaulted a police convoy. That week is now regarded as the first
week of Kosovo's undeclared war. About 80 Albanians, including at
least 25 women and children, and six Serbian policemen were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Western threats of force against Milosevic, his security
forces launched a scorched-earth assault last summer to try to
quell the revolt.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter of a million people fled their homes under bombardment
and took refuge in the woods and hills. By year's end, 2,000 people
were dead and at least 100,000 homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Liberation Army, formed in the mid-1990s to fight for
independence from Serbia, meanwhile swelled.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanian men in Kosovo took up arms, grabbing World War
II rifles until they could capture or buy a new automatic weapon,
often supplied to the rebels over mountain tracks from neighboring
Albania. Abroad, the Albanian diaspora raised money.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, the ragtag peasant army has changed beyond
recognition. It now appears akin to a real army, the men outfitted
in new camouflage uniforms, carrying new weapons, including
anti-tank grenades and automatic weapons, alongside the standard
AK-47 rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Many of its commanders were trained in the Yugoslav People's
Army before the breakup of Yugoslavia. Some even saw active service
in the wars in Croatia and Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   One of the seven zone commanders in Kosovo, an officer known as
Commander Drini, is an example. The 38-year-old commander had spent
18 years in the Yugoslav army, becoming a captain teaching at the
military college in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign military observers in Kosovo say the guerrilla leaders
understand that they cannot win the war against the Serbian police
and Yugoslav army, who have tanks, heavy weapons and far more guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better that NATO come and control the situation,''
Commander Drini said recently. ``Like firemen, because we are
matches to the fire.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
