<HEADER>
A0119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOSANGELES-CHARTER-AR     03-06 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSANGELES-CHARTER-ART-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES VOTERS TO DECIDE OVERHAUL OF CITY GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To a Midwesterner, whose idea of big city
governance is the Daley dynasty of Chicago, or to a New Yorker,
steeped in the strong-mayor legacy of a La Guardia, Koch or
Giuliani, the government of Los Angeles can sometimes seem as
quaint and collective as a Quaker meeting. Here, the mayor can't
even fire his own department heads, much less make them cry.
</P>
<P>
   But Angelenos cherish the Progressive-era protections of their
City Hall, in which mayoral power is heavily filtered through
civilian commissions that oversee major departments like police and
fire, and where the 15-member City Council has long shared
important elements of executive authority.
</P>
<P>
   So it was no small miracle last month when not one but two
separate commissions charged with recommending changes in the Los
Angeles city charter agreed on a set of proposals that would amount
to the most significant overhaul in the government of the nation's
second largest city since 1925.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the City Council unanimously agreed to put the
recommendations to the voters in June, even as some council members
vowed to campaign against the measure because it could diminish
their power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The end is infinitely better than I could have hoped for,''
said Erwin Chemerinsky, a law professor at the University of
Southern California who helped draft the constitution of Belarus.
He also led the charter commission that was elected by the voters
two years ago, after Mayor Richard Riordan pressed for such a move,
in an effort to head off a drive for secession by the suburban San
Fernando Valley. This commission had the power to put its
recommendations directly on the ballot, and they would take effect
with voter approval.
</P>
<P>
   But the City Council, which has feuded bitterly with Riordan, a
millionaire Republican businessman, for most of his six-year
tenure, appointed a rival commission, whose recommendations
required approval by the council itself before going to the voters.
For a time, it seemed likely that voters would face competing and
possibly contradictory proposals.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, after months of sometimes fractious debate,
arm-twisting and compromise, the two commissions backed a single
joint proposal, which won the grudging support of both mayor and
council.
</P>
<P>
   Under the unified plan, the mayor would have expanded powers,
including the right to dismiss municipal department heads, subject
to an override by the council. Now, the mayor may make such
dismissals only after a majority vote by the council. Riordan had
wanted the power to dismiss managers at will.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, some advocates of increased local control wanted the
commissions to expand the City Council from its current size, in
which members represent districts of some 250,000 people each and
five different council members represent parts of the valley
enclave of Van Nuys, for example. But instead, the proposal gives
voters the option of leaving the council the same or adding up to
10 new members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the mayor's authority has been
increased to a degree,'' said George Kieffer, a lawyer and the
chairman of the appointed commission. ``But by the same token,
we've increased the council's authority in a way that has not
generally resonated, by taking a lot of the rules and
specifications out of the charter and leaving them up to the
council to decide by ordinance.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, there were some interesting twists. At one point,
Riordan, angered that he had not won all he wanted from the
compromise proposal, threatened to back only the elected
commission's recommendations, and because he has the kind of deep
pockets needed to finance a public campaign, that threatened to
scuttle any deal. But under pressure from longtime civic leaders,
including former Secretary of State Warren Christopher, Riordan
reversed himself and backed the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new city charter will help people hold Dick Riordan
accountable,'' Riordan told a state commission on local government
on Friday, ``and also the next mayor and the next mayor,'' adding:
``Secession is simply not the answer.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An early effort by Chemerinsky to include a ``bill of rights,''
, an enumeration of civil liberties for city residents, including
``reproductive autonomy,'' was quickly caricatured as a kind of
tie-dyed manifesto likely to unite a wide range of potential
opponents, and the idea was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``In part, I think it reflects the fact that it would be very
difficult to get the Bill of Rights itself passed today,''
Chemerinsky said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading voices of discontent in the valley, the
Valley Industry and Commerce Association, threatened to oppose any
charter that did not call for creating an independent citizens'
commission to draw new City Council districts.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise plan would leave districting in the hands of the
council. But even this group now says it will take another look at
the proposal, and has not ruled out an endorsement, said its
chairman, Steve Lew.
</P>
<P>
   The next challenge for charter advocates: winning the support of
a majority of voters in a low-turnout municipal election in which
apathy often rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters have to be made aware of what this is and why they have
a stake in it, and why this is going to be better for the city,''
said Bill Carrick, a political consultant who works for Riordan and
expects to help sell the new charter this spring. ``That case has
to be made to the voters, and if it's not made in a serious and
aggressive way, the forces of the status quo will nit-pick it to
death.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1312EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
