A0120 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-MOUNTIES-NYT     03-06 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MOUNTIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW GAFFE, AND CANADIAN MOUNTIES PUT THE FORCE UNDER INQUIRY
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ A casino license awarded in British Columbia last
December has triggered two sensitive police investigations. One led
to a raid on the home of the province's premier, Glen Clark, by the
Royal Canadian Mounted Police. The other is forcing the Mounties to
look at themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mounties' commercial-crime unit showed up at Clark's
East Vancouver home Tuesday night with a search warrant, a local
television news crew taped everything, including a frazzled-looking
Clark pacing inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``This leaves the Mounties looking very insensitive and
authoritarian,'' said Paul R. Tennant, a political scientist at the
University of British Columbia in Vancouver. ``In my view they have
much to explain at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The video clip was broadcast on local television and across
Canada, triggering a political scandal in which calls for Clark's
resignation have already been heard. Clark, premier since 1996,
says he has done nothing wrong and will not step down.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Henley, a police spokesman in Surrey, British Columbia,
made it clear that ``it is not Clark who is under investigation.''
The police target is the local businessman, Dimitrios Pilarinos,
who won the license to open a charity casino. Clark has said he
played no part in reviewing the license application of Pilarinos, a
neighbor who built an addition to the premier's house.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's lawyer has accused local media of smearing the premier,
and Clark's supporters are angry at the police, who they believe
tipped off a local reporter about the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Henley denied that the police tipped off anyone, but he said an
internal investigation was launched anyway to determine if there
had been a leak.
</P>
<P>
   Clive Jackson, managing editor at the local television station,
BCTV, said there had been no tip. One of his reporters had covered
a raid earlier that day, Jackson said, and was playing out a hunch
that there would be another raid at the premier's house.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they sold the right to use their widely recognized
image to the Walt Disney Co. in 1995, the Mounties remain among
Canada's strongest, and usually most highly respected, symbols.
</P>
<P>
   But this is just the latest in a string of questionable
incidents that have tarnished their reputation. Most recently, the
police were harshly criticized when they admitted that they set the
bomb that blew up a gas well shed in Alberta. The explosion was
intended to flush out the person responsible for a series of
similar explosions but some Canadians questioned the force's
tactics.
</P>
<P>
   In another blow to the Mounties' image, a public inquiry is
still proceeding in Vancouver over the way they handled student
protesters at an international economic conference in 1997.
Television crews caught the police subduing the students with
pepper spray, and the videotape has been replayed repeatedly on
national and local television.
</P>
<P>
   And the police were humiliated in 1995 when an intruder bypassed
guards and wandered around Prime Minister Jean Chretien's home in
Ottawa for half an hour before Chretien threatened him with a stone
carving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadians are coming to grips with the fact that the RCMP is
not an infallible institution,'' said Allen Seager, director of the
Center for Canadian Studies, at Simon Fraser University. ``The role
of the police force is being reassessed on a wide front.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald E. Sparks, executive director of the RCMP Veterans
Association, said he does not believe the recent controversies have
dimmed the reputation of the Mounties in the minds of most
Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get criticized but so does the FBI, so does the Secret
Service,'' said Sparks, who retired in 1982 as a staff sergeant.
``They're policemen, that's all. And they sometimes become handy
scapegoats for whatever goes on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
