<SLUG> BC-TAX-POOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANDFUL OF STATES STILL TAX THE POOR AND THE VERY POOR
</HEADLINE>
  
(Attn: N.J., Kan., Miss., Ky, Ala., Hawaii, Ill., Va.)  (fb) 
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After seven years in which surging revenues have allowed 41
states to cut taxes, 19 states continue to tax the incomes of those
below the federal poverty line, according to a study by a
Washington research group. Six of those states, including New
Jersey, tax people who have so little money that even if they
doubled their income, they would still be officially classified as
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, however, two more states, Kansas and Mississippi,
revised their income tax laws to exempt the poor, according to the
study, by the Center on Budget and Policy Priorities, a nonprofit
organization that studies how government policies affect low-income
people.
</P>
<P>
   Taxing the incomes of poor people at a time when governments are
trying to move people off welfare and into work illustrates how tax
policies can create obstacles to welfare reform. Most people
leaving welfare find only low-income jobs, often just the minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, changes in the tax system can help efforts to move
people off welfare and into work,'' said Scott Mackey, chief
economist for the National Conference of State Legislatures. ``That
is why a handful of states have adopted or expanded their earned
income tax credit program, to provide more of an incentive to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Nichols, an author of the budget center's study,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Income tax relief,'' Nichols said, ``is one of the simplest
ways states can help low-income working families to meet the costs
of child care, transportation and other expenses and thereby become
self-sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky imposes the heaviest income tax burden on poor
families, followed closely by Alabama and Hawaii, the budget center
said. Kentucky taxes the incomes of families of four making as
little as $5,000. A family making the federal poverty-line income _
which was $16,655 last year for two parents with two children _
paid $550 in Kentucky income taxes last year, the center said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Jim Wayne, a Democrat, said Kentucky had a
progressive tax system in the 1940s, when the state first taxed
incomes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, because taxes haven't been adjusted for inflation for a
half-century, Kentucky's system is regressive,'' Wayne said.
</P>
<P>
   Someone earning $19,000 would pay Kentucky income, sales,
property and other taxes equal to 10.5 percent of income, he said,
compared with only 8.2 percent for someone earning $214,000.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky is tripling its standard deduction over three years as
part of a strategy to reduce the income tax burdens on the working
poor, said Melissa Forsythe, press secretary to Gov. Paul E.
Patton, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey, which has passed some of the biggest tax cuts in the
country over the last few years, is another of the six states that
tax people making less than half the poverty line. The other states
are Alabama, Hawaii, Illinois and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In Trenton, Assembly Speaker Jack Collins and Joseph V. Doria
Jr., the minority leader, have sponsored a bill that would remove
200,000 low-income people from the state income tax roles. Gov.
Christine Todd Whitman has said she supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the first time in recent decades that a majority
of states exempted the poor from their income tax systems, the
budget center said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 42 states with an income tax, the budget center said, 23
now exempt families of three or four whose incomes are at or below
the official poverty line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
