<HEADLINE>
U.N. TO USE PEACE-PRIZE MONEY FOR MONUMENT TO PEACEKEEPERS
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Almost 11 years after winning the Nobel Peace
Prize for its peacekeeping efforts in trouble spots around the
world, the United Nations has finally decided to spend the money on
a monument commemorating all peacekeepers who lose their lives on
duty and has invited Sweden and Norway to help select a design.
</P>
<P>
   The organization tentatively plans to erect the memorial on the
esplanade outside the visitors' entrance to its New York
headquarters, thus making it accessible to the public, said
Assistant Secretary-General Alvaro de Soto, who is in charge of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are thinking of something very sober, not at all flashy or
innovative,'' said de Soto, who hopes the memorial can be finished
at the latest by next year's millennial General Assembly. The heads
of state of all the countries in the world are being invited to
come to the United Nations for that celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden and Norway were asked to propose a short list of possible
designs because Alfred Bernard Nobel, the inventor of dynamite and
founder of the prizes that bear his name, was himself a Swede.
However he entrusted the awarding of his Peace Prize to Norway,
which was then governed by Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope to speed up the process of choosing a design
after the United Nations had spent so much time trying to decide
what to do with its prize money, which thanks to compound interest
has grown from $339,000 to around $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly we didn't want the design issue to get buried for
another decade in the United Nations committee system,'' said
Shashi Tharoor, executive assistant to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan. But the final decision on which design to choose will be
Annan's.
</P>
<P>
   The Swedish government has nominated Bo Grandien, director of
the Royal Swedish Academy of Fine Art, to the two-member jury that
will select a short list of possible designs. Norway's nominee is
Per Boym, who heads Copenhagen's Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   De Soto said the United Nations has created a number of
guidelines for the judges. It has ruled out an eternal flame,
largely because the city of New York is worried about a potential
fire hazard. It has also excluded any kind of fountain because of
the cost of maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   The monument will not carry the names of the roughly 1,580
military and civilian peacekeepers who have died on active service,
to avoid the awkward problem of whether to include those who died
from natural causes _ or in drunken driving accidents.
</P>
<P>
   After the original Nobel Peace Prize check was handed to the
secretary-general at that time, Javier Perez de Cuellar, on Dec.
10, 1988, at a ceremony at Oslo University, the world organization
found it could not agree on how to use the money.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, to commemorate the 50th anniversary of
peacekeeping, the United Nations said it would give a specially
designed crystal medal to the family members of all peacekeepers,
civil and military, who died on active service, paying for them out
of its own funds rather than the Nobel Prize money.
</P>
<P>
   But there will not be any presentations for a while. Under U.N.
procurement rules the organization must get bids from many crystal
manufacturers before it places a bulk order.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Myiot, the French-born director of peacekeeping, throws
up his hands in Gallic despair. ``How long will it take? That's
what I keep asking myself. I have no idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
