<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCSEC-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON TALK: MOTIVATION FOR FIXING SOCIAL SECURITY POLITICAL
NOT PRACTICAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Without any changes, the Social Security system
will remain solvent well into the next century. So why are the
politicians here, who normally put off difficult decisions as long
as possible, tackling the subject now in the absence of a crisis?
</P>
<P>
   Granted, most economists and social policy analysts believe that
acting now is the responsible course to take. Ultimately, they say,
a crunch is bound to arrive because so many baby boomers will be in
retirement, and the sooner the shortfall is addressed, the more
gradually the remedies can be applied and the less painful they
will be.
</P>
<P>
   But the reason President Clinton and the Republicans who control
Congress are seriously talking this year about the herculean task
of overhauling the Social Security system has almost nothing to do
with long-term responsibility and almost everything to do with the
politics of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when economic forecasters unexpectedly began
projecting large federal budget surpluses, Republicans eagerly
began to discuss ways of returning this money to the public in the
form of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   To counter that, the president played his wild card. The issue,
he asserted, was not, as Republicans maintained, whether the
surplus should go for tax cuts or government spending. Rather, he
said, it was whether the money should be used to give tax benefits
to the wealthy or to save Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans knew they could not win that argument. The most
popular government program ever created in this country, Social
Security was begun by Democrats during the New Deal over Republican
opposition, and it has been the Democrats' strongest suit ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Clinton has triumphed and Republicans have been
badly burned every time he has created a contest between Social
Security and Medicare on one hand and tax cuts on the other.
</P>
<P>
   So Republicans took another tack. They proposed strengthening
the system by allowing workers to invest at least some of the
Social Security taxes withheld from their paychecks in private
stock market accounts that would be preserved for their retirement.
This meshes the public's infatuation with the booming stock market
and the Republicans' ideological preference for a private
retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is now joined. And as counterintuitive as it seems,
since no sword is hanging over their heads, the president and
congressional leaders seem committed to try to pass the most
sweeping legislation in terms of the number of people affected
since at least the Tax Reform Act of 1986 and possibly since the
Great Society era of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   But two immediate problems are standing in the way.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that the crucial matter of how burdensome and
politically distasteful it will be to put Social Security on sound
footing depends in large part on how big the shortfall in the
financing will be and when it will appear. That in turn depends on
how well the economy and the stock market perform over the next
generation. And no one can predict that with any confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Just two years ago, the Clinton administration and the
Congressional Budget Office were projecting large budget deficits
indefinitely. But the economy has been so strong that forecasts
show a surplus of about $4.5 trillion over the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way, Social Security actuaries projected in the
spring of 1997 that Social Security reserves would be insufficient
to pay benefits in 2029. The economy over the next year was so much
stronger than anticipated that, last April, the actuaries pushed
the date back by three years, estimating that the system would
remain sound until 2032.
</P>
<P>
   The economy was even stronger in 1998, and it is a safe bet that
the date of insolvency will be extended even further when the
actuaries make their 1999 report next month.
</P>
<P>
   An even more difficult problem politically is that the ultimate
solution to Social Security's long-term financial difficulty will
require higher taxes, lower retirement benefits or both. So far,
neither side has been willing to concede that.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, in fact, have not agreed on a specific Social
Security proposal. At the request of Rep. Bill Archer, D-Texas, who
heads the House Ways and Means Committee, Kenneth J. Kies, a
prominent tax lawyer and lobbyist who is the former chief of staff
of the Joint Congressional Committee on Taxation, is drafting a
measure for Republicans in the House to use as a starting point.
</P>
<P>
   At this stage, the Republican plan would use the budget surplus
to give workers a tax cut if they invested in stocks and bonds in
private retirement accounts within Social Security. If the market
improved, their retirement benefits would increase.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the market turned sour or they made bad investments,
workers would be guaranteed that their retirement benefits would
never be lower under the new Social Security plan than under the
current one. So they could invest, not risking a dime.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds like an unrealistic free lunch, it is. But
Clinton and his allies can hardly complain. The proposals he made
in his State of the Union message _ using most of the surplus to
pay off the national debt and transferring bonds from the general
treasury into Social Security reserves _ are just as misleadingly
pain-free.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
