<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPE-COD-PROTECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPE COD TOWNS ARE PROTECTING LAND
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mass.)  (fb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. _ A half mile east of Quaker Meeting House Road
and just south of the Midcape Highway are two well-paved roads that
lead to nothing, a situation that delights Sandwich town officials.
</P>
<P>
   Using most its share of a new Cape Cod fund to preserve
undeveloped land, the town will buy 275 acres, blocking
construction of 75 large houses that the two roads were supposed to
serve. The fund, called a land bank, was approved by Cape Cod
voters last November to help the Cape's 15 towns buy and protect as
much as possible of their undeveloped land. It is financed by a 3
percent surtax on local real estate assessments.
</P>
<P>
   Besides helping the towns limit further residential and
commercial building, money from the land bank will help them
preserve well sites and rain-water collection areas for badly
needed fresh water on the rapidly developing Cape.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Carbonell, executive director of the Cape Cod
Commission, the Cape's regional planning body, which led the fight
to establish the land bank, said it was not intended to block all
new construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be more development and there should be,''
Carbonell said. ``What the commission and the towns need is a
better tool to help control that building and retain the quality of
life that has made the Cape a magnet for so much new construction.
The land bank helps do that.''
</P>
<P>
   About 38 percent of the Cape's 412 square miles have been
developed. Another 28 percent had already been protected, leaving
about 34 percent still available to the towns or the developers.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwich, on the northwest corner of the 70-mile-long peninsula,
will receive $726,000 from the land bank this year and will use
about $625,000 of that for the 275 acres, which is the largest
single use of land-bank money so far.
</P>
<P>
   The surtax will raise about $8.8 million this year and the state
will make a one-time contribution of $15 million. Each town's share
of the land-bank money will be the amount that the surtax raises on
its real estate assessments. The surtax will add between $50 and
$60 each year to most property owners' tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   The acreage that Sandwich is buying adjoins the privately owned
Round Hill Country Club's 18-hole golf course, which the town
expects to buy with a private loan, and pay off with green fees.
Both parcels will be joined with the 500-acre Maple Swamp, a
conservation area with hiking trails, which the town already owns.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Teehan, chairman of the Sandwich Board of Selectmen, said
that the two parcels were the largest area of privately owned land
left in the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now those 75 houses won't be built, and with the golf course
and Maple Swamp, we'll be able to keep 1,000 acres clear of further
development forever,'' she said. ``And I'm happily telling you
that, thanks to those land-bank funds and matching state money, the
town won't have to levy any additional taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the town of Orleans has used land-bank money to buy
eight acres of prime forest that could have been developed and the
town of Barnstable bought 25 undeveloped acres of well sites near
Cotuit.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Cape's 15 towns have appointed committees to study
the best use of their land-bank money.
</P>
<P>
   The Town of Truro's committee has proposed buying land that will
provide more well sites for its water and for a green belt along
Route 6. Provincetown expects to use land bank money to help buy 25
acres near Shankpainter Pond, which had been approved for
development. Included is a rare quaking bog that is the habitat of
several species of exotic plants and some unusual animals.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past decade the permanent population of Cape Cod
has been increasing by at least 5,000 people a year. The population
now exceeds 205,000, a number that more than doubles when tourists
arrive in the summer. Every drop of fresh water on the Cape must
come from wells that must be replenished yearly by rain collected
at open sites.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, developers obtained permits to build 2,226 houses,
one of the largest numbers of annual permits on record for the
Cape. In 1998, traffic engineers counted more than 34 million cars
and trucks crossing the Cape's two bridges in both directions,
nearly double the number that crossed in 1978. And the hydrologists
are now predicting that by the year 2020 more than 10 million
gallons of fresh water will have to be added to each day's supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
