A0133 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-COOPER-430-NYT     03-06 0427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COOPER-430-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. FRANKLIN S. COOPER, 90, RESEARCHER IN SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By RICHARD SEVERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Franklin Seaney Cooper, a pioneer in speech research whose work
was later applied to computerized speech synthesis, died on Feb. 20
in Palo Alto, Calif., where he lived. He was 90.
</P>
<P>
   Much of his work was theoretical and seemed arcane. But in 1973,
he served on a panel with five other experts who were asked to
investigate the nature of the 18{-minute gap in a tape made by
President Richard M. Nixon in the Oval Office, which became a part
of the Watergate investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of Cooper's career was mostly dedicated to less
well-known research. Born and raised on a farm in Robinson, Ill.,
and educated at the University of Illinois, where he got his
bachelor's degree, and the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
where he earned his Ph.D., Cooper first worked for General Electric
in Schenectady, N.Y., as a research engineer, then left it in 1935
to join Caryl P. Haskins in founding the Haskins Laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   At Haskins in the 1950s, he played an important role in
developing an electromechanical machine to synthesize speech. He
wanted to codify how speech was perceived and understood and how
noise and distortion affected the understand of it.
</P>
<P>
   He did extensive experimentation with speech patterns. His
approach enabled Cooper and his colleagues to determine which
elements in speech carried the information needed for
understanding. He also analyzed how words were formed and the
relationship between the gestures people make and phonetics.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Cooper served under Vannevar Bush,
President Franklin D. Roosevelt's science adviser, as head of the
liaison office of the U.S. Office of Scientific Research. His
wartime service earned him a certificate of merit from President
Harry S. Truman in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as a consultant to the United Nations on atomic
power, and was involved in the postwar years in the effort to bring
atomic energy under international control.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper taught approaches to phonetics at both Columbia
University and the University of Connecticut and maintained a
research affiliation with Yale University. He was given an honorary
doctorate by Yale and was elected to the National Academy of
Engineering.
</P>
<P>
   He married Frances E. Clem in 1935; she died in 1991. Among his
survivors are two sons, Alan Kent Cooper of Palo Alto and Robert
Craig Cooper of Amherst, Va.; four grandchildren; and two
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
