<HEADER>
A0147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAITH-HEALING07-COX     03-06 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITH-HEALING07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faith healing questioned in Colorado woman's death
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Rather than take her grandmother to the
hospital before she died, Jana Colosimo watched members of her
grandmother's church pour a mix of bleach and water over her bed
sores and then cover them with lard and gauze.
</P>
<P>
   Colosimo's grandmother, a member of the General Assembly and
Church of the Firstborn, had fallen, probably breaking her hip, but
the church's strong belief in spiritual healing and the rejection
of medical help for the sick kept her from seeing a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Colosimo and her sister, Deborah Davis, said they respected
their grandmother's desire to live without medical care, but said
they believe she would have gone to a doctor before her death if
church members had not kept such a close watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``A simple, medical technique could have taken care of it,''
Davis said. ``I believe she would have been alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The same may be true for a Clifton infant who died last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Mesa County Sheriff's Department is investigating the death
of Warren Glory, the 18-day-old infant son of two church members.
Paramedics were called to the Glory home Feb. 28, after Warren went
into cardiac arrest. He died at St. Mary's Hospital that night of
pneumonia and bacterial meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Prell, a sheriff's department spokeswoman, said
authorities suspect the child did not receive medical care for his
illnesses because of his parents' religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa County Coroner Rob Kurtzman said both diseases are ``very
treatable'' with a course of antibiotics and hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters said Warren's situation is not unique within the
church. Members do not seek medical attention for any type of
illness or receive immunizations against childhood diseases,
Colosimo said, leaving the children of the congregation susceptible
to health problems.
</P>
<P>
   But, Colosimo said many members still go to the dentist, visit
eye doctors, and sometimes use birth control pills or
over-the-counter pain medication.
</P>
<P>
   Their grandfather, Marion Paul Brown, was one of the founding
elders of the Grand Junction branch of the church. After his death
in the 1960s, both Colosimo and Davis severed their ties to the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said she decided when she was still in grade school that
she wouldn't stay with the church because of the reliance on faith
healing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at that young age, I knew I couldn't live with that
tenant,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Because their mother married outside the church, both Colosimo
and Davis received medical care throughout their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Colosimo said she believes her grandfather would have embraced
some of the modern medical advancements that have been developed
since his death, especially in the case of children.
</P>
<P>
   The church derives its belief in healing prayer from a passage
in the New Testament. The verses, outlined in a pamphlet from a
church member called ``General Assembly and Church of the
Firstborn: Who We Are and What We believe,'' come from the fifth
chapter of the book of James.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is any sick among you? Let him call for the elders of the
church and let them pray over him anointing him with oil in the
name of the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the prayer of the faithful shall save the sick and the
Lord shall raise him up; and if he have committed sins, they shall
be forgiven.''
</P>
<P>
   Before their grandmother died, Colosimo and Davis said her house
filled with members of the church, who prayed and anointed her with
oil. As her pain grew more intense, Davis said she helped her
grandmother hide pain medication from the church elders.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Encyclopedia of American Religions, the
90-year-old church does not have paid clergy, and a loose
organization of church elders lead services and other church
activities. No official membership rolls are kept, and researchers
estimate the church has about 30 congregations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the church does not have trained faith-healers like
those found in Christian Science, but uses the church elders to
pray for the sick and anoint them with oil.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Christian denominations that do not believe in
medical treatment, the church has faced several court battles over
the death of its young members.
</P>
<P>
   The church has been investigated three times on the Western
Slope:
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1982, 14-year-old Travis Drake died after his appendix
ruptured. Drake had been sick for about a week with stomach cramps,
but a coroner's jury ruled his parents did not realize the extent
of his illness and they were not prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   _ In 1987, Luck Long died 10 hours after he was born in a
difficult, at-home breech delivery.
</P>
<P>
   _ The parents of Angela Sweet, a 7-year-old Delta girl who died
in 1990 five weeks after her appendix burst, received a three-year
deferred sentence and probation for her death. The court also
ordered the parents to report any life-threatening situations for
their other 10 children.
</P>
<P>
   Under Colorado law, a parent can be prosecuted for the death of
a child if medical care was not provided, even for religious
reasons. Mesa County District Attorney Frank Daniels said the law
clearly states that if a child is in a life-threatening situation,
the parents must seek medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Faith healing is recognized as medical treatment under the law
if the fees are allowed to be deducted as medical expenses by the
U.S. Internal Revenue Service or if insurance companies recognize
the expense as reimbursable, and if the treatment has a success
rate equal to that of regular medical care.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
