<HEADER>
A0152 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-     03-06 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERRACIAL PARTNERSHIP TAKES ON MANDELA'S PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMERSET WEST, South Africa _ The partners move through the
bustle of an upscale mall in this Cape Town suburb, shaking hands
and calling greetings.
</P>
<P>
   One is a black man, Bantu Holomisa, 43 and elegantly dressed in
a tailored suit. Most of the customers are white and pass without
recognizing him. Those who stop are usually black and dressed in
the uniforms of maintenance men and salespeople. They clasp
Holomisa's hand as if he were a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him is a white man, Roelf Meyer, 51, who is natty too,
and often talking on his cellular phone. Meyer was once the golden
boy of the National Party, which ran the former white supremacist
government. But these days, he and Holomisa are trying to do
something never done in South Africa: build a new multiracial
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you, man,'' Meyer says to an eager white customer, who
pumps his hand.
</P>
<P>
   When Holomisa and Meyer first teamed up they largely were
dismissed as a curiosity _ odd bedfellows who had each been forced
out of his own party. But one recent poll suggests they already may
have won over as much as 9 percent of voters. That is twice the
goal they set when they formed their United Democratic Movement
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even they seem a little amazed.
</P>
<P>
   They operate on a shoestring. Neither takes a salary. They have
only seven paid employees in their national office. In the mall,
they are trailed by volunteers handing out photocopies of their
fliers. One clutches a half dozen of the party's yellow baseball
caps. It is all they can afford to give out.
</P>
<P>
   They have just come from doing 15 minutes on the local radio
station. The studio is a small glass enclosure near a grocery store
in the mall and the noise of the shopping carts could be heard
through the walls. Children came up to the glass and made faces at
them as they talked. But they were smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The UDM is about uniting the country,'' said Holomisa. ``It's
about creating a new political home for those who are not
satisfied. It's about narrowing the gap between the haves and the
have-nots because as you know we have this unfortunate past. Roelf
and I were at one stage opponents, but we are working together
now.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the Holomisa-Meyer team _ Holomisa is the party
president and Meyer is his deputy _ to win South Africa's second
post-apartheid elections, which are scheduled to take place June 2.
But suddenly they seem like contenders to push aside the crumbling
former National Party and the Zulu-focused Inkatha Freedom Party to
become the biggest opposition party. Political analysts are
wondering whether they might have the potential some day to
challenge President Nelson Mandela's African National Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 elections, the National Party won about 20 percent
of the vote; the Inkatha Freedom Party about 10 percent. But polls
show a sharp drop in their support, perhaps by as much as half. The
only other opposition party that is growing at the moment is the
liberal, largely white-supported Democratic Party, which won about
2 percent of the vote in 1994. Polls show it may now win 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released Feb. 24 found Holomisa to be the
third-most-popular politician in the country, behind President
Mandela and his heir apparent, Thabo Mbeki. Mbeki is virtually
assured the presidency if the African National Congress, as
expected, wins the elections.
</P>
<P>
   But putting together a new party in South Africa is not easy.
While the established parties get public campaign money based on
the number of seats they have in Parliament, the United Democratic
Movement gets nothing. Raising funds from corporations or
international donors has yielded little, both candidates say. For
the time being, Meyer says the African National Congress seems
unbeatable and Mandela's moral authority looms so large that there
is little interest in an opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Both Holomisa and Meyer are outcasts from their former parties,
the African National Congress and the National Party, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Both are often called boyish. Holomisa has a mischievous kind of
charm while Meyer seems as straight an arrow as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   Holomisa was once one of Mandela's proteges and a member of his
Cabinet. But in 1996, in a spectacular fall from grace he was
drummed out of the African National Congress for insubordination.
</P>
<P>
   Holomisa's sin was to continue to repeat allegations of
corruption against other party officials. But the final straw
appeared to be when he disclosed that Mandela had accepted a large
campaign contribution from Sol Kerzner, a casino owner who was
under investigation for bribery. Holomisa began his career in the
army in Transkei, one of the apartheid-era enclaves carved out for
blacks and called homelands. In 1987, as a young major general, he
led a bloodless coup taking over from notoriously corrupt
officials. Then, in defiance of the South African government, he
allowed the outlawed African National Congress to operate in his
territory.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, he was capable of colorful, if questionable,
statements. But these days, Holomisa, is more polished and often
funny. He criticizes the African National Congress for failing to
deliver on housing, crime, jobs and medical care. Sure, he says,
there is free treatment at health clinics for young children. But
go there and there is only one kind of treatment _ Panado, South
Africa's Tylenol. ``You get the Panado, whether you have ear
problems, eye problems or you are vomiting,'' he deadpans.
</P>
<P>
   He gives the government credit for delivering on new license
plates. ``They have done that,'' he says. ``I give them credit for
that. In the Eastern Cape, where I come from, we have changed them
three times since 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issues, the United Democratic Movement offers a little
for everyone. The party has outlined an anti-crime strategy that
includes having a referendum on reinstituting the death penalty.
Many blacks support the death penalty even though the African
National Congress has been adamant in its opposition.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the United Democratic Movement opposes
affirmative action, which is a stand many white voters would
appreciate. The African National Congress has passed legislation
making affirmative action programs mandatory. On employment, the
United Democratic Movement would have the government more actively
involved in job creation. For the time being, the governing party
is counting on market forces.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys indicate that the United Democratic Movement has
attracted supporters from across South Africa's racial spectrum
roughly in proportion to the breakdown in the population. At the
same time, they also show that large numbers of voters still do not
know much about the party.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   As Holomisa and Meyer moved through the mall, many of those who
stopped to talk to them were intrigued by their partnership. ``It's
so good for the country, if it can work,'' said John Lombard, a
retired teacher who was having coffee with his wife, when Holomisa
approached. ``Others have people of color but not like two leaders.
This is a new breath of air.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer resigned from the National Party, now called the New
National Party, in 1997. Trained as a lawyer, he had been a key
player in negotiating the country's peaceful transition to a modern
democracy and then in the writing of its new constitution. But his
belief that the National Party had to, in effect, dissolve itself
and try again was too much for many of the old-timers. He soon
found himself sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of handshaking, baby-kissing campaigning Americans are
so used to is new here. But Holomisa shows clear signs of getting
the hang of it. Meyer still looks shy, particularly when the
twosome moves from the mall to an area outside where black workers
congregate.
</P>
<P>
   Holomisa does little to bail him out and laughs at his partner's
awkwardness. ``It doesn't matter,'' he says generously. ``Because
the people respect him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0154 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISNEY-CIRQUE07-COX     03-06 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-CIRQUE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Daring, dramatic circus vaults, tumbles into Disney's world
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Cirque du Soleil's new show at Disney World is a
daredevil circus _ and its nerves of steel extend all the way to
the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Adult tickets are $59.89 (kids 3 to 9 cost $47.92) for the
nearly two-hour Cirque show, La Nouba, created just for Disney.
That's nearly $18 more than a one-day ticket to any of Disney's
four theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high price, Disney workers quiz the crowds
leaving the Cirque show La Nouba with a five-page survey that
includes: ``Was it worth the money?''
</P>
<P>
   And so far, price seems to be no object. Since the Dec. 23
premiere _ 10 shows each week _ La Nouba has played to 90
percent-plus capacity crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price has not been a consideration,'' says Karl Holz, Downtown
Disney vice president after seeing initial survey results.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest question seems to be ``What was your favorite
act?''
</P>
<P>
   Was it the woman doing a one-arm handstand atop the head of a
man walking a high wire three stories above the stage?
</P>
<P>
   Or the teen girls flipping Chinese yo-yos with dizzying
precision while tumbling over and under one another?
</P>
<P>
   Or the shirtless Russian, muscles stretching, straining, his
arms like wings as he ``flies'' by simply hanging on to red cloth
banners?
</P>
<P>
   This sophisticated circus is a far cry from P.T. Barnum. There
are no freaks, tiger tamers or human cannonballs. In La Nouba,
circus athletes star with cutting-edge lighting, exotic costumes
and live music that runs from techno to light opera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is possible here,'' says Carmen Ruest, La Nouba's
artistic coordinator. ``We are dream sellers.''
</P>
<P>
   La Nouba plays at the 1,671-seat theater built especially for
Cirque at Downtown Disney West Side, which also features
restaurants such as the Wolfgang Puck Cafe and nightclubs including
The House of Blues.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first stand-alone theater for the Montreal-based
Cirque du Soleil (Circus of the Sun), which also has shows at two
Las Vegas hotels. This spring seven different Cirque shows will be
running around the world including Alegria, opening near Biloxi,
Miss., at the Beau Rivage casino/resort. As Quidam tours Europe,
Saltimbanco tours Australia. A new show begins a three-year North
American tour soon in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   La Nouba at Disney is set to run 10 years with new acts rotated
in regularly. The show is written and directed by Franco Dragone,
who's created 10 of Cirque du Soleil's 11 shows since '84. He was
inspired by his 17-year-old son Luca's coming of age. La Nouba is a
French term (faire la Nouba) meaning to live it up, to party.
</P>
<P>
   There is no literal storyline. Dramatic visual symbols let you
create a story much as color and shape let you interpret a
painting.
</P>
<P>
   La Nouba is Mad Max meets Timothy Leary as marching columns of
drab, identically dressed ``urbanites'' are contrasted by the color
and flair of those playing on trapeze, high-wire and trampolines.
</P>
<P>
   There are also tricks on bicycles and savvy clown skits. A door
and frame raised 34 feet above the stage offers an aerial show.
Performers locked into giant wheels spin, turn, dodge and dance
with each other.
</P>
<P>
   When Disney targeted Cirque du Soleil as a can't-miss Downtown
Disney adult attraction, Guy Laliberte, Cirque du Soleil
co-founder, feared sharing creative control. But Michael Eisner,
Disney CEO, had a simple offer: We'll build the theater, you build
the show.
</P>
<P>
   Disney owns the $27 million theater made to resemble a
futuristic circus tent. Cirque built the $13 million La Nouba with
a cast of 66 performers. The partners split profits through the
12-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   The troupe's pied piper is Laliberte, a pony-tailed, high school
dropout who worked Quebec streets playing accordion, stilt walking
and eating fire before forming Cirque 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Laliberte is Cirque du Soleil's creative boss. Co-founder Daniel
Gauthier runs the business side. After surviving the early days
touring Canada with an 800-seat tent and a $1.5 million Canadian
government grant, the men broke into the U.S. market with a 1987
show that stunned critics at the Los Angeles Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1984, 18 million people have seen Cirque du Soleil shows
in 120 cities.
</P>
<P>
   There are 1,500 people on the Cirque payroll including 435
performers from 30 countries. Salaries run from a beginner's
$21,000 to a veteran's $175,000. Besides liberal health insurance,
each show is staffed by a masseuse/physical therapist and a
chef/nutritionist.
</P>
<P>
   Taking care of employees is just smart business, says Americas
division general manager Jacques Marois from his Montreal office.
``It's very grueling to work for Cirque du Soleil. This is no Club
Med. It's really, really tough on the performers to do what they do
10 times a week.''
</P>
<P>
   While falling backward three stories to a trampoline, and
popping back to ``walk'' up the side of a building may look easy,
it isn't. The heaving chests of the lean, muscled performers taking
bows tell you how tough each act is.
</P>
<P>
   Finding talent is Cirque du Soleil's ongoing drama. Cirque
talent scouts recruit retired gymnasts, tumblers and other athletes
in the hopes they can be taught theater.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Henderson, 27, is a recent hire for La Nouba. The
Bloomington, Minn., native, a five-time teen-age national
trampoline champion, describes his 1997 Cirque audition as ``Wow!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every little thing you could think of,'' he recalls.``I had
people standing on my shoulders. `Can you tumble?' And then came
dance. That was toughest for me and it was for Debra Brown,''
Cirque's choreographer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing she said was `Show me you.' I was afraid of
that,'' he laughs. ``I don't even remember what I did but I just
started going. You can't be shy about doing what they ask. Knowing
that, I just went for it.''
</P>
<P>
   He quickly learned Cirque du Soleil's No. 1 obsession: quality
control.
</P>
<P>
   Every show has a resident ``guardian of the concept'' and
another cross-checker who visits regularly such as artistic
director Chantal Tremblay a former Cirque dancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come in, I'm fresh,'' she says, ``I will look at the
show and see, whoops, we're missing timing, that focus isn't
right.''
</P>
<P>
   From obsessive quality control to a guy who can do a handstand
on a stack of eight kitchen chairs, the survey says that this show
is worth $59.89.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' says Downtown Disney's Holz. On those after-show
surveys, he says, ``you hear comments like `That's the best
entertainment bargain I've ever gotten', `It was worth every penny
of it' and `I've got to figure out how I can come back again and
real soon.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
