<HEADER>
A0155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWDISNEY-ATTRACTIONS     03-06 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWDISNEY-ATTRACTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disney debuts: Test track thrills, rockin' coaster, `Fantasmic!'
show
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ So far, Epcot's General Motors Test Track is
known more for the glitches that keep closing it down than for its
high-speed thrills. It is open now for what Disney calls ``sneak
previews,'' but won't officially open until March 17.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Imagineers and GM engineers based this ride on various
proving grounds and test tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The 5 1/2-minute ride's payoff is the final minute, the
high-speed test that takes riders at a top speed of 65 mph with a
50-degree banked curve. You get plastered against the set with the
kind of G-force rush that creates roller coaster fanatics.
</P>
<P>
   But this ain't Space Mountain or Busch Gardens' Kumba. It's a
very brief thrill that usually comes after a very long wait.
</P>
<P>
   You can spend more than an hour shuffling in a ``pre-show'' line
that snakes through a large, very bright testing garage with
videos, noise and news about how cars are tested.
</P>
<P>
   When you get to the ride, it's a convertible following a track
through a building. You and five other passengers experience
various tests such as hill climbing, braking, suspension and ride
handling. It's bumpy, zig-zaggy and even hot and cold when you go
through a temperature tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   This part of the ride creates a strong feeling of been-here,
done-this. When you seem ready to crash into a big door, you may
recall a similar near-crash on the defunct Mr. Toad's Wild Ride.
</P>
<P>
   But give the designer a shrewd award. The coolest part of the
ride, the speed test, takes you on a track that wraps outside the
front of the Test Track building. With mirrors, those waiting in
line see you fly past and it cements them in the line for the long
haul.
</P>
<P>
   Test Track replaces GM's World of Motion (1982-96).
</P>
<P>
   All-Star Movies is the third of Disney's lowest priced resorts
at $74 to $104 a night (depending on the season). Half the rooms
are ready now with the other half available in April.
</P>
<P>
   From check-in to the food court to the gift shop to the rooms,
the new Movies Resort mirrors neighboring All-Star Sports and Music
Resorts.
</P>
<P>
   Each All-Star resort has 1,920 rooms, and the buildings are
located near Disney's Animal Kingdom. The icons that define the
Movies Resort include three-story statues of Pongo and Perdita from
``101 Dalmatians'' and Buzz Lightyear from ``Toy Story.'' The
resort's 10 buildings have themes related to other Disney movies
including ``Mighty Ducks,'' ``Fantasia,'' and ``Love Bug.''
</P>
<P>
   The main pool is a Mighty Ducks theme with a giant hockey mask.
A kiddie pool features ``Fantasia'' water spouts and accompanying
symphony. Proving that Disney does not lack confidence in its
films, the Movie Resort's theme includes ``Fantasia 2000,'' due in
theaters at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   One new twist at Movies is soap/shampoo dispensers instead of
bars in the showers. (Just like a truck stop restroom.)
</P>
<P>
   The food court is a series of theater marquees such as Rialto,
Lyric, Grand. There's a bakery. Breakfast is $5 to $6 per person
with lunches a few bucks more. You can eat dinner _ pasta, pizza,
burgers _ for under $10.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasmic! is a new outdoor stage show behind The Twilight Zone
Tower of Terror at the Disney-MGM Studios. The 6,500-capacity
Hollywood Hills Amphitheater is filled _ half seated, half standing
_ an hour before the 7 p.m. show each night. (Show times can change
with park hours.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a good show if you invest as little time as possible
waiting. (Many late arrivals get the VIP rows that are empty at
showtime.)
</P>
<P>
   Against the night backdrop, Fantasmic! is performed on a big
stage sandwiched between a 1.9-million gallon moat and a man-made
mountain. You'll see Mickey Mouse's imagination under assault by
every famous Disney villain from Cruella de Vil to the Lion King's
Scar.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the audience who don't know there's a storyline,
this is simply a parade of Disney characters. The 25-minute show
includes 50 performers on cliffs and the waterway, fireworks,
music, thunder and lightning. A highlight is seeing a film
projected on a ``screen'' of spraying water.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasmic! premiered at California's Disneyland in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Disney's Rock 'n' Roller Coaster opens late summer at the
Disney/MGM Studios. It'll be Disney's second roller coaster. Space
Mountain at the Magic Kingdom is the first. The new indoor roller
coaster will take you on the road with a rock band rushing to a
recording session. The band, promised to be one we've all heard of,
will provide original music that goes with the ride.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz Lightyear's Space Ranger Spin, an interactive Magic Kingdom
ride, is great for mid-kids (age 8 to 12).
</P>
<P>
   Two kids (or adults) ride and shoot in an ``XP-37 space
cruiser'' that you can make spin in a full circle. You want to spin
because to your right and left are targets both riders are trying
to hit with a ``laser cannon.''
</P>
<P>
   Zap a target and watch the digital score climb on your
dashboard. The object is to save the universe and, while you're at
it, capture the evil Zurg. The targets you aim for are Emperor Zurg
insignias.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz Lightyear replaces the generic Take Flight that closed in
January '98 at the Magic Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Asia is the new addition to Animal Kingdom, Disney's fourth
theme park that opened last April.
</P>
<P>
   Here, you walk the Maharajah Jungle Trek with six Asian tigers
and a roost of giant fruit bats that you can see up close along
with a Komodo dragon, deer and tapir. There's also an aviary.
</P>
<P>
   The Kali River Rapids' 12-person raft ride opens this month.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
