<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   OLY-OLYMPIC-FOUNDATION _ ATLANTA _ The non-profit foundation
charged with building Atlanta's Olympic legacy has done essentially
nothing in the nearly three years that have passed since the Games
except funnel nearly $1 million to its chairman, Billy Payne.
Though the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation's stated tax-exempt
purpose is to foster amateur sports development, little has been
spent on youth athletics. A community Olympic development program
which pledged to pump $1 million into kids sports programs in
Atlanta has yet to get underway nearly three years after the Games,
and visions for an Olympic museum have yet to come into focus. Now
the foundation is on the verge of losing its public charity status
if it doesn't start raising money and giving it away. (Turner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MARCH-CIVILRIGHTS _ John Lewis leads a bipartisan congressional
delegation today across the Edmund Pettus Bridge to commemorate the
1965 march for voting rights of African Americans. This year's
march (he did it for the first time last year) takes on special
significance in light of the partisan rancor that has engulfed the
House this year. Several members of the Judiciary committee and the
Republican who presided over the impeachment debate will attend,
and Lewis sees it as a chance to help heal both racial and partisan
divides. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-SOUTH _ Fire-scarred Florida and other Southern states are
fighting a wave of winter wildfires triggered by unusually dry
weather. Troublesome fires have blazed in Alabama and South
Carolina, while in Florida the Gatorland tourist attraction in
Kissimmee was evacuated over last weekend when a large fire came
dangerously close. We round up the hot spots and check in with the
weather experts to see if the coming summer will be worse.
(MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FAITH-HEALING _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Rather than take her
grandmother to the hospital before she died, Jana Colosimo watched
members of her grandmother's church pour a mix of bleach and water
over her bed sores and then cover them with lard and gauze.
Colosimo's grandmother, a member of the General Assembly and Church
of the Firstborn, had fallen, probably breaking her hip, but the
church's strong belief in spiritual healing and the rejection of
medical help for the sick kept her from seeing a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Colosimo and her sister, Deborah Davis, believe she would have
gone to a doctor before her death if church members had not kept
such a close watch. (Joyce, Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
