A0166 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IDAHO-IMMUNIZE-NYT &LR;      03-06 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDAHO-IMMUNIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT TO INCREASE CHILD IMMUNIZATION IS UNDER ATTACK IN IDAHO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN STUEBNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ Jim Hawkins has a tough time understanding why
parents would not immunize their children from preventable diseases
like polio and hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins is Gov. Dirk Kempthorne's point man on a new initiative
to lift the state's immunization rates from a rank of 49th in the
nation to no lower than 10th. Hawkins contracted polio, hepatitis
and rheumatic fever while growing up in north Idaho in the late
1940s and early 1950s, when no vaccines were available.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was isolated for three months, and I was told that I might
not live through it,'' Hawkins said of his bout with polio in 1948.
``We need to give kids a chance at starting a healthy life. I
didn't have that chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Hawkins, who retired recently as director of the state's
Department of Commerce, pushes a bill in the Idaho Legislature to
create a statewide computerized immunization registry, he is
running into opposition from the Idaho Christian Coalition and
receiving hate mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried that the government wants to keep medical
records on every man, woman and child, and we'll have no right to
privacy,'' said Nancy Bloomer, executive director of the Christian
Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christian Coalition members also question the need for
certain vaccinations, and cast doubt on their effectiveness, Ms.
Bloomer said. Shots can cause bad side effects, too, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kempthorne and Hawkins are beginning to see at least one
reason why Idaho's immunization rates have hovered in the 70
percent range _ certain religious and anti-government groups do not
want the government telling them how to raise their children.
Followers of paramilitary groups and white separatists do not want
their children's names or Social Security numbers on any kind of
public lists.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the Idaho State Senate passed the statewide
registry bill 26 to 6, advancing the measure to the Idaho House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsor, State Sen. Jack Riggs, a physician in Coeur
d'Alene, noted that under the bill, parents must sign a form before
their children's names can be placed on the registry. No one is
obligated to be on the list, he said. A state survey of parents
indicates that more than 95 percent want their children to get
vaccinated against diseases, he said, adding that they just forget
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they're on a registry, they'll get a reminder phone call
or a postcard,'' Riggs said.
</P>
<P>
   Computerized registration links immunization data from
hospitals, health clinics and private doctors, making it easier to
keep track of vaccination records inside or outside the state.
Keeping track of shots can be difficult because children need about
20 shots by the age of 5.
</P>
<P>
   Low vaccination rates in Idaho have led to outbreaks of whooping
cough (pertussis), measles and rubella, health officials said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Idaho's effort, Hawkins is studying how other states
have achieved success. In Maine, which leads the nation with a 90
percent rate, the keys to success include providing free vaccines
to all medical providers, developing a two-state computerized
registry with New Hampshire and mail-out reminders, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate goal in Idaho, Hawkins said, is to give children a
healthy start, which should prepare them for school, college and a
promising career. ``We want give our children the best chance to
succeed in life,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
