<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-UNITY-NYT &LR;      03-06 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-UNITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS NEED TO REVIEW '92 IF THEY'RE TO PASS THIS YEAR'S CHEMISTRY
TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ If the New York Mets have not learned from
history, are they doomed to repeat it? That is a question hovering
over their heads as the Mets try to meld a new group of name
players into a cohesive unit and avoid the kind of meltdown that
scuttled the 1992 team, which was bolstered by a series of bold
moves.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen represented one of those moves. The Mets
acquired him in a trade with Kansas City, signed Bobby Bonilla and
Eddie Murray as free agents and hired Jeff Torborg as their highly
paid manager. As a result, they were a popular pick for the
division championship.
</P>
<P>
   Because of physical breakdowns, though, they fell far short.
They also had a chemistry problem, Saberhagen said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to compare this year's Mets with the Mets he joined six
years ago, Saberhagen, now a member of the Boston Red Sox, said:
``They have a great team on paper. We had the same thing in '92.
They've got a lot of different personalities on that team. It's a
matter of getting them all to blend and jell together and become a
team and not go out and play as individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen was one of the players whose injuries undermined the
Mets' chances in 1992. A sore arm left him unable to pitch after
May 15. Later in the season, Bonilla and Howard Johnson suffered
disabling injuries less than a week apart, and the Mets doubled
their deficit in the space of a week, falling from five and a half
games out on Aug. 2 to 11{ behind on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Not far below the surface, however, was a condition that was
just as devastating, Saberhagen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed like it was one thing after another,'' he
recalled. ``It was never baseball. I don't think we had a really
close-knit team. There were a few guys here and a few guys there,
not like the team we had here last year where everybody goes out to
dinner, hangs out together, always shooting the bull together.
Everybody was friendly on that Mets team, but everybody kind of had
their groups that they hung out in.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen attributed the condition to a difference in
personalities, which were never merged into a championship effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like living on a block and liking some of your neighbors
and not liking other neighbors,'' he said. ``You have to live with
them, but it doesn't mean you have to associate with them off the
field. When you see them around, you say hello, but you don't
invite them over to dinner. That was pretty much it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why do baseball people place so much emphasis on team chemistry?
(Jim Frey, former manager and general manager and nonconformist,
used to say, ``Give me a three-run home run and I'll show you good
team chemistry.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``If you play as a team on the field and get together and hang
out off the field, you don't have any problems,'' Saberhagen said.
``If you have a problem with somebody, it's talked about, you don't
go behind somebody's back. It just makes things a lot easier when
everybody gets along and everybody has one common goal and plays
hard to win ball games.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who will be 35 years old next month, said he did not
know if the current Mets team harbors the potential for problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get a lot of superstars together, that can possibly
happen,'' he said. ``I'm not saying it's going to, but it's always
a possibility. I think the best guy they have over there to stop
that stuff is Johnny Franco. Johnny doesn't put up with any
nonsense. If he sees things happening, he's the one guy who could
possibly keep the team clicking on all cylinders.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco, the relief pitcher, who has Saberhagen's baseball card
above his locker at Port St. Lucie, was in his third season with
the Mets in 1992. Why didn't he oil the cylinders then?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was my place to stop it then,'' he said.
``But now I'm the elder statesman. You know what to look for.''
</P>
<P>
   And is there anything he has to look for?
</P>
<P>
   ``You're still going to have your little cliques here and
there,'' he said, ``but the last few years everybody's pretty much
hung out together.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
