<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      03-06 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Yuck, New Yuck
</P>
<P>
   Mel Rojas played baseball for eight months in New York _ two
months in 1997 after the Mets obtained him from the Chicago Cubs
and all of last season. He did not enjoy himself, and his record
reflected it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of trouble pitching in New York,'' said Rojas, the
relief pitcher, who also had trouble pitching in Chicago. ``I don't
feel comfortable in that city. I really don't like that city. When
I played in Montreal, I said I don't like to play in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Why doesn't he like to play in New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many Latin people there,'' said Rojas, a native of the
Dominican Republic. ``Every time I play there, they're looking for
me and call me everywhere. All my friends call me. I couldn't get
good concentration in that city. There are a lot of distractions
over there. I don't like that city.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, who last season had a 6.05 earned run average and allowed
a .305 batting average and 101 base-runners in 58 innings, said he
welcomed his trade to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I didn't want to go back over there,'' he said.
``I said I want a trade anywhere, but I don't want to go back to
New York. The thing is I don't like that city. Any place but New
York. I've never liked New York. I feel comfortable here so far. I
can't say anything about the city in Los Angeles. It's got to be
better than New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to clarify Rojas' position, he doesn't like New York.
</P>
<P>
   A Personal Hitting Coach
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Baerga has nothing against New York; he just doesn't like
what he did there. Playing for the Mets, he had the two worst
seasons of his career. He was depressed enough to do something
about it. He hired a personal hitting coach.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Morales, who was a coach in Cleveland when Baerga played
there, was his choice, and Morales worked with him in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to him, `I really need you to find what I'm doing
wrong,''' said Baerga, now with the St. Louis Cardinals. ``I sent
him some videos before he came to Puerto Rico. He watched me
hitting a lot so when he came down, we talked about what I was
doing wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   At the ball park where Baerga and Morales worked, the second
baseman had a friend tape his batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we went to my house and watched tapes from Cleveland and
the Mets,'' Baerga said. ``The way I hit before, I used my legs and
body. With the Mets, I was just using my hands. The power wasn't
there. We worked for a week and a half, and it was really good.''
</P>
<P>
   It's early in the exhibition schedule, but Baerga said he feels
he has regained his old hitting form. ``I feel it in the way I hit
the ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The work has also produced positive results for the coach.
Baerga talked to Tony La Russa, the Cardinals' manager, about
Morales, and La Russa agreed it would be a good idea to have
Morales in camp as an extra hitting instructor.
</P>
<P>
   But even better, Baerga said, ``They might keep him after the
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   A More Relaxed Pace
</P>
<P>
   The look was different. Standing near the batting cage on a
Minnesota Twins practice field in Fort Myers, Joe McIlvaine wore
sneakers and blue jeans, a sign of relaxation. He can afford to
relax these days because he is no longer a general manager, but a
scout.
</P>
<P>
   ``As general manager, you are responsible for a lot of people,''
said McIlvaine, officially a special assistant to Twins General
Manager Terry Ryan. ``A lot of people report to you. A lot of
people are dependent upon your decisions. The difference in this
job is I don't have anyone really reporting to me, except the Latin
American guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get back to your hotel, the phone doesn't have the
red light on. When you used to go back before, you'd have your list
of 15 calls from people who were looking for you or who needed
advice or needed a decision. You're more of an independent doing
what I'm doing. You make your own schedule and go do it.''
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine, who scouts players at all levels, is doing what some
other Mets executives suggested he was doing _ whatever he
preferred _ leading up to his dismissal as their general manager
during the 1997 season. No one said it publicly, but privately
people said McIlvaine often was not available for meetings and did
not take care of matters he was asked to handle. In short, they
said, he had lost interest in the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things said that weren't accurate,''
McIlvaine said, obviously still not pleased with the picture that
was painted then. ``I chose silence. I didn't want to get into the
public debate about things like that. If that's the way they felt,
fine. But I was a professional. I was there to do my job and I did
my job.''
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine still lives in the New York area and closely follows
the team for which he worked so many years. ``I enjoyed my 15 years
with the Mets,'' he said. ``I'm realistic. Things like that are
going to happen to you. It's part of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   McIlvaine, who worked his way up through the scouting ranks,
said he plans to remain in baseball at whatever level he finds
himself. ``I'm a baseball lifer,'' he said. Does he want to be a
general manager again? ``If the opportunity came along again, I
would have to consider it,'' he said, ``but I'm not going to jump
into something just because it's a general manager's job.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1424EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
