<HEADER>
A0178 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-TEACHERS-2takes     03-06 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-TEACHERS-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS FEAR UNION MUSCLE DILUTING CALIFORNIA EDUCATION REFORM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TERRY HARDY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO -- &UR;  &LR; Nobody really wants to discuss it. Nobody wants
to make the new governor mad. Nobody wants to kill a fragile deal
when everybody wants to believe there is a quick fix for
California's failing public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a glaring hole in Gov. Gray Davis' school reform
plan, one that critics say could fundamentally defeat the entire
effort to improve public education.
</P>
<P>
   Although principals could be fired if their schools don't
perform well and students could be denied diplomas, there is no
provision to make it easier to get rid of bad teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about the governor wanting his victory, but there
is nothing approaching accountability for teachers in these reforms
_ this is truly the `Emperor Has No Clothes' story,'' said state
Sen. Ray Haynes, R-Riverside, one of the few willing to publicly
protest Davis' centerpiece education plan. ``The teachers unions
are cashing in all their chips. They gave to the governor and
helped get him elected _ this is where they get their payback.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Assemblyman Tom McClintock, R-Granada Hills: ``It's all
symbolism and very little substance.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other lawmakers and education groups want to sidestep the
issue. Not only are the reforms the governor's No. 1 priority, but
the bills are authored by such heavy-hitting lawmakers as Assembly
Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, D-Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Sacramento insiders warn of the ``delicacy'' of the
situation, and wonder how to explain the unequal accountability
provisions in ``politically correct'' terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the governor's proposal makes it easier to fire an
incompetent teacher, and without that, there is no real way to
change what's going on in our schools,'' noted one education
insider who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's education experts, as well as union officials,
deny that Davis is going soft on teachers. Education Undersecretary
Sue Burr said the governor is committed to doing what is necessary
to improve California's schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is not to fire teachers. Our goal is to improve the
teaching force we have,'' Burr said. She added that charges that
Davis was paying back unions were absolutely untrue.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bergan, president of the California Federation of Teachers,
agreed, saying that her organization was pushing for reforms and
better teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Bergan said her organization appreciates that Davis' plan
included more attention and support to teachers, but it has
reservations about the speed of implementation and provisions that
make accountability mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the bill we would write,'' Bergan said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Davis administration, as well as outside
education experts, say teachers' acceptance of the education
reforms is crucial.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, some say, recent events in the Los Angeles
Unified School District could point to more problems ahead for
implementation of the governor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers union, United Teachers Los Angeles, recently
convinced a majority of the Los Angeles school board to grant
instructors a pay increase without tying the raise to performance.
</P>
<P>
   During negotiations, union leaders were even unwilling to
approve accountability measures for their worst 150 teachers _ out
of a 36,000-strong teaching force _ who received unsatisfactory
evaluations. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Given the Los Angeles school board's unwillingness to adopt
accountability reforms for its instructors _ and with the same
attitude coming from Sacramento _ critics believe that reform of
public schools throughout the state will be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at our history, I'm not optimistic about our future,''
said Eli Brent, president of the Associated Administrators of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It is a rare occurrence when teachers are fired within the LAUSD
and even rarer for a teacher to be forced out because of
incompetence, said Howard Friedman, assistant general counsel for
the school district. In an average year, there are eight to 10
cases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That includes cases that range from molesting to abuse to
actual incompetence _ and that is the rarest type of case,''
Friedman said. ``Getting to the point of dismissal for an
incompetent teacher is such an encumbered, laborious process that
there is a tendency not to want to take on a task that takes 30
percent to 40 percent of your time.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes more than a year to document an incompetent teacher and
bring the case for action before the school board. If the teacher
fights dismissal, then the cases go before the Commission on
Professional Competence. Rarely, if ever, does the district prevail
there on incompetency cases, Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD is not alone in this problem. For that reason, many
districts with successful reform plans, such as the Chicago school
district, have included expedited measures to fire teachers. And
many experts believe that those potential severe consequences are a
key part of reform plans.
</P>
<P>
   (second take to follow)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1429EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0179 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-TEACHERS-2nd-ta     03-06 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-TEACHERS-2nd-take-LADN </SLUG>
  
SACRAMENTO: reform plans.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruno Manno, a senior fellow at the Annie E. Casey Foundation in
Baltimore, a nonprofit organization that looks at education reform
and other efforts for disadvantaged children, agreed. He said
successful accountability plans must have three components: clear
standards, a way to assess progress, and rewards and sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These efforts have to be across the board, for kids, for
principals and for teachers _ and some would say even for
parents,'' Manno said. ``Systems that lack those components are
full of holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' goals for education reforms are making their way through
the Legislature on a fast track, with an eye on final approval by
the end of this month. They call for intensive reading instruction
for struggling students; an exit exam for students before receiving
their diploma; peer review and support for teachers; and an
accountability system that would rank all 8,000 schools and set up
rewards and sanctions for the 430 worst-performing campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Within those bills are provisions for increased teacher training
and support. Individual teacher evaluation is mostly addressed
within the peer review law, authored by Villaraigosa. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Carl Cohn, superintendent of the Long Beach Unified School
District, said he believes Davis is gambling with California
schools' success by pushing the largely untried peer review system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a one-size-fits-all answer for the 1,000 districts
in California,'' Cohn said. ``What evidence does Gray Davis have
about the efficacy of this type of approach? I don't believe he has
any.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it was first written as a mandatory plan, teachers
unions successfully won an amended, voluntary version that requires
any peer review system to be collectively bargained.
</P>
<P>
   However, districts that do not participate will lose part of
$419million in state teaching assistance funds.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers will go through peer review automatically if they are
given an unsatisfactory performance evaluation. Or instructors can
ask for help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Critics point out that the evaluation process ends with a
report.
</P>
<P>
   As one education expert, who asked not to be named, said: ``So
what if an evaluation goes into a file? These teachers are still
tenured, and tenure goes on a long, long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the accountability system bill, the measure provides for
a series of increasingly serious actions if a school does not
improve student achievement _ as evaluated by test scores and
attendance. Under those provisions, all teachers at failing schools
can be transferred. The principal, however, faces the threat of
dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Richard Alarcon, D-Van Nuys, pushed through an
amendment that would allow the principals at failing schools to be
fired only if they have had control of the school's budget,
curriculum and personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The laws do not allow teachers to be evaluated by their
classrooms' test results, except for a small part of the exam that
is now aligned to state standards.
</P>
<P>
   McClintock, who voted for the two education bills that have come
before the Assembly _ the reading initiative and peer review _ said
he did so reluctantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very small step in the right direction, but the bills
won't likely translate into anything effective because they are so
badly framed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Given that Davis has a Democrat-controlled Legislature behind
him, the governor missed a chance to implement real reforms,
McClintock said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Change is controversial and threatening,'' he said. ``When you
go the way of a centrist, you have no intention of changing the
status quo. When this is all over, the school system will be
slightly more expensive and slightly less productive than the year
before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1429EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-HURD-NYT     03-06 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HURD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
T. NORMAN HURD, 88, ROCKEFELLER'S CONFIDANT
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By ERIC PACE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   T. Norman Hurd, a budget director for the state of New York
under Gov. Nelson A. Rockefeller and the governor's close
confidant, died on Feb. 27 at his home in Loudonville, N.Y., a
suburb of Albany. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd, who earned his doctorate in agricultural business
management at Cornell University, was budget director under Gov.
Thomas E. Dewey from 1950 to 1954 and under Rockefeller from 1959
to 1971, when Rockefeller named him director of state operations.
From 1956 to 1958, Hurd was a member of the State Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   By late 1971, he had become Rockefeller's treasured factotum and
was admired by colleagues in state government for his attention to
detail. Hurd was ``noted for boiling down pages of detail into
understandable notions for the governor,'' The New York Times said
that year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Hurd was appointed secretary to the governor by
Rockefeller.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd served in that post for the rest of Rockefeller's tenure as
governor and also under the next governor, Malcolm Wilson. After
Rockefeller became vice president in 1974, Hurd joined his vice
presidential staff as a special assistant.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, his name was mentioned in a furor involving
N.Y. state political figures and the nursing home industry. One
state commission issued a report in 1976 that said Rockefeller was
to blame for political influence, official neglect and poor care
that it said were rife in the nursing home industry while he was
governor. But the report said that Rockefeller and Hurd regarded
their repeated interventions in nursing home matters as ``mere
courtesies,'' and that they had denied that they had had an
intimidating effect on civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd was active in the affairs of the Nelson A. Rockefeller
Institute of Government, based in Albany, and was an editor of the
book ``Rockefeller in Retrospect: The Governor's New York Legacy''
(1984).
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Michigan, and worked on a family farm from until
he was 17. He graduated in 1931 from Michigan State College and
received his doctorate in 1936. He taught agricultural economics on
the Cornell campus and became a full professor in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Anne Wolstenholme Hurd, died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Hurd is survived by a son, Hollis T. Hurd of Pittsburgh; two
daughters, Linda Hurd Ewing of West Lafayette, Ind., and Sandra
Hurd Hennemeyer of St. Louis; three grandchildren; one
great-grandchild; a brother, Russell, of Detroit; and two sisters,
Frieda Broadway and Mary Bricker, both of Yale, Mich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
