<HEADER>
A0185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOATING-FROSTBITING-N     03-06 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-FROSTBITING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SAILORS OF WINTER: IN THE COLD, COLD SEA 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: NY, NJ, Conn.) (fb) 
 By CAITLIN KELLY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARCHMONT, N.Y. _ Larchmont Yacht Club, which began its
frostbiting program in 1932, has the oldest winter fleet in the
Northeast, says Stanley Bell, a former racer and frostbiter who has
headed the club's race committee for 19 years. Despite the many
skeptics (Sailing? In the winter?), frostbiting has its
accomplished devotees. It is absolutely not a place for beginners
to come out and test their skills.
</P>
<P>
   When a day of racing means the wind-chill is minus 15 and the
water temperature can kill you, recreational racers stay close to
the fire while the truly hard-core head for the water. And several
big-boat racers who enjoy top positions in summer regattas
skippering their 40- to 45-footers find themselves pushed to the
middle of this small, fast fleet by the intense competition, Bell
said. This weekly nautical ferocity on Long Island Sound comes
contained in 11.5-foot Interclub dinghies.
</P>
<P>
   Larchmont's frostbiting fleet, which officially numbers 72 but
usually fields 60, includes the Mallory Cup winner Bill Healy, who
drives 90 minutes from Niantic, Conn., to enjoy the high-level
competition. Racers range in age from 15 to 68, and include many
college all-Americans, sailmakers and the former Olympic silver
medalist Steve Benjamin. Six to eight women regularly compete.
</P>
<P>
   Cedar Point Yacht Club, in Westport, Conn., races 14-foot Lasers
in the winter, with a fleet of about 60, according to the club
manager, Stephen Shaw. Cedar Point, which has had a frostbiting
fleet for 15 years, has 24 to 10 boats out every Sunday. They are
single-man boats, and being an Olympic class, attract serious
racers who want to stay in shape year-round. While frostbiting,
with its use of small boats, bundled-up competitors, shorter, more
numerous races and eccentric dedication, invites comparisons to
adult bumper cars, it is as serious as big-boat action.
</P>
<P>
   Don Woodsworth of Northport, N.Y., was out on a sunny, crisp
Saturday recently at Larchmont wearing a red hat with earflaps, a
drysuit, black bike shorts over the top and yellow rubber gloves
with olive-green army-surplus wool liners. He looked, as did most
of the racers, like a cross between Captain Nemo, the Michelin Man
and a mad scientist. He laughed, and didn't care: frostbiters are a
breed apart from the blue-blazer, pressed-khakis crowd. ``It's the
only exercise I get in the winter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Norton, a manufacturer of kitchen counters from Ramsey,
N.J., was out on the water, too, competing with fellow American
Yacht Club members in a team event against sailors from Seawanhaka,
a club in Oyster Bay on Long Island. In the summer, Norton usually
races a Thistle out of Nyack, N.Y., on the Hudson River, but takes
out a winter membership at American in Rye, N.Y., in order to
frostbite. There, they race 30 11-foot Cook 11's. Norton, who
happily admits to being obsessed with frostbiting, said that he
even races in winds up to 25 knots although these small craft start
tipping in winds as low as 10 to 12 knots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very tippy boat downwind,'' he said. That Saturday,
Norton was wearing long johns, sweat pants, wool socks inside heavy
construction boots and ski gloves. Most of his competitors wore
drysuits, one-piece rubber affairs that seal at the neck and
wrists. You step in, squat deeply to burp out all the air, then
have a friend zip up the suit across the width of your shoulders.
Since frostbiters expect to fall into the water, and often do,
staying warm and mostly dry, is essential.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first go in, it's not so bad,'' Norton said. ``Then
you thank God you're wearing your drysuit and your life jacket.
You're paralyzed after about 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   What attracts Norton to frostbiting is competition. ``I'm racing
here against guys who own and race Mumm 30's, Etchells, Sonars,''
he said. ``You're getting to compete against all the best in a boat
we all can afford.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Mooney, a graduate student in marine biology who was
representing Seawanhaka, says the club's frostbiting fleet includes
20 Lasers, 4 Vanguards and 6 Dyers. ``I like the crowd that does
it,'' she said. ``It's a different atmosphere, a more cohesive
group.''
</P>
<P>
   The winds are fiercer in winter, she notes, the water freezing,
the fleet skilled. ``A lot of people just don't have the confidence
to frostbite,'' she said. ``I discourage beginners from trying it.
It can get very shifty and very puffy so it's a lot easier to
capsize. We sail close to shore and that tends to exaggerate the
puffs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not a sport likely to be overrun with devotees,''
Woodsworth said. ``People either think it's dangerous or not
enjoyable.'' Dozens of grinning red-cheeked faces on the line tell
a different story.
</P>
</TEXT>
