<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0197 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUHAMMED-ALI-PROJECT-     03-06 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUHAMMED-ALI-PROJECT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOATING, AS EVER, ALI BUILDS HIS LEGACY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ An ornately dressed woman who had changed her
name to Nana Yaa Asantewa rushed across the lobby of Central High
School and flung herself at a large man who had changed his name to
Muhammad Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gloria Brady, Gloria Brady, 1959,'' she cried. ``Remember what
you did in Mrs. Robinson's Latin class?''
</P>
<P>
   The former Cassius Clay scrunched up his face at the former
Gloria Brady and clucked his tongue as he threw three short
upper-cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You remembered!'' she said. Her own face became a girl's
again. ``Oh, we were so serious in that class. Mrs. Robinson wanted
us to make something of ourselves. We loved it when you stuck your
head in. It was a breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the executive producer of an African-American arts program,
Asantewa turned to the gathering audience of students and teachers.
``We laughed at him,'' she said. ``He had a rinky-dink bike. He
said he was going to be a champion boxer. We teased him, but he
never got mad. He just cuddled you. He's what he always was. He
gave us kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   If the visit to Ali's old high school had not been at the sudden
whim of a reporter, it might have seemed like the perfectly
orchestrated photo op and sound bite for the 57-year-old former
champion's most ambitious project since he first challenged Sonny
Liston for the heavyweight title 35 years ago. He and his wife,
Lonnie, also a Louisville native, are leading the development of an
$80 million downtown riverfront center that will celebrate Ali as
boxer, social lightning rod, Muslim and Parkinson's disease patient
as a way to reach adolescents with messages of racial, gender,
religious and ethnic healing and tolerance. The Alis, who live on
an 80-acre farm in Michigan with their adopted 8-year-old son,
Asaad, say they hope to relocate to 25 acres or so outside
Louisville once the center is closer to reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just don't call it a museum,'' said Lonnie Ali, his
42-year-old fourth wife. ``This is about what he stood for, what he
paid a price for. I want it done while he's alive so the kids who
come can actually touch him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali is touchable. In fact, he seems to derive his energy from
the affection of strangers. His voice rarely rises above a phlegmy
whisper that must often be interpreted by Lonnie. His gait is
frequently unsteady and his facial expressions depend more on
twinkle and glow than mobility. But he has no trouble communicating
_ when he feels engaged. Bored at dinner here with a reporter he
had known since 1964 (``If I had a lower IQ, I might enjoy your
interview,'' he said amiably), he took off his shoes under the
table and napped between courses. He would happily wake to greet
visitors who apologized for disturbing his meal but just had to
tell him how much he had meant in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   It was only his wife's stern warnings that could keep him from
offering the visitors one of his inappropriate jokes. Somehow, they
seemed endearing from an athlete who claimed to have thrown his
Olympic medal off the Second Street Bridge in 1960 after he was
denied restaurant service because of his color. He might ignore
Lonnie to ask, ``What did Abraham Lincoln say when he woke up from
a two-day drunk?'' While his audience blinked in confusion, he
would answer himself, ``I freed who?'' and burst into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie would roll her eyes in mock despair. She revels in his
``lightness,'' she says, and imagines that he is cloaked with a
holy innocence that allows him to believe that the universe will
protect him no matter what he says or does. So far, despite
injurious ring defeats, three divorces, worldwide controversy,
serious illness and financial setbacks, he has been protected.
</P>
<P>
   When she married him 12 years ago, she said, his affairs were in
``disarray.'' In late 1996, after he lighted the Olympic torch in
Atlanta with shaking hands, he became the world's darling in ways
that eluded him even when he floated like a butterfly and stung
like a bee.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, according to Louisville politicians and boosters,
the city has become serious about honoring Ali as a native son and
using his celebrity to raise its visibility and ranking among other
smaller cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got an international airport now and international
companies, and we want people to visit us,'' said Mayor David
Armstrong at City Hall, while Ali dozed at his conference table.
``What better person to open a window to help us think about and
understand tolerance, and to appreciate our differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Ali snapped awake at that, and while his wife tensed for a joke,
he merely said, ``The schools are integrated now.''
</P>
<P>
   The city donated a site on the Ohio River said to be worth $10
million, near the Louisville Slugger Museum and factory and the
performing arts center.
</P>
<P>
   State aid and private contributions raised by board members
total about $30 million, according to Larry G. Townsend, pro bono
chairman of the Muhammad Ali Center. Townsend, who attended Ali's
first pro fight here when both were 18, is chairman of Riverboat
Development Inc., which operates a nearby gambling casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be an institution for dreamers,'' said
Townsend, who was secretary of commerce under the former governor
John Y. Brown. Along with the former mayor Jerry E. Abramson, Brown
was a prime mover of the project.
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie is a tall, handsome woman whose light-skinned, freckly
face is reminiscent of Ali's mother. Their mothers were friends and
neighbors. Lonnie says she determined at 17 that she would someday
marry the champ. While waiting out two wives, she graduated from
Vanderbilt and received a master's in business administration from
UCLA. Lonnie is as mystical as she is practical. She says that her
preparation included, besides the degrees, martyrdom in a previous
life as a nun in South America. Born Catholic, she converted to
Islam in 1982, four years before marrying Ali.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fanatical about protecting him and his name because he
means too much to the world,'' she said. ``America has a way of
tearing down its heroes. I've assumed a responsibility, like Rachel
Robinson or Jeannie Ashe or Coretta Scott King.''
</P>
<P>
   At that, Ali woke up from dinner to ask, ``If a Mexican, a
Puerto Rican and a black guy are sitting in the back of a car, who
is driving?''
</P>
<P>
   Lonnie shook her head. ``Oh, Muhammad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A policeman,'' he said. He milked his laugh, then returned to
sleep mode.
</P>
<P>
   After dinner, he seemed tired and eager to go up to his room
until he was spotted by a crowd of business people drinking in the
lobby. As they surrounded him, patted him, told him how good he
looked, he plucked a red handkerchief from his jacket pocket. He
made it vanish inside his fist. The crowd applauded. Ali did it
again, and then explained the trick, which involved a false thumb.
He said it was a sin to deceive people; he didn't want anyone to
think he had magical powers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she thought there was something slightly pathetic about
this lobby lounge act, Lonnie shrugged. ``He loves to entertain and
they want to be entertained.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   At Central High, it was hard to get beyond personal
hero-worship. Students knew he was ``the Greatest,'' and he
referred to them as ``my people.'' The administrators, who were
close to his age, were just as star-struck. His former classmate,
Gloria Brady, was entranced. ``We loved to just look at him, he was
so cute,'' she said. ``He hasn't changed at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The last official stop of the Alis' 24-hour visit was a meeting
with the mayor. As a weary Ali lumbered up the City Hall steps,
throwaway cameras began clicking and flashing in front of the faces
of 20 young men and women. They were Catholics and Protestants from
Ireland and Northern Ireland who had recently arrived in neutral
Kentucky to get to know each other in a peace and reconciliation
program called Wider Horizons. They had interrupted their own
ceremonial visit when they heard Ali was on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 16- to 21-year-olds were toddlers at best when Ali
last fought, in 1981. But they said they knew all about him, his
life and his career. Pictures snapped, they flowed down the steps
in a tide of love. Ali's step quickened as he climbed to meet
them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
