<HEADER>
A0201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     03-06 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE HEAVYWEIGHT THINKER WHO LIKES HIS CHESS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTRUN, Pa. _ In a black tank top, black-and-blue tights, white
boxing shoes and a white cap, Lennox Lewis was on display for the
last time here at the Caesars Brookdale resort among the bare trees
in the Poconos. Soon he would be in a limo Friday night on the way
to a midtown New York hotel to await next Saturday's heavyweight
title showdown with Evander Holyfield at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as Lewis moved around the ring in the resort's Fun and
Fitness Center, his trainer, Emanuel Steward, assessed the World
Boxing Council champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technical things, he's done everything I've wanted him to
do since I took over four years ago,'' Steward said. ``Like
balance. I'm big on balance. He's definitely improved that. But he
could be a little crisper with his delivery. Put more punches
together rather than looking to throw the big right hand. And he
could utilize his left jab more instead of pawing with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward paused.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still doesn't always throw punches instinctively,'' the
boxing sculptor of Thomas `Hit Man' Hearns and several other world
champions said. ``He has a tendency to think too much.''
</P>
<P>
   To think too much?
</P>
<P>
   ``To hesitate,'' he said. ``Against Zeljko Mavrovic, he had
chances to end the fight, but he hesitated when he should have been
throwing punches. He won, but the fight went the distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Why does he hesitate?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a chess player,'' Steward said. ``I wish he wouldn't play
chess so much. When he's playing chess, sometimes he'll take 20
minutes to think about making a move. In boxing, you don't have
time to think. Boxing is instinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Steward ever had a boxer who plays chess?
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is the first one I've had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To kill time in their training camps, most boxers play cards,
listen to music or just sleep. Oscar De La Hoya sometimes plays
golf. Before dethroning Jack Dempsey as the heavyweight champion in
1926, Gene Tunney was seen reading, of all things, Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   But a chess player? Lennox Lewis apparently is unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can play two or three games at once, but I don't,'' the
English heavyweight was saying now after his workout. ``I'm not the
best player in my camp. Frazzle beats me.
</P>
<P>
   Frazzle, alias Scott DeMercardo, accompanies Lewis on the
heavyweight's morning roadwork.
</P>
<P>
   But if thinking too long about chess moves translates to Lewis'
hesitating instead of throwing punches instinctively, it hasn't
caused Lewis to hesitate about why he thinks he will unify the
heavyweight title by ending Holyfield's reign as the champion of
both the World Boxing Association and the International Boxing
Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win,'' Lewis said, ``all I need to do is just be right on
the night. Assert myself. Do everything I'm supposed to do. Evander
Holyfield has never seen no one like me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Holyfield has seen Mike Tyson for 11 rounds and three
rounds, and won twice. He's seen George Foreman for 12 rounds, and
won. He's seen Buster Douglas for three rounds, and won. He's also
seen Riddick Bowe for 12, 12 and 8 rounds, and won only once. He's
seen Michael Moorer for 12 and eight rounds, and won once and lost
once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holyfield has no particular strength,'' Lewis said. ``He has a
good left jab, a good left hook, good combinations, but they only
work against somebody who's there to be hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old Holyfield, who usually disdains making a
prediction, has proclaimed that he will stop the 33-year-old Lewis
in the third round of their scheduled 12-round bout, an almost
instant Garden sellout that will be available on TVKO pay-per-view.
The prediction stunned Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Evander to do that was peculiar and funny, but I'm trying
to think of a better word,'' he said. ``Just say the audacity of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with chess perhaps subconsciously causing Lewis to
hesitate before throwing punches, Steward believed that the
6-foot-5-inch Lewis, whose wingspan is 6{ inches longer than
Holyfield's, will win because he is a naturally stronger boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holyfield's a weight lifter; he's artificially strong,''
Steward said. ``Lennox is like George Foreman and Sonny Liston
were, naturally strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has a 34-1 record, with 27 knockouts, losing only to
Oliver McCall in a second-round knockout that dethroned him as the
WBC champion in 1994. He regained the title in 1997 when McCall
wouldn't fight. He has retained it against Henry Akinwande, Andrew
Golota, Shannon Briggs and Mavrovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect Holyfield to be very aggressive,'' Steward said,
``but he has to alter his whole style because he's not used to
fighting taller guys. He has to try to get inside, but that won't
be easy. And whenever Lennox has been in a big fight, he has always
been more aggressive. Exceptionally aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   But as a heavyweight who plays chess, Lennox Lewis can't afford
to think too much.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
