<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-EVANDER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Holyfield: `Stronger than I ever have been'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He is at the strangest of crossroads, a 36-year-old
eager to take hold of not only this era in his profession but
others, a champion who visualizes a globe-trot to open the new
millennium and close his career while at the same time somewhat
returning to the start line of his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I'm stronger today than I ever have been before,'' said
Evander Holyfield, and though he could have been speaking of his
physical strength, he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Already holder of the WBA and IBF heavyweight title belts,
Holyfield aims to bring boxing's other major alphabet accessory to
his collection Saturday when he meets WBC champion Lennox Lewis at
New York's Madison Square Garden. The winner will be the first
unified heavyweight champion since Riddick Bowe defeated Holyfield
in 1992, only to fracture the crown one month later by literally
throwing the WBC belt in a garbage can rather than fight a
mandatory bout against Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Bowe's ill-fated decision was one Holyfield would never make,
for as he said, ``When you're the unified champion and you say
you're the best, nobody can say, `Well, that's just a matter of
opinion.'''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who completed training for Lewis last week in
Houston, feels certain he will smother any lingering doubts that he
is the division's best. The greater battle in public opinion comes
in his personal life, having acknowledged six months ago that he
fathered two more children out of wedlock since his marriage to his
second wife, Janice, in 1996. Although adultery was a basis for
Holyfield's first divorce and he already had fathered three
out-of-wedlock children, the latest admission set off a firestorm
of criticism in the public and the media, especially with the
backdrop of his very public religious convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Evander and Janice Holyfield went through several counseling
sessions but those have since ceased, and Evander says the two are
separated. He will not discuss the future of the marriage. He says
only that he has had extensive counseling himself for, what he
terms, ``the problems I've had,'' and adds, ``I feel like now I'm a
better man.''
</P>
<P>
   Greater inner strength has been needed to fend off the public
attacks. Most recently, Lewis called Holyfield a ``hypocrite,'' and
reiterated his remarks this week, adding, ``I'm only saying what
people think. If I say I don't drink and I drink, I'd be a
hypocrite. I'm just citing reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield is taking the barbs in stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way things will change is by changing your life and
not doing those things any more,'' he said. ``This is what I did.
But I've been able to construct a better life for myself. Was it an
embarrassment for myself? Yeah. But it was more embarrassing when
it happened than when the story was told. As a matter of fact, when
the story was told, I was more relieved. You know, when you do
something dumb, it's going to come to life at some point in time.
People came up to me and said, `You met with a writer to talk about
that? For what?' But I said, `Well, it was the truth. It's not like
anybody made me go out and do it.' The question is, how did it
inspire you? Did it inspire you to be better or did it inspire you
to be sneaky? It inspired me to be better. I pray and I thank God
for giving me the knowledge to change. I was able to get
counseling. The family's a lot better. If you hurt your family, the
whole thing is to not hurt them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Janice Holyfield did not want her husband speaking publicly of
the affairs in September, but Evander said, ``To me it was better
at that time than, all of sudden, if we were to get divorced, have
people say, `Oh, he's gonna leave that girl. Look what he did to
her.' Now, whatever happens, people are going to realize, `Well, he
made a bad decision in that relationship.' But this is the reason
these things happen. There was no love.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield actually believed the criticism could have been much
worse. He attended a Braves game shortly after the admission and
recalled people cheering for him. ``My attorney turned to me and
said, `I thought they were going to boo you,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield had prepared his children for cruel jokes from
classmates, but he said, ``Thankfully, that didn't happen. . . . I
had told them, `Look, your daddy made some mistakes, and somebody
asks you about this, you just say, ``He taught us not to make the
same mistakes so we wouldn't have to suffer like him.'''''
</P>
<P>
   Life is good, Holyfield says. He is finally living in his
54,000-square foot, $18 million dream house in Fayette County, even
if the decorations have taken a bigger bite out of his budget than
he expected. To furnish the formal living room alone cost $450,000.
But when his decorator sent him a bill for $250,000 for ``bows and
mirrors,'' he drew the line. ``I told her to take it all back,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Not that finances are a problem. He will earn at least $20
million Saturday, bringing his career ring earnings to $205
million, including $92 million in the last five fights. He could
have afforded the bows and mirrors.
</P>
<P>
   Of more importance to Holyfield right now is his legacy. Ring
Magazine recently placed him as the third greatest heavyweight in
history behind only Muhammad Ali and Joe Louis. Holyfield smiled
when asked about that, and then said, ``I'm not done fighting
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he will be soon, although he has said that before.
Before being beaten by Michael Moorer in 1994, Holyfield vowed to
retire in 1996, exclaiming, ``When they snuff out that Olympic
flame, they can snuff me out, too.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about that now, he said, ``I told the truth. They did
snuff me out. But I never said my flame wouldn't be lit again. My
new career started with God. God started promoting me.''
</P>
<P>
   An improbable rebirth in the sport followed. The medical
clearance from the Mayo Clinic after a misdiagnosed heart ailment.
Uneven performances again men were more comfortable, because they
were intimidated by his knowledge.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary said, ``Every time we'd take a break, all the men would be
over there by my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   The Taylors also went coastal with their fly rods, guiding
mainly for redfish at Bray's Island Plantation in South Carolina
1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the Taylors have had fun, which is a suggestion
both have for the frustrated angler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had days when I've taken some guys down the river that
were tight as banjo strings,'' he recalls. ``We got halfway down
the river, and I'd drop the anchor. I'd sit cross-ways in the boat
and say, `I'm taking a nap. When y'all want to go on down the river
let me know. We're going to enjoy this day. Y'all need to chill out
a little bit. It's not only about catching fish.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's not just about catching fish. If a man wants to go
lean up against an old mossy oak tree on the side of the river and
not even string up his rod, that's still fly fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
