<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pricey private streams jump with trophy trout
 &HT;    By Scott Bernarde
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HIAWASSEE, Ga. _ You don't just lean from the banks of the
Chattahoochee River and catch trout the size that they grow on this
short stretch of stream south of Lake Chatuge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They average 22 inches here,'' says Lee Howard, manager of the
Upper Hi Fly Fishing and Outfitters in Hiawassee, whose store also
runs the Hiawassee River Trout Lodge, which includes five cabins
located along the trophy trout stream. ``The biggest one I've ever
gotten out of here was 34 inches (a brown trout). And it probably
weighed 15 or 16 pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Places like the Hiawassee River Trout Lodge offer trout-fishing
experiences thought to be available only in a Rocky Mountain
stream. The memory comes at a cost, however. The Hiawassee stream
costs $150 per night for a cabin, but you can also pay a $125 rod
fee for a day's fishing without lodging. Other private streams _
the Brigadoon on the Soque River and Nacoochee Bend on the
Chattahoochee River near Helen _ have similar pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Some cheaper alternatives exist, including state-run Duke's
Creek, Water's Creek and Smith Creek _ the ``lower-income version
of trophy waters,'' says Jeff Durniak, Wildlife Resources Division
regional fisheries supervisor based in Gainesville. It takes only a
$2 parking pass at Duke's and Smith, and a WMA stamp to fish
Water's. There's a 15-angler limit at Duke's, but no limit at the
other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for solitude and huge trophies, it's hard to compete with
the private folks,'' Durniak said.
</P>
<P>
   A positive of private streams, he said, is that the owners tend
to be conservation-minded. ``Those proprietors are pretty strong
advocates of trout stream protection,'' he said. ``The more
advocates of conservation the better.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
