</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Iverson's leap forward
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the voting were done today, any writer worth the
ink on his or her shirt would jot ``Allen Iverson, Philadelphia
76ers'' on the top line of the NBA's most valuable player ballot.
And he would do it for no reason other than the guy has earned it.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson has been labeled as the epitome of the Generation X
player. That is, one who received a lucrative contract before
earning it, whose attitude and respect for the game have been
questioned, who is far more interested in commercials and sneaker
deals than winning. All that, and he wears his hair in braids and
is more aloof than personable.
</P>
<P>
   Then the 76ers 6-foot guard goes out this season and becomes the
best player in the league. No longer is he the rookie guard who
darted around the court recklessly, forcing up shots from all
angles under duress, while the 76ers took so many defeats.
</P>
<P>
   In his third pro season and second under coach Larry Brown,
Iverson is a paradox _ he plays with a noticeable calm while
inflicting damage in volatile fashion. In the past, he could not
turn that trick, his eagerness to establish himself prompting
selfishness and wildness.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. Iverson went into the weekend as the league's No. 1
scorer at 29.1 points a game, which is impressive enough. But more
significant is that he so far has helped turn Philadelphia into _
gulp before saying it _ a winner.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers were 10-6 after Friday's 89-78 loss to the Miami Heat
that ended a six-game winning streak, the longest for the franchise
in 13 years. And each of the victories had a similar theme. Philly
would hold opponents to less than 90 points on one end, and Iverson
would dazzle on the other.
</P>
<P>
   He averaged 32.1 points and 7.0 assists during the half-dozen
triumphs, but ``I would rather win than score a lot of points,'' he
said. ``I believe God gave me my talent and gifts. I've just taken
advantage of it and made myself better. I'm willing to work. I want
to use all my ability in a team game. I want to win
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   He is on the correct path. The fact that Iverson is traveling it
with controlled explosion signifies that he's catching on to what
Brown has tried to establish for the last year. He's still
unguardable, but his decision-making has been mostly exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   Brown says Iverson is ``playing the game the right way.''
Translation: He is less reliant on long-range jumpers and more
dependent on his unparalleled quickness and speed to penetrate into
the gut of the defense, creating for himself and teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The coach made the former Georgetown star an off guard despite
his lack of height, and starts Eric Snow at the point. The move has
taken some of the ball-handling chores off Iverson, who led the
league in turnovers as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen is a point guard with a shooter's mentality,'' Brown
said. ``But he's at his best when he doesn't have all the
ball-handling responsibilities. He's gotten better because he
realized that he couldn't do it by himself. He's making the effort
to improve. He's grown up a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Iverson, who was selected the NBA Player of the Month for
February: ``I show that you can be smaller and still have an impact
on the game. I'm a little quicker, but I also want to be a good
all-around player. Quick is good, but you have to know when to pass
and when to take the shot.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
