<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With H.O.O.P., Cato hopes to help
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kelvin Cato, now of the Portland Trail Blazers, last
week released a children's book he wrote called ``H.O.O.P.''
</P>
<P>
   Cato, a 6-foot-11 center, kicked off the NBA's Reading Month
calendar with the unveiling at Portland's Martin Luther King Jr.
Elementary School before 800 students. The letters stand for Help
Out Other People.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and father pushed me to read and do my homework
every day when I was a kid,'' Cato said. ``Now, I have the
opportunity to reach out to kids and teach them how important
reading is through my book. I had such a great time writing this
book over this past year that I plan to create a series in the
future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``H.O.O.P.'' is a colorful, rhyming book about an NBA player who
implores youths to do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   An excerpt: ``I play basketball in the NBA. Hard work and
dedication have given me the right. You won't see me in a gang or
looking for a fight. . . . I stay off the streets at night. My
dream for you _ learn to read and write. . . Have faith and go to a
steeple. Help out other people.''
</P>
<P>
   A CRYING SHAME
</P>
<P>
   It has not been a grand year so far for Seattle's Vin Baker.
First, he showed up for training camp at least 15 pounds
overweight, which affected his mobility, which has affected his
play.
</P>
<P>
   His frustrations reached an apex in San Antonio last week when
he scored just two points, then sat in front of his locker after
the game and wept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel awful, just terrible,'' Baker said. ``I feel bad about
my game. I just am not happy with Vin Baker right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And with good reason. He missed 18 straight foul shots to start
the season and is shooting 16 percent from the line. His scoring
average is just over 11 a game, down from 19.2 last year.
</P>
<P>
   But he could be on the rebound. He scored 16 the next outing
against the Spurs and 31 against Sacramento, including a key late
perimeter jumper.
</P>
<P>
   THEY SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominique was one of the best to ever play the game. Now he
can't get in the game. That's the worst way to go out, and I don't
want it to be like that. I just want respect, and he doesn't get
any respect. It's really sad, and I don't want to be that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Magic guard Penny Hardaway said of former Hawk Dominique
Wilkins, who's stranded on the Magic bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it has been (disappointing). It'll all work out.
Sometimes, it's one of those roads you travel. You can't worry
about it. As long as you have my health and my strength, you should
play as long as you feel good,'' Wilkins said of his role with the
team.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To Portland's Brian Grant. Considered trade bait much of his
time with the Trail Blazers, Grant has become a younger version of
Dennis Rodman, leading the league in rebounding while helping
Portland evolve into a serious contender.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To Seattle's Olden Polynice. The SuperSonics big man gave ``the
finger'' to fans at Sacramento's Arco Arena who booed him as he
left the court last week, drawing a $5,000 fine from the NBA.
``(The fans) threw things at me,'' said Polynice, who played for
the Kings for 4 1/2 seasons. ``I'll tell you, if one of them had
hit me, they were going to get dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
