<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WESTNOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doc to coach Spurs?
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Greg Popovich probably will save his coaching position
until he is relieved during the offseason. The reason is the
schedule. The Spurs are in a stretch with 14 of 18 games against
sub-.500 teams, so they'll look better than they are. But there are
problems. Popovich is disliked in San Antonio for the high-handed
manner in which he dumped then-coach Bob Hill on the eve of center
David Robinson's return from a serious back injury two years ago.
Minority owners want him out. One San Antonio columnist, Kevin
O'Keefe, resigned when his bosses told him to stop ripping
Popovich. Attendance is off and the push for a new arena is
stalling. So, who's out there as a prime candidate when Popovich
moves upstairs to concentrate on his general manager job? Why,
ex-Hawks guard Doc Rivers, the Spurs (and TNT) game commentator.
Rivers wants to coach and his other option figures to be in
Washington. Meanwhile, Portland has offered Rasheed Wallace to the
Spurs for San Antonio icon Robinson. It would be a risky political
move for San Antonio, but the Spurs haven't said no, yet.
</P>
<P>
   NO CENSURE FOR MAVS
</P>
<P>
   NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said the league won't take
action against the Mavericks for playing four starters 12 minutes
or less in last week's 80-65 loss at Utah. Mavs coach Don Nelson
admitted he was resting his best players for a home game against
Sacramento (Dallas won it). ``We've had that happen at the end of
the season, when games don't count because a team's playoff
position is already set, and that we don't allow,'' Granik said.
``But I don't think we want to get involved in telling teams how to
play and who they should play.''
</P>
<P>
   BARKLEY SPEAKS
</P>
<P>
   Rockets forward Charles Barkley is impressed with his own quick
recovery from cartilage repair on his left knee. ``I'm very
encouraged. I'm in a lot less pain than when I started, before I
had the surgery. As long as I don't have the swelling, I'll be
fine.'' That leaves Barkley to express other concerns, like NBC's
appetite for the Lakers. ``NBC thinks because they show the Lakers
every weekend they're a championship team. And y'all think because
y'all tell (Lakers guard) Kobe (Bryant) he's Jordanesque, he's
going to be the next Michael Jordan. They're not and he's not. And
I'm sick of hearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   LAKERS' CHARADE
</P>
<P>
   The ``interview process'' in L.A. with Lakers assistants Kurt
Rambis and Larry Drew for fired coach Del Harris' job was a joke.
Rambis was known to be the heir apparent for months, ever since
people close to both Shaquille O'Neal and Bryant put the word out
both wanted him, which also sealed Harris' fate.WEBBER'S PLOY
</P>
<P>
   Chris Webber says he is absolutely out of Sacramento after the
2000-2001 season, when his contract runs out, a ploy to get the
Kings to trade him. Skeptics think Webber is playing so well as a
ploy to make a trade appealing for other teams. The key: If he is
still a King, watch his performance after Thursday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
