<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Avalanche banks on Fleury
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Colorado Avalanche general manager Pierre Lacroix
views things, the importation of Theoren Fleury should not have
come as any great surprise because, by his count, ``I've traded for
20 players in the last four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Left unsaid by Lacroix was that it's hard to imagine another
trade in NHL history that put a team in such a strong position for
a Stanley Cup title and at the same time set up the front office
for an avalanche of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche had long since rebounded from an awful start
(0-4-1, then 17-19-4 before a 12-game winning streak) in part
because of the improved goaltending of Patrick Roy. Acquiring
Fleury from the cash-strapped Calgary Flames _ by which the Flames
kissed off any playoff hopes, although they likely would've lost
the unrestricted free agent after the season _ adds depth to an
offense that already had Peter Forsberg, Joe Sakic, Adam Deadmarsh,
Valeri Kamensky and Claude Lemieux. (The Avalanche, in fact, scored
seven goals in the last 22 minutes at Florida Wednesday without
Fleury, who is out indefinitely with a sprained knee.)
</P>
<P>
   The risk? If Lacroix and Fleury speak the truth, there has been
and will be no talks about a contract extension until after the
season. Lacroix called the trade ``purely a hockey decision; it's
not a business matter,'' and Fleury reiterated his desire to test
the free agent market.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado already has sacrificed one of its top prospects (to be
determined) and two players (left winger Rene Corbet and defenseman
Wade Belak) in the trade. If Fleury re-signs, the Avalanche also
will send a first-round pick to Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Colorado moving into the new Pepsi Center next season,
there may not be enough revenue streams to support this team's
growing payroll. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Forsberg will be a restricted free agent after this season and
will command a salary of $8 million to $10 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fleury already has turned down a deal averaging $6.25 million
per year and is expected to land at about $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Avalanche already has signed three key players to
lucrative extensions _ Roy ($7.5 million next season) and
defensemen Sandis Ozolinsh ($4 million) and Adam Foote ($1.2
million).
</P>
<P>
   Factoring in Sakic, who will earn $2 million in the final season
of his deal next year, Lemieux ($2.5 million) and Deadmarsh ($1.8
million), the Avalanche would be committing at least $34 million
for eight players in 1999-2000 if it retains Fleury. That equals
their current payroll for 23 players.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado also has four players scheduled to become unrestricted
free agents after this season: Kamensky, Sylvain Lefebvre, Alexei
Gusarov and Warren Rychel.
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix's choice basically is this: 1) re-sign Fleury and be
certain to lose money _ no matter how many ``Fleury'' jerseys are
sold at the concession stands; 2) lose Fleury and get nothing for
the three players.
</P>
<P>
   Well, possibly nothing. If the Avalanche wins the Cup, would
that suffice? Is this merely an expensive, short-term rental?
Lacroix would only say, ``Our ownership wants to win. That's why we
did this. Whatever happens after that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the impending contract talks, Lacroix, a former player
agent, said, ``It's just another file on the pile. We've gotten
commitments lately from Foote and Ozolinsh and Roy. We've been
negotiating hard for seven or eight months with Forsberg. The key
thing now is we have a chance to win the Stanley Cup and build a
relationship with Fleury. But I'm not going to talk about
hypothetical situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacroix had quietly explored a Fleury trade for two months and
decided to make the move after a Calgary-Los Angeles deal fell
apart three weeks ago when the Kings wanted assurances from Fleury
that he would sign an extension. Colorado had four first-round
draft picks and seven in the first two rounds last season, felt it
could deal because of its depth, although many of the amateurs
remain unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Lacroix's win-now/worry-later attitude is playing
well with his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't worry about next year or whatever is going to
happen,'' Roy said. ``The urgency on our club is right now, not
tomorrow. When you have (stars) like we have, it's something that
you have to look at right away. Maybe tomorrow will be too late.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
