<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hello, I must be going
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Art Williams was back in Atlanta this week to get the
battery in his pacemaker replaced. Presumably, the former insurance
executive was under a bit of strain during his brief but costly run
as owner of the Tampa Bay Lightning. Williams sold the team for
$100 million, $17 million less than he bought it for 10 months
earlier. But his actual losses will come close to $40 million.
Despite the Lightning's problems on the ice and at the gate, it's a
sweet deal for billionaire Bill Davidson, who also gains control of
the Ice Palace and developmental rights to six acres surrounding
the arena. This was a real-estate deal more than a hockey deal, and
for that reason Tampa fans can be certain the team isn't going
anywhere and Davidson is in this for the long haul. Williams
cleaned up a lot of the mess left by previous ownership but he was
slammed by fans and media recently when he stopped coming to games,
saying he couldn't take the losses, and then deciding to bail out
of his investment quickly. Perhaps trying to repair his image, the
former Georgia high school football coach said of the discounted
sale price, ``If I wanted to auction this thing off, I think I
could get substantially more money, but I wanted to make sure we
had the right owner. I am willing to sell at a discount because
there's no doubt Bill Davidson will be a better sports owner than I
was.''
</P>
<P>
   GLOVE STORY
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh, already shaky defensively, took an obvious step back
when goalie Tom Barrasso was hit on his glove hand by a shot that
shattered a bone and will sideline him for four to six weeks. But
the Penguins could be hurt offensively as much as defensively by
Barrasso's absence. Barrasso arguably is the best puck-handling
goaltender in the league and often intercepts dump-ins by opponents
and starts the Pens' transition game with an outlet pass. His
replacement, Peter Skudra, is weak in that area and probably is too
paranoid about being the No. 1 stopper to spend time worrying about
outlet passes. Coach Kevin Constantine said of Barrasso, ``He gets
the puck by himself out of our zone five to 10 times a game and
takes some of the pressure off us breaking out.''
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia is making a strong push for Montreal's Mark Recchi
(scheduled to become an unrestricted free agent) or Vladimir
Malakhov before the March 23 trading deadline. ... One interesting
sidelight to Mario Lemieux's bid to lead a new ownership group for
the Pittsburgh Penguins is the former star's refusal to join Pens
co-owner Roger Marino in a takeover bid. Why? Lemieux is suing
Marino for $31.4 million in deferred salary and blames him for
taking the team into bankruptcy. ... Nothing is going right for the
Islanders. Interim coach Bill Stewart totaled his 4x4 truck when he
was cut off by a dump truck. Stewart coached despite having a
concussion. No jokes. ... Buffalo's Matthew Barnaby, who continues
to seek a trade, suited up the first time in two weeks the other
night.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
