<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Goaltending the hot topic in Dallas
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ``Big D'' in Dallas is for decision. With the
Stars continuing to win despite the absence of Brett Hull, many in
the Dallas area are focusing on other matters _ such as what the
team will or should do with its goaltending situation. The Dallas
Morning News actually is running a cyberpoll asking, ``Are you
confident Ed Belfour can do the job in the playoffs?'' despite the
fact Belfour is 28-9-8 with a 1.98 goals against average and .912
saves percentage. General manager Bob Gainey also is hearing calls
to train backup Roman Turek (11-2-2, .190, .922) before the Stars
lose him to the Thrashers in the expansion draft. Dallas could be
helped by adding a speedy forward to an aging team.
Belfour-bashers, meanwhile, are convinced the team should protect
Turek, not the veteran, in June. It's conceiveable that if Gainey
does not trade Turek, and that seems unlikely now, the decision on
who to protect will be based on the team's playoff success.
Postscript: So far, 73 percent of those polled have confidence in
Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. STORIES
</P>
<P>
   If Los Angeles doesn't make the playoffs, it can blame the
goalie of the crosstown Anaheim Mighty Ducks. Guy Hebert, whom the
Ducks wisely signed to a new contract recently, stopped 33 of 34
Kings shots in a 2-1 win recently and has allowed only three goals
in 122 shots in four games against L.A. this year. The teams
clearly are headed in opposite directions. While the Kings continue
to struggle in what could be coach Larry Robinson's final days, the
Ducks had won 11 of 14 going into the weekend and are 9-2-4 within
the Pacific Division. Anaheim's Paul Kariya said the team can't
afford to get overly confident, especially in light of the fact
only three of the 11 wins during the streak came against winning
teams (Philadelphia, St. Louis, Phoenix). ``It's important when
things are going well to almost bring everyone down sometimes and
remember where we came from and how hard we have to work to
maintain it.'' ... One day in Robinson's life last week: 1) He got
an early phone call that one of his horses died of a heart attack
on a farm in Florida; 2) The Kings lost to the Ducks; 3) After the
game, he learned his mother, Isobel, 78, died near Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Flames general manager Al Coates admission after the Theo Fleury
trade: ``It's fair to say this wasn't our first choice, we wanted
to sign Theo. But frankly and simply it was something we couldn't
do here in Calgary, we can't pay that kind of salary for one player
on our team. It's impossible.'' ... For what it's worth, Fleury and
Colorado stars Peter Forberg and Joe Sakic all share the same
agent, Winnipeg's Don Baizley. Fleury and Forsberg will get new
deals after this year, Sakic after next season, after which Baizley
will be able to purchase half of Canada with his commissions. ...
Count Anaheim's Teemu Selanne among those who favor shootouts to
break ties. ``The fans now leave with 10 minutes left in the game,
but they would stay for the penalty shots,'' he said. ``If you play
four-on-four in overtime (which is being tested in the AHL), if the
ice is bad you can't do anything. Penalty shots are good for the
players and the fans. Maybe not for the goalies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
