<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bratzke tops Colts' new defensive look
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With a 12th-rated offense that includes a nucleus of
young stars led by quarterback Peyton Manning and tailback Marshall
Faulk, coach Jim Mora went into the spring intent on improving an
Indianapolis Colts defense that ranked No. 29 and squandered five
second-half leads. So far, the results are encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bill Polian added defensive ends Chad Bratzke
and Shawn King, linebacker Cornelius Bennett and strong safety Chad
Cota and signed tackle Ellis Johnson to an extension. The Colts
should land a premier linebacker prospect, likely Chris Claiborne
of Southern Cal, with the fourth choice in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Polian noted last week that if Heisman Trophy tailback Ricky
Williams slips to fourth, as some now think probable, the team
would have a tough time passing him. But Polian probably is
posturing, priming the pump for a potential trade-down with a club
desperately seeking Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The key to turning around a defense that produced only 38 sacks
last year is Bratzke. The Colts are gambling a $9million signing
bonus that his career-best 11 1/2 sacks in '99 were no fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Few defenders have as big a motor as Bratzke, but it will be
interesting to see how many sacks the former New York Giants right
end gets now that he won't be with one-gap rushers Michael Strahan,
Robert Harris and Keith Hamilton. Giants officials say only five of
Bratzke's sacks came when he beat a tackle one-on-one, with the
balance coming on combination stunts. He had 8 1/2 sacks his first
four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   MILLER TRYING COMEBACK?
</P>
<P>
   His career ended with a series of concussions, but former
Falcons quarterback Chris Miller is contemplating a comeback at age
33. Miller, who hasn't played since December of '95, recently
worked out for Seattle coach Mike Holmgren and threw the ball very
well. Agent Frank Bauer confirmed that Miller received a positive
evaluation from a Chicago-based neurologist and Seahawks team
doctors are following up with analysis of their own.
</P>
<P>
   TIP SHEET
</P>
<P>
   Former Falcons personnel director Ken Herock will assume the
same position in Green Bay after the draft. The move will reunite
Herock with his best friend, Packers GM Ron Wolf, and son Shaun
Herock, a scout for Green Bay. ... Fueling speculation that
Philadelphia will use the second pick in the draft on a
quarterback, the club had six representatives at the workout of
Central Florida's Daunte Culpepper last week. The Eagles contingent
included new coach Andy Reid, who also attended the workout of
Syracuse quarterback Donovan McNabb. ... Pittsburgh offensive left
tackle Will Wolford may be reconsidering his retirement. Ralph
Cindrich, agent for the 13-year veteran, is trying to get the
Steelers to release his client. Wolford would then try to find a
Super Bowl contender willing to let him play guard for a year or
two. ... San Diego is close to a deal for quarterback Jim Harbaugh
from Baltimore. Chargers coach Mike Riley still will meet on
Monday, though, with Mark Rypien. ... Giants linebacker Jesse
Armstead has been a no-show at offseason workings, and his absence
is probably a sign he wants his contract reworked. ... Former
Virginia safety Anthony Poindexter, a certain first-rounder before
blowing out his knee, conceded his rookie season in the NFL ``could
be a redshirt year for me.'' ... Minnesota has targeted cornerback
Champ Bailey in the draft and is working to move up for a shot at
the former Georgia star. The Vikings, who lost starting corner
Corey Fuller in free agency, will offer both their first-round
draft choices and wide receiver Jake Reed. ... Some scouts are
wondering how Oregon quarterback Akili Smith scored 12 on the
Wonderlic IQ test at an all-star game and a 37 on the 50-question
quiz at the combine.
</P>
<P>
   MCKITTRICK AILING
</P>
<P>
   The situation hasn't received the attention afforded Walter
Payton, but longtime 49ers offensive line coach Bobb McKittrick
also is in need of a liver transplant. The former Marine has cancer
of the bile duct and likely will need to have his gall bladder
removed as well. Yet McKittrick, 63, has continued to work and is
pragmatic about his condition. ``You see `Saving Private Ryan,' and
the boat comes up and and bow drops, and you've got to go out
because that's what you're paid to do,'' he said. New team
president Bill Walsh has suggested McKittrick cut back his
schedule, and coach Steve Mariucci has asked tight ends coach Pat
Morris to help with the line.
</P>
<P>
   JETS JUGGLING
</P>
<P>
   The addition of free agent linebacker Roman Phifer means Bill
Parcells will accelerate efforts to trade 1997 first-rounder James
Farrior, and it accentuates the dubious job the Jets coach has done
with his first two drafts in New York. Parcells had 23 choices but
got just two starters, offensive tackle Jason Fabini and defensive
tackle Jason Ferguson (formerly of Georgia), in those drafts. In
'97 Parcells could have taken offensive tackle Orlando Pace or
defensive tackle Darrell Russell, both of them superior prospects.
Instead he traded down twice, collected extra middle-round picks
and chose Farrior, who has been inconsistent as a weakside 'backer.
Phifer, a superb athlete who has been a chronic underachiever in
his eight-year career, will get more chances to blitz under Jets
defensive boss Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   GIANTS MERRY-GO-ROUND
</P>
<P>
   As if the addition of free agent Kerry Collins wasn't enough,
the track record of Giants coach Jim Fassel also suggests starting
quarterback Kent Graham will be unemployed by next spring. In 1997,
Fassel publicly backed Dave Brown in preseason, replaced him with
Danny Kanell at midseason, then discarded him. Last spring Fassel
announced Kanell would be unchallenged for the starting job,
supplanted him with Graham at the 10-game mark and then cut Kanell
two weeks ago. Now Fassel is saying Graham is his starter. The
four-year, $16.9 million contract awarded Collins by GM Ernie
Accorsi, including a $5 million signing bonus, suggests
otherwise.FALCONS FODDER
</P>
<P>
   The New York-to-Suwanee pipeline that helped net Kanell might
not be turned off yet. The Falcons maintain an interest in free
agent guard Greg Bishop, a four-year starter for the Giants. ...
Coach Dan Reeves has a high regard now for Kanell, but in the 1996
draft he wanted then-GM George Young to select defensive lineman
Shane Burton, and not the quarterback, in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
