<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waddell won't change much with Orlando Solar Bears
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Thrashers GM Don Waddell doesn't figure to make any
radical changes with the IHL's Orlando Solar Bears, signed as the
team's top minor-league affiliate. Why? Waddell was Orando's GM for
the first two seasons before moving on to Detroit and hired the
team's current coach, Curt Fraser, and assistant Peter Horachek.
Fraser went 147-78-21 (.640) in his first three seasons and is
34-24-2 this year.
</P>
<P>
   John Weisbrod, who replaced Waddell as GM, said it shouldn't be
assumed the entire roster will be stocked with Atlanta prospects
next season. The current agreement between the teams leaves open
the number of players the Thrashers will supply next season because
of the uncertainty of who will make the NHL roster and who will be
worth retaining in the organization. Weisbrod anticipates about a
50-50 split of personnel on the roster between prospects and
unattached players. ``There will be more competition for jobs next
year because the talent pool will be expanded,'' Weisbrod said.
``But I wouldn't say everybody's job will be in jeopardy.
Traditionally we turn over about half our roster every year. Even
with the influx of players from Atlanta, this may not be much
different. It's just hard to tell right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential No. 1 pick in the amateur draft _ and a potential
Thrasher _ is back on the ice. Center Patrik Stefan, an 18-year-old
Czech playing with the Long Beach Ice Dogs of the IHL, returned
last week after missing three months with a concussion and bruised
spinal column. Stefan, who is rated as the top prospect by the
NHL's Central Scouting, must be feeling better because he scored
the Ice Dogs' first goal in his first game back. Stefan wore a neck
brace for a few weeks, but his agent, Rich Winter, said the long
absence was primarily precautionary.
</P>
<P>
   CLASS OF '99
</P>
<P>
   Of 66 previous winners of the Calder Trophy for the NHL's Rookie
of the Year, only nine came out of the college ranks, most recently
North Dakota goalie Ed Belfour in 1991 (with Chicago). But three of
the top four rookie scorers in the league this season are from
college. The current rookie leaders:
</P>
<P>
   Player (Team) _ College/Juniors _ G-A-Pts.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Muckalt (Van.) _ Michigan _ 16-18-34
</P>
<P>
   Chris Drury (Col.) _ Boston Univ. _ 13-19-32
</P>
<P>
   Jan Hrdina (Pitt.) _ Juniors (Seattle) _ 9-22-31
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Morrison (N.J.) _ Michigan _ 8-22-30
</P>
<P>
   Milan Hejduk (Col.) _ Europe (Czech) _ 8-19-27
</P>
<P>
   Mark Parrish (Fa.) _ St. Cloud St. _ 17-9-26
</P>
<P>
   Vadim Sharifijanov (N.J.) _ Europe (Russia) _ 8-15-23
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Lecavalier (T.B.) _ Juniors (Rimouski) _ 11-9-20
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Kvasha (Fla. ) _ Europe (Russia) _ 10-10-20
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Briere (Phoe.) _ Juniors (Drummondville) _ 8-11-19
</P>
<P>
   FACE-OFF: TEEMU SELANNE
</P>
<P>
   _ Team, pos: Anaheim, RW.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown: Helsinki, Finland.
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: Had 34 goals, 45 assists, 79 points through 54 games,
third in the league. Named the NHL's player of the month for
February, with 25 points (12 goals) in 13 games to lead the Mighty
Ducks, who were 10-3-0. Last week scored his 300th career goal in
his 464th game, the sixth fastest to 300 in league history. Coming
off consecutive 50-goal seasons.
</P>
<P>
   _ On what makes a great goal scorer: ``Great scorers can read
what other players are going to do. A lot of great scorers are not
real good skaters. But they know where the puck is going to be and
they know where other players are. I also try to study goalies so
that I know where their weaknesses are.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On the two-ref system: ``It's a different game but I like it
because there are a lot of things one referee can't see. They
should give the referees more power to call different things, like
whether somebody is standing in the crease (during a goal). That
shouldn't be decided by an official upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rule changes that need to be implemented: ``The biggest thing
they should do is after overtime I would be happy to see penalty
shots (a shootout). It would make the games much more exciting if
they did that.''
</P>
