<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, March 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, snow fell at the rate of 1 inch per hour across
portions of Pennsylvania as a strengthening low-pressure center
crossed the Middle Atlantic States.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, this low will further intensify as it draws energy
from the open waters of the Atlantic Ocean. As a result, a swath of
heavy snow will fall over interior New England with over a foot of
windswept snow occurring from the White Mountains of New Hampshire
to central and northern Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the low, very gusty winds from the northwest will import
unseasonably cold air into the Great Lakes on Sunday with the
strongest winds occurring across eastern sections of this region.
</P>
<P>
   As the frigid air gathers moisture in transit over the unfrozen
lake waters, snow showers will form southeast of Lake Erie and over
central New York. Meanwhile, dry and cooler air will surge into the
Southeast on Sunday but it will stay warm over southern and central
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Areas of light snow will develop in the northern Plains as winds
from the south direct increasingly moist air northward. Meanwhile,
patchy rain will occur farther south near a warm front draped
across the Red River Valley. Some light sleet could fall in Kansas,
especially on Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy snow will accompany a jet-stream disturbance crossing the
mountains of northern Arizona and southern Utah on Sunday. Patchy
clouds and lighter rain showers will speckle the lowlands of the
interior West. Elsewhere, light rain should arrive Sunday afternoon
in western Washington while the remainder of the West Coast stays
dry and cool.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: Of Lions and Lambs
</P>
<P>
   For much of the Northeast, March has had a stormy start with
episodes of heavy snow and strong winds from the Middle West to New
England. The weather folklore ``in like a lion, out like a lamb''
would suggest that the month will end on a more tranquil note. Much
folklore began in early America as farmers carefully observed
nature in hopes of finding clues to upcoming weather. Though
individual observations may have been accurate, the conclusions
that were drawn were not universally true. Indeed, there is no
known reliable connection between the weather at the start and at
the end of March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
