</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOMO-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' NOMO IS HAVING A WILD TIME AT SPRING TRAINING
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ Publicly, the Mets are saying that Hideo
Nomo's control is back to where it was a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``His command has been very impressive,'' Bob Apodaca, the
pitching coach, recently insisted. It is a sentiment that has been
echoed by most of the team's brass.
</P>
<P>
   But when Nomo was asked on Friday about the control that has
gradually deserted him over the last two seasons, his response was
telling on the eve of his first spring start.
</P>
<P>
   With no translator around, Nomo _ who was scheduled to toss a
couple of innings against his former team, the Los Angeles Dodgers,
here Saturday _ understood the question immediately.
</P>
<P>
   How has your control been on your fastball? ``So-so,'' the
Japanese pitcher said in English, shrugging his shoulders to
punctuate the response.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the Mets' front office will even suggest that Nomo is
still the pitcher whose wildness caused him to walk 56 batters in
892/3 innings last season after the Mets had acquired him from the
Dodgers on June 4. And that is probably because it is too early to
tell, what with Nomo _ and the rest of the pitchers _ throwing
mostly on the side thus far.
</P>
<P>
   There are lingering questions about the soundness of Nomo's
shoulder, but it is in the best interest of the Mets not to
acknowledge them. Nomo, who was dropped from the team's rotation in
the final month of last season, signed a one-year deal for $2.975
million this season.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Mets decide that Paul Wilson _ who threw an
impressive two innings in Friday night's exhibition opener, an 8-4
victory over Montreal in Jupiter, Fla. _ is major league ready, the
Mets might try to peddle Nomo somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   And if there are no takers, the Mets could always release the
30-year-old right-hander later this month. The Mets' budget has
climbed over its owner-mandated preseason target of $65 million to
nearly $68 million, a figure that ranks the team among the top five
in the major leagues. Should the Mets release Nomo this month, they
will have to pick up either one-sixth of Nomo's salary or
one-fourth, depending on the date of the release.
</P>
<P>
   Should Nomo begin this season with the Mets, his contract
immediately becomes guaranteed. But General Manager Steve Phillips
and members of his staff scoffed at suggestions that Nomo was still
struggling and that he could become a candidate for early release.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff is every bit as good as it ever was,'' Apodaca said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But that was true last year, when opposing batters hit .226
against him (lower than against both Kevin Brown and John Smoltz).
Left-handers particularly struggled against Nomo, batting only
.210.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that Nomo could not find the plate. And the
problem is continuing. Since his arrival from Japan in 1996, Nomo's
strikeouts have slipped each year from 236 to 234 to 233 to 167.
His walks, however, have risen from 78 to 85 to 92 to 94.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent side session, Nomo appeared to be high with his
fastball when he was throwing out of the windup. His command,
however, appeared sharper out of the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Later, his catcher that day, the rookie Mike Kinkade (who is
normally an infielder), said that Nomo's control appeared to be
fine. And another player who has caught Nomo this spring, Todd
Pratt, reported that the pitcher's control was above average _
compared with his velocity, which seemed to be just average.
</P>
<P>
   If Nomo's command has indeed returned, his re-emergence as a
dominating force could help transform what looks like a solid Mets
rotation on paper to one of the best in the league. Nomo was
considered an ace early on with the Dodgers. Should he establish
himself this season as a solid No. 2 pitcher behind Al Leiter, the
Mets might seriously have a chance to challenge the Braves'
decade-long dominance of the National League East.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But should Nomo struggle, the back of the Mets' rotation looks a
little suspect. Rick Reed has tired badly over the last two
seasons. Bobby Jones is 12-15 since opening the 1997 season with a
12-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   And Masato Yoshii, who was surprisingly re-signed by the Mets
for $5 million over the next two seasons, has shown a propensity to
allow home runs, as he did again during the first inning Friday
night. The Expos' young star Vladimir Guerrero tagged Yoshii for a
two-run shot well beyond the left-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo, therefore, seems to be a key to a veteran Mets staff. This
week, manager Bobby Valentine cautioned that Nomo's spring
statistics may not be indicative of how will he fare this year.
Valentine said that Nomo's numbers in the spring have always been
high, because he concentrates first on his fastball, then his
curve, then finally his forkball _ and sometimes throws only one
pitch an entire outing. But there is no question that Nomo needs to
harness his fastball if he is to be effective this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spring he really has been focused on the fastball,''
Apodaca said. ``He recognizes it is the pitch he was most
inconsistent with last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
