<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 15:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRES-SOUTH07-COX     03-06 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRES-SOUTH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parched Florida faces new threat from raging fires
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM COAST, Fla. _ Tara Cromer doesn't need any state officials
to warn her that fire-scarred Florida is dry and in danger of a new
round of wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   After last summer's blazes singed her new home with $39,000 in
damage and turned her neighborhood's lovely pine forest into
blackened stumps and cinders, Cromer has a nose for the slightest
whiff of wood smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke up one morning and smelled smoke and almost crawled out
of my skin,'' Cromer said, standing in the once-lush Seminole Woods
neighborhood, now a sooty plain. ``My husband had to calm me down.
They were doing a controlled burn nearby.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cromers and thousands of other Floridians who lived through
last summer's wildfire nightmare are worried by the unusually dry
winter _ and the prospect that a dry spring could lead to another
dangerous summer.
</P>
<P>
   NO RELIEF IN SIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Weather experts are not encouraging, saying the current
large-scale pattern that has brought a mild, dry winter to the
South will likely continue into the spring and maybe even the
summer. Mobile, Ala., just experienced its driest February on
record.
</P>
<P>
   The experts warn that the wildfires that have already broken out
in Florida, South Carolina and other states may get worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a regionwide event,'' said Michael Helfert, director of
the Southeastern Regional Climate Center in Columbia, S.C. ``The
long-range climate forecast is for more of the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Winter is normally fire season in Florida and other parts of the
South, as dry conditions lead to what are typically small fires
that are relatively easy to control.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida has seen more than its routine number of fires this
winter, jumping from the expected 8 to 10 fires a day to 20 to 30
fires each day statewide. Thunderstorms last week did little to
alleviate the dryness, which contributed to more than 250 wildfires
that had burned more than 5,000 acres by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to sound alarmist, but we're entering drought
conditions in many parts of the state and there doesn't appear to
be any relief in sight in the short term,'' said state
meteorologist Andy Devanas. ``And the long-term forecast doesn't
look favorable, either.''
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of Central Florida, drought index readings have
topped 600 on an 800-point scale, with 800 representing bone-dry.
Several parts of the state hit the high 700s last summer, when
Florida was consumed in a frightening wildfire inferno.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500,000 acres burned, destroying 342 homes. The fires
were so bad officials closed a 200-mile stretch of Interstate 95
and ordered the evacuation of an entire county _ Flagler, just
north of Daytona Beach. The crisis hit on the Fourth of July
weekend, prompting the cancellation of Daytona Beach's Pepsi 400
NASCAR race, which cost the state's precious tourism industry
millions.
</P>
<P>
   This winter's fires haven't remotely approached the scale of
last summer's disaster. The largest fires are burning hundreds of
acres, not thousands, and so far only two mobile homes have been
damaged.
</P>
<P>
   But last weekend, a fire prompted evacuation of the Gatorland
tourist attraction in Kissimmee, while thick smoke combined with
fog just west of Orlando triggered several car wrecks that sent a
dozen people to the hospital Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Just like last summer, authorities suspect some of the fires
have been deliberately set, and they are warning that any arsonists
caught will be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Climatologists say the culprit in the latest round of disturbing
weather is another large-scale phenomenon with a catchy nickname.
Last summer, it was El Nino, a warming of Pacific Ocean waters that
disrupted the jet stream and caused massive, worldwide weather
events, including Florida's desertlike drought.
</P>
<P>
   Now El Nino _ named for the Christ child by South American
fisherman because it usually appears around Christmastime _ has
been displaced by its ``sister,'' La Nina, an infusion of cold
water in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   ``La Nina is typically strongest from March to May, which means
the dry, warm weather in the Southeast will continue,'' Helfert
said. ``It's not unusual for La Ninas to last for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   That has prompted Florida officials to warn the public to clear
brush and overhanging trees away from their homes, creating a clear
zone of 30 feet or more around any structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not have a short memory,'' said Gene Madden, spokesman
for the Florida Division of Forestry. ``We're also urging people
with large properties to conduct prescribed burns to remove the
fuel that helped cause last summer's problems.''
</P>
<P>
   UNDERBRUSH CURTAILED
</P>
<P>
   Officials are hoping they won't see a repeat of last year's
fiery disaster. One factor in their favor: This winter's drought is
holding back the underbrush, although a prolonged drought will
leave whatever remains on the ground bone-dry. Last winter Florida
was deluged with heavy rains, which sparked the growth of thick
underbrush, creating more fuel for the summer fires
</P>
<P>
   Anyone taking the fire threat lightly should visit Flagler
County and neighborhoods such as Seminole Woods. What were once
lush hideaways with homes tucked onto forested lots are now barren
moonscapes marked by stumps and mounds of blackened debris.
</P>
<P>
   The Cromers bought their home just four months before last
summer's fires nearly destroyed it. Once they couldn't even see the
house across the street because the trees were so thick, but now
they watch huge trucks roar down I-95 more than a mile away across
the blackened plain.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we moved here was for the trees and the
privacy,'' said Mark Cromer. ``Now people are starting to put up
privacy fences. They don't want to have to walk outside and look at
this.''
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, the Rev. David Vannoy's family is just
finishing rebuilding the home they lost to last summer's fires.
While losing the house was bad enough, the family almost got
trapped when they tried to escape the blazes and had to drive down
a road surrounded by roaring flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``A firestorm is unlike anything you've seen,'' Vannoy said.
``It creates its own wind that just pushes it along. It's like a
tidal wave, except it's fire.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
