<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST'S BOSNIA MOVE MAY HURT KOSOVO BID
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary _ Just before peace talks on Kosovo are due to
resume, the United States and its allies are sending contradictory
signals to Belgrade, making it less likely that President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia will capitulate on American terms.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the West opened a new front of diplomatic
confrontation with Milosevic, this time in Bosnia. The Western
envoy who essentially runs Bosnia, Carlos Westendorp, fired the
elected Bosnian Serb president, Nikola Poplasen, and announced that
the strategic northern Bosnian town of Brcko was to be taken out of
Bosnian Serb hands.
</P>
<P>
   Officials asserted that the timing was coincidental, but the
unseating of an elected official may increase Milosevic's anger
with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with the United States and Europe on the verge of a
trade war over bananas, Europeans in NATO are increasingly
skeptical about American pressure for a bombing campaign against
Belgrade, senior NATO-nation diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has not responded to egregious Yugoslav violations of an
October cease-fire agreement _ largely, the diplomats say, because
the rebels of the Kosovo Liberation Army have also violated the
agreements in a worsening but predictable Balkan cycle of attack
and reprisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Americans are openly embracing one side in a situation
where the fighting and the blame are not, unfortunately,
one-sided,'' a senior NATO-nation diplomat closely involved in
Kosovo said Saturday, pointing to another ambush of a Serbian
police patrol by the rebels. ``When we say we do not want NATO to
be the KLA's air force, some of us actually mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough language ``is fine in its place,'' the diplomat said.
``But in the end there is going to have to be a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   While American officials _ including President Clinton on Friday
_ repeat threats of NATO bombing if Milosevic does not capitulate
and allow foreign troops on sovereign Yugoslav territory, the State
Department announced on Friday that American diplomats would now
return to Belgrade. So-called nonessential staff and families had
left Belgrade in February in a big show intended to underscore the
credibility of NATO's threat to bomb Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Their return now is sure to send the opposite message: that NATO
airstrikes are more remote than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Friday's twin moves in Bosnia were not connected.
But senior American officials had said the timing of the Brcko
decision, originally scheduled for March 1, would be affected by
the state of the negotiations over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   If the Serbs are cooperating on Bosnia, a senior American
official said in late February, ``we don't want Brcko to hit them
in the teeth at the same time as Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the Serbs are not cooperating, and the firing of
Poplasen, the Bosnian Serb president, combined with Brcko, may have
been intended to remind Milosevic of the risks he is running.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Balkans invariably produce unintended consequences.
Poplasen, a hard-line Serbian ally of Milosevic, was freely elected
in September in Western-monitored voting. One reason he won was the
open embrace Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright gave his
rival, Biljana Plavsic, who had broken with Karadzic and supported
the Dayton peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Poplasen was fired, according to Westendorp, for not supporting
the Dayton accord and not allowing a more moderate acting prime
minister, Milorad Dodik, to be confirmed in office.
</P>
<P>
   But Dodik, a Western favorite, quit on Friday, because he could
not stomach the Brcko decision. Dodik had long said he would resign
``on moral grounds'' if Brcko, which straddles the narrow land
corridor linking Serbian holdings in eastern and western Bosnia,
was taken from Bosnian Serb jurisdiction. On Friday, he did just
that, leaving Western diplomats scrambling to get him to change his
mind.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Bosnian Serb who is in the country's joint
three-man presidency, Zivko Radisic, also resigned. That leaves the
political structure created by the Dayton accord to run Bosnia in
disarray. The Bosnian Serb vice president also declined to assume
the presidency after Poplasen was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   As the victims and refugees mount again in Kosovo, Albright
insists that ``force is the only language Milosevic understands.''
But Milosevic is also looking for benefits and sweeteners for
handing over a prize as big as Kosovo, and Washington has thus far
offered none.
</P>
<P>
   Serbs argue that if Milosevic understands only force, that is
also true of Kosovo's Albanians, who traditionally have sustained
feuds for generations. Both sides are also prepared to take
apparently illogical risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dress in Western clothes and drink espresso,'' said
Aleksandr Tijanic, a Serbian journalist and former information
minister. ``But our minds are Oriental, like the Albanians. The
Americans are reasonable people and expect others to be reasonable.
But for honor, pride and revenge, we very often act against our own
interests.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
