<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-CUBANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE DEPARTMENT PUTS SNAG IN ORIOLES-CUBA EXHIBITIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAINES CITY, Fla. _ Representatives of Major League Baseball,
the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban government went into a meeting
in Washington Friday night with a deal in principle for a game in
Havana March 28, but they emerged early Saturday with nothing set
and the game in possible peril.
</P>
<P>
   The representatives planned to meet again Saturday to try to
salvage the game that, a participant in the meeting said, had been
put on hold by State Department objections to the proposed
recipients of any proceeds from the game.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department, the participant said Saturday, had told
the commissioner's office and the Orioles to make an agreement with
the Cuban government, which they did. ``But then,'' the person
said, ``they came in and said conditions had to be changed. That
happened about four times last night.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball people who attended the Friday meeting expected it
to be relatively brief, perhaps an hour and a half, the person
said, with the topics of discussion the logistics for the game in
Cuba and a possible second game in Baltimore. They expected to put
in place the deal in principle reached earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   But eight or so hours later, shortly after 4 a.m., the meeting
broke up with no agreement. ``The hangup,'' the participant said,
``was over the issue of the proceeds.''
</P>
<P>
   The people negotiating the game believed they had dispensed with
that issue because no proceeds from the Havana game are expected.
But the State Department representatives who attended the meeting
opposed the agreement baseball and Cuba had reached and refused to
approve the game.
</P>
<P>
   Among those present at the meeting were three representatives
from the State Department, four from the Cuban government, Sandy
Alderson of Major League Baseball, Peter Angelos of the Orioles,
William Schweitzer, the American League lawyer, and Michael Weiner
and Tony Bernazard of the Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this past week, Alderson had said a decision on the game
would be reached by the end of the week. He didn't say that was a
deadline, but there realistically is a deadline. Commissioner Bud
Selig has set a meeting for 7:30 a.m. Monday at his office in New
York to put details for the game in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is a deal in place before then, there won't be a
game,'' the meeting participant said.
</P>
<P>
   If the game is played, the Orioles are expected to take the
players who will start for them during the season. ``They aren't
interested in losing,'' said a person with knowledge of the team's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   If the Havana game is scheduled, a second game could be played
in Baltimore next month. The Orioles' preferred date is April 3,
but the game could be played later in April. The Orioles are not
scheduled on three consecutive Mondays, April 12, 19 and 26. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
