<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0259 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANOREXIA-COSTLY07-COX     03-06 0344
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANOREXIA-COSTLY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Curing anorexia a costly commitment
 &HT;    EDs: EMBARGOED for Monday, March 8
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When Bill and Susan Winkler decided to send their
daughter Caroline to the Renfrew Center for treatment of her eating
disorder, they knew it was a $16,000 commitment. They also knew
people with eating disorders often need to return for further
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to think about it as if it were another deadly
disease,'' Susan Winkler says. ``If Caroline had cancer and we knew
going in that we had to spend $16,000 for three weeks of treatment,
we wouldn't even hesitate. Then if the cancer came back and she had
to go for more treatment, we certainly wouldn't be disappointed in
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most parents would go to any expense to save their children.
Why should this be any different?''
</P>
<P>
   But many parents can't afford five-figure medical fees out of
their pockets, whatever the stakes. Unlike treatments for most
deadly diseases, treatment for eating disorders is rarely covered
by health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   How many people, wondered Caroline, go without that treatment
because their families don't have the money? The internationally
renowned Renfrew Center is expensive, but good treatment for eating
disorders doesn't come cheap.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, she began establishing a foundation to fund
treatment scholarships soon after her return from Renfrew in late
January. It's called the SOS Foundation, for Save Our Selves, a
term used repeatedly in her treatment at Renfrew.
</P>
<P>
   Winkler also hopes to talk to as many people as she can about
eating disorders, whether at school assemblies or at creative
seminars following, for example, a prom fashion show. ``I want to
help some people's lives,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation still is being established, but people can
contact Winkler by e-mail at sosfound(at)glasscity.net or by mail
in care of 679 Lyons Road, Centerville, OH, 45458.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
