<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-MAINE-COD-NY     03-06 1572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-MAINE-COD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRASTIC MEASURES TO SAVE COD ARE DISCUSSED IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Maine, Mass, N.H.) (Eds: fyi, Paul Molyneaux of Whiting, Maine, was a commercial
fisherman for 20 years.) 
 (fb) 
 By PAUL MOLYNEAUX   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKLAND, Maine _ At the beginning of this century, New
England's cod fishery was dominated by dorymen fishing with baited
hooks. When the Bay State Fishing Company introduced the first
trawler, the Spray, in 1905, the dorymen railed against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It scrapes and tears and scrapes and tears the fishing
grounds,'' the fisherman William H. Thomas wrote in the 1913
program of the Master Mariners' Association in Gloucester, Mass.
``Let this method alone,'' he warned, ``and not many years hence a
dearth of fish will be certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 86 years later, the sad state of New England's fisheries in
general, and the cod fishery in particular, is well established.
Fishermen and regional regulators are under increasing pressure to
come to terms with the federal Sustainable Fisheries Act of 1996
before any more damage is done.
</P>
<P>
   The act was designed as a holistic approach to fisheries
management that would restore fish stocks and ocean habitat while
preserving fishing communities. As enforced so far, however, the
act has failed on every count. Scientists see Gulf of Maine cod
stocks continuing to collapse. Little has been done to protect
habitat beyond the ancillary benefits of temporarily closed areas,
and fishing communities are in need of life support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Closing inshore areas forces people to get bigger boats so
they can get offshore, it cripples small coastal communities, and
it does nothing to protect habitat,'' said Paul Cohan, president of
the Gulf of Maine Fishermen's Alliance. ``Let's face it, big
draggers beat the hell out of the fishing grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who run small boats _ gillnetters, trawlers and hook boats
under 60 feet _ from the ports around Gloucester, Mass., and
Portsmouth, N.H., say they are hardest hit. Area closings to
protect cod stocks, primarily in the inshore waters between Cape
Cod and southern Maine, have left them nowhere to fish. Their
increasing frustration culminated last November when they asked the
New England Fishery Management Council to shut the entire Gulf of
Maine to all fishing for at least three years. A compromise plan
was passed in January after three days of arduous and emotional
meetings. The compromise closed more areas offshore while allowing
fishing inshore with more restricted trawling gear.
</P>
<P>
   Vito Calomo, executive director of the Gloucester Fisheries
Commission, backed the inshore fishermen's demand for closure at
the Nov. 16 meeting of the council's groundfish committee. ``We
finally, after 375 years of being fishermen, are united,'' Calomo
said. ``These people feel they can't survive, and we're telling you
we can't make it. Do you really believe I want to close the fishing
industry down?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation. I don't say it's bad management,
overfishing, pollution. I say it's a combination of everything. If
anybody could come up with a way to solve this problem, I'd be the
first one behind you. But we've been pounding our heads for years,
and it doesn't seem like it's coming back. We listen to the
scientists and they paint a very, very bleak picture, and we look
at our fishermen dwindled down, people out of the industry. We need
to work together, the management, the fishermen, industry people;
we need to work together to solve this problem. We don't know what
to do anymore, so we're saying, close it down.''
</P>
<P>
   The council, which regulates fisheries in Federal waters off the
five coastal New England states, was shocked by the closure demand,
but some members understood the fishermen's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most fishermen realize there is no way to meet the
requirements of the Sustainable Fisheries Act,'' said Jim Kendall,
a council member from New Bedford, Mass., ``and not many years
hence a dearth of fish will be certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Poor spawning success, often blamed on pollution and loss of
habitat to trawler damage, has led to continued declines in cod
despite cutbacks in landings. The current assessment calls for ``as
close to zero mortality as possible'' for Gulf of Maine cod and
increased efforts to minimize bycatch, cod caught incidentally in
other fisheries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total allowable catch this year is 772 metric tons,'' said
Kendall. ``They caught almost that much just in the month of June
last year. Bycatch alone will fill the quota and shut the fishery
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohan, of the fishermen's alliance, was among those who
initiated the shutdown demand, but he came back to the table at the
December, and January council meetings in an effort to work out a
plan that would meet federal targets and allow inshore boats to
fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to close the whole Gulf of Maine, let stocks
rebuild, get some sort of government relief package to keep us
alive, and take a hard look at how we fish,'' Cohan said. ``But we
realized the political fortitude to do that did not exist, within
the industry or on the council.''
</P>
<P>
   The compromise was passed on Jan. 28 after meetings with a
conspicuous police presence to insure the security of council
members. The new plan will close more areas offshore, allow more
fishing inshore and require trawlers to use less intrusive gear
inshore. But it will also allow fishing in areas with high
concentrations of cod. A trip limit of 200 pounds a day, included
in the plan, means that fishermen will have to dump any excess cod
back into the ocean, dead.
</P>
<P>
   The incentive to discard overages is hard to ignore. One council
member, Jim O'Malley, asked the council to take a hard look at the
issue. ``I have reports of vessels offshore fishing on flounder in
areas where they were getting a lot of cod,'' he said, ``and
railroading the cod over the side so they could keep fishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another council member, Tom Hill, a former charter boat
operator, said there was one sure way to deal with discards. ``You
cannot regulate a single species in a multispecies fishery without
closing large areas for extended periods of time,'' he said.
``That's what has worked on Georges Bank, and it's the
internationally accepted norm. Every bone in my body tells me the
compromise is a mistake, but I voted for it. The inshore fishermen
tell us they can fish in areas with high concentrations of cod and
not catch cod, and I think we have to give them a chance. But this
is the last roll of the dice and all their money is on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a bitter pill to swallow for the recreational
industry that is accountable for only 4.5 percent of the total
landings to have to close this fishery and essentially hand the
resource over to the people who destroyed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Inshore fishermen say they know what is at stake and can avoid
cod through gear modifications coupled with their intimate
knowledge of the areas they fish.
</P>
<P>
   Niaz Dorry of Greenpeace asserts that myopic attention to the
requirements of the Sustainable Fisheries Act has led to a
merry-go-round of collapsing stocks and ineffective regulation. ``I
am thoroughly disgusted with the process and the contention that
everything is being done to meet SFA when most of the requirements
of SFA are being ignored,'' she said. ``There are provisions that
call for the landing of all bycatch, and habitat-impact statements
for all gear.''
</P>
<P>
   She sees ``regulators focusing on rebuilding targets, and
fishermen focusing on maintaining their communities, while ignoring
the far-reaching goals'' of the fisheries act.
</P>
<P>
   Dorry also said environmentalists who talk about gear impact,
without consulting fishermen, ``are continuing to live in ignorance
of the wisdom of fishermen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the solutions coming out of the industry address the
concerns of the environmental community better than what the
managers are coming up with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fisheries act was intended to protect the resource for the
entire nation. Access to fish, either directly through recreational
fishing or indirectly through commercial fishermen, is what matters
to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Casella, director of the Sea Party Coalition, which
represents more than 2,000 recreational fishermen, said his group
was ready to do whatever it took to rebuild cod stocks despite the
industry's low impact on the fishery.
</P>
<P>
   To protect the future of cod and other species, Dorry
recommended that consumers ask questions when they buy fish: Where
does it come from and how was it caught? ``Buy fresh fish,'' she
said, ``because it is more likely to have been caught in a
low-impact fishery, and whenever possible buy local.''
</P>
<P>
   The next stock assessment is expected to call for more drastic
closures to protect other stocks such as hake and plaice (dab), and
many participants think closing the Gulf of Maine and subsidizing
fishermen is inevitable. But what that means is worth pondering.
</P>
<P>
   A moratorium in Newfoundland, established in 1992 to rebuild the
collapsed cod stocks, has cost the Canadian government $3 billion
so far, and it is a long way from over. Scientists say Gulf of
Maine cod could take eight years to recover, even with no fishing
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Finlayson, assistant commissioner of Maine's Department of
Marine Resources, said of the latest plan, ``We're buying one more
year for the boats that can still fish.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
