<HEADLINE>
RICE DEAL SIMMERING 
BULKY IS BEAUTIFUL FOR KEMP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long-rumored deal that has Glen Rice going to the Los
Angeles Lakers and Eddie Jones coming to Charlotte is at least
another week away from being consummated, a Hornets official said
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, who underwent elbow surgery before the season, is expected
to be dealt to the Lakers with J.R. Reid and B.J. Armstrong for
Jones and Elden Campbell by the middle of March.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte coaching staff is leery of losing the team's
leading scorer, but it appears the deal is nearing completion. One
of the main holdups: Rice's wife is about to give birth to the
couple's first child, and Rice does not want anything to interfere
with the pregnancy, the team official said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Lakers playing as well as they have been since the
season began, a trade could upset team chemistry. And Rice has
often felt that his skills would be hampered with the Lakers, where
he would become the No. 3 option on offense behind Shaquille O'Neal
and Kobe Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   But a reliable long-distance shooter is perhaps the one weapon
keeping the Lakers from getting over the hump in the playoffs. With
a team like Utah rotating on defense and forcing the Lakers into a
half-court game, kicking it out to a player of Rice's caliber could
make even more of a difference than having Dennis Rodman under the
boards.
</P>
<P>
   Bulky Is Beautiful for Kemp  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A portly, less mobile Shawn Kemp has endured every imaginable
crack about his weight so far this month. But more than one-quarter
into the short season, he has somehow managed to prove that bigger
is better for his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger, I used to dunk and they criticized me for
the dunk,'' said Kemp, who at a less-than-svelte 280 pounds is
averaging 20.2 points and 9.3 rebounds per game. ``They said I
couldn't be an All-Star because I dunked too much. So in order to
get the respect from the people, I felt like I had to change my
game. I actually felt bad because I was dunking the ball so much. I
led the league in dunks one year, and they told me that was the
wrong thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That hardly explains why he came to training camp near 303
pounds and carrying a few rolls of pork over his game shorts. But
he slimmed down to about 291 when the season started and kept
dropping pounds. He is using his bulkier frame to get position and
easy baskets. The results have been less highlight-reel dunks but
more production inside.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
