<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-76ERS-IVERSON-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IVERSON GETS THE POINT BY MOVING AWAY FROM IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Allen Iverson, Philadelphia freedom once meant driving the
length of the court, and then using the defense and his teammates
for pylons. He would score spectacularly and often. But the 76ers
would invariably drop another game, after which Iverson would shrug
his shoulders and exclaim, ``What more do you want me to do?''
</P>
<P>
   Now look who's all grown up.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three years after the 76ers made him the No. 1 pick in
the 1996 draft, the days of frustration for the young team and the
young guard are nearing an end.
</P>
<P>
   Through 14 games, Iverson is leading the NBA in scoring at 28.8
points per game. He is also averaging six assists and 5.4 rebounds
and is most responsible for Philadelphia's best start since the
1990-91 season.
</P>
<P>
   The 76ers are 10-6 going into Sunday's game against Washington.
They are ahead of the Knicks in the Atlantic Division and in solid
contention for a playoff spot in this lockout-shortened year.
</P>
<P>
   Their accomplishments have much to do with Iverson's making a
huge adjustment: converting from point guard to shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that I have learned a lot from my first two seasons,''
Iverson said in a national conference call with the news media
before scoring 34 points in a loss to Miami on Friday. ``Playing
shooting guard has taken a lot of pressure off of me and I think my
teammates are doing a great job of getting me the ball in spots
where I am moving and creating scoring opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Named the NBA's player of the month for February, Iverson is the
first Philadelphia player to be chosen for the award since Charles
Barkley in November 1988. Wilt Chamberlain was the last member of
the 76ers to lead the league in scoring, when he averaged 33.5
points a game in 1965-66.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely playing the best ball of his career,'' coach
Larry Brown said. ``He listens to everything I say, he does
everything I ask of him and he's playing harder than ever. He's
been absolutely phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Isiah Thomas is regarded as one of the greatest little men to
play the game. Though Iverson is still a few years away from
becoming a genuinely great player, his game already is striking.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two years ago, Iverson symbolized much of what was
wrong with the NBA. It wasn't just that he monopolized the ball; he
was one of the worst examples of the NBA's crop of shoot-first and
pass-later point guards.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson believed that as long as he looked good on the floor,
losing could be tolerated. After all, he was one of only two
players from the 1996 draft to have his own signature line of
sneakers before his team won a game.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, he refused to disassociate himself from the
unsavory characters of his past just because he was successful.
While he has not cut ties to his friends, professing loyalty, he
has made an effort to keep his personal and professional lives
separate, which has meant no hangers-on at practice or on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Though the last infraction Iverson was involved in was in August
1997 _ he was a passenger in a car that was found to have marijuana
and a concealed weapon inside it _ the bad-guy label is still in
the back of the public's mind.
</P>
<P>
   On the court at the least, Iverson, who routinely butted heads
with Brown in his first two seasons, has accepted his new role and
flourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year, I didn't know the NBA game at all,'' he said.
``I knew the college game because of coach John Thompson, and I
knew how to play high school ball because of my high school coach.
Now coach Brown is teaching me the whole, overall NBA game. I know
it takes time and I have a long way to go, but that has been the
difference, learning how to play the game a little bit more.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of Brown, he added: ``He came in with the identity of being hard
on point guards. And that is true. He knows that is where a team
really starts and that is where it ends _ at the point-guard
position. We started out kind of rocky, but once we got to know
each other and understand each other better, we started to have a
great relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson scored 32.4 percent of the 76ers' points during
February, and had 30 or more points six times (Philadelphia was 4-2
in those games) including 46 points against San Antonio on Feb. 12.
He scored 10 or more points in a quarter 14 times and 20 or more
points in a half six times, and extended his double-figure scoring
streak to 27 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he's also won the respect of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just unstoppable,'' Aaron McKie said. ``To be so little,
he's so tough. He gets knocked down, gets right back up and is
ready to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
