<HEADER>
A0274 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATEX-ALLERGY-ART-2ND     03-06 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATEX-ALLERGY-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: scientific complexity. '' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Glove manufacturers, which have found themselves the subjects of
lawsuits, have tried to block legislation banning latex gloves. At
the same time, they are creating alternative products.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from Johnson &AMP; Johnson, for example, have
written to state legislators arguing against bills that would ban
powdered latex in hospitals. Meanwhile, the company has been
producing low-powder gloves and options to latex.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been putting forward the alternatives,'' said John
McKeegan, a company spokesman. ``But there is a demand out there
for powdered gloves, and they are the ones that sell the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Regent Medical has been very aggressive in marketing its
powder-free gloves, including surgical gloves called Biogel, which
have a powder substitute that helps the glove slip on. Yet
powder-free gloves make up only 5 percent of the company's glove
business, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of hospitals across the country _ including Johns
Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore, St. Mary's Hospital in Waterbury,
Conn., and Olean Hospital in Olean, N.Y. _ have either banned latex
gloves or restricted them to certain parts of their buildings. But
in general, doctors, particularly surgeons, are extremely resistant
to nonlatex alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, even medical workers with the allergy resist change.
``They think, `I desperately need this high-paying job in this
prestigious teaching hospital, I need the medical insurance and I
cannot afford to acknowledge a latex allergy,''' said Gail Lenehan,
chairwoman of the Massachusetts Emergency Nurses Association's
Latex Allergy Task Force. ``I have heard female surgeons say they
live in a man's world and fear a bias against them, and residents
say they won't speak up because they are low on the totem pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, some hospitals are starting to change. ``We wanted to be
a leader in this area,'' said Robert G. Hamilton, an associate
professor of medicine and pathology at Johns Hopkins, which is
becoming latex-free. ``Cost is the fundamental question. But we
purchased a sufficient volume of stretch vinyl, which resulted in
no change in cost.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, an increasing number of lawsuits are charging
manufacturers with negligence and product liability, or with
continuing to market a product that they know to be harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Howell Rosenberg, a partner with Brookman, Rosenberg, Brown &AMP;
Sandler, a law firm in Philadelphia, estimated that about 250 cases
against glove manufacturers have gone to federal courts around the
country, up from about 25 cases two and a half years ago. His
office is handling a suit on behalf of all the Federal cases,
roughly 12 percent of which are from New York. Dozens more are
being tried in state courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to be closely watched,'' Rosenberg said.
``We are talking about lots of people, and the greatest number of
victims are in health care. That is a very significant segment of
the work force who are doing very important jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
