<HEADER>
A0284 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-REPUBLICANS-NYT &LR;      03-06 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-REPUBLICANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW TACK FOR REPUBLICANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, March 7:
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton put Republicans on the defensive when he
proposed to tap most of the budget surplus in the next 15 years to
shore up Social Security and pay down the national debt, not to cut
taxes as they wanted. Most voter surveys show that Americans
embrace Clinton's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in their first formal response to the president's budget,
the Republicans have tried to outdo him by setting aside even more
money for Social Security than Clinton proposed. They would also
defer their tax cuts for at least two years. Their new approach is
a step in the right direction. But it has many flaws, including
unacceptable cuts in Medicare and other domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican move reflects a clear recognition that the
party's lawmakers cannot be seen as less than zealous about
protecting Social Security. At present, the system generates a
surplus, but it is due to slip into insolvency in the next 15 years
as baby boomers start to retire. For many years the Social Security
surplus has been used to pay for other spending in the budget, and
the Republicans now say they want to end that practice right away.
The problem with such a step is that it would require steep budget
cuts next year. The Republicans already have said they want
spending increases in defense and some education programs, so the
cuts would have to come in myriad other programs that they have not
yet specified.
</P>
<P>
   There always are places to find budget savings. The White
House's proposal for an increase in cigarette taxes would provide
some revenue to avoid cuts. Rep. John Kasich, chairman of the House
Budget Committee and a likely presidential candidate, has long
promised to get tough on unnecessary federal subsidies to business
known as ``corporate welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if these savings materialize, it is doubtful that the
Republicans can reach their goal without gutting vital programs in
health, nutrition and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The new Republican budget is a little more realistic on tax
cuts. It deals a rebuff to Kasich, the House's biggest advocate of
immediate across-the-board tax cuts, by recognizing that there is
not enough money available for significant tax cuts right now. But
the plan violates common sense by proposing tax cuts for the years
ahead. No one can be sure what the economy will look like in three
years, and tax cuts should not be enacted until Congress figures
out how to rescue the nation's other big program threatened with
insolvency, Medicare, which is due to run deficits in less than 10
years. The White House's call for Medicare reform, including an
expansion of some services like prescription drugs, ought to be one
of this Congress' biggest priorities.
</P>
<P>
   For all their problems, the Republicans are to be commended for
beginning to wrestle with the budget problems. Nothing can be done
unless each positive step by one side is met with a positive
gesture by the other side. The conventional wisdom in Washington is
that in the current poisonous atmosphere, Congress and the White
House cannot think big thoughts or do big things. The new
Republican budget proposals are vague and full of pitfalls, but
they could also hasten serious negotiations and compromises in
everyone's interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1701EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
