<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-NYT     03-06 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: )  
 ANALYSIS: LOOKING PAST A SINGLE PILOT, SCRUTINY SHIFTS TO MARINE
CORPS 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. _ Capt. Richard Ashby alone, and not the
Marine Corps, was on trial in the court-martial that ended on
Thursday with his acquittal on charges of involuntary homicide and
manslaughter for flying his Prowler jet into gondola cables in the
Italian Alps.
</P>
<P>
   But it did not look good for the Marine Corps, which emerged as
a sort of unindicted co-conspirator in the accident that resulted
in the charges. Twenty people were killed when their ski gondola
plummeted near Cavalese on Feb. 3, 1998, after Ashby's jet cut the
cables 360 feet above the ground, ostensibly while he was trying to
maintain an altitude of 1,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Information presented at Ashby's court-martial and drawn from
related investigations indicates that the corps had no program to
be sure its pilots were up-to-date on all rules, that the Marine
Corps sent crews on routes so infrequently that they could not be
expected to maintain proficiency, and that it equipped crews with
charts lacking important features _ most significantly, the
existence of the gondola ski lift.
</P>
<P>
   If an investigation showed that a civilian airline involved in
an accident had had similar problems, that airline would face a lot
of orders from regulators, and maybe worse.
</P>
<P>
   In both the civilian and military worlds, though, prosecutions
of airline pilots are rare, partly because pilots who err badly
seldom live to be defendants. Even airlines and other aviation
companies that commit major lapses seldom face criminal charges. In
that sense, the prosecution of Ashby was unusual by any measure.
</P>
<P>
   But the acquittal does not mean that no one was responsible,
only that prosecutors did not persuade at least six of the eight
jurors that enough of the blame was Ashby's that he should go to
prison. (The court-martial of his navigator, Capt. Joseph
Schweitzer, is scheduled for this month but is now uncertain.)
</P>
<P>
   The jurors declined requests for interviews, having been warned
by the judge that other charges were pending, including one for
obstruction of justice against Ashby. Their ballot sheets were
shredded.
</P>
<P>
   But a Marine spokeswoman, Lt. Col. Ellen Haddock, said it was a
``reasonable explanation'' that if jurors failed to assign enough
blame to Ashby to convict him, then some of the blame must lie with
the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   One likely spot to look for accountability is in the failure of
officers in Ashby's squadron to keep track of incoming information,
identify what was important and then require all pilots to read the
information. Another problem was the failure of the Marine
squadrons, which rotated through the Aviano Air Base in Italy, to
coordinate with the Air Force squadron, which was assigned there
permanently, on the flow of information.
</P>
<P>
   At the trial, the defense argued that there were communications
failures within the Marine Corps and between the Marines and the
Air Force, which was supposed to provide information for the
Marines. The Air Force had warned its own pilots of a local rule
prohibiting flight below 2,000 feet, but paperwork on file in the
Marine office gave minimum altitudes as low as 500 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps, though, says it is learning from the accident.
It is reviewing its procedures for all flights, Haddock said, and
has put ``increased emphasis on receipt, maintenance, dissemination
and accountability of safety-of-flight information.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, when aircraft squadrons deploy to new
places, their commanders must ``personally brief the commanding
general about the training and operations that will be conducted
during the deployment.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the near term, the assurance President Clinton gave on
Friday to the Italian prime minister, Massimo D'Alema, that the
Aviano accident would not be repeated, may rely more on following
existing rules than on making procedural changes. American
warplanes at Aviano are strictly adhering to a 2,000-foot altitude
restriction, the existence of which was not known to all pilots
before the crash, and the Prowler pilots are not flying any
low-altitude missions from Aviano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1705EST &QL; 
