<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0286 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAHRAIN-EMIR-ART-525&AMP;     03-06 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHRAIN-EMIR-ART-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAHRAIN EMIR DIES AFTER MEETING ON U.S. ARMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia _ The emir of Bahrain, a key U.S. ally in
the Persian Gulf region, collapsed and died Saturday at the age of
66 after a meeting with visiting Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   The emir, Sheik Isa bin Sulman Al-Khalifa, had ruled the tiny
island nation since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   He was immediately succeeded by his son Sheik Hamad bin Isa
Al-Khalifa, 49, in what by all appearances was a smooth transfer of
power.
</P>
<P>
   Hamad, who had been crown prince, had already held the title of
commander in chief of Bahrain's armed forces. He is said to share
the pro-Western orientation that has made Bahrain an important base
for U.S. military operations in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the transfer of power marks the end of an era for
Bahrain, where the emir had been a dominant force for nearly four
decades. It may also offer a foretaste of what lies in store for
several other Persian Gulf monarchies whose leaders are in
questionable health.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi ruler, King Fahd, 79, has been hospitalized several
times in the past three years; the monarch's brother, Crown Prince
Abdullah, 77, is now running the kingdom on a day-to-day-basis.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, in Bahrain at the start of a nine-country tour of the
Middle East, said he had been ``stunned and saddened'' to learn of
Isa's sudden death. The cause, according to Bahraini officials, was
a heart attack that the emir suffered just minutes after the two
ended a half-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Isa had suffered heart problems in the past; he visited
Cleveland, Ohio, last year to undergo heart treatment. He had shown
no recent signs of ill health.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said that Cohen, who arrived Saturday night in
Riyadh, the Saudi capital, on the second leg of his journey, had
offered to stay in Bahrain to attend Isa's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Bahrain said that as many as 10,000 people attended
the funeral, and that flower petals were strewn on the capital's
streets. Bahrain state radio said that Hamad had earlier informed
an emergency Cabinet meeting of his father's death and that he was
taking power under the kingdom's laws.
</P>
<P>
   Isa's death was announced to the people of Bahrain after state
television began broadcasting recitations from the Koran, the
Islamic holy book, a standard practice after the death of a leader
in the Muslim world. The scenes were reminiscent of those played on
Jordanian television just one month ago, after the death of King
Hussein, another key U.S. ally.
</P>
<P>
   Bahrain's new emir, Hamad, is an experienced military commander
who graduated from the British military academy at Sandhurst. As
crown prince since 1964, he presided over a buildup of Bahrain's
armed forces, and has been seen as a strong proponent of Bahrain's
emerging partnership with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials say he has shown no indication that he would
back away from the arrangements that have made Bahrain the
headquarters for the United States' 5th Fleet, which patrols the
Persian Gulf. Nor, they say, has he voiced opposition to
arrangements that, in a series of recent crises, have allowed U.S.
warplanes to be in Bahrain for possible use against Iraq.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hamad inherits an emirate whose strength as a banking and
financial capital has helped to make up for its relative lack of
oil, though it remains a poor cousin among its Persian Gulf
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   There are also deep domestic strains, particularly between
Bahrain's majority population of Shiite Muslims and the more
prosperous Sunni minority, headed by the Al-Khalifa family, which
controls nearly all power and privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, those strains have played out in a campaign of
low-level violence, including bombings and other attacks, that have
claimed more than two dozen lives.
</P>
<P>
   Under Isa, Bahraini authorities responded with a heavy hand,
sending security forces into the streets and arresting scores of
Shiite activists, many of whom remain in jail. As commander of
Bahrain's military forces, Hamad has been closely identified with
that policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
