<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WITH JARVIS AND CALHOUN, TENSION RETURNS 
</HEADLINE>
 (fb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Big East Commissioner Mike Tranghese kicked off Big East
Tournament week he acknowledged Pearl Washington, the former
Syracuse star. Then Tranghese recalled the Big East championship
game in 1984 between Syracuse and Georgetown, a game still
remembered as one of the fiercest championship games in Big East
history with Michael Graham decking Syracuse's Andre Hawkins, the
game going into overtime and Jim Boeheim storming off the podium,
knocking over a folding chair as he left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really had to be there,'' Tranghese said. Like many fans
of the era, the commissioner longed for that time when the Big East
was legendary.
</P>
<P>
   The rivalries were forged not by teams or institutions but by
personalities. John Thompson and Rick Pitino going at it, with
Thompson calling Pitino a ``young punk'' and Pitino shouting:
``Grow up, John.'' Or Lou Carnesecca calling Rollie Massimino a
``Hollywood Hotdog'' a year after Massimino led Villanova to the
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   The personalities faded and the thrill was gone as well. But
there was a resurgence of bad blood and angst over the last week.
In its 20th anniversary, the Big East got the championship game it
has craved: Connecticut, which for the last eight years has set the
standard in the Big East and St. John's, the conference's nerve
center.
</P>
<P>
   The tension was back, largely because St. John's was back.
</P>
<P>
   In January UConn overcame a 12-point deficit and handed St.
John's a 78-74 defeat at Madison Square Garden. After that loss,
Jarvis said: ``We can play with them _ and we can beat them. And
they know it. The day will come, I hope sooner than later. We will
beat them. In our house. Madison Square Garden. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing friendly about this rivalry. The tension
between the coaches is expressed through their respective players.
Ron Artest, St. John's sophomore forward, said of Connecticut,
``They're one of the more arrogant teams we play.''
</P>
<P>
   This tension has deep roots. Calhoun, 56, and Jarvis, 53, first
met as players: Jarvis at Northeastern, Calhoun at American
International. In 1972, Calhoun was hired to coach Northeastern,
effectively passing over Jarvis, who had been an assistant at
Northeastern since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun, who would put Northeastern on the national map, hired
Jarvis as freshman coach. Jarvis held the job but continued to
teach physical education at Cambridge Rindge and Latin High school.
</P>
<P>
   He left after a season and took a job as assistant coach at
Harvard then got his first head coaching job in 1985 when he became
head coach at Boston University. Last night's championship game
marked the eighth time Calhoun and Jarvis have met. Calhoun led the
series 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   The tension between the two grew out of Calhoun's one loss _ an
80-71 defeat in December 1986 in a game at B.U. It was Calhoun's
fifth game at UConn.
</P>
<P>
   The team bus was involved in an accident beforehand and UConn
wanted to postpone the game. B.U. told the Huskies they would have
to forfeit if they didn't show. Before the game Calhoun told
reporters about the accident and said Jarvis did not give his team
enough time to warm up. Calhoun vowed never to play B.U. again.
</P>
<P>
   The schools did not meet again until a 1990 match during the
opening round of the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament. When a reporter asked Calhoun how he felt about playing
against a Jarvis-coached team, he said: ``You don't have to be
dance partners to respect somebody. My relationship with him has
been very good _ because we're 100 miles apart.'' In 1993, Jarvis
and Calhoun served on the staff of Kansas Coach Roy Williams for
the U.S. 22- and-under team and apparently mended fences.
</P>
<P>
   But for two coaches with the same stubborn, ego-centric
personalities, no fence will stay mended for long. The relationship
took another turn last year when Jarvis and Calhoun were honored at
the America East Conference 20th anniversary banquet. Jarvis spoke
first, offering insights and comments about his accomplishments.
When Calhoun stepped up to podium that was close to a wall, he said
he was surprised there was enough room to accommodate Jarvis and
his ego.
</P>
<P>
   In an odd way that only those who have followed the Big East
from the beginning can know, the Calhoun-Jarvis feud and St. John's
resurgence answers a larger question: Will the Big East ever
recapture its glow of the 1980s? If Calhoun's relationship with
Jarvis is any indication, the answer is a resounding yes.
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese put his finger on it earlier this week. What makes the
Big East so tantalizing is the mix and clash of personalities. In
this conference, it's never business, it's personal. UConn and St.
John's-Jarvis and Calhoun. This is a rivalry worth watching.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
