</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY TEXANS AT ODDS ON LATINO GROUPS, DETENTION CENTERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENNIFER DAY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two Texans named to ranking membership posts on the
House immigration subcommittee are taking opposing positions on two
issues of consequence to the state.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's unclear whether Reps. Sheila Jackson Lee,
D-Houston, and Lamar Smith, R-San Antonio, will agree on many
issues before the subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigration's impact on Americans is so great that it's not an
exaggeration to say that you either change immigration policy or
you change every other policy,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't accept the goodness of immigration and what the
immigrants have been able to do and at the same time characterize
immigrants for all of the ailments and problems in America,''
Jackson Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2 million of the state's residents are immigrants, an
increase of 51 percent over the last decade. As many as 700,000
illegal immigrants may be living in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, chairman of the Subcommittee on Immigration and Claims,
and Jackson Lee, the subcommittee's ranking minority member, have
taken opposing stances on issues involving Central American
immigrants and overcrowded detention centers:
</P>
<P>
   _ Jackson Lee, following the Clinton administration's lead, has
said she would like to ``balance'' the playing field for
Guatemalans, Salvadorans, Nicaraguans and Cubans who came to the
United States as refugees during the 1980s. Nicaraguans and Cubans
were granted amnesty by Congress in &UR;  &LR; 1997. Guatemalans and
Salvadorans, who sued for special benefits, are allowed to stay in
the United States only if they show they would be subjected to
``extreme hardship'' if deported.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in the discrepancies between Nicaraguans and
Guatemalans,'' Jackson Lee said. ``Some are given waivers and some
aren't. We need to be balanced and fair, not pitting one country
against the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith has spoken out against the White House's efforts, which he
contends could make 240,000 people and 360,000 dependents eligible
for what he calls ``de facto amnesty.''
</P>
<P>
   The two groups have nothing in common, said Allen Kay, Smith's
spokesman. Guatemalans and Salvadorans came to the United States
because of civil strife in their homelands, while Cuban and
Nicaraguan refugees were allies in the fight against communism
during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said changing the rules would encourage others to come to
the country illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sets a terrible precedent,'' he said at a recent
subcommittee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the detention debate, Smith called for INS Commissioner
Doris Meissner's resignation after reports surfaced that the INS
may have been planning to release immigrants who are criminals to
relieve overcrowding in its detention facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Although neither representative thinks violent offenders should
be released, they have different ideas as to what caused the
crowding and how it should be fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Smith contends that overcrowded detention centers are a result
of mismanagement at INS, which has mushroomed in size over the past
five years. The agency now employs more armed agents with arrest
powers than the FBI and federal Bureau of Prisons.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee blames crowding on Congress, which she said passed
overly broad laws requiring the INS to lock up productive, legal
immigrants ``It's not a question of too many detainees; it's
whether we have a rational law,'' said Lee, who cited cases in
which legal immigrants with minor convictions were detained under a
1996 immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said there are ``a handful of compelling exceptions,'' but
that the vast majority of immigrants with convictions are violent
offenders no one would want on the streets. A revision of the law
that put those ``compelling exceptions'' in detention centers is
unnecessary, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although detention centers and Central American immigrants
have been top priorities, Smith and Lee have their own ideas about
what the rest of the year's focus should be.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee wants to explore whether caps on immigration from
certain countries are fair and how to reconcile the practice of
allowing migrants into the country for labor but not for
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Smith plans to investigate how immigration affects the U.S.
economy and its native workers as well as whether there should be
educational requirements for immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   The INS has an agenda, too. It would like Congress to restore
its authority to determine whether illegal immigrants with criminal
records should be detained.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one item that seems to pop up on everyone's agenda,
it's that something needs to be done to reform the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals for reorganization range from eliminating the agency
to making it a free-standing department &UR;  &LR; in which a commissioner
could have more say in policy decision-making.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Lee said she supports a restructuring of the agency
rather than a dismantling.
</P>
<P>
   INS is attempting to head off the issue by working on a reform
plan that it will present to Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he is not sure it will work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interested in (INS's plan) if it's productive. I'm not
interested in moving boxes around on an organizational chart,'' he
said. ``Do we need restructuring or do we need better management of
what we have?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
