<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DELL _ XIAMEN, China _ It's beginning to look as though
Michael Dell will do it again. This time in the People's Republic
of China. In less than a year, a landing party of expatriates from
Dell Computer Corp.'s Singapore office has paddled through China's
notorious bureaucratic reefs. (Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in International/Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   w/DELL-SIDE _ XIAMEN, China _ A dual profile about the two main
movers in the Dell's China operation _ Buddy Griffin, an Irishman
who is the inside man in charge of the manufacturing plant, and
Dell China president David Chan, the ex-IBM outside man who lives
out of a suitcase and travels around China trying to sell
computers. (Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in International/Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   w/DELL-Q&AMP;A _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A question-and-answer with Dell
Computer Corp. founder and chairman Michael Dell. (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman). 10.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in International/Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   w/LATAM-DELL _ MIAMI _ Despite economic turmoil in Brazil, Dell
Computer Corp. hopes to repeat its U.S. success throughout Latin
America in coming years. By 2002, the Round Rock, Texas-based
company, which sold 3.8 million units to Latin America in 1997,
hopes to see a growth rate of 23 percent in the region. Dell is
even on track with plans to open a manufacturing and customer
service plant in Brazil this summer. But continued growth won't be
easy. Not only is Brazil's economy expected to fall into a
recession this year, buying patterns in Latin America are changing
fast and many other U.S. companies are already struggling to
maintain their share of a slower-growing market. (Emling, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED in International/Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ A recommendation that Microsoft be
broken up if it loses its antitrust case is but one of the ideas
being floated on a 'what if' basis in a case that has a long way to
go before being resolved. (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MOVED Friday in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   KASICH _ AMES, Iowa _ John Kasich's ``Rolling Through Iowa''
tour of bowling alleys is the kind of novel campaign touch that
makes some people think the Ohio congressman may have the right
combination of ideas and youthful energy to make his mark in the
Republican president race. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving Saturday in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-FAMILY _ WASHINGTON _ It's not easy to be a parent and
a member of Congress. We talk to lawmakers about balancing the
needs of their children with those of the nation. (Moscoso, Cox
News Service). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-BUSINESS _ WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore is actively
courting business groups as he runs for the Democratic presidential
nomination. This requires some careful positioning for a candidate
better known as an environmental activist. (Shepard, Cox News
Service). 30. MOVED Friday in (w) Washington and (p) politics
categories.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-SAFETY _ WASHINGTON _ At a time when the trucking industry
is under congressional scrutiny for an increasing number of deaths
in crashes between big rigs and passenger cars, a Cox Newspapers
analysis finds that the car drivers are three times more likely to
be cited by police investigators for driving errors that
contributed to the accident. The numbers suggest that while safety
advocates are urging a crackdown on unsafe trucks and truck
drivers, the biggest opportunity to save lives may be to better
educate car drivers how to avoid risky behavior around trucks.
(Dart and Jaspin, Cox News Service 1200).
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-ADVOCATES _ WASHINGTON _ Truck safety advocates say that
statistics are misleading, and that the keys to reducing highway
deaths are lighter, better-maintained trucks and expert, rested
drivers. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-DATA _ Graphics material.
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-DRIVER _ ON THE ROAD _ Hal T. Burks has been a
long-distance trucker for 24 years. As he rolls across the South,
he talks about the ups and downs of the trucker's life. (Dart, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: MOVED Tuesday, Feb. 23 in (l) lifestyle category.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HAITIANS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Two boats carrying a total of
30 Haitians sank in the Bahamas early today. Four are confirmed
dead, three were rescued, and the search is on for the rest of the
survivors. developing. (Gonzalez/Hobbs, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-OLYMPIC-FOUNDATION _ ATLANTA _ The non-profit foundation
charged with building Atlanta's Olympic legacy has done essentially
nothing in the nearly three years that have passed since the Games
except funnel nearly $1 million to its chairman, Billy Payne.
Though the Georgia Amateur Athletics Foundation's stated tax-exempt
purpose is to foster amateur sports development, little has been
spent on youth athletics. A community Olympic development program
which pledged to pump $1 million into kids sports programs in
Atlanta has yet to get underway nearly three years after the Games,
and visions for an Olympic museum have yet to come into focus. Now
the foundation is on the verge of losing its public charity status
if it doesn't start raising money and giving it away. (Turner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MARCH-CIVILRIGHTS _ John Lewis leads a bipartisan congressional
delegation today across the Edmund Pettus Bridge to commemorate the
1965 march for voting rights of African Americans. This year's
march (he did it for the first time last year) takes on special
significance in light of the partisan rancor that has engulfed the
House this year. Several members of the Judiciary committee and the
Republican who presided over the impeachment debate will attend,
and Lewis sees it as a chance to help heal both racial and partisan
divides. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-SOUTH _ Fire-scarred Florida and other Southern states are
fighting a wave of winter wildfires triggered by unusually dry
weather. Troublesome fires have blazed in Alabama and South
Carolina, while in Florida the Gatorland tourist attraction in
Kissimmee was evacuated over last weekend when a large fire came
dangerously close. We round up the hot spots and check in with the
weather experts to see if the coming summer will be worse.
(MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FAITH-HEALING _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Rather than take her
grandmother to the hospital before she died, Jana Colosimo watched
members of her grandmother's church pour a mix of bleach and water
over her bed sores and then cover them with lard and gauze.
Colosimo's grandmother, a member of the General Assembly and Church
of the Firstborn, had fallen, probably breaking her hip, but the
church's strong belief in spiritual healing and the rejection of
medical help for the sick kept her from seeing a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Colosimo and her sister, Deborah Davis, believe she would have
gone to a doctor before her death if church members had not kept
such a close watch. (Joyce, Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
