<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-IOWA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS GOP CANDIDATES FLOCK TO IOWA, SOME ASK WHY GOV. BUSH IS ABSENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Hugh Winebrenner, unofficial statistician of
the Iowa presidential caucuses, scanned his latest tabulation of
how many times prospective Republican candidates have shown up in
the important early-caucus state.
</P>
<P>
   From Jan. 20, 1997, through early last week, Sen. Bob Smith of
New Hampshire had spent 44 days in Iowa, former Tennessee Gov.
Lamar Alexander 41 days, former Vice President Dan Quayle 21 days,
House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich 20 days _ and so on
through the list of more than a dozen probable as well as
implausible contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Even New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has spent three days in
Iowa. And hardly a week goes by that another would-be president or
two doesn't swirl through.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously missing from Winebrenner's list is the most
talked-about prospective candidate: Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has pledged to remain in Texas until the Legislature
adjourns in May, but then plans to travel the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has pointedly avoided travel to Iowa, the state that put
his father, former President Bush, on a winding road to the White
House almost 20 years ago with a surprise caucus victory over
Ronald Reagan. Reagan won the 1980 nomination and named Bush his
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   So, Iowans ask, where is the Texas governor? When will he come
roam the rural towns and neatly trimmed suburbs? When will he
unveil a staff? When will he begin to set up the
precinct-by-precinct organization in the state's 99 counties that
is the traditional key to victory here?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he might be very strong. There is a lot of respect
here for the Bush name,'' said Greg E. Mollman, an insurance
executive active in Republican politics. ``But people here want to
see the candidate, look him in the eyes, before they make any
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   It's known as ``retail'' politics, and it takes time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowa is a trench game,'' said Marlys Popma, former Iowa GOP
executive director who has become a leader in conservative activist
Gary Bauer's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even as vice president, Bush's father spent 43 days in Iowa in
the two years before the 1988 caucuses _ in which he ran third and
had to scramble to recover in the New Hampshire primary and go on
to win the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain risk in not showing up,'' said Winebrenner,
a professor of public administration at Drake University in Des
Moines.
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides in Austin, Texas, refused to detail how much time the
governor was willing to spend in Iowa in the 11 months before the
Feb. 7 caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told the Iowa legislators that if he does run he will take
Iowa seriously and he will campaign there,'' said Bush spokeswoman
Karen Hughes. ``But we've not gotten as far as discussing the
number of days anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Any idea that Bush can triumph in Iowa without a lot of personal
attention to the state and its Republican voters is ``totally
unrealistic,'' said David Kochel, state director for the
presidential campaign of Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't just show up and wave from the tarmac,'' Kochel
said.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush stumps sufficiently in Iowa, he could do well if his
polling numbers remain high, activists agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to go with the winner. It would be foolish to deny
that's in people's thought process,'' said Popma, who was a state
leader in 1996 for the failed campaign of Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be true for Elizabeth Hanford Dole, the wife of
the former senator and 1996 GOP presidential nominee, who will
announce Wednesday in Iowa that she is forming an exploratory
committee to consider running.
</P>
<P>
   Dole has been in Iowa three days over the last two years,
according to Winebrenner's count, and on her latest visit drew
2,500 people to a ``nonpolitical'' meeting in Ames, Iowa. She also
has the experience of campaigning often in the state for her
husband, Bob.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he will not formally launch a campaign until late
summer, and some Iowa political operatives, including Bush
supporters, believe that will give him a rationale for skipping an
Iowa Republican straw poll scheduled for Aug. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's father ran third in the straw ballot in 1987, signaling
the problems he would face six months later in the Iowa caucuses.
But as the elder Bush proved, there is life after a political death
in Iowa _ he eventually won the nomination and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush supporters try not to show any alarm about the governor's
decision to stay away from Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. E. Thurman Gaskill of Corwith, a longtime Bush family
friend and supporter, said that whenever Bush comes to Iowa he will
know how to approach the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will go out into the small communities,'' said Gaskill,
former president of the National Corn Growers Association. ``He
will meet people one on one. I think this is where the governor
comes across well.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Brown, the Dallas Center lawyer who helped to run the 1980
George Bush campaign, predicted the younger Bush can pick up
supporters quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are excited about the prospect of a George (W.)
Bush candidacy,'' Brown said. ``People are looking for a new
generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Bush and his campaign leaders may turn to an untested
generation of Iowans as organizers, in part because so many of the
old-line GOP tacticians are already signed up with other
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest problem George W. is going to have is
finding leadership individuals who have organizational ability,''
Popma said. ``So many of those people are gone. I don't know where
he's going to for his leadership people.''
</P>
<P>
   It has not gone unnoticed here that Karl Rove, Bush's top
political organizer in Austin, is the former direct-mail vendor for
the Iowa GOP and, like Bush, has close ties to many key party
activists. Bush campaign chief possibilities include Rep. Chuck
Larsen Jr., who organized a letter from Iowa legislators urging
Bush to run.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Alexander has rounded up the biggest Iowa GOP stars,
including former Gov. Terry Branstad.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Roberts, a Des Moines lawyer who is national
Republican committeeman from Iowa, said the Texas governor should
not despair: ``The Bush organization has an abundance of riches
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question is, when will Bush begin to mobilize them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Iowans like to be romanced,'' Alexander told a group of GOP
activists last week, ``and it needs to be a longish courtship.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
