<HEADER>
A0305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KASICH07-COX     03-06 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KASICH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KASICH BOWLS OVER VOTERS IN IOWA
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    With AP photos.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMES, Iowa _ John Kasich's ``Rolling Through Iowa'' tour of
bowling centers scored a strike this weekend among those looking
for a true man of the people in the Republican presidential field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no zip,'' Kasich laughed Saturday after leaving a
7-10 split on Lane 2 at the 20th Century Bowling Center. It was the
second of six bowling centers on his four-day weekend visit to
Iowa, where the first presidential voting in the nation will take
place in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Karen, his wife, laughed. What the hyperkenetic congressman does
not lack is zip. He may have bowled only a 96, but he was bouncing
from one lane to the next, talking about ``running America from the
bottom up,'' with ``everyday people ... having more power over
their lives and more freedom to pursue their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The political establishment sees Kasich's chances of winning the
Republican presidential nomination in 2000 as about equal to those
of converting that 7-10 split. He front-running opponents have
establishment names like Bush and Dole, and his poll numbers put
him far back in the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not going to go anywhere,'' said Charles Cook, publisher
of the Cook Political Report newsletter in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Ed Goeas, a veteran GOP pollster who has signed on with the
Kasich campaign, insisted his client has a chance to break out of
the pack because he is the least packaged and programmed candidate
in the field. ``He catches the imagination,'' said Goeas.
</P>
<P>
   That view was shared by some at the 20th Century Bowling Center,
where a $20 bill will get you a 12-inch pizza, a pitcher of
Budweiser and 20 frames of bowling, with change to spare _ if you
have your own ball and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich, a man of modest background, was seen as a true populist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really relates to people,'' said Bud Legg, athletic
director of Ames High School. ``He has the knack for bringing all
factions together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a hell-raiser,'' Kasich told a group of small business
owners as he described how he would shake up the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you logged on to my Web site, kiddo?'' he asked
9-year-old Dana Deyoe, daughter of hog farmer Dave Deyoe from the
nearby town of Nevada. ``There's a lot on there about my dog, Penny
Bird. There's more about my dog than about me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll wear a toga,'' he told a group of Iowa State University
students as they jointly planned his return visit for a fantasy
rock concert.
</P>
<P>
   And rarely does Kasich forget to mention his roots, that he is
the ``son of a mailman.'' It is left to his listeners to draw their
own contrast of Kasich to Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
millionaire son of a millionaire ex-president, or to Elizabeth
Dole, the millionaire wife of a millionaire ex-senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been where we are,'' said Terri Loney, an Ames middle
school teacher who accepted Kasich's invitation to join him in
bowling. ``It's refreshing to see his enthusiasm, his concern for
the common man. His background clearly makes a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   On this Saturday, while acknowledging that he ``didn't grow up
poor,'' he recalled how as a child he used to wish the family car
had automatic transmission and a radio. His father always bought
the cheaper, standard-shift cars with no costly extras.
</P>
<P>
   Heads nodded.
</P>
<P>
   Making that personal connection is just as important, at least
at this stage in the campaign, as his nuts-and-bolts agenda of tax
cuts, reforming Social Security and Medicare, school vouchers and
eliminating the Departments of Commerce and Education.
</P>
<P>
   It's one reason that his 16 years in the House, the last five as
chairman of the Budget Committee, do not seem to count against him
at a time when Congress is held in low esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the ins and outs of the government's finances like
nobody else,'' said Deyoe.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich acknowledged to the reporters tagging along that his
``Rolling Through Iowa'' tour is a shameless publicity stunt. But
he still believes that the bowling centers are perfect settings for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not going to be a campaign just run from television,''
Kasich said. ``I want people to come look me in the eye, poke me,
smell me, and I think they'll love me.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
