<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS TAKE A CASUAL STROLL TO OBLIVION
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the undisputed worst team in the Eastern Conference was run
off its home floor by a banged-up and bad Charlotte Hornets team
Thursday night, an annual rite of winter returned to the
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   Open season on those poor old Nets began anew after nearly a
year off due to renovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put in Jack Haley,'' someone yelled facetiously from behind
the team bench, imploring the assistant coach/team mascot to suit
up. Someone else sat on the opposite baseline, holding up a sign
that read, ``We Need a New Coach.''
</P>
<P>
   John Calipari, the current coach, claimed he did not notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Changing the culture'' has been a huge theme for the coach and
the team, but watching the Hornets open a 17-point lead in the
first quarter was enough to make you wonder how much had changed.
Once again, that old Net malcontent, Derrick Coleman, was on the
floor _ albeit for Charlotte _ the fans were fed up and the
playoffs were for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Hyped to no end, the team that looked good on a glossy magazine
cover in early February is now in danger of playing out the rest of
its days next to the automobile classified ads.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets meet a Knicks team on Sunday at Madison Square Garden
that badly needs a victory after falling hard on the road two
straight times. But at a depressing 3-12, Keith Van Horn, Jayson
Williams and their teammates need the game more. But that's not how
it works with the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   You can fire Calipari, which, unless the Nets completely bottom
out, is unlikely. You can ship players out and bring new blood in
until you fool yourself into believing you have the right
chemistry. You can wait for Sam Cassell to recover from a sprained
ankle and create on offense again. You can even make impressive
runs until you get back into every game.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't run from the obvious: As a franchise, the Nets
don't want it right now.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds Rileyish, but the observation does not come from a
South Beach motivational seminar. Instead, it comes from watching
the Nets up close on Friday, a few feet from behind the team bench.
</P>
<P>
   They simply do not want to win badly enough. They give up
uncontested layups in a half-court defense. They let the man
they're guarding beat them for position under the basket. As
athletic as they can be on offense, they have this soft, West Coast
feel about them, like they believe they can match your circus move
with their own. It's as if some carefree, Venice Beach pick-up
crowd won an all-expense paid trip to play in the NBA for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Not that you have to be a thug to win in the East, but a little
more nasty disposition would help their cause.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets don't need a point guard as much as they need a
presence, a Mario Elie or Charles Oakley, to tidy the place up with
some elbow grease.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced expectations probably wouldn't hurt, either.
</P>
<P>
   Some deranged prophet from this newspaper picked them to go to
the Eastern Conference finals. Of course, that prediction was
brought to you by the same person who said the lockout would end in
early December. So I got caught up in the hype, too.
</P>
<P>
   But trust me on this one: knee-jerk solutions are not the
answer. They don't need a coaching change as much as they need a
heart transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Watching them against the Hornets, you never got the feeling the
players stopped playing for Calipari. With a few minutes left in
the game and the Nets coming back from a 25-point deficit, they
were actually clapping like high school kids after one of his
timeout pep talks.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem was that Williams played only 11 minutes and
then was off getting X-rays on a badly sprained finger.
</P>
<P>
   He is taking a lot of heat for this mess, which makes little
sense. Just because you sign an $86 million deal doesn't mean
you're supposed to average 20 points a game. Williams was never a
great offensive player, and now he can barely hold the ball with
two hands. If he can put back five missed shots a game and play
with the same tenacity, he should be as blameless as Van Horn.
</P>
<P>
   With players occasionally sniping at each other and everyone
throwing darts at Calipari behind his back, Van Horn is one of the
few people in the organization who seems to understand that a
bunker mentality is one of the few ways in this league that bad
teams become good.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari, John Nash, the general manager, and Michael Rowe, the
team president, had a briefing session with the new owners last
week regarding trades. The prevailing feeling was that unless a
no-brainer comes along, this lockout-tinged season is not worth
backing up the truck over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You check the thickness of your skin to make sure it's as
thick as it was last season,'' Rowe said when asked if he expected
troubled teams to be making wholesale changes. ``There's more
pressure in this season, because there's a limited amount of time
to correct problems. But in the history of the NBA, this season
will always have an asterisk next to it, almost like Roger Maris'
61 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We'll get through it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Calipari's job is indeed safe for the moment and moving
players is unlikely, maybe the Nets will realize they are in this
miserable season together and change course _ before the lottery do
them part.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
