<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COMMENTARY:   POSADA IS EVIDENCE OF OWNERS' CONTROL THAT
CONE WANTS TO END
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Yankees renewed Jorge Posada's contract last week with
unilateral frugality, there was little debate about the players'
true market worth. There was no harping on fairness and
faithfulness, as there was last Thanksgiving when Bernie Williams
had the audacity to play the field and make a $90 million catch.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Boss in charge, and the public yawned. In
exercising his contractual leverage over two notable contributors
to last season's all-conquering team, Steinbrenner had a rare
chance to play the game in 50s fashion. He picked the figures, drew
up the contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Take it, he said, or go play in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Steinbrenner knew, those players will be eligible for
arbitration, along the six-year climb to unrestricted free agency.
By that time, beyond the 2001 expiration of baseball's collective
bargaining agreement, major league owners may be counting on a new
set of rules. How dearly they would love to play the NBA game, pay
their players along fixed salary lines.
</P>
<P>
   They should not hold their breath. This will not happen. ``Not
without a huge fight,'' David Cone said recently at his dressing
stall in the Yankees' spring training clubhouse in Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   These were not fighting words, the American League's longtime
player representative wanted to say. They merely reflected the
reality of a different sport, an organized union, a hardened
membership. The basketball players backed themselves into a corner,
ultimately dealt with their first taste of labor strife the way
most people thought they would.
</P>
<P>
   ``They held out for a while,'' Cone said. ``Then they basically
caved.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not that simple, given the careers on the edge and the
many mouths to feed. The NBA players are still reeling in sums
unimaginable to the working stiff, but within a uniform system that
has already had a numbing effect on the upwardly mobile. The NBA
badly needed financial constraints on its young, like Major League
Baseball's, but now makes no special allowances for its most gifted
talent, its most marketable stars.
</P>
<P>
   The next Patrick Ewing will be paid the same as the next Michael
Jordan. There is something inherently unjust and anti-competitive
in a system such as this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Player A gets the same as Player B, no matter how much more
productive, how many more championships, how many more tickets he's
sold,'' said Cone. ``This is tough for me to fathom.''
</P>
<P>
   The general public perception is that the NBA has a system that
is fixed, while Major League Baseball's is broke. Cone would argue,
rather convincingly, for the opposite. He cites the fact that
Bernie Williams toiled in the Yankees' organization for 13 years
before free agency, and wonders what a power and switch-hitting
catcher like Posada, who turns 28 in August, would be worth to any
number of teams.
</P>
<P>
   At least a couple of million more, in all likelihood, than the
$350,000 he got from the Yanks. Steinbrenner's stinginess, of
course, was directly related to Williams' haul, but the rules favor
those who achieve. If he earns it on the field, Posada's day will
come, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pay us whatever you want,'' Cone said, ``but all we ask is
that at some point in our careers, let us be free agents.''
</P>
<P>
   He understands that these pleas do not resonate with the paying
public. ``They just see it as millionaires versus billionaires,''
said Cone. ``But that doesn't mean you just agree to one of those
so-called deals where the owners say, `Let's be 50-50 partners and
we make all decisions.' We've seen what happened when the NFL got a
hard salary cap.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, he said, got locked in and the owners wound up with
soaring franchise values. Over $500 million, Cone couldn't help but
notice, for a Cleveland franchise that didn't yet own one set of
cleats. Steinbrenner, along those lines, smartened up recently, and
created a more leveraged market for his principal ownership, rather
than let Charles Dolan dictate terms as an unchallenged suitor for
the team or its television rights.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are part of baseball's aristocracy. They are not the
Montreal Expos. Yes, Cone admits, baseball's competitive imbalance
must be addressed. No, he added, the answer is not to force players
to solve every problem the owners won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know what the models are,'' he said. ``When I first pitched
in the American League, the places nobody wanted to go were
Baltimore and Cleveland. I'm not saying stadiums are the whole
problem but that's part of it. There comes a time when you just
have to say to a Montreal, if you can't get a stadium, publicly or
privately, maybe it's time to move.''
</P>
<P>
   From a public-relations standpoint, Cone admits that baseball's
warring sides did no better than basketball's during their 1994
strike. The positions were uncompromising, the arguments strident,
the personalities bland. ``Next time, we don't need to see Donald
Fehr and Bud Selig on TV,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone has high hopes for Paul Beeston, now operating as
baseball's chief operating officer. By 2001, if his enduring right
shoulder has run out of innings, New York's most savvy athlete in
the field of communications said he might even be inclined to put a
more engaging face on the players' plight.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada could do much worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
