<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARCH-CIVILRIGHTS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Much is still left to be done' as Lewis leads delegation across
Alabama
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ ``I remember how vivid the sounds were as the
troopers rushed toward us _ the clunk of the troopers' heavy boots,
the whoops of rebel yells from the white onlookers, the clip-clop
of horses' hooves hitting the hard asphalt of the highway, the
voice of a woman shouting, `Get'em! '''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep. John Lewis in his memoir, ``Walking with the Wind,''
recalling the 1965 voters' rights march across the Edmund Pettus
Bridge in Selma, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) walks across the Edmund Pettus
Bridge today, he will have a congressional delegation at his side
instead of a band of civil rights protestors. He will be escorted
by Alabama state troopers rather than face their bully clubs as he
did 34 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed since ``Bloody Sunday,'' a march that riveted
the nation and created a ground swell of support for lifting
restrictions on the right of African-Americans to vote. But as
Lewis sees it, ``Much is still left to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   His message today will be about hope for an open dialogue on how
to dismantle the social barriers between blacks and whites more
than three decades after Congress passed the Civil Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis hopes some of the lessons learned during that struggle can
now be used by Congress as it begins to mend the bitter divisions
left in the wake of the impeachment trial of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do see this as an opportunity to do some healing and to
build some bridges of understanding, some bridges of
reconciliation,'' Lewis said. ``The goal is not to just go on the
trip to observe. It is to learn and to grow _ to take some lessons
from the civil rights movements, to learn that in spite of what
happened in places like Birmingham, Montgomery and Selma, people
didn't become bitter, they didn't become hostile.'' Sponsored by
the Washington D.C.-based Faith and Politics Institute, two
busloads of lawmakers, their families and staff are making their
way through Alabama to see firsthand where the civil rights
movement was born and some of the movement's bloodiest battles
fought.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 17 congressmen, there was noticeable relief to be away
from partisan rancor over Clinton's cover-up of his affair with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure changes our focus and gets us talking about meaningful
issues away from the controversy swirling around us,'' said Rep.
Ray LaHood (R-Ill.), who presided over the House vote last December
to impeach a president for the second time in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the group had never been to Alabama. Some were too young
to remember the blood that was lost protesting written and
unwritten laws that separated blacks and whites in housing,
schools, laundry facilities, restaurants, marriage, and even water
fountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a boy when John Lewis was fighting the struggle. We
know the pilgrimage is not over, there is work to be done,'' said
Rep. Fred Upton (R-Mich.), referring to a recent racist incident in
Texas where a black man was dragged behind a pickup truck and
killed.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights movement ``is something we should always
remember and can never forget,'' said Rep. Sherrod Brown (D-Ohio),
who brought his two daughters on the journey.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Rev. C.L. Bachus of Kansas City, Kan., was in
Alabama, signs warned blacks that they were ``Entering Wallace
Country.'' The signs _ referring to the late Gov. George Wallace,
who was then a strident segregationist _ used to send shivers down
his spine because, ``we never knew what would happen to us in
Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to the state with a black congressman filled Bachus
with pride. ``You forget about what it once was like,'' he said
watching a film at the Birmingham Civil Rights Institute on Friday
night. In the film, police sprayed young black children with
firehoses so strong that the water removed bark from trees.
</P>
<P>
   The white-only signs in front of public bathrooms are long gone,
but racial discrimination still exists in more subtle ways, said
William Alexander, a 16-year-old high school junior from Washington
who is traveling with the group as a reporter for National Public
Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander said he is discouraged at the way Congress has focused
so intently on the Lewinsky saga instead of ``what is going on
outside, like racism.'' Issues such as economic disparity between
races and job preferences that favor whites should be addressed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is showing me how far we have advanced and that there is
something we can do about tomorrow,'' Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
