<SLUG> BC-BKW-DROESCH-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH SCHOOL SOPHOMORE BEING COMPARED TO HOLDSCLAW 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She has that shy, awkward manner typical of
teen-agers. But there are moments when the blushing young woman
exudes a poise and quiet confidence beyond her years.
</P>
<P>
   Age is not what it used to be. Not when you have become somewhat
of a basketball legend at 16.
</P>
<P>
   Clare Droesch, a 5-foot-10-inch sophomore guard for Christ the
King High School girls' varsity in Queens, knows the feeling _ the
one that comes when you are being mentioned in the same breath with
alumnae such as Chamique Holdsclaw, the Tennessee Vols forward
considered by many to be the greatest high school girls basketball
player ever, and Sue Bird, the Lady Royal now of Connecticut
Huskies fame who was known in her high school days as Ms.
Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The talk of Droesch's being the ``next Holdsclaw'' started in
January, when she broke the school's single-game scoring record
first set with Holdsclaw's 38 points, then reset at 39 by Bird.
Droesch scored 48 points against Bishop Kearney of Brooklyn on Jan.
8 during an away game.
</P>
<P>
   Droesch remembered being so caught up in the rhythm-and-flow of
the game that she did not realize she was shooting her way into
school history. As she was walking off the court at the end of the
game, a teammate, Patricia Tubridy, approached her and said:
``Clare, you did it. You broke Chamique's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that career-defining moment, Droesch has been inundated
with news media attention; opponents have started to double-team
her; teammates are expecting her to make the shot in clutch
situations and five to 10 colleges a week have been sending
brochures to her family's Rockaway Beach home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life's definitely changed a lot with the press and
everything and people comparing me to Chamique and Sue,'' Droesch
said. ``I see it in the way my family and friends treat me. It's
all cool, like I did something good as a sophomore. Now I can try
to break my own record.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, there is a more immediate goal she is shooting for:
helping her teammates maintain Christ the King's consecutive state
championship streak, which is currently at nine.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Royals, the defending Catholic High School Athletic
Association girls champions, finished the regular season with a
19-3 record and are ranked No. 1 in the city and 24th in the nation
by USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   The team faced Bishop Loughlin of Brooklyn in the first round of
the playoffs Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to help take this team to a state championship,'' said
Droesch, who averaged 24 points and 6.7 rebounds and is being
touted as the best female sophomore playing today. ``When Chamique
was here, the team won four state championships. That's a mark I'd
like to strive for.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Droesch is determined not to let the hype go to her
head. She admits that she has to work on her overall game and is
the first to tell anyone who asks that she doesn't consider herself
in Holdsclaw's or Bird's league _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a sophomore; I'm still learning a lot and I want to
work on my defense and my inside game, like posting up,'' Droesch
said as she sat beside her beaming parents, Patti and George
Droesch.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vincent Cannizzaro hails his star's versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has multiple ways she can score points,'' Cannizzaro said.
``It's not that she needs to have the ball in a certain area of the
court or take a certain kind of shot. It's not that she's a post
player or a perimeter player. She can do both. She can score inside
or outside.''
</P>
<P>
   The last player to see the court like that was Holdsclaw,
according to Cannizzaro, who said the comparisons do not end there.
</P>
<P>
   Droesch is as good a passer as Holdsclaw, and Droesch, like
Holdsclaw, was constantly working on her defense. But the coach
thinks that Droesch has the potential to become the school's
highest scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's not just that she scores points, she shoots in
the high percentages, close to 50 percent from the floor,''
Cannizzaro said. ``We're constantly telling Clare we'd like for her
to make in the range of 23 to 30 shots a game. If she can shoot in
that range, at 50 percent, it's really a plus for the team.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
