<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0313 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-500&AMP;ADD-NY     03-06 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAHAN WELCOMES THE CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michael Strahan, the Pro Bowl defensive end who is the New York
Giants' most dominant player, has a message for any teammate miffed
at the $5 million signing bonus and $4 million annual salary given
to Kerry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 21 guys making a million or more a year,'' Strahan
said. ``And we were 8-8 last year. If you're upset with what
Kerry's making, think about whether you should be earning what
you're earning.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan is the epitome of the 21st-century professional athlete
in that he knows his game and knows his business, and knows there
is only a subtle difference between the two.
</P>
<P>
   The 280-pound Strahan has the speed to outrun most quarterbacks
and the strength to body slam them when he catches them. He is a
loud, teasing locker-room leader and equally adept at the quiet,
corner-of-the-room philosophical or motivational discussion. And he
can count.
</P>
<P>
   When he looks at the Giants, he sees more seven-figure salaries
than any other team in the National Football League. But he is
aware that the game is played at an emotional pitch, and Strahan
has come to the conclusion that the financially secure Giants,
comforted by a management style that has been decidedly
conservative, have grown complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were just collecting checks last year,'' Strahan said in
the locker room last week as he dressed for the Giants' off-season
conditioning workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This off-season there's been a lot of turnover in here, and I
think it's good. We need to put a little fright in people. This is
a place that stuck with guys too long. If you're not happy here or
they're not happy with you, get out and go someplace else.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point, Strahan said, is running back Tyrone Wheatley,
whom the Giants traded to Miami last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyrone had the same problems with two sets of coaching
staffs,'' Strahan said. ``If it happens with two coaching staffs
then you've got to look at yourself. Tyrone needs to start blaming
Tyrone for some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan added that he wished the Giants were playing Miami this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a shot at him,'' Strahan said. ``He used to say to
us: `If I go somewhere else, I'll be running over you guys.' Well,
I hope we get him some day. We'll see what happens, Tyrone.''
</P>
<P>
   Strahan, scheduled to be a free agent in 2000, is on the verge
of the biggest pay day for a defensive player in the history of the
NFL. The Giants are determined to sign him to a new contract this
spring or summer. It will break the bank for someone who isn't a
quarterback or star running back and should easily be in the $8
million range annually.
</P>
<P>
   But Strahan is far from content.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm impatient,'' he said. ``I'm so sick of the distractions to
winning I've seen around here. I heard guys talking about their
contracts in the middle of last season, and I wanted to tell them:
`Shut your mouth. Our record is 3-7, you're lucky this team wants
you.''''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Strahan is close to Giants linebacker Jessie Armstead, who has
boycotted the team's off-season conditioning program this year in
an apparent protest over a contract he wants to renegotiate.
Strahan, who talks with Armstead almost daily, said he understands
Armstead's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any problem with Jessie,'' Strahan said. ``I know
he hasn't missed a workout in six years, but he's at home in Dallas
working out every day. It's hard when salaries are going through
the roof and you're one of the best at your position and you're not
getting what you think you deserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's how he feels.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is an incongruity to Strahan's stance on Armstead and
how he feels about other Giants concerned about their pay, Strahan
sees the distinction as easily explainable. Armstead, the team's
only other Pro Bowl player, has performed at a high level, played
hurt and, when he felt it necessary, threatened teammates he
thought weren't playing hard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more guys who are angry about losing,'' Strahan said.
``Jessie and me, our patience is very short. And that's what I like
about Ernie Accorsi; I think he's the same way. He hasn't been
afraid to pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi, who has been the general manager for 14 months, has cut
wide receiver Chris Calloway and quarterback Danny Kanell and
signed Collins. Accorsi, along with Coach Jim Fassel, has also
ignored the longtime Giant guard Greg Bishop in free agency, cut
cornerback Carlton Gray and exposed the starting safety Tito Wooten
in the expansion draft, which cowed Wooten into a huge pay cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's blowing people's minds around here, but I like the new
direction,'' Strahan said. ``It's like the Kerry Collins signing.
People say, `How do you give him all that money?' Well, suppose he
stays on the right track and something happens around here, and we
need him? If he plays well, we will look like geniuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have gotten somebody real cheap because winning
quarterbacks make a lot of money. It's one of the chances you have
to take. I'm willing to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   And if it doesn't work out?
</P>
<P>
   Strahan motioned toward the vacant locker where Kanell dressed
until a month ago. ``Guys aren't getting forever to make it
anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Strahan, a throwback to a different era and a modern athlete
at the same time, there's a new Giants order and he likes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the business side and there's the team,'' he said.
``Once the season starts, I just want to win. And I don't care
about hurting people's feelings if that's what it takes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
