<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ACC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLOSIVE DUKE ADVANCES TO ACC FINAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BARRY JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ The capacity crowd in the Charlotte Coliseum
Saturday afternoon was pulling loudly for the underdog, North
Carolina State. Top-ranked Duke was playing without a starter,
Trajan Langdon, and it lacked its accustomed air of domination. Two
more starters, Elton Brand and Chris Carrawell, were
uncharacteristically ineffective in the early going.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it took the Blue Devils all of five minutes to take the
lead for good, and another 20 to put away the fifth-seeded Wolfpack
in a semifinal of the Atlantic Coast Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The 83-68 victory, Duke's 26th in a row, improved the Blue
Devils' record to 31-1 and moved them to the tournament final for
the second consecutive year. On Sunday, they will face the winner
of Saturday's second semifinal between second-seeded Maryland
(26-4) and No. 3 North Carolina (23-8).
</P>
<P>
   Duke, undefeated during the conference regular season, last won
an ACC tournament title in 1992. N.C. State, still harboring hopes
of a bid to the NCAA tournament despite losses in five of its last
eight games and a weak nonconference schedule, fell to 18-13.
</P>
<P>
   Given his first start in Langdon's place, the freshman Corey
Maggette scored 17 points in the half to lead all scorers and
finished with 24, a personal best.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils led by only 43-35 at halftime, and N.C. State
remained within eight points until the customary Duke explosion
came about five minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Over a span of five and a half minutes the Blue Devils went on a
21-5 run, taking a 74-50 lead with 9 minutes 23 seconds left on a
fast-break layup by guard Will Avery. Duke hit 11 of its first 12
shots in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   During the decisive stretch Duke's defense forced five
turnovers, all of which resulted in scores, and held N.C. State to
1-of-6 shooting. Brand was a key factor in the run, and finished
the game with 19 points and 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Wolfpack never drew closer than 15 points the rest of the
way.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. State, a quarterfinal winner over Wake Forest, played with
surprising confidence in the early going against Duke, which beat
the Wolfpack twice this season by an average margin of 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   There were four lead changes in the first five minutes, with
Duke finally emerging with a 9-8 edge at the 15:04 mark on a follow
shot by the sophomore big man Chris Burgess.
</P>
<P>
   Brand, Duke's leading scorer, missed his first five shots from
the floor, all at short range.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the degree of difficulty, Duke also played without
Langdon, its second-leading scorer. The senior guard, who had
started 121 consecutive games, sprained his left foot in Duke's
104-67 victory over Virginia in Thursday's opening round. He
remains questionable for Sunday
</P>
<P>
   Handicaps notwithstanding, the Blue Devils permanently took the
lead with a dozen unanswered points, capped by a pair of Brand free
throws that pushed their lead to 19-8 with 11:34.
</P>
<P>
   But N.C. State was not to be put off easily. Every time Duke
built its margin to double figures in the first 25 minutes, the
Wolfpack responded with a flurry. Key to each rally was the
perimeter scoring of Justin Gainey and Anthony Grundy.
</P>
<P>
   Each made a trio of 3-pointers in the first half; N.C. State
usually averages five a game. The guards had 11 points each in the
period, with Gainey's 3-pointer at the buzzer cutting Duke's
halftime lead to single digits.
</P>
<P>
   Grundy, a freshman, finished with 19 points, while Gainey had
12.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Wolfpack's 2-3 zone drew a number of offensive
fouls from the Blue Devils and often forced them to the perimeter.
Duke shot only 40.6 percent from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps concerned about the game's drift and his team's apparent
acceptance of the conventional wisdom that the Wolfpack posed
little threat, Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski was unusually animated on
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski's vociferous objections to several calls finally
resulted in a technical foul, his first in two seasons, at the 6:44
mark of the first half. But N.C. State got only 1 point from the
possession.
</P>
</TEXT>
