<SLUG> BC-FORGERY-RELEASE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGED LETTER RESULTS IN RELEASE OF PRISONER FACING FORGERY TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ It's only fitting that it was a man charged with
forgery who slipped out of the Johnson County Jail recently on the
strength of a phony letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some very creative minds out there,'' said Bill
Miskell, a spokesman for the Kansas Department of Corrections.
``And we're real interested in finding the creative mind that faxed
that letter.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter notified jail officials that a parole violation
warrant against Joshua Williams would be dropped on Feb. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Believing the letter to be genuine, deputies allowed Williams,
38, of Kansas City, Kan., to leave the jail that day after he
posted bond on two forgery cases.
</P>
<P>
   The letter appears to be on Corrections Department letterhead,
but it contains typographical errors, including ``Govenor.'' It
ends with the forged signature of an actual parole officer.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had been in the jail since Feb. 1. He was on parole for
a Wyandotte County forgery conviction, and the Department of
Corrections had filed a warrant alleging that he had violated
parole.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was re-arrested Wednesday in Kansas City, Kan., and he
was returned to the Johnson County Jail on Friday. His trial on
four counts of forgery is scheduled to start Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Sheriff's Department and the Corrections Department
said the incident was a first, and both are taking steps to ensure
it doesn't happen again.
</P>
<P>
   And they hope to prosecute whoever sent the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear someone else was involved,'' said Maj.
Bernie Johnston of the Sheriff's Department. ``Some of these people
seem to have a lot more time to concoct these things than we do to
try and catch them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
