<HEADER>
A0317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TRUCK-ADVOCATES07     03-06 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TRUCK-ADVOCATES07 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAFETY ADVOCATES WANT TIGHTER TRUCKING REGULATION
 &HT;    With TRUCK-SAFETY. For release Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With more people being killed in crashes between
passenger vehicles and big rigs, some consumer groups and members
of Congress are blaming the federal agency responsible for
maintaining truck safety.
</P>
<P>
   The critics charge that the Transportation Department's Office
of Motor Carriers (OMC) has been lax in enforcing safety
regulations on commercial motor vehicles. The alarming results,
they say, are more defective trucks on the roads and more fatigued
drivers falsifying their required log books in order to evade
federal limits on time behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``OMC has not been doing a good job,'' said Rep. Frank Wolf,
R-Va., chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee on
transportation. ``The office has become too cozy with the trucking
industry, which it is supposed to be regulating.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf recently held a hearing on his proposal to move OMC from
Transportation's Federal Highway Administration to the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
</P>
<P>
   That agency ``is charged with the responsibility of overseeing
the safe operation of the nation's highways,'' Wolf said, while the
Federal Highway Administration has a broader mission that includes
construction of interstate roadways.
</P>
<P>
   Among the witnesses at Wolf's hearing was Bonnie Pierce, an Elm
City, N.C., mother who told how her son Terry, a high school
wrestler, and his teammate were killed in a head-on crash with a
fatigued truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why was the tired trucker who killed my son still on the road
after 16 hours?'' she asked. ``The answer is simple. The federal
Office of Motor Carriers is incapable of enforcing safety
regulations and the Federal Highway Administration is incapable of
implementing new, more effective regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The trucking industry and safety advocates agree that it's time
to change the 65-year-old driving limits _ which generally require
eight hours off the road after 10 hours behind the wheel _ to force
drivers to get more rest. The Federal Highway Administration is
developing a proposal for new hours-of-service regulations.
</P>
<P>
   There could be disagreement between the truckers and consumer
groups, however, on what the hours should be.
</P>
<P>
   Walter McCormick, president of the American Trucking
Associations, which represents the major carriers, also agrees with
the safety activists that there should be more inspections of
commercial trucks and tougher penalties on carriers who put unsafe
big rigs on the roads. McCormick has proposed doubling the current
$100 million in federal funding for roadside inspections.
</P>
<P>
   However, Todd Spencer, vice president of the Owner-Operator
Independent Drivers Association, believes that pushing for more
inspections is ``a very narrow focus'' in seeking improved truck
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``How often trucks are inspected has little to do with how well
a driver is trained or with the economic coercion imposed upon
drivers to make impossible deadlines,'' Spencer testified recently
in a congressional hearing on truck safety.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to requiring truckers to pass the tests needed to
obtain a federal Commercial Drivers License, he said training and
an on-the-road apprenticeship should be required. He said the
independent truckers he represents also need regulations protecting
them from shippers who effectively force them to break safety laws
to meet their delivery schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers who refuse are blackballed by the industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry critics want several other reforms:
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring commercial trucks to have on-board satellite
tracking systems that record their speed and position, making it
impossible for drivers to fake their log-book entries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mandating on-board ``black boxes'' like those in airlines that
would determine causes of crashes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring trucks to have engine governors that limit their
speed.
</P>
<P>
   The truckers and some safety advocates agree that states should
opening more roadside rest stops and lengthen stay limits so
drivers will have places to pull over and sleep. Many states now
limit truckers to two hours in a rest stop.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
