<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With TRUCK-SAFETY. For release Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TWO-VEHICLE FATAL CRASHES INVOLVING LARGE TRUCKS, 1997
</P>
<P>
   Who died in the crash?
</P>
<P>
   .............................Truck.......Car
</P>
<P>
   .............................Driver......Driver
</P>
<P>
   U.S. .......................646.......2,613
</P>
<P>
   Whom did police cite for driving errors in connection with the
crash?
</P>
<P>
   .............................Truck.......Car
</P>
<P>
   .............................Driver......Driver
</P>
<P>
   U.S. .......................679.......2,381
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Highway Traffic Safety Administration, Fatal
Accident Reporting System
</P>
<P>
   TIPS FOR DRIVING SAFELY AROUND LARGE TRUCKS
</P>
<P>
   _ Remember trucks are heavier and take longer to safely respond
and come to a complete stop.
</P>
<P>
   _ If a truck is signaling its intention to change lanes, allow
it space to do so. Often, it's trying to avoid another vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leave a safety cushion between you and the vehicle in front of
you. A good tip is to find a stationary object on the side of the
road and count 4 seconds as a cushion for a truck.
</P>
<P>
   _ At intersections, stay behind the wide white lines so trucks
can safely complete their turns.
</P>
<P>
   Source: American Trucking Associations.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
