<HEADER>
A0319 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      03-06 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 MYTH OF SOCIAL SECURITY TRUST FUND HAMPERS TAX RELIEf  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Tax-cut proponents seeking a more politically appealing
way to ease the working-class tax burden have begun to focus more
on reducing Social Security taxes.
</P>
<P>
   This tactic is seen as having more potential for success because
it avoids objections that across-the-board reductions in marginal
tax rates help the well-off but provide no comfort to low-income
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a bogus economic argument, because the more income
workers receive, the more taxes they would normally have to pay.
Although it seems logical for tax relief to be proportional to tax
burdens, the phony claim that it's not fair invariably plays well
politically.
</P>
<P>
   What's inexplicable, however, is how those eager to play the
unfairness card when it comes to income-tax relief at the margin
never champion reducing Social Security taxes, which fall most
heavily on those at the bottom of the income ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Since Social Security stakes its claim on the very first dollar
of a worker's income, this is the only form of income taxation
relevant to those with modest incomes. About 75 percent of all
workers pay more in Social Security taxes than they do in income
taxes, and the comparable number is almost 100 percent for those
making $20,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these lowest-paid workers, incidentally, contribute a
significant portion of their meager wages to the income stream of
many affluent retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Given this socioeconomic inequity, it should make people of
conscience wonder why there isn't more support for reducing Social
Security taxes. This is especially so considering Social Security
enjoyed surplus revenues of about $100 billion last year. It's not
as if Social Security can't afford meaningful tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   What makes reducing Social Security taxes politically difficult
is the myth of the trust fund. After Uncle Sam spends surplus
Social Security revenues, the so-called trust fund is credited with
a claim against the Treasury to be redeemed as needed.
</P>
<P>
   When excessive Social Security taxes are criticized as unfair to
low-income workers, opponents of relief say the extra money is
needed to build up the trust fund for future beneficiaries. This is
an artful dodge, though. Assuming benefit cuts would be politically
impossible and tax increases politically difficult, future claims
will be handled the same way whether the trust fund exists or not.
</P>
<P>
   When surplus revenues are spent by Uncle Sam and the trust fund
gets a credit in return, as is currently done, how do you suppose
the money will be raised to honor this claim when it's needed to
cover revenue shortfalls? If there happened to be a budget surplus,
it could be used to make up the difference. If not, Treasury would
have to borrow the money.
</P>
<P>
   Say, however, Social Security tax cuts transformed the system
into a pay-as you-go operation. What would be necessary if no trust
fund existed when revenues fell short of what was needed to pay
benefits? The same exact thing. The difference would have to be
covered either by budget surpluses or Treasury borrowing.
</P>
<P>
   When the system is viewed in the context of economic reality, it
becomes much easier to justify Social Security tax relief because
the trust fund is exposed for the mythical slush fund it is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 1826EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
