<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0321 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-TRUCK-SAFETY07     03-06 1878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-TRUCK-SAFETY07 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY FINDS DRIVERS, NOT TRUCKERS, MAKE MOST FATAL ROAD ERRORS
 &HT;    1220&AMP;add. With TRUCK-ADVOCATES and TRUCK-DATA. Moving in (w)
Washington and (a) national categories for release Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    With photos and graphics.
 &HT;    A related story, TRUCK-DRIVER, is moving in the (l) lifestyle
category.
 &HT;    By BOB DART and ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hal T. Burks eased his big Freightliner to the left lane of I-75
as a shiny red Ford pickup came barreling down an on-ramp near the
Georgia-Florida line.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think the law obligates trucks to move over and let them
on,'' complained Burks, who drives an 18-wheeler for M.S. Carriers.
``But sometimes I can't because there's traffic in the lane beside
me. Then a lot of times the four-wheeler will squeeze in right in
front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a recipe for tragedy. According to a Cox Newspapers
computer analysis of federal highway safety records, the most
common fatal accident involving a large truck and a car comes when
the car pulls in front of the truck and the larger vehicle can't
slow down in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we have 18 wheels with tread doesn't mean we can
stop on a dime,'' explained Burks.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths in car-truck crashes _ overwhelmingly of car drivers _
are on the rise, and the trucking industry's safety record is under
congressional scrutiny. But the Cox analysis found that police
investigators are three times more likely to cite car drivers for
driving errors that contributed to an accident.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers suggest that the biggest opportunity to save lives
may be teaching car drivers how to stay safe around trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Cox examined 1997 data from the federal government's Fatal
Accident Reporting System (FARS) showing that in fatal crashes
involving cars and large trucks, the investigating police at the
accident scene cited the car drivers 2,381 times for deficiencies
such as ``failure to keep in proper lane,'' ``drowsiness'' or
``reckless driving.'' They cited truck drivers 679 times.
</P>
<P>
   In fatal crashes where drinking was a factor, the FARS data
show, 15 percent of the car drivers had an alcohol blood content
over the most common legal limit of .10 percent. By comparison,
fewer than 1 percent of the truck drivers had that much alcohol in
their systems.
</P>
<P>
   After analyzing the same FARS data, the General Accounting
Office (GAO), the investigating arm of Congress, reached a similar
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Errors by car drivers were reported in 80 percent of the
crashes, while errors by truck drivers were reported in 28 percent
of the crashes,'' said Phyllis Scheinberg, the GAO's associate
director for transportation issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gordy Wright, a spokesman for Georgia State Patrol, said
statistics from his state tell the same story. Of 121 fatal wrecks
involving large trucks in Georgia in 1997, the car driver was cited
nearly two-thirds of the time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox analysis found that the most common fatal crash scenario
came when both truck and car were driving in the same direction
during daylight in good weather, and the truck hit the car either
at an angle or from the rear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anecdotally, that is what I would have said about the
situation even without the computer study,'' said Major Ken Howes,
a spokesman for Florida State Patrol. ``I've been on the highway
patrol for over 20 years, and the vast majority of truck drivers
I've come into contact with are professional, very careful drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you're driving an 80,000-pound rig down an interstate
highway and a car abruptly changes lanes in front of you and then
hits the brakes, you can't stop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA)
cautions that the contributing driver factors cited by
investigating police ``can only be suggestive about why truck
crashes occur'' and ``cannot be used to determine causation or
fault.''
</P>
<P>
   The factors ``are based on the officer's judgment at the scene
of the accident _ his observations and discussions with
witnesses,'' said Dave Longo, a spokesman for the federal Office of
Motor Carriers (OMC). ``They are not an absolute causation
determination, because they are not made with the benefit of a more
thorough investigation and accident reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Highway safety advocates disparage the data in stronger terms.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are ``a bunch of malarkey,'' said Joan Claybrook,
director of CRASH, or Citizens for Reliable and Safe Highways.
``It's become a canard _ heavily promoted by the trucking industry
_ that car drivers are responsible for most of these (fatal)
crashes.''
</P>
<P>
   The car drivers are usually killed, and when police arrive to
investigate, ``the only one talking is the truck driver,'' said
Claybrook. So the account of the accident is likely to be biased,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the same pattern of driver factors was found in a study
of crashes where both the truck driver and car driver survived, the
GAO's Scheinberg testified at a House hearing on truck safety last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Car driver errors were cited in 74 percent of the crashes,
compared to 35 percent for truck driver errors,'' she noted in
written testimony. ``This finding lends some support to the
hypothesis that, compared to truck drivers, car drivers contribute
more to fatal crashes between large trucks and cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Donaldson, senior research director for Advocates for
Highway and Auto Safety, argues that data from fatal crashes is not
comparable to data from non-fatal crashes.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dispute on one statistic: Regardless of who caused
the accident, occupants of a car, van or sports utility vehicle are
much more likely to be killed in a crash with a big rig than is the
truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox analysis showed that of the 5,355 people who died in
crashes involving a large truck in 1997, about 87 percent were
occupants of the passenger vehicles. The death toll, up 213 from
the previous year, marks a continuing slow increase.
</P>
<P>
   After the toll reached 5,679 in 1988, it fell to 4,462 in 1992,
only to begin climbing again as traffic increased.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, car drivers were four times more likely to die in these
crashes than were the truck drivers _ 2,613 car drivers compared to
646 truck drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in deaths has spurred demands from highway safety
advocates for more federal inspections and regulation of trucking.
Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., has charged that the agency responsible for
enforcing truck safety _ the Office of Motor Carriers _ has not
done its job and should be moved from the Department of
Transportation to the independent NHTSA.
</P>
<P>
   But Donaldson also agreed that the danger to car passengers in
truck accidents needs to be hammered home by the trucking industry
and government licensing agencies. A public education campaign
should be waged to inform car drivers ``that their chances of
survival are extremely remote'' in a crash with a big rig, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burks agreed that if the drivers of ``four-wheelers'' realized
how likely they are to be killed or injured if hit by a truck, they
wouldn't try to squeeze in front of a big rig trying to maintain a
safe distance from the vehicle ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to continue to educate drivers on sharing the road,''
said Walter McCormick, president of the American Trucking
Associations (ATA), the group that represents many of the major
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The ATA and the U.S. Department of Transportation have begun a
``No Zone'' campaign to publicize the areas surrounding a moving
truck where motorists are in danger. The safety advocates say the
effort is ineffectual.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Driving down I-75, Burks pointed to the mirrors outside his cab
windows and protruding from both sides of his hood. ``If the
mirrors are properly adjusted,'' he said, ``the only truly blind
spot on a truck is directly in the rear.''
</P>
<P>
   There is even a window in the bottom of the passenger door on
his truck so he can see cars directly on his right.
</P>
<P>
   The trucking industry contends that it is being unfairly
maligned in the safety debate.
</P>
<P>
   As the total truck mileage on the nation's highways has risen 77
percent since 1980, the fatal crash rate per 100 million miles
traveled has been cut in half, McCormick told Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than moving the Office of Motor Carriers, McCormick
testified, the trucking industry would support setting up a
separate federal agency to oversee its operations, with a
relationship like the Federal Aviation Administration has with
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   From the cab of his Freightliner, Burks dismisses the debate as
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Having driven 2.8 million miles without an accident, the
51-year-old driver takes safety seriously. Burks is a 1997
America's Road Team Captain _ selected by the trucking industry as
one of its safest drivers. He insists that both the government and
the industry have taken steps to ensure that commercial truckers
are safer than the average motorist on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Burks points out that truck drivers are required to earn a
federal Commercial Driver's License with more rigorous requirements
than the licenses held by most motorists. Federal law also requires
truck drivers to stop and rest for at least eight hours after
driving for 10 hours, and to record their periods of driving and
rest in a log book.
</P>
<P>
   Burks' employer, M.S. Carriers of Memphis, Tenn., is one of the
largest companies in the business. Like many of its peers, the
company invests heavily in safety equipment and training.
</P>
<P>
   On the dashboard of Burks' Freightliner is a computer connected
to a satellite positioning system that allows his dispatcher to
track him anywhere on the continent. This Qualcom system provides a
wealth of information _ the truck's speed, fuel consumption, idling
time, and rest periods. This data eliminates the possibility of a
driver cheating on the written log book.
</P>
<P>
   A Qualcom spokesman said about 230,000 long-distance, irregular
run drivers like Burks have satellite tracking systems tying their
trucks to dispatchers in the United States. Similar communications
systems such as cellular are also increasing in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The system ``can even show when a driver might be tailgating''
because it records how many times and how hard he hits the brakes,
said Burks.
</P>
<P>
   The 430-horsepower engine of Burks' truck also has a governor
that limits his speed to a maximum 65 mph.
</P>
<P>
   When he is not on the road, Burks is an instructor at the M.S.
Carriers driving and safety academy in Memphis. New drivers undergo
four weeks of schooling before going out on the road with a veteran
driver as a trainee.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of driving without an accident, M.S. Carriers
gives its drivers a ring with a blue stone in the middle. For the
next four years without an accident, a small diamond is added in
each corner. After 10 years, a big diamond goes in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appraises at about $3,500,'' said Burks, showing the ring
to a rider.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks to high school drivers education classes and other
groups to convey the trucker's viewpoint on to regular motorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to share the highway,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
