<HEADER>
A0322 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-COL-FIREHOUSES-NYT     03-06 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-COL-FIREHOUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AT FIREHOUSES, SOUNDING ALARM OVER DOWNSIZING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMILTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ Joseph Bellina is the business
administrator of Hamilton Township, and on the subject of reforming
the local volunteer fire department system, he says this: ``Nobody
wants to upset the volunteers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to mess with the 380 or so men who can be counted
on to get out of bed at 3 a.m. or walk out of church or skip dinner
when their pagers go off.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers save towns millions by reducing the need for paid
firefighters, and while most towns are struggling to keep enough
volunteers active, Hamilton is a genial throwback, a neighborly
sprawl of aging Trenton suburbs and new subdivisions that still
produce enough volunteers to answer the call.
</P>
<P>
   But as Henry Ryan or Ferdinand Mather Jr. or Dave Sabo will tell
you, that loyalty is not necessarily to the township but to their
individual fire companies, and to the territories they serve.
Hamilton has eight fire districts, each with its own history,
firehouse, tax rates and board of commissioners, and eight is at
least two too many, according to a management study conducted for
the town last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The report's principal recommendations to improve service and
save money: Close two firehouses, get rid of the district
commissioners and consolidate the system.
</P>
<P>
   Don't upset the volunteers?
</P>
<P>
   ``When that thing came out, it just broke our hearts,'' said
Mather, the chief at DeCou Hose Company, which was founded in 1914
and is one of the companies that the study suggested closing.
``There is a history of generations of volunteer firemen in this
place, fathers and sons and grandfathers coming through here. These
guys aren't going to just move to another fire company in the
township if they closed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Beer has not been served in the bars of the Hamilton firehouses
in decades, and instead of poker games, the men (there are
currently no female firefighters) are now more likely to be working
out in the weight room or playing video games. Hanging out at the
firehouse has given way to second jobs or soccer games or watching
the children while the wife is at work.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteering itself, in fact, has become a career path for many
young men, a way of getting on the list for a job on a municipal
police force or as a paid firefighter in Hamilton or other towns.
</P>
<P>
   But spend time with the Hamilton volunteers and the stories come
out, stories about roots in the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got married, I told my wife our first priority was to
find a house in this fire district, and the closer to the station
the better,'' said Ryan, a state tax division supervisor who joined
the Mercerville fire company 29 years ago and is now one of the
Mercerville district's five commissioners. The house the Ryans
chose on Stevens Street had Mercerville volunteers on either side,
and one of them, Sam Layton, is godfather to their son Jason.
</P>
<P>
   So the thousands of newcomers in Hamilton may be only dimly
aware of the guys washing their fire engines on summer weekends or
tearing along in their cars, blue lights flashing, on their way to
the firehouse when their beepers go off. Most homeowners go for a
lifetime without calling for a fire engine, and may only think of
the volunteers when they run their annual fund drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a lot of people we're just yahoos _ you know, `foundation
savers' or `blue-lighters,''' said Sabo, the volunteer chief at the
Rusling firehouse. ``But for the guys who do it, this is something
their fathers did and their grandfathers, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellina, the business administrator, said the township had not
yet decided whether to adopt the recommendations in the study. He
said town officials planned to meet with the volunteers to discuss
the matter. In the meantime, however, many of the firefighters are
talking as if the consolidation were a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   Mather, for one, insisted that his men would volunteer in
Bordentown, the next town south of here, if their firehouse was
closed. Others think that consolidation would bring a mix of
responses.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have a segment that will walk away and say, `This isn't
the way it used to be,' and you'll have some who will stay as a
career move and hope that there might be a job opening in
consolidation,'' Ryan said. ``And you'll have the old geezers like
me who will stick around just because this is what we do. This is
what we do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
