<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0323 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UTILITY-PURCHASE-KAN &LR;      03-06 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UTILITY-PURCHASE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD UTILICORP, ST. JOSEPH LIGHT &AMP; POWER AGREE TO MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ UtiliCorp United Inc., in a move that
reflects the consolidation transforming the utility business, has
agreed to buy St. Joseph Light &AMP; Power Co.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is valued at $270 million and is expected to be
completed in 2000. It will give UtiliCorp 61,000 electric customers
and 6,000 natural gas customers in 10 counties in northwest
Missouri, next to territory served by Missouri Public Service Co.,
another UtiliCorp unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good fit,'' said Richard C. Green Jr., UtiliCorp's
chairman and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph Light shareholders will receive $191 million in
UtiliCorp stock, or $23 for each share of St. Joseph Light stock.
That's a 36 percent premium over the St. Joseph utility's closing
stock price Thursday. UtiliCorp has also agreed to assume about $80
million of the utility's debt.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph Light has 350 employees, and the merger will cause
cutbacks. UtiliCorp said it would try to offer affected employees
jobs at other UtiliCorp operations. St. Joseph Light will also
offer a severance package.
</P>
<P>
   St. Joseph Light, which has some of the lowest rates in the
state, sought to reassure its customers Friday that it would still
be treated as a separate entity by regulators setting rates.
</P>
<P>
   The utility will keep its name but become a unit of UtiliCorp,
which is based in Kansas City. An office will be kept in St.
Joseph, and UtiliCorp has agreed to continue St. Joseph Light's
current charitable contributions for five years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, an advisory board will be kept in St. Joseph for
three years that will make suggestions to UtiliCorp, said Terry
Steinbecker, president and chief executive officer of St. Joseph
Light.
</P>
<P>
   He said the agreement is a culmination of work begun by the
utility's board in 1992 to consider the effects of deregulation as
it unfolds. An inescapable conclusion was that St. Joseph Light had
to be part of a bigger company and the larger resources it could
deploy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in the best long-term interest of our shareholders and
customers,'' Steinbecker said.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit is the premium that shareholders will get on their
stock, he said. Also, customers will have more assurances of a
reliable energy supply and more services, and employees should have
more opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   UtiliCorp has 5,500 employees serving 3 million customers in
eight states and Canada, Australia, New Zealand and the United
Kingdom. Its 1998 revenues were $12.6 billion, compared with St.
Joseph's revenue of $124 million in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, some residents couldn't escape the sense that an
era was passing, because St. Joseph Light traces its roots to 1883.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad to see this consolidation, but it's a sign of the
times,'' said Barry Yantis, president of Chase Candy Co. in St.
Joseph, which makes the Cherry Mash candy bar.
</P>
<P>
   Wholesale electricity markets are now deregulated, so prices are
allowed to float. Retail rates to a utility's customers, however,
are still regulated, and no date has been set in Missouri to change
that.
</P>
<P>
   When that happens, utilities will lose their monopoly status and
be allowed to poach on each other's territories. That will make
size an important factor in competition, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The merger strengthens our competitive positions in our home
state and in the Midwest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the agreement to buy St. Joseph Light didn't preclude
other acquisitions in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The deal must still be approved by St. Joseph Light shareholders
and state and federal regulators. Kevin Kelly, a spokesman for the
Missouri Public Service Commission in Jefferson City, said a
timetable to consider the merger would be set once the application
was submitted.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Hogerty, Missouri's public counsel, said it was too early
to comment on the St. Joseph Light deal. But it's part of an ironic
trend, she said, that the prospect of deregulation is reducing the
number of companies to compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``The behemoths just get bigger,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the financial side, Robin Diedrich, an analyst with Edward
Jones, said the deal was relatively small but St. Joseph Light was
well-managed, and the proximity to other UtiliCorp operations made
it a good acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a lot of sense,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
