<HEADER>
A0324 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISTORY-MUSEUM-KAN &LR;      03-06 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORY-MUSEUM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM DISPLAYS CITY'S HISTORIC SIDE AS WELL AS ITS ECCENTRIC
SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. JOSEPH, Mo. _ It takes rare alchemy to transform a 10-cup
coffee brewer into a crowd-pleasing attraction.
</P>
<P>
   But that's exactly what the Patee House Museum here accomplished
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've seen it on television. You've read about it. Here it is
in person!'' announced a large sign beside a routine-looking Mr.
Coffee machine.
</P>
<P>
   The display was no flea-circus hoax. Like everything in the
Patee House, a vast, enchanting and truly goofy museum, it had a
legitimate story behind it _ albeit a strange one.
</P>
<P>
   The pot was the infamous carafe into which an employee at the
nearby Wire Rope Corp. had angrily relieved himself in full view of
a hidden video camera. That peculiar act, aimed, so to speak, at a
fellow employee, soon was reported by newspapers and TV broadcasts
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we got the pot,'' said Patee Director Gary Chilcote, 64, a
retired newspaper reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to capture the flavor of St. Joe,'' he added.
``We caught a lot of flak for that display, but our goal is to get
people to appreciate history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've got to entertain them, or they won't come. And
because we're a private institution, we can do things a bit
tongue-in-cheek. People enjoyed that pot exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, though, the coffee consumption at our board
meetings fell off dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patee House Museum occupies a huge 1858 building first
constructed as a hotel. It is one block square, four stories high,
in the west-central section of this city (population 75,000).
</P>
<P>
   Its displays are so eclectic that a local TV news producer once
said a visit there was like walking through his grandmother's
attic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being in a giant history book,'' said Chilcote.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Patee House, you drink sarsaparilla in the re-created
Buffalo Saloon as you listen to ragtime piano.
</P>
<P>
   You stroll down a painstakingly rebuilt 19th-century St. Joseph
street and visit the original Pony Express office along with
numerous other shops and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   You drop by the dental office run by the father and grandfather
of newsman Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``city jail,'' you view a collection of murder weapons.
Many of them are hammers, including the claw model favored by the
1937 killer of one Arthur Ferguson, and the ball-peen variety that
killed a woman in 1939. (``He loved her but was angry,'' reads the
display sign below its broken handle.)
</P>
<P>
   As you wander onward through a seemingly endless maze of
wonders, you'll encounter a 1,050-pound ball of twine and a fully
restored train depot complete with a Hannibal &AMP; St. Joseph Railroad
locomotive.
</P>
<P>
   You stroll by antique fire engines, a goat-powered treadmill and
a unique collection of brass ``bawdyhouse tokens'' once purchased
in the lobbies of certain downtown establishments and then
exchanged upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   You also see airplanes, spittoons, a 1920s service station,
vaudeville posters and a photographic display of the famous ``Horn
Furniture of Herman Metz.''
</P>
<P>
   A fine example of rare horn furniture, in this case a settee
made entirely of bull's horns, can be found in the beautifully
re-created hotel lobby.
</P>
<P>
   It is, perhaps, a pointed commentary on the final career of the
hotel's founder.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel was built by John Patee, a druggist, teacher and land
speculator who was among the early boosters of St. Joseph's
short-lived role as gateway to the West.
</P>
<P>
   He built well but not wisely. His timing was off.
</P>
<P>
   When the Civil War interrupted St. Joseph's boom years, Patee
compounded his business error by siding with the South.
</P>
<P>
   In 1865, faced with ruin, Patee came up with a remarkable idea
he called the Grand Benevolent Raffle.
</P>
<P>
   He printed some 150,000 raffle tickets ($2 each) and conducted a
nationwide lottery in which the stakes were his hotel, valued at
$140,000, and two acres of St. Joseph property.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the drawing, 100 unsold tickets were dramatically
returned by an agent in Quincy, Ill. Patee generously bought the
lot ``to allow the drawing to continue on schedule,'' although why
that purchase was necessary was never explained.
</P>
<P>
   When the winning number was announced, it turned out to be one
of the tickets Patee held. Amazingly, he had won back his own hotel
and pocketed more than $200,000 in lottery proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``His reputation was so good that no one questioned his
honesty,'' Chilcote said. ``At least not at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Patee died in 1868, St. Joseph's richest man. But among the
people of the city, he was known thereafter as Lucky John, a phrase
that has about it a certain ironic ring.
</P>
<P>
   And, curiously, according to Chilcote's research, just one year
after the raffle, the man who had returned the 100 unsold tickets
married Patee's niece.
</P>
<P>
   After Patee's demise, his hotel went through a series of
incarnations: a women's college, a hotel again, a shirt factory
and, finally, a World War II defense plant.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963 it was condemned by the city but rescued at the last
moment by a committee of eight who dubbed themselves the Pony
Express Historical Association. The hotel had been the headquarters
of the Pony Express in 1860 and is a registered National Landmark.
</P>
<P>
   Chilcote was among the eight.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the museum's collection, almost entirely donated,
has grown so large that two floors of the building are now filled
with well-mounted exhibits and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The top two stories, though, are like something out of the movie
``Citizen Kane'' _ a colossal warehouse containing tens of
thousands of artifacts from St. Joseph's colorful past.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of movie and TV people come to us,'' said Chilcote.
``And we can supply anything they want.''
</P>
<P>
   And that, he added tongue-in-cheek, includes a slightly used
coffee pot stored in a third-floor room with other former display
items.
</P>
<P>
   Next to the pot, on a long and cluttered table, there is an 1886
photograph of a well-dressed St. Joseph gentleman sitting in a
buggy.
</P>
<P>
   The buggy reins, however, are not attached to a horse. They are
linked to a bird: The one-and-only, world-famous Celebrated
Trotting Ostrich.
</P>
<P>
   Chilcote glanced at the old photo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll use it sooner or later,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
