<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUD-HOUSING-COSTS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DARK SIDE OF EXPANSION: HOUSING COSTS RISE RAPIDLY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: See also WVA-WELFARE-NYT.)  
 (fb) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A strong national economy that is rewarding many
Americans through steady employment, low interest rates and rising
stock prices is hurting millions of the nation's poorest people by
delaying their access to affordable housing, a new report by the
federal government says.
</P>
<P>
   Research collected by the Department of Housing and Urban
Development found that as the economy has expanded, poor people
have been waiting longer for public housing units, rental costs
have been increasing and the number of affordable units has been
falling as landlords seeking greater profits get out of the public
housing business.
</P>
<P>
   In some cities, as many as 25 percent more families are on
waiting lists for affordable apartments than there were last year,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rising economic tide is raising many boats, but it is also
drowning some,'' said Housing Secretary Andrew M. Cuomo, reflecting
a report the department plans to release this week. ``As an
unintended consequence of this amazingly strong economy, there is
less affordable housing stock and the prices are beyond the reach
of those at the bottom of the income spectrum.''
</P>
<P>
   Those conclusions are generally shared by advocates for the poor
who have campaigned for years for more affordable housing. Maria
Foscarinis, executive director of the National Law Center on
Homelessness and Poverty, said the findings of the report reflected
``the convergence of many different trends in the private markets
and public policy that are squeezing poor people the most.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a paradox of booming times,'' Foscarinis said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to citing economic conditions for the housing
problems, the report, ``Waiting in Vain: An Update on America's
Housing Crisis,'' strikes a familiar note in blaming the
Republican-led Congress. Echoing one of Cuomo's frequent complaints
since he succeeded Henry Cisneros as secretary in 1995, it points
to a decision that year to stop increasing the amount of money to
expand rental subsidy programs after money had been appropriated
for an additional 230,000 households each year from 1978 to 1984
and for 126,000 households from 1985 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Cassidy, a spokesman for Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., chairman
of the House housing subcommittee, said Lazio had not read the
report and could not comment on it until he did.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A House banking committee staff member who works on housing
issues and spoke on the condition of anonymity defended the
decision, saying that Congress stopped paying for new subsidies
because HUD could not account for money it already had.
</P>
<P>
   After the department put into effect plans to improve efficiency
and programs to weed out fraud and abuse in housing programs,
Congress passed new public housing legislation and agreed last year
to a request to authorize 100,000 new Section 8 vouchers, which
entitle the holder to a rent subsidy. The staff member said
lawmakers would authorize ``a reasonable number'' of new vouchers
in President Clinton's 2000 budget request.
</P>
<P>
   The new vouchers eased some of the growing demand for affordable
housing, but pressure has continued to build.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo said the most alarming finding is that the time poor
families spend waiting for housing assistance _ a public housing
unit or a Section 8 voucher _ has grown longer, especially in big
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the average wait for a public housing unit
increased to 11 months last year from 10 months in 1996 and the
average wait for a voucher had increased to 28 months last year
from 26 months in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers found that the wait for housing had increased to
eight years in New York, six years in Oakland and up to five years
in Oakland and Washington; the wait for a voucher had stretched to
10 years in Newark and Los Angeles, seven years in Houston and five
years in Chicago and Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said a comparison of 18 cities in the last year
showed a 34 percent increase, to 660,000 from 500,000, in the
number of families waiting for a voucher.
</P>
<P>
   Among the economic conditions that most strikingly show how the
booming economy has progressed at the expense of the poor,
according to the report, is housing costs.
</P>
<P>
   While home ownership has reached a record level of 66.3 percent,
largely because low interest rates have offset rising home prices,
the rise in rents, 6.2 percent from 1996 through 1998, surpassed
the rise in income for the 20 percent of households with the lowest
incomes, Bureau of Labor Statistics says.
</P>
<P>
   The report does not mention any potential impact on housing
costs from welfare changes that began in 1996. A study by the
General Accounting Office in December said it was too soon to
determine the effects of lost welfare benefits on housing for the
poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
