<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-MUSEEUW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEEUW ON THE FAST TRACK BACK TO PROMINENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GHENT, Belgium _ The early morning drizzle was cold, of course,
and promised to continue all day, of course. That's winter in
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of bicycle racers prefer to avoid the place. They spent
last weekend in Spain, at the Tour of Valencia, where temperatures
were in the low 70s, or in Italy, at the Trophee Pantalica, where
temperatures were lower, but still not the 45 degrees recorded in
Ghent.
</P>
<P>
   This city in eastern Flanders staged the start of the 54th Het
Volk race on Feb. 27, the traditional opening of the season in
Belgium and, as always, it was a gathering of tough men. Of these,
the toughest _ no argument possible _ is Johan Museeuw.
</P>
<P>
   The king of the classics, Museeuw comes from Flanders and, as
always, was the center of attention for his fellow Belgians. Young
and old, male and female, they surrounded the parked Mapei team car
in which he sat in the front passenger's seat before the start.
Through a slightly opened window on the driver's side, small boys
passed a team official sheets of paper for Museeuw to autograph.
The mood was reverential.
</P>
<P>
   Museeuw crashed last April in the Paris-Roubaix race, falling in
the mud and cobblestones of the Arenberg woods and fracturing his
left kneecap. He was taken to a Belgian hospital, and the leg was
immobilized in plaster.
</P>
<P>
   But his wound had not been thoroughly cleaned, and under the
cast his knee became septic. His kidneys and liver nearly failed,
and even after doctors understood what was happening and corrected
it, they feared the leg might become gangrenous and have to come
off. Months of recuperation followed. Museeuw kept the leg.
</P>
<P>
   At age 32, after a decade as a professional, Museeuw had long
been talking about retiring. He seemed especially serious in 1996,
but then won the world road race championship and decided to carry
on.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, he had reduced his schedule by dropping the Tour de
France and concentrating on the 10 one-day classics that comprise
the World Cup. Museeuw has won a big classic nine times.
</P>
<P>
   He could not return to competition until September, when he
tested his atrophied leg in small races. He decided that much as he
would like to retire, he did not want to leave the sport that way.
He signed a two-year renewal with Mapei and spent the winter
training on his bicycle, swimming long laps and working out in a
gym.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've returned to see how far I can go,'' he has said. ``Now
that I've got my health back, I'd very much like to be at the front
of races again. At the front, as in winning.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first couple of races in Spain last month, he did fine on
the flats but struggled on climbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's natural,'' said his team manager and confidant, Patrick
Lefevere, before the start of the Het Volk, which is rated a
semiclassic. ``We're not expecting too much of him now. He's got a
lot of races ahead of him in the next month and a half, and after
Paris-Roubaix we'll evaluate his progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's doing well, but this is his first real test,''
Lefevere said. ``He's very motivated, and very calm. It's amazing
that he's alive and amazing he still has his leg.''
</P>
<P>
   For a final amazement, Museeuw rode a strong Het Volk, 202
kilometers (126 miles) over 11 short but steep hills lined with
treacherous cobblestones. As one rider after another wearily
dropped back or out, Museeuw remained consistently near the front.
</P>
<P>
   With about 15 kilometers to go, he even went on the offensive,
speeding away from a group of nine leaders. He was quickly chased
down, and an attack then by Frank Vandenbroucke, a Belgian with the
Cofidis team, proved to be the winning move.
</P>
<P>
   Vandenbroucke easily won the race in a sprint finish with
Wilfried Peeters, another Belgian with Mapei. Thirty-four seconds
behind were six riders, with Museeuw in the middle of the group,
finishing an impressive sixth. Only 44 of 199 starters completed
the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
