u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARTFORD-THEATER-REAL     03-06 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARTFORD-THEATER-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAJOR THEATER IN HARTFORD ADDS A SMALL, NEW AUDITORIUM 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Conn.)  (fb) 
 By ROBERT A. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bushnell in downtown Hartford will break ground this spring
on an 88,000-square-foot, $30 million addition that will give the
69-year-old, 2,800-seat theater a 950-seat modern auditorium for
smaller productions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is also about economic development and activity in
the downtown,'' said Douglas C. Evans, the Bushnell's executive
director. ``Phantom of the Opera,'' he said, brought 135,000 people
to the Bushnell's Great Hall from August to October 1995, a record,
and grossed $6.7 million. But the impact on the community, for
everything from apartments for the cast to meals for theatergoers,
was estimated at more than twice that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arts community has been slow to embrace that concept, that
philosophy, that arts is a driver of the economy,'' Evans said.
``When we first started discussing it, it was taboo. The economic
aspect was considered dirty. But one of my platforms since the day
I arrived has been that arts are good for the economy, good for the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   H. Scott Phelps, president of the Greater Hartford Convention
and Visitors Bureau, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're promoting Hartford as a convention destination,
you're not just selling the convention space,'' he said. ``People
want to get out and see and do things , and having something like
the Bushnell in the downtown is critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold C. Greenberg, president of the Bushnell's board of
directors, said a fund-raising campaign had set a goal of $45
million, not only to cover the costs of construction but to
establish a larger endowment for the expanded theater. The campaign
is halfway to its goal, including a $1.25-million gift from a
trustee, Anthony D. Autorino, and a $4-million gift from Maxwell M.
Belding, a trustee emeritus, and his wife, Ruth R. Belding, of Old
Lyme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic climate now is much healthier than the early
1990s, and I think the vision now is much more compelling,''
Greenberg said. ``There's an appreciation of what this will do not
only for local arts and community groups, but to bolster the
economic revitalization of Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the next decade, the city expects a total of more than $1
billion in new construction downtown, including Adriaen's Landing,
the $374-million stadium for the New England Patriots; a convention
center; a community technical college and 1,000 units of housing,
according to figures from the state's Department of Economic and
Community Development.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell's new theater will rise on an employee parking lot east
of the existing hall.
</P>
<P>
   Glass walls at the front of the addition will enclose a
three-story Grand Stair Hall, featuring a curved stairway, as well
as a cafe, gift shop and concierge office on the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   The second floor will be for intermission space or cabaret-style
performances. A luxury suite will provide a setting for corporate
functions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we're only increasing the capacity by about one-third,
we don't expect the net effect to be that great,'' said David A.
Dalena, the Bushnell spokesman. ``Obviously, we'll have to make
some changes operationally, such as staggered starting times for
the performances, but that is all part of the planning process.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to angling the addition away from the main hall, the
site slopes slightly down to the east, which further decreases the
impact of the new building on the old, said William D. Clegg Jr.,
an architect with Schoenhardt Associates in Simsbury, which is
working with Wilson Butler Lodge of Boston on the plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some thoughts about enclosing the old building's
east portico in glass, but it's an important part of the building
and we felt the best way to preserve it was to leave it open,''
Clegg said. ``It was tough, and it was tight, but it came
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Clegg, who specializes in historic preservation, said that the
Bushnell was close to his heart. In the late 20's, his wife's
grandfather, Howard Christian Peter, assumed the duties of head
carpenter on the Bushnell construction on the death of his
father-in-law, Ludwig Miller. Clegg's mother-in-law, Verna Carlson
of Bristol, still has pictures of the construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a project for me, it's a part of my
heritage,'' Clegg said. ``When I found out we had the job, I called
my wife and told her to go buy a dozen roses and we went over to
tell her mother. As I gave her the flowers I said, `The heritage
continues.' I look forward to taking her to the first show.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bushnell project, which has a $10 million grant from the
state and $2.5-million from the Federal Department of Housing and
Urban Development, is currently being reviewed by the Connecticut
Historical Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very significant structure,'' said Susan R. Chandler, a
staff historical architect with the commission. ``It's a cultural
landmark as well as a historical landmark. It's one of the most
important stand-alone historical resources in the downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she has not completed her review, she noted that the
designers of the addition had taken an innovative approach, angling
it away from the main hall so the east face of the building, with
its blend of Georgian-style columns and Art Deco exterior, would
still be visible from the street.
</P>
<P>
   Since Evans arrived to head the Bushnell in 1990, it has
strengthened considerably. When he arrived, about 180,000 tickets
were being sold each year. This year, it expects to sell 400,000 to
500,000 tickets, thanks to some of the lavish Broadway productions
he has attracted to Hartford. Large Broadway shows currently take
up 25 percent of the theater's schedule, but account for 90 percent
of the revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But the growth also meant a tightening of availability for shows
by the Bushnell's tenant organizations _ the Hartford Ballet,
Hartford Symphony Orchestra, Connecticut Opera Association, and
Chamber Music Plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of the second hall means there's more flexibility
in getting dates, and there are a number of ballet shows that we
would rather do in a more intimate setting, that sort of cry out
for a smaller hall,'' said Trevor A. Cushman, president of the
Hartford Ballet. ``So on both counts, we're looking forward to
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a normal season the ballet might do four shows, two
full-length and two triple-bills, or repertory shows. The repertory
shows might sell 800 seats, or fewer, on a slow night, which means
almost one out of four seats in the Great Hall would be vacant _
not the message an arts organization wants to send.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hartford Symphony is always squeezed for time in the big
hall, and if our vacating some slots in the big hall gives them
more time to get in there, we're all for it,'' Cushman said. ``And
in Bushnell II, as we're calling it, there's going to be better
seats for our purposes. They're going to be closer to the stage, so
everyone is going to be better served.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
