<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-COMMUNITY-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ONLY COMPLAINT ABOUT CELEBRATION IS THAT IT MAY BE TOO
PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CELEBRATION, Fla. _ Diane Kupchak was tired of South Florida. It
had grown too fast. She didn't know her neighbors. She wanted to
live somewhere like Rutherford, N.J., her hometown, which she
remembered as a place where neighbors were family.
</P>
<P>
   So when she heard of Celebration, a town built from scratch by
the Disney Co. and designed in a way to encourage a sense of
community, she suspected she had found what she wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels right,'' she said recently, after having lived in the
community for a year.
</P>
<P>
   With nearly 700 homes built here now and house prices
appreciating an average of 1 percent a month, residents and Disney
executives say the experiment has shown signs of success.
</P>
<P>
   On average, a house is sold here every other day, with an
average sales price of $377,300, by far Osceola County's price
leader. The average home price in the county that includes Orlando
and Disney World is $230,000, county figures show.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jason Canin, vice president of Charles Wayne
Consulting, which tracks home sales in the Orlando area, the dollar
value of sales at Celebration for January through September 1998,
the firm's most recent report, was 42 percent higher than sales at
any other central Florida development. The sales totaled $52.5
million, with an average price of $370,000, Canin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very active market there,'' said Linda Goodwin, who
has sold real estate in Osceola County for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Only recently has a resale market developed, and homeowners are
making money. One town house sold for $225,000 last September, 15
months after the original buyer paid $181,900 for it.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Goodwin said many of the resales are Celebration apartment
renters buying town houses and town-house owners buying bigger
homes. A few have left the community because of job transfers, Mrs.
Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Celebration's planners envisioned a community reminiscent of the
quaint villages that dot New England's landscape. They wanted a
downtown, parks, playgrounds and a school, all within walking
distance of the homes. They wanted sidewalks and picket fences, a
town not unrelated to Disney World's Main Street USA, just a mile
or so away. They wanted to bring back a way of life lost when
suburbs appeared and cars became the only way to get to distant
stores, school and work.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Co. took a 10,000-acre tract of Florida scrub land
and turned half of it into an upscale community that eventually
will include 5,000 houses and apartments. The other half will
remain natural.
</P>
<P>
   The first residents moved in almost three years ago. In all, 772
residences have been built, 466 detached houses, 74 town houses and
232 apartments. Houses range in price from $160,000 for a garden
home of about 1,400 square feet to more than $1 million for the
estate homes, which range in size from 3,500 to 10,000 square feet.
</P>
<P>
   All 123 downtown apartments are leased, including those above
the shops. An additional 231 apartments will come to the market by
year-end. The one-, two-and three-bedroom units will rent for $830
to $2,500 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Perry Reader, vice president and general manager of the
Celebration Co., the town's developer, said the quick sellout of
the town houses had resulted in the construction of 29 more town
houses than the 74 originally planned.
</P>
<P>
   The downtown sports four restaurants and a myriad of shops.
Bicycles, baked goods, clothing, gifts, antiques, books, kitchen
utensils and jewelry can all be purchased in the shops at the edge
of a man-made lake, which has no name. Celebration also features a
real oddity: a twin-screen, 515-seat downtown movie theater. A
short stroll away is the 115-room Celebration Hotel, which will be
completed this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Disney brought in famed architecture firms from around the
country to design the signature buildings: Michael Graves created
the Post Office, Philip Johnson the Town Hall and Robert A.M. Stern
Architects designed Celebration Health, a full-service medical
center. The Stern firm and Cooper Robertson, both of Manhattan,
designed the master plan.
</P>
<P>
   When the development was announced, demand was so high, a
drawing was held in November 1995 to decide who would get first
dibs at talking with a sales agent. Karen Howard remembers feeling
frustration because her number was so high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just said, `Oh forget it, we're never going to get it,' ''
she recalled. But eventually she and her husband, Jack, were able
to buy a house that had been built for another family that had
backed out of the deal. The 3,000-square-foot coastal-style home
with a wraparound porch on the town's main thoroughfare came on the
market on a Friday and they signed a contract the next day. They
paid full price.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Howard's company, Herman Miller Inc., an office furniture
manufacturer, transferred him from Houghton, N.Y., to the Orlando
area five years ago. They settled in nearby Winter Springs, but
were intrigued with Celebration. Ultimately, they and two of their
neighbors bought homes here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an old-time kind of place,'' said Mrs. Howard. When
her 16-year-old son, Kyle, was injured in a soccer game, one of the
few she did not attend, her neighbor accompanied him to the
hospital. Recently, she and a friend were bike riding when they saw
a stray rabbit hopping among the lush foliage in a neighbor's yard.
They jumped off their bikes and quickly found the animal's owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other places a bunny wouldn't have a prayer,'' said Mrs.
Kupchak, who got in on the search.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Healy, the other rabbit rescuer, said, ``I can't imagine
not living here.''
</P>
<P>
   Her two children, ages 10 and 5, attend the K-12 Celebration
School, which has 800 students. It offers hands-on instruction in
multigrade classrooms. Recently some of the high schoolers created
web pages for local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The school is operated by the Celebration Co. in conjunction
with the Osceola County School District. The government for the
unincorporated development is run by the five-member Community
Development District, elected by property owners. Fees, averaging
about $400 a year, paid to the' association for the maintenance of
public areas are added to the bill for property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But the lifestyle is clearly not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I came here my sister told me it creeped her out, it
was too perfect,'' said Julie Jensen who was visiting the town
recently. ``It is kind of Stepford Wife-like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going to spend that much money on a house I'd want
more space around me.'' said her friend, Sally Manko. ``The yard's
postage stamp-sized.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Celebration exudes uniformity and perfection in the
same way Disney World does. Streets are meticulously clean, lawns
manicured, trees trimmed. It looks like Ozzie and Harriet Nelson's
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Howard said she had heard many rumors about her town. Her
daughter, Courtney, a college student, teaches dance in a nearby
town and hears people there say that Disney pays the residents to
walk their dogs and sit on their porches a certain number of hours
each week.
</P>
<P>
   Ridiculous, said Mrs. Howard, but people do enjoy sitting on
their porches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come home and drive through those white picket fences I
say `whew' and think I'm home and I don't have to go back out,''
she said. ``It's neat and organized. What's not to love?''
</P>
<P>
   Reader, the vice president and general manager of the
Celebration Co., believes the original dream has become reality.
``Over half of the residents volunteer in one of the 20 community
groups that the Celebration Foundation gave birth to,'' he said.
``We have a nice collection of people, very diverse backgrounds.
For a community as young as we are, that's a real success story.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
