<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-RETAIL-REAL-2TAKES     03-06 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-RETAIL-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CALDOR FADES, RETAIL MARKET IS UNFAZED
</HEADLINE>
  (fb) 
 By RACHELLE GARBARINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Caldor, the discount-store chain, announced in January that
it was closing its 145 stores, including 28 in New Jersey, William
A. Farber was struck by a sense of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   Farber is chief operating officer at Levin Management Corp. of
North Plainfield, which owns and manages 66 shopping centers, 45 of
them, totaling nearly 4 million square feet, in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Levin worked through the bankruptcies of W.T.
Grant and E.J. Korvettes. Now it is faced with the same situation
because Caldor anchors five of the company's centers, having
replaced Korvettes in the '80s. The centers are in Paramus, West
Orange, Woodbridge, Watchung and North Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the stores in those centers will signal what
impact, if any, Caldor's bankruptcy will have on the state's retail
market, and on landlords like Levin. Two of its stores _ one on
Route 4 West in Paramus, the other on Route 22 in Watchung _ are
already spoken for by Kohl's, a discount department store chain
based in Menomonee Falls, Wis., which is looking to build its
presence in the New York metropolitan area. If the leases of the
other three stores are not taken over by other retailers, Farber
said the space would be reconfigured for new users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting with a sound retail market and good real estate
locations, where land for new construction is scarce, so even
though one retailer couldn't make it, another one will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most retail analysts and brokers said Caldor's bankruptcy was
not expected to have a harsh impact on the overall market, and
might come and go without incident, much like the closing last year
of the Rickel stores, said Matthew J. Schnurr, senior vice
president of the investment services group at the West Orange
office of Grubb &AMP; Ellis, the national commercial brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the home-improvement chain's 53 stores, 40 of them in
New Jersey, were taken over by Staples, the office-supply store,
said Schnurr, whose firm handled the disposition of the Rickel
stores.
</P>
<P>
   A key reason why analysts are optimistic is that the closing of
Caldor stores, which average about 84,000 square feet, comes at a
time when the state's economy and retail market continue to be
strong. Projections are that it will remain so at least through the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the booming economy along with the fact that many
Caldor stores are in prime locations, very few are expected to be
hurt,'' said Ted Kraus, who heads TKO Real Estate Advisory Group, a
retail consulting firm in Mercerville.
</P>
<P>
   The statewide retail vacancy rate is hovering between 3.5
percent and 4 percent, virtually unchanged from last year, and
rents continue to rise, albeit not as aggressively as in the past,
according to TKO. For example, the firm puts the rents for stores
of 70,000 to 100,000 square feet for stores in good locations at
$10 to $13 a square foot, up about $1 from last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Caldor closes its stores, other national and regional
retailers continue to expand in or enter the state, said Jonathan
Schultz, president of the Schultz Organization, a brokerage in
Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Kohl's, as well as Wal-Mart and Kmart, are looking to
grow by picking up some of the leases on the stores left behind by
Caldor. Under bankruptcy laws, bidders for the company would be
able to assume the leases at the same rents Caldor was paying,
which may be significantly below today's rents since many of the
leases were negotiated years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is way for growing companies to get into a tight market in
a much quicker and less expensive way,'' Schultz said. That, in
turn, may ``slow development in the state, keeping supply in
balance with demand,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One negative, added Kraus of TKO, is what will happen once new
retailers take over the Caldor stores. ``Some merchants who
survived because Caldor was a weak competitor will need to work
more aggressively or lose out to the new competition,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Late last month Kohl's received approval from the bankruptcy
court to buy for $142 million the leases of 33 Caldor stores.
Eleven of them are in New Jersey, including the two stores at
Levin's centers. They will be added to the six stores Kohl's
already has in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been expanding into the mid-Atlantic region over the
last two years,'' said Gary Vasques, executive vice president of
marketing at Kohl's. Taking over the Caldor leases is a logical
move ``and allows us to enter the New York metropolitan area with a
critical mass of stores,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, he said, is to invest a total of $165 million to
renovate all the stores and open them by the spring of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   At the same, time Wal-Mart, the nation's largest retailer, which
is based in Bentonville, Ark., was given the green light to buy 12
store leases for $75 million, none in New Jersey. And Kmart, of
Troy, Mich., put in a bid for 11 stores. Just one, a Levin property
in West Orange, is in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The bidding for the leases, analysts said, is likely to continue
for another two months and may bring in more bids from the same
players or new ones from other retailers. In addition, retailers
who may not want to get involved with the bidding process _ waiting
instead for the leases to go back to landlords _ are said to be
eyeing the stores. Likely candidates are other so-called big-box
users, including discounters like Target, Ames and Bradlees, the
latter two of which worked themselves out of bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Stores in choice locations _ in densely populated areas with
strong demographics and next to and visible from major highways _
will be snapped up quickly, said Schnurr, of Grubb &AMP; Ellis.
Landlords with stores in less than prime spots ``will have to
become creative and come up with adaptive reuses,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Farber of Levin Management said that his company sees
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the Caldor stores in his company's centers are
taken over by a new retailer at a rent that ``is out-of step with
today's market,'' he said, there is room to renegotiate certain
aspects of the lease that pertain, for example, to rents based on
sales volume. He said there was also the possibility that the new
tenant would not need all the space, giving his company the chance
to take back any excess space and rent it to other tenants at
market rates.
</P>
<P>
   Farber said that was the plan at the Paramus center, a
270,000-square-foot community shopping strip anchored by a
130,000-square-foot Caldor store.
</P>
<P>
   There Kohl's intends to use only 90,000 feet, enabling Levin to
take back the rest, he said, noting that in tandem with Kohl's
plans to renovate the store's facade his company will invest $2.5
million to refurbish the center.
</P>
<P>
   Levin intends to repeat that plan at its 400,000-square-foot
Watchung Center, which is anchored by a 138,000-square-foot Caldor
store.
</P>
<P>
   The center is in the process of a $5 million rehabilitation,
which Levin is undertaking with Federal Realty Investment Trust,
based in Washington, D.C. That, together with Kohl's arrival,
``gives the center a shot in the arm to remain competitive,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Caldor stores at Levin's other three centers are still up
for grabs and Farber said his firm would be just as pleased if it
got back those leases. The first choice would be to lease the space
to a single user or to two smaller anchors and ``fill in everything
else from there,'' he said, noting that the alternative was to
carve up the space for multiple smaller uses.
</P>
<P>
   In cases where the stores are on two stories or have a basement
level, he said his firm would do what it had done many times
before: lease that space to complementary uses like health clubs or
day care centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``History has shown that retailers have a limited life span, but
as long as the location is viable and the economics are sound, life
for the real estate goes on,'' Farber said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
