<HEADER>
A0354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      03-06 1928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENSON TAKES ANOTHER WRONG TURN 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shayne Stevenson's hockey odyssey continues. The former
Bruin first-round pick (No. 17 overall in '89), who played only 19
games with Boston before being given away in the '92 expansion
draft, is a left wing with the San Angelo (Texas) Outlaws this
season.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday morning, according to published reports, the
28-year-old Stevenson found himself on the outs with the law.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson and teammate Kevin McKinnon were arrested in the
predawn hours for allegedly stealing a taxi in Bossier City, La.,
and fleeing onto Interstate 20 before being pulled over by police.
Both Outlaws were charged with unauthorized use of a moveable (cab
without the cabbie), McKinnon also nailed for first-offense driving
while intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``About all we can say,'' said Suzanne Moore, whose husband,
Dick Moore, owns the San Angelo club, ``is thank God it wasn't
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson did not return a phone message left with Moore by a
Globe reporter.
</P>
<P>
   According to Moore, Stevenson has been sidelined recently by a
groin injury, but nonetheless joined the team on the trip that had
the Outlaws facing the Shreveport Mudbugs Thursday night _ sans
Stevenson and McKinnon, who spent a few hours in the Bossier Parish
Jail in Benton, La., before each posted a bond of $7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson was an affable, fun-loving 18-year-old when the Bruins
selected him, hoping his blend of skill and quick-trigger
feistiness could bring them some production and nastiness up front.
It was the same draft that produced Mats Sundin (No. 1), Bill
Guerin (5), Bobby Holik (10), Olaf Kolzig (19), Adam Foote (22),
and Byron Dafoe (35).
</P>
<P>
   In the same draft, the Bruins took Mike Parson with the No. 38
pick and the highly-touted-but-short Wes Walz at No. 57. Of the 11
players the Bruins selected in '89, only Stevenson and Walz ever
made it to the NHL, contributing a total of 9 goals and 22 points
in a combined 92 games with Boston. Stevenson's totals with Boston:
0-1_1 in 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   His end in the Hub came when the Bruins, deciding early that he
was a writeoff, left him exposed in the Ottawa-Tampa Bay expansion
draft. The Bolts bit, but he played only eight games with Tampa
Bay, picking up what stands as his last NHL point (an assist in
'92-93).
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' said Stevenson, shortly before going to
Tampa in '92. ``The Bruins thought they were drafting a man and
they got a boy. I had to learn how to be a professional hockey
player, and unfortunately, I did that at the Bruins' expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all my fault, and I wasted two years of my life _ and the
Bruins paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson returned home to Aurora, Ontario, after his final
go-round with Boston and his parents, Tom and Linda, insisted that
he seek professional counseling. He wouldn't specify the reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got checked in,'' said Stevenson, who, when asked to
clarify, said he was not hospitalized. ``I went to see a
psychologist, that's all. I had problems. It's a lot of things. I
left home at 15, and you miss a lot, how to eat, how to spend your
money. But the shrink's helped me out, a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson has played in Europe and for a variety of lower-tier
US-based minor league teams. His longest stay was in Utica, where
he played two-plus seasons with the Blizzard. He spent last season
with the Port Huron Border Cats before signing in the summer with
the Outlaws, in the Western Professional Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson and McKinnon are scheduled to appear in Bossier Parish
District Court for arraignment April 5, the same day the Canadiens
visit Causeway Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of player was he in Boston?'' Suzanne Moore asked a
caller to the Outlaws office on Friday. ``Here, he comes out strong
each game _ he's a nice skater _ and then, I don't know, he just
sort of disappears.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's late in the season, which means, of course, it's time again
for the Flyers to worry about their netminding (did you hear there
will be tulips in the Public Garden this year, too?). Rookie
Jean-Marc Pelletier (Georgia-born and ex- of Cornell) was tossed
into the net Thursday night for his NHL debut (a 5-0 whitewashing
by the Senators), which bumped free agent signee John Vanbiesbrouck
(five straight losses) to backup and Ron Hextall to the press box.
The move came after the Flyers lost four straight and were a dismal
2-8-2 over their last 12. It's general manager Bob Clarke's way of
trying to kick-start the karma. If this doesn't work out, look for
the spotlight to get pointed, appropriately, directly on the nose
of Eric Lindros. Another short postseason (the Flyers were knocked
out by the Sabres in Round 1 last spring) inevitably will reignite
rumors that Lindros will get moved in a blockbuster deal this
summer. But with whom? Los Angeles would make sense, especially
with a new building to fill, but the Kings lack the bodies to make
a swap viable. Would it make any sense for the Flyers to consider
Mike Modano? L'enfant Terrible is some three years younger than
Modano, and more of a physical presence, but maybe the Flyers could
use more touch/speed and the Stars more big-line bulk. It's really
about the only center-for-center swap that makes sense. Don't even
bring up the name Peter Forsberg. He's the best of the three . . .
Senators GM Rick Dudley got under the collar of his Islander
counterpart, Mike Milbury, when he said last week that Ottawa's
search for a second-line center included the possible acquisition
of the Islanders' Trevor Linden. ``It's nice to be wanted,'' said
Linden. ``But I don't want to leave.'' Milbury was disgruntled that
Dudley leaked Linden's name, saying it was ``inappropriate'' and
``counterproductive'' for another GM to be talking openly about
another team's players. The bluster aside, the betting is the
Islanders will move Linden, among many others, ideally dumping his
salary ($2.5 million) for at least one young prospect. ``If they're
throwing names like Trevor Linden around,'' said Milbury, ``we'd be
throwing names like (Alexei) Yashin and (Daniel) Alfredsson.''
Other clubs with interest in Linden: Toronto, Detroit, and
Vancouver (the club that sent him to Long Island for Bryan McCabe
and Todd Bertuzzi last February) . . . Adam Oates would be another
good No. 2 fit in Ottawa, but the Capitals aren't yet in the same
no-man's land as the Islanders in terms of the playoff picture. If
the Capitals dish Oates, it's tantamount to passing on the
playoffs, not unlike Calgary's sending Theo Fleury to the Avalanche
last weekend . . . The Rangers figured their playoff chances were
about to fade to black when Wayne Gretzky exited the lineup with a
bulging cervical disc. Result: a Petr Nedved hat trick, the
blossoming of some young forwards (Manny Malhotra and Marc Savard),
and a 3-0-1 undefeated streak headed into Sunday's match at the
Vault. Remember, the Rangers refused to part with Malhotra when the
Canucks were shopping Pavel Bure. What now, when the Great One
returns? Coach John Muckler may have no choice but to hand him
reduced minutes, in hopes of having the kids lead the way to the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Frightening sight at Toronto's new Air Canada Centre Wednesday
night when Alyn McCauley (5 feet 11 inches on tiptoes) was knocked
cold in a rear-board collision with the Devils' Sheldon Souray (6-4
in stocking feet). After a few minutes on the ice _ five of which
he was out cold _ McCauley was lugged out on a stretcher, though he
was able to squeeze Tie Domi's hand as he exited. Hospital tests
revealed a concussion, the fourth of his career . . . Amid all the
Canucks' injuries, left winger Peter Schaefer, a Syracuse callup,
has been impressive, showing some touch. Gotta like a guy who hails
from Yellow Grass, Saskatchewan . . . Jim Carey finally got what he
wanted: an NHL club to give him a chance. So he took the buyout
from the Bruins _ a savings of about $2 million for Boston _ and
showed up in St. Louis just in time to see prospect Brent Johnson
rattle off his second and third victories in net. Carey finally saw
his first NHL action in some 18 months when he took over for
Johnson in a 4-0 loss to the Leafs Thursday, allowing one goal on
four shots. Johnson was demoted to Worcester Friday. If Carey gets
in enough games (10) before the end of the season, he could be
exposed in the waiver draft. If not, look for the Blues to put up
either Grant Fuhr or Jamie McLennan for the Atlanta yard sale.
Carey's deal will bring him $200,000 this season and at least three
times that in 1999-2000 . . . UPN has landed over-the-air rights to
broadcast the Atlanta Thrashers games. Georgia, you're going to
love mini one-on-one (hint: it's not a race between modified
pickups).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oiler foward Georges Laraque, whose crushing hit Feb. 9 on
Darren Van Impe knocked the defenseman out of the Boston lineup,
had a highlight-reel punchfest with Sabres bad guy Rob Ray
Wednesday night in Buffalo. The pummeled Ray left the battle
clutching his left leg (pulled hamstring), tried to come back in
the second period, but couldn't continue (TKO, Laraque). During the
morning skate, Ray had been shown a printed report in which Laraque
said he would be looking to tangle. ``What's he going to do, beat
me up?'' said Ray. Ain't it awful being right? . . . The Oilers
have renewed their interest in acquiring Buffalo's Matthew Barnaby
(they were poking around last year) and have put out a feeler for
the Bay State's Jim Campbell (doing little in St. Loo). Rumor on
Friday had the Sabres ready to move Barnaby, netminding prospect
Martin Biron, and defenseman Jean-Luc Grand-Pierre (find a better
hockey name) in a package. If they're talking with Edmonton, the
Sabres no doubt would have to give up defenseman Bo Mironov. They'd
also be only too happy to dump netminder Mikhail Shtalenkov . . .
Perhaps as early as Friday, former Penguins great Mario Lemieux is
expected to file a bankruptcy reorganization plan that ultimately
could lead to the club being sold to a group he is assembling. The
investors would pony up some $50 million, he would fold in a
portion of the $31.4 million he is owed in deferred compensation,
and $60 million in debt also would be assumed. The Penguins are
about $125 million in debt. Lemieux, candidly, says he wants two
things out of the deal: 1. the money he's owed, and 2. the club to
remain in Pittsburgh (ultimately playing in a new rink). Meanwhile,
the current ownership group (including Revere-raised Roger Marino)
has a March 19 date in bankruptcy court, a hearing in which it
hopes to gain permission to pursue out-of-town suitors . . . The
Bruins' alumni squad will take to the ice Tuesday, 7 p.m., at the
Norfolk Arena for the benefit of the local Autism Family Center . .
. Ex-Bruin Geoff Courtnall, limited to 21 games this season with
the Blues because of postconcussion syndrome, might not be able to
return until 1999-2000 . . . Craig Janney has become the same spare
part on Long Island that he was in Tampa Bay. After being scratched
for two games, he told Newsday reporter John Valenti: ``You come
here, you're not dressing, and you're sitting in a hotel room for a
month, and it's going on two (months) away from my family.''
Islanders head coach Bill Stewart responded in part: ``It goes back
to `Shut up and play and don't tell me how wonderful you were 10
years ago.' '' Put a hold on those Janney-Cam Neely highlight
clips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
