<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 03/06/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   Attention editors and clients who access New York Times photos
via Newscom. Newscom is experiencing difficulties with their photo
website. Any questions you may regarding delays should be directed
to their support line at 213-237-4577. The Times will post all
material as soon as Newscom is up and running.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- March 06, 1999 -- OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN, 03-06
-- Dominique Moceanu, 17, who was part of the gold-medal American
gymnastics team at the 1996 Summer Games, with the official poster
created for the 10th Special Olympics for the mentally handicapped.
Moceanu, who took four months off from training in October, not
just to avoid the gym, but to survive a vicious public scandal
involving her father, still has empathy for others. ``These games
do so much for people,'' says Moceanu. ``They give them dreams,
they motivate them.'' (Phillip Greenberg/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MANCHESTER, N.H. -- March 06, 1999 -- RELIGIOUS-RIGHT,
03-06 -- Randy Tate, Steve Forbes, Pat Robertson and Rep. John H.
Sununu, R.-N.H., left to right, at prayer during a New Hampshire
Christian Coalition meeting in February. Twenty years after the
Rev. Jerry Falwell's Moral Majority Inc. propelled religious
conservatives into a heavyweight force in U.S. politics, the
movement is struggling without a clear strategy, and for the first
time a debate has erupted among leading figures over whether they
should scale back their political efforts. (Kirsten Elstner/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador -- March 06, 1999 --
CENTAM-U.S., 03-06 -- Facundo Guardado, a candidate for the
presidency of Nicaragua, and a former guerrilla commander, speaking
to euphoric supporters in San Salvador. President Clinton is to
open a four-day visit to El Salvador, Nicaragua, Honduras and
Guatemala on Monday, the day after Salvadorans vote on a new
president and further cement a remarkable democratic transformation
after 12 years of civil war that left more than 70,000 people dead.
(Cindy Karp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SOUTH BEND, Ind. -- March 06, 1999 --
HOMELESS-CLASSICS-2, 03-06 -- The University of Notre Dame holding
a weekly humanities seminar for homeless men and women, whose
personal stories often have the weight of classic tragedy and who
study the so-called great books under the guidance of two
professors. The class, which includes works by Shakespeare and
Melville, was inspired by Earl Shorris, a New York author, who
created a humanities course for the poor, although not necessarily
homeless, on the Lower East Side of Manhattan, four years ago.
(Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SOUTH BEND, Ind. -- March 06, 1999 --
HOMELESS-CLASSICS-1, 03-06 -- F. Clark Power, a professor in the
liberal studies program at The University of Notre Dame, holding a
weekly humanities seminar for homeless men and women. The
participants, whose personal stories often have the weight of
classic tragedy, study the so-called great books under the guidance
of Clark and another professor. The class was inspired by Earl
Shorris, a New York author, who created a humanities course for the
poor, although not necessarily homeless, on the Lower East Side of
Manhattan. (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- March 06, 1999 -- LATEX-ALLERGY-2, 03-06 --
Lieut. Harold Henderson, a military nurse in San Diego, here with
his wife, Christine, went into shock and died in 1997 during a
hospital stay for an allergic reaction to latex. ``He had three
heart attacks while I was there to pick him up,'' says his wife,
adding that although the staff knew he was allergic and tried to
keep his room free of latex, powder in a doctor's hair or something
else probably caused the fatal reaction. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- March 06, 1999 -- LATEX-ALLERGY-1, 03-06 --
Dr. Barbara Zucker-Pinchoff, with her daughters, Lilly, left, and
Marian, cannot work as an anesthesiologist because she is extremely
allergic to latex. The first signs of Dr. Zucker-Pinchoff's
allergy, was discovered in 1988, as doctors were delivering her
second child by Caesarean section. The latex gloves that covered
the hands dipped inside her during surgery almost sent her into
anaphylactic shock and nearly killed her. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ALGIERS, Algeria -- March 06, 1999 -- ALGERIA-UNREST-3,
03-06 -- Men preparing to pray at a mosque in Algiers. An end to
the civil war between the group of generals who control the
government, known to French-speaking Algerians as ``Le Pouvoir'' --
The Power -- and the Islamic Salvation Army, the guerrilla group
that launched the war in 1992, may be near at hand. To the surprise
of many Algerians, a presidential election, scheduled for April 15,
has come alive, with a promise from the army not to rig the ballot,
as it has in the past. (John Giannini/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ALGIERS, Algeria -- March 06, 1999 -- ALGERIA-UNREST-2,
03-06 -- A man carries his son through part of the Casbah, a maze
of streets in the old Turkish quarter of Algiers, which for many
people became almost completely off-limits since 1992, its
traditional vitality dulled by the lurking presence of Islamic
guerrillas entrenched in a civil war with Algeria's military
rulers. To the surprise of many Algerians, a presidential election,
scheduled for April 15, has come alive, with a promise from the
army not to rig the ballot, as it has in the past. (John
Giannini/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ALGIERS, Algeria -- March 06, 1999 -- ALGERIA-UNREST-1,
03-06 -- In a village near Algiers, a woman mourns and remembers
how her grandchildren once played in her courtyard. The children
were among nearly 500 people killed in the village in 1997. As were
many other people, they were caught in the midst of the civil war
between Algeria's military rulers and Islamic guerrilla groups. The
fighting has claimed 80,000 lives since it began in 1992. (John
Giannini/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
