<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0362 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      03-06 3251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS LOSE GROUND STANDING STILL 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ WARNING TO PATRIOT FANS: Do not read on if
you have angina.
</P>
<P>
   New England's football brass keeps insisting it will do
something before the free agency period is over, but if it turns
out to be replacing Todd Collins with Tedy Bruschi and Robert
Edwards with someone like Travis Jervey, they will slide back to
the pack in the AFC East, less than three years after reaching the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That's not because they lack talent but because their
competition has strengthened itself almost across the board while
the Patriots' ship has taken on more water. The way to compete is
not to hold a pat hand in Pats land and keep saying, ``It's all
about the injuries.'' But that seems to be the prevailing approach
at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Bruschi can replace Collins full time, but if he proved
that at the end of last season I missed it. Maybe Jervey or Sedrick
Shaw can duplicate Edwards's 1,000-yard season, but in three years
that position has gone from Curtis Martin to Edwards to a large
question mark.
</P>
<P>
   And if Heath Irwin can do what Dave Wohlabaugh did at center, he
must have really put on a show at those no-contact, closed practice
sessions last season.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even if every one of these non-moves works out, the Patriots
will still face an improved set of rivals in a division that put
four teams in the playoffs last season. Here's a closer look at
what the AFC East teams have done this offseason.
</P>
<P>
   JETS (12-4 in 1998): New York has not had a significant player
loss in free agency and has added a still-young eight-time Pro Bowl
safety in Steve Atwater, massive blocking tight end Eric Green,
punter/quarterback Tom Tupa, defensive end Mike Frederick, and
solid linebacker Roman Phifer, who had 99 tackles last year with
the Rams.
</P>
<P>
   That is in addition to the re-signing of quarterback Vinny
Testaverde to a three-year, $19.5 million contract. If you're
howling at that, consider this: Testaverde was 13-2 as a starter
last year and his 29 touchdown passes to 7 interceptions was the
fourth-best ratio in NFL history. He is no longer the
interception-prone quarterback of his early days in Tampa. Since
leaving there six years ago, he has had more TDs than INTs five
times.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (10-6): They, too, have lost little but added more
toughness and size to their offensive line by trading for Kevin
Gogan. Jimmy Johnson will try to rehabilitate former No. 1 pick
Tyrone Wheatley, the running back who took up residence in the
Giants' doghouse early and never got out of it. He also added speed
receiver Willie Green and may go after another one with big numbers
in Tony Martin, if Martin's off-field troubles can be worked out.
Most important, the Dolphins did not lose key free agent
linebackers Zach Thomas and Robert Jones, finding cap room to
re-sign both. If Dan Marino stays healthy and an improving line
with two power blockers inside (Gogan and Kevin Donnalley) can open
more holes for the running game, Miami will continue to be a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO (10-6): The Bills are the only team in the division to
do less than the Patriots thus far. They've added no one and lost
receiver Quinn Early and linebackers Chris Spielman (who didn't
play last year anyway) and Wayne Simmons. But they did re-sign
guard Jerry Ostroski and cornerback Ken Irvin, who were pursued by
other teams.
</P>
<P>
   They also have the most depth at quarterback with Doug Flutie
and Rob Johnson, a quality running back in Antowain Smith with a
veteran backup in Thurman Thomas, and a team that plays scrappy
defense that will keep them alive in most games, especially as the
weather worsens.
</P>
<P>
   NEW ENGLAND (9-7): The Patriots' salary-cap mismanagement (e.g.
Max Lane and Todd Rucci earning $2.5 million apiece as the team
benches one and tries to give the other to Cleveland) cost them
Wohlabaugh, and bad luck cost them Edwards. If they have
replacements in house, nobody has seen them.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Glenn remains a question mark because of persistent injury
problems and they still lack a dominating pass rusher unless Willie
McGinest blossoms and finds ways to avoid his own injury jinx. With
front office pressure on the head coach and fan pressure on
everyone, New England cannot afford to come out of the box slowly;
that would increase the public scrutiny and could lead to a mutiny.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (3-13): The Colts are the most improved team in the
division. That figures, since they won only three games, but chief
architect Bill Polian has remade a defense ranked 29th in total
yards, rushing yards, and points allowed by signing free agents
Chad Bratzke, Chad Cota, Cornelius Bennett, and Shawn King for
$14.5 million in bonus money and nearly $50 million in new
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Bratzke, a defensive end who had 11 1/2 sacks last season for
the Giants, was one of the hot commodites among this year's free
agent class, and Polian outbid Cleveland to get him. He will miss
Pro Bowl teammate Michael Strahan, but Bennett, Cota, and fellow
defensive end King should make it easier for him to earn the
six-year, $30 million contract he got.
</P>
<P>
   King is a run stopper not a pass rusher, but Bratzke and Bennett
may handle the latter chore. They still need help at linebacker and
a punter to replace Chris Gardocki, but their defense will have
some pop, especially from Cota, who loves to KO people from his
safety spot and is strong against the run. All of this can only
help an improving Peyton Manning. The Colts may not reach the
playoffs but they could prevent someone else in the division from
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are still nearly six months to go before the
first ball is kicked off in September, and when it is, a healthy
Patriot team will still be favored to win the AFC East. But if
things stay as they are, the Patriots won't be prohibitive
favorites, just the best of a tightly bunched group. And who would
have thought just three short years ago that we'd be saying that?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, the Herald attacked a Globe report that said
Patriots kicker Adam Vinatieri had been offered a three-year, $2.5
million proposal to jump to the Browns. Cleveland personnel
director Dwight Clark was quoted as saying he had had only one
phone conversation with Vinatieri and had not signed him to an
offer sheet, which was a nifty way to deny something that had never
been written. This came out 12 hours after Vinatieri was saying on
local radio that he planned to sign the offer Clark was insisting
hadn't been made. Agents then began to call Vinatieri, who was
representing himself, telling him they could get him more money. He
hired one, who is now trying to get Cleveland to increase its
offer. So what did Clark say on Wednesday when the deal still
wasn't done? ``If it goes (back) to square one, then we're probably
going to get out of it. It was our understanding we had a deal that
was getting ready to go on an offer sheet and be signed by both
parties. We're not changing our deal.'' I thought Clark told the
Herald there was no deal? I thought Clark said all he had was one
phone conversation with Vinatieri? And teams wonder why they are
not believed when they try to get out their side of a story. The
fact is Vinatieri had the offer but had not yet received the
printed sheet when he decided to change direction. That may or may
not end up making him more money. Historically, such negotiating
shifts after a deal is done do not bode well for the player unless
it is one with a lot more leverage than a kicker who can't kick
off. Sources still believe Vinatieri will sign a Cleveland offer
sheet because the Patriots are not inclined to give him a
considerably bigger contract and have no need to until he signs
something because he's restricted. Worst-case scenario for
Vinatieri is getting no sheet to browbeat the Patriots with.
Next-worse is getting the same offer from Cleveland he had two
weeks ago, but having to pay an agent 3 percent of it for doing
nothing . . . Cleveland, by the way, likes to know what it's
getting into. When the Browns signed running back Terry Kirby last
week, he became the 12th ex-49er on their roster. At least five are
expected to be starters. Former 49er president Carmen Policy has
filled his front office with his ex-employees, and they are filling
coach Chris Palmer's roster with the same. Considering the Niners'
track record, that's not a bad idea. Another signee was defensive
back Marquez Pope, who was also pursued by the Patriots. Cleveland
used the same ploy _ offering a roster bonus rather than a signing
bonus _ they intended to use with Vinatieri to make it impossible
for New England to match. Roster bonuses count against this year's
salary cap while signing bonuses can be spread out for bookkeeping
purposes over the life of the contract, even if the money is paid
up front.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Odd things can happen when you gather 300 college football
players to be poked, prodded, and examined by NFL teams. During the
recent scouting combine in Indianapolis, a Jets trainer was
examining the knees of a young prospect from Weber State whom he
knew little about. When asked how he thought he'd do in the draft,
the player responded that he just hoped to get a chance. So the
trainer then asked if he might like to come to the Jets and the kid
replied, ``Come on, I'd never play for the Jets.'' A bit taken
aback, the trainer asked why. ``Because my dad coaches the
Giants.'' The player was John Fassel, son of Giants head coach Jim
Fassel. He was a quarterback for three seasons but moved to wide
receiver last year and caught 16 passes for 197 yards and two
touchdowns. At best, he will be a late-round pick. Probably not by
the Jets . . . A name you will hear much about between now and the
draft on April 17 is McNeese State running back Cecil ``The
Diesel'' Collins. He is being perceived as the next Randy Moss, a
guy with a reputation for having problems off the field but a
battering ram on it. A college teammate of Collins now starting in
the NFL called him ``the best player I ever played with.''
Unfortunately, that former teammate also said, ``He's got a few
problems when he's not playing football.'' A few problems? He was
kicked off the Louisiana State team last June after being arrested
for unlawful entry into a woman's apartment, which is a felony. He
was indicted on that and misdemeanor battery charges. He
transferred to McNeese State so he could play last fall and lasted
two games, rushing for 117 yards and a touchdown before being
thrown off the team for possession of marijuana. So why is he such
a hot property? Because his talent may be second only to Ricky
Williams among available running backs. In the three full games he
played at LSU in 1997, Collins rushed for 172 yards vs. Mississippi
State, 232 and two touchdowns against Auburn, and 179 against Akron
on 20 carries. He was leading the nation with an 8.2-yard average
and 583 yards when he broke his leg in the next game against
Vanderbilt. When asked at the combine if the success of the
troubled Moss might convince teams to take a long look at him,
Collins said, ``You ain't lying. I've got to show them I'm not a
bad person. I'm a good person.'' Collins chose to run for the
scouts at the combine despite a hamstring injury he aggravated
taking a Cybex test in Indianapolis. He ripped off a 4.48 40 and
weighed in at a svelte 208. But if the Patriots are hoping Collins
will become the next Moss, they should consider this: For every
Moss, there are a dozen like Lawrence Phillips who bring their
baggage into the NFL instead of leaving it at the airport. Moss's
indiscretions had not resurfaced for two years when the Vikings
drafted him, and he went to a unique situation where both his
brother and a father figure (Cris Carter) were on hand to monitor
him. The Diesel went off the tracks twice just a year ago and would
have no such monitors here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Someone will grab Collins early, of course, because this is a
league of football players, not fine fellows. If you think
otherwise, consider that the Dolphins have been talking with
Martin, who was released by the Falcons after being indicted on
federal money laundering changes. Martin's father personally
appealed to Marino to talk with Johnson about the receiver, an
explosive ex-Dolphin who caught 66 passes for 1,181 yards and a
17.9-yard average last season. Johnson will not agree to give
Martin any up-front money since he could end up behind bars before
the season begins. But Martin's lawyer, Roy Black, will seek to
have the May 3 trial date postponed until after the '99 season; if
that happens, Johnson could sign Martin to an incentive-laden
contract . . . Hot unknown of the week? Peppi Zellner, a
6-foot-5-inch, 246-pound defensive end from Fort Valley State. He
ran a 4.68 40 and had a 35-inch vertical leap at the combine. He is
a versatile pass rusher who played football in 1996, basketball in
1997, and football again last fall . . . Troubled Hall of Fame
center Mike Webster was arrested twice last week for forging
prescriptions. Webster was getting Ritalin, a stimulant used to
treat hyperactive children with learning disorders. He had 18
prescriptions with forged doctor's signatures when he was arrested.
Sad story of a great player fallen . . . Al Davis never quits,
which is how he built the Raiders in their heyday. After having his
lawsuit against the NFL dismissed in federal court, Davis declared
it a victory and refiled in California state court still claiming
he controlled the lucrative Los Angeles market . . . It is still
believed that NFL owners will approve an expansion franchise for
Los Angeles at their annual meetings in Phoenix March 14-18,
despite the fact that no one there has a stadium plan or solid
political backing. That would be an injustice to Houston bidder Bob
McNair, who has followed every guideline given him by the league
and come up with a marvelous stadium proposal and the money to
finance it. But he has been privately assured he will land an
existing franchise soon enough from one of several teams with
stadium problems . . . Those meetings could be very contentious in
several other areas. Lions owner William Ford is irate at an effort
afoot to begin rotating the Thanksgiving Day games among all 31
teams instead of keeping one in Detroit. That's the tradition, and
anyone who grew up with the NFL knows it, but these guys don't give
a damn about tradition any more . . . The other problem is with
Howard Milstein's bid to buy the Redskins. A coterie of old owners
is trying to do for John Kent Cooke what his father wouldn't.
They're trying to save the Redskins for him. Problem is, the team
was left to a charitable trust that has to sell to the highest
bidder, and that's Milstein, not Cooke the Cheaper. Word is the
league will claim Milstein is leveraging too much of the purchase
price even though he has a $400 million line of credit from Societe
General Bank, which has helped finance six purchases of NFL teams.
Isn't he the same guy whose application fees the NFL took when they
approved him as a final bidder for the Browns, which was then the
highest sale in league history? You can bet that's a question
Milstein's lawyers will soon be asking Paul Tagliabue in
depositions if the NFL doesn't do the right thing by him. Tagliabue
is claiming the league never actually looked closely enough at his
finances to see if he could afford an $800 million bid. If not, was
it just taking his money and using him to drive up the price of the
Browns when he was not really a viable candidate? . . . Why do guys
like Patriots owner Bob Kraft want new stadiums? In Denver a seat
in a luxury box at Mile High Stadium cost between $262-$360 a game.
Seats in the new one go for $500-$821 a pop . . . The Bengals have
an interesting problem at quarterback. They paid Jeff Blake a
$500,000 roster bonus he was due last week, ensuring that he will
be back with the team and indicating that Neil O'Donnell won't be
after June 1. But the payment came two days after Blake called the
Bengals ``disloyal'' to him. Blake is still steaming about losing
his job to Boomer Esiason two years ago and O'Donnell last year,
and he was even angrier when he learned that Chancellor Media
Corp., which owns the radio broadcast rights to Bengal games,
offered to contribute $1 million to Esiason's charity to fight
cystic fibrosis if Esiason played for the Bengals this year.
Esiason declined, saying he was happy doing ``Monday Night
Football'' on ABC and a radio show in Cincinnati, but when Bengal
owner Mike Brown had an informal meeting with Esiason Feb. 23,
Blake got wind of it and was irked. Blake, 28, remains a vastly
talented quarterback who was the starter in 22 of Cincinnati's last
28 victories, but when he says, ``I can't trust anyone there,
there's no loyalty to me there,'' he's blinding himself to reality.
Head coach Bruce Coslet took Blake from the scrap heap and gave him
a second chance after the Jets released him, and Coslet stuck with
Blake far longer as a starter than anyone thought he should. The
fact is, Esiason came off the bench two years ago and played better
than Blake, so he won the job before retiring. Isn't that what
competition is about? If Blake doesn't like it, he should give back
the $500,000 . . . Jets quarterback Glenn Foley is due a $400,000
roster bonus March 15. If he gets it, he still could be cut after
June 1 for salary cap reasons . . . You'll hear a lot of talk about
whether the Browns will take Heisman Trophy winner Williams or
Kentucky quarterback Tim Couch with the first overall pick. Bet on
Couch. The Browns have built a solid line to protect him with
tackles Lomas Brown and Orlando Brown, center Wohlabaugh and left
guard Jim Pyne. Right guard will be a fight among ex-Patriot Scott
Rehberg, Ben Cavil, and 6-7, 315-pound Eric Bateman, who was signed
off the street recently. They have a veteran quarterback to start
with in Ty Detmer and know they can get running backs a lot easier
than quarterbacks. Palmer went to watch Syracuse quarterback
Donovan McNabb work out last week, and Williams now says he will
work out for Cleveland after refusing to do so at the combine. But
on Thursday, Palmer appeared with Couch at the Greater Cleveland
International Auto Show . . . Baltimore continues to work on a
trade for Detroit quarterback Scott Mitchell, but the Lions'
insistence on second- and third-round picks remains a problem. New
coach Brian Billick has said something has to give this week. If it
does, Jim Harbaugh could end up in San Diego in a three-cornered
deal . . . New Packers coach Ray Rhodes passed on a radio and TV
deal that would have earned him an additional $250,000 . . . The
Packers, by the way, made a solid move hiring Ken Herock away from
the Raiders to become director of college scouting. The Pack may
have lost a lot of free agents the past two years but hiring Herock
was a win for Ron Wolf . . . How fragile is a career as an NFL
quarterback? Consider this. Going into training camp this summer,
Arizona's Jake Plummer will be second in seniority to Troy Aikman
among NFC East quarterbacks, with new starters in Philadelphia and
Washington and likely a new one soon with the Giants after they
made erratic Kerry Collins the highest-paid player in team history
despite the fact that he had no competing offer in front of him.
</P>
</TEXT>
