<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-MELIAN-NYT &LR;      03-06 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MELIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIP TO MAJORS TARNISHED BY A MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Jackson Melian does not like to talk about the
night. What should he say? How do you explain coming upon a
terrible car accident and discovering that the two people killed in
it were your parents?
</P>
<P>
   It was warm and clear in the early morning hours last Aug. 28
and Melian, a 19-year-old who is expected to someday play the
outfield for the Yankees, was traveling with their Class A
Greensboro, N.C., minor league team from Columbia, S.C., to
Hickory, N.C. His parents and brother, who were visiting from
Venezuela, were driving a few miles head of the team bus.
</P>
<P>
   Melian was sleeping when the team bus slowed because of a wreck
just ahead on Interstate 77 in Charlotte. Lights flashed as the
groggy players looked out the window. A delivery truck had been
abandoned in the center lane because of engine trouble and a sports
utility vehicle had barreled into it at high speed. The driver and
a passenger had died instantly of massive head injuries.
</P>
<P>
   When the coaches and players on the bus noticed that the sports
utility vehicle had Florida license plates, they were apprehensive.
It was indeed the Melians' vehicle and the victims were Jackson's
father, Vicente Melian, 49, and mother, Jasmin Melian, 43.
Johnathan Melian, Jackson's 23-year-old brother, who was a
passenger in the front seat, survived. Jackson did not get off the
bus at the site of the accident. Seven months later, in an
interview at the Yankees' minor league camp last week, the pain of
that night was evident on his freckled face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never going to get over this,'' he said. ``But I know they
see me and see what I'm doing. I think they're proud because I'm
doing what they wanted me to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The accident report from the Mecklenburg County Highway Patrol
indicated that Vicente, the driver, was going 80 miles an hour in a
55 mph zone. The vehicle left skid marks of 120 feet, hit the truck
at 58 mph and moved it 17 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't get over this,'' Melian said. ``You're not going to
get over it ever. But this is what they wanted me to do. They
wanted to me play baseball in the major leagues and they wanted my
brother to be a lawyer, so we just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Melian has decorated his apartment here with several pictures of
his parents. He wears a gold chain with a pair of his mother's
earrings around his neck, never removing it. He smiled only to
describe how passionate a Yankee fan his father was, which
motivated him to arrive here almost two months early this year.
</P>
<P>
   Melian could pass for a high school fullback, based on his baby
face and the thickness of his legs and chest. In 1996, he was the
$1.6 million wonder boy, the young man from Venezuela who was given
the biggest signing bonus the Yankees had ever awarded an amateur.
Now, he seems more like a teen-ager trying to cope.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing you can really say to him and nothing you can
do,'' Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, said. ``You pray
for him and his family. You wrap your arms around him as an
organization and help him make life's choices. You make sure you're
there.''
</P>
<P>
   When Melian was asked what he missed the most about not having
his parents, he looked down and said: ``Everything. I miss
everything. You don't hear anybody in the house. When you call,
there's nobody home. It's really everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rios, the director of Latin American operations for the
agent Scott Boras and the man Melian now calls his ``second
father,'' said more than 600 people flocked to the funeral services
for Vicente and Jasmin in Barcelona, Venezuela. There was so much
attention given to the deaths that the family had to hold a news
conference before the mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first got into the room with Jackson and Johnathan
after the accident, I'll be honest with you, I told them I had no
answers,'' Rios said. ``I didn't know what to say, but we got down
on our knees and prayed. We asked God to give us the strength to
get through this. That's how we've handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   Three or four times a week, Jackson places a call to Johnathan,
a former minor leaguer with the Seattle Mariners and now a law
student in Venezuela. They discuss baseball, school and, of course,
their parents, consoling and counseling each other. They both live
in the off season in the condominium their parents owned.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson is talking about baseball, he is confident, even
borderline cocky. He proudly said he has gained 27 pounds _ ``all
muscle'' _ since the Yankees signed him, and at 6 feet 2 inches and
215 pounds, he said he was sure he would someday play for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I'm ready, I'll be there,'' said Melian, who batted
.255 with eight homers and 45 runs batted in and had 15 stolen
bases for Greensboro. ``They're watching me play and hoping I can
prove everything I'm supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashman said: ``He's got a demeanor that reeks of success. He's
got an aura. It's not cockiness. He just kind of lets you know he's
going to find a way to beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Melian is still a baseball baby, a raw talent who strikes out
too much (120 times in 135 games) because he needs to learn how to
hit breaking pitches. He will start the season at Class A Tampa in
the Florida State League as the only teen-ager on the roster and
will probably spend the entire year there. Baseball is his
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Melian visited Yankee Stadium and sat in the
first-base dugout with his father. Vicente wore a Yankee cap,
carried a video camera and Venezuelan flag and boasted how Jackson,
whom he named after Reggie Jackson, was destined to become a star
for the Yankees. Melian does not want to return to the stadium
again until he is there as a player.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened is something I'm going to have to talk about,''
Melian said. ``You can't put it behind you and change what
happened. There will be a time where I'll have to talk about it
even more. Maybe not now. Maybe later.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Melian looked away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
