<HEADLINE>
NICKLAUS TAKES FIRST STEPS IN COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Jack Nicklaus returned to Boston last Wednesday to visit
his doctor at New England Baptist Hospital and was advised that he
could discard the crutches he has been using since having hip
replacement surgery Jan. 27. He returned to South Florida Thursday
and followed son Gary in the opening round of the Doral Open,
walking with a cane and riding in a cart. He's on schedule for a
return to the game.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time in 29 years that Nicklaus has missed the
Doral, and he won't play in the Masters next month after 40
straight appearances. He will go to Augusta National for the past
champions dinner, but won't stay for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go up some time in the afternoon,'' he said, ``go out and
take a ride around the golf course, go to the dinner, and come
home.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery Nicklaus had was experimental in that Dr. Benjamin
Bierbaum used a ceramic insert instead of a plastic one. The early
returns were positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing he was concerned about was unwanted bone
growth around the prosthesis, which would limit the range of
motion,'' said Nicklaus. ``He put the X-rays above and said, `Jack,
look at that. No bone growth.' I was clean as a whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically released me to do whatever I feel like I can do.
He took me off crutches and put me on a cane. He said when I can
walk straight and get my weight to where you feel you have good
balance, I can throw the cane away and start chipping, putting, and
swinging the golf club.''
</P>
<P>
   Inactivity has never been a Nicklaus trademark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had three exercise programs to do every day,'' he said.
``I don't have much time to do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, 59, stirred echoes of past glory when he shot himself
into contention at last year's Masters before finishing tied for
sixth. But he knew surgery was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't walk,'' he said. ``I couldn't do enough exercise to
get back to neutral. The doctor said the part that looked like it
had cartilage wasn't cartilage. It was all bone spurs, and the bone
spurs kept turning. I had a mess in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hurt when I was sleeping, so that was why I didn't
really rush into it. It wasn't that bad, but I couldn't do
anything. Then all of a sudden it became a quality-of-life issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The road back will be a slow one, perhaps slower than Nicklaus
realizes. He has said that he'd like to return for the Memorial
(June 3-6) at the course he designed outside his hometown of
Columbus in Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss playing golf,'' he said. ``Do I miss going out and
playing poorly? No. I enjoy going and playing well. I played nine
holes with Gary in December, and it was quite evident I wasn't
going to be able to play golf this year with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I am ahead of schedule. The doctor told me I
couldn't hit a golf ball for three months. Now he's told me that
whenever I am stable on my leg, I can start swinging a golf club.
He said he didn't think I would make the Memorial. If I don't, I
don't. I'm not going to rush it.''
</P>
<P>
   So for now, his sporting participation was limited to throwing
out the first ball before an exhibition game between the Expos and
Mets Friday night at Jupiter Island. The urge to become active
again fires him from within.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Greg Norman, who underwent surgery on his left shoulder
following a painful withdrawal at the Masters last April and this
weekend is playing in his first PGA Tour competition in nearly a
year, will oversee a complete rebuilding of the white course at
Doral.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to renovate,'' said Norman, ``and I said, `I won't
renovate it.' So they said, `Let's just blow it up and start all
over again.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you start renovating, you start opening up the closet
door and there are a lot of ghosts in there underneath the grounds.
So you have to redo irrigation, put in new drainage and a new
surface. You might as well do the golf course over. It's going to
cost the same amount of money if you're going to do all 18 holes.
They said, `Let's redo the whole thing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are changes, too, at Augusta National, including the
growing of rough for the first time. Norman is not a big advocate
of the subtle renovations there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so much history,'' he said. ``I like to step up on
the tee and say, `Well, Gene Sarazen did this or Byron Nelson did
this' and feel the same piece of nostalgia and history under your
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   While noting that some of the classic courses all over the world
have changed _ including Royal Melbourne in his native Australia
and Doral's Blue Monster _ Norman added, ``It just blows my mind. I
just don't understand it. I guess I'm a bit more of a
traditionalist. I don't like to see that stuff happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman said the game plan at Doral is to eliminate the rough
entirely and put in yellow coquina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be firm, but not waste bunkers,'' Norman said. ``If
you miss the fairways, you are in the coquina. If you look at the
Blue Monster, there are a lot of bunkers. They're huge. I want to
get away from that, get to smaller pot bunkers. It's going to look
different.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pat Horgan, who grew up in Newport, R.I., and went to the
University of Rhode Island on a football scholarship, was followed
in the second round at Doral by his brother, Harry, who was
paralyzed in an automobile accident more than a dozen years ago. It
was just the second time that Harry has followed his brother; the
accessibility of paved paths here made it possible for him to get
around. Harry heads up a program called Shake-A-Leg Miami that
helps people with disabilities participate in water sports ranging
from sailing to kayaking. The Golf Channel will air a special piece
on Pat and Harry Monday night at 7:30 p.m. It will be repeated at
11 and again in the 7-9 report on Tuesday morning . . . The World
Match Play Championship a week ago at La Costa in Carlsbad, Calif.,
undoubtedly hurt the field at Doral, where the only one of the top
seven players in the world rankings to show up was South African
Ernie Els, who lost in the opening round at La Costa. There is no
question the World Championships are going to hurt the smaller
tournaments; such things ultimately led to the demise of the
tournament at Pleasant Valley in Sutton, Mass. ``From a player's
standpoint, there are a lot of guys who can play out here,'' was
the assessment of Franklin Langham, who tied for the Doral lead
after the opening round. ``Maybe a lot of guys in the media or the
general public might know their names, but I guarantee if you look
at the winning score it's going to be a good score that wins. You
might argue the field isn't that deep, but you have 144 guys here
who can play.'' . . . The escalating cost of the Ryder Cup has some
news organizations gasping. The cost for a single room at the
designated media hotel, the Sheraton Boston, has risen to $236 per
night. The price at the media hotel for the Super Bowl in Miami two
months ago reportedly was almost $50 per night less _ at the peak
of tourist season . . . But there was a real ``bargain'' available
at Doral last Wednesday. During a rain delay in the pro-am, a man
identified by the Miami Herald as Walter Robinson apparently lifted
a bag of Orlimar Tri-Metal clubs from under a trailer and tried to
sell them for $5 apiece to multiple Doral Open champion Raymond
Floyd. Police arrested Robinson, who reportedly has a criminal
history that includes grand theft. The clubs were valued in the
range of $15,000 . . . The PGA Tour has entered into an arrangement
with IBM to apply technology to the week-to-week lives of the
players. It's called PGA Tour Links. Said Tour commissioner Tim
Finchem, ``We have over 18 players who have received a computer and
have been educated on the basics that will benefit the interaction
of a player with a tournament and our tournament organization.'' .
. . How's this for politeness? Chip Beck, who set himself up to
make just his third cut in his last 38 events by shooting a 71 in
Thursday's opening round, was talking to reporters when Fulton
Allem, who played in the group behind Beck, shouted, ``Why don't
you ask him why he's so slow?'' Beck had just shot his best round
in five years, and was limping on an ailing leg. ``Why do people
complain?'' he asked. ``They've got no idea what people go
through.'' This was reported in the Palm Beach Post by Craig Dolch.
For the record, Beck made the cut at 71-73_144, and Allem missed it
with 74-74_148.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
