<HEADLINE>
NOT ROUTINE START FOR MARTINEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Pedro Martinez doesn't eat hamburgers anymore.
He had his fill in Great Falls, Mont., his first year in pro ball,
when his limited English kept him from ordering much else on the
menu.
</P>
<P>
   For a while last spring, Martinez drank only milk and took
protein supplements, after a frightening stomach disorder sapped
him of strength for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He was happy to report Saturday that back home in his native
Dominican Republic this winter, his diet was ideal: plenty of
steamed rice and vegetables, seafood and chicken, enough to pack an
additional 8 pounds on his flyweight's frame.
</P>
<P>
   He's feeling strong, even more so after not throwing this winter
for the first time since he has been playing pro ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Jimy's idea,'' Martinez said, referring to manager Jimy
Williams, ``and I decided to follow Jimy's advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez pitched 240 innings last season, including his seven
innings against the Indians in Game 1 of the playoffs. Throw in
another 20-plus innings in spring training, and Martinez's workload
exceeded 260 innings. A break was in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimy told me he wanted me to start here like everybody else,''
Martinez said. ``Take the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that Martinez is being counted on to be the staff ace at
least through 2003, it's obviously in the Red Sox' interests to
take the long view. Especially when they have $75 million tied up
in preserving him.
</P>
<P>
   The only downside, if it can be called that, is that Martinez
usually is sharp from the first moment he takes the mound in spring
training. That wasn't the case Saturday in Boston's 6-4 loss to
Cincinnati, when his first spring start was terminated after just
one inning. Martinez threw 46 pitches, nearly half a normal game's
work for him, walked three, forgot to cover first base, and gave up
four runs on just one hit. Nomar Garciaparra's two-run fielding
error added to Martinez's agony.
</P>
<P>
   In Tampa, another Sox squad beat the Yankees, 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worthless,'' Martinez said. ``Coming so far for just one
inning. I should have settled down, but I just didn't feel right.''
</P>
<P>
   The 90-minute bus ride from Fort Myers wasn't a total waste of
fuel. One scout said Martinez was throwing consistently in the
mid-90s, topping out at 97. Another had him even higher on his
radar gun: 96-98 consistently, maxing out at 99 on one pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blanked,'' Martinez said of his outing. ``I was thinking too
much. I was just lost. I didn't feel my mechanics were right. My
arm is really strong, but I couldn't find anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Joe Kerrigan said that this in essence was a
makeup session for the round of batting practice Martinez missed by
reporting a couple days after camp opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``He threw the same number of pitches he would have in a BP,''
Kerrigan said. ``Today was all fastballs and changeups. He's not
trusting his curveball yet. But it will all come when we get him
back on the right schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   It's somewhat misleading, too, Kerrigan said, to suggest that
Martinez took the winter off. He may not have thrown off a mound
three times a week as he usually does, but he and his brother Ramon
worked on a long-toss program with their personal trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think he needed to rest and recoup,'' Kerrigan said. ``He's
had three years in a row where he's thrown over 200 innings, and
been the No. 1 starter on his staff. He's just out of whack right
now, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez reminded his questioners that it takes little to make a
pitcher appear out of sorts. ``There are small things we do with
our legs and shoulders that cause us to make a pitch differently
than we want to,'' he said. ``You almost have to be a pitcher
yourself to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered no excuse for his failure to cover first base on what
could have been a double play started by first baseman Bob Hamelin.
It wasn't until Garciaparra had taken the throw at second that he
remembered to break for the bag.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
