<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL KRAFT WARNING 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It seemed for a time that Floridian Greg Kraft might run
away and hide. After building his lead to three shots in Saturday's
third round of the Doral-Ryder Open, he came back to earth briefly
but wavered just once as those in pursuit were unable to sustain a
serious charge.
</P>
<P>
   When Kraft lagged a putt from the back fringe of the 18th green
to tap-in length, it gave him a 70_205 aggregate and a two-shot
advantage over Ernie Els (70) and Glen Day (67) in a $3 million
tournament whose field took a hit because of the last week's World
Match Play Championship.
</P>
<P>
   The mere presence of Els, who has won the US Open twice in the
past five years and is the only one of the world's top seven
players here, sets up Sunday's final round. Els birdied the 16th
and 18th holes on a day that saw major challenger Scott Dunlap find
the water on 18 and take a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap still finished three shots astern at 69_208, where he was
eventually joined by Andy Bean, who made a remarkable recovery out
of a trap on the 18th and coaxed in his putt to save par.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might have been the greatest par I've ever seen in my
life,'' said playing partner Pat Horgan of Newport, R.I., whose
71_210 tied him with Ocean State compatriot Billy Andrade (68).
</P>
<P>
   Kraft, whose best finishes in eight years on the PGA Tour are a
pair of seconds, started with a birdie when he hit a 3-wood out of
a fairway bunker on the par-5 and eventually made a 4-foot putt.
After eight straight pars, he made birdies on the 10th (two putts)
and 11th (8-iron, 10 feet) to widen his lead to three before taking
a bogey on the 14th out of a fairway bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I did make a bogey, I figured I was still leading the
tournament,'' said Kraft. ``I hope I regain a little of the magic I
had the first two days. The first part of the round was a bit of a
struggle. I was kind of in a little funk but I finally settled into
a thought that really seemed to work and I played pretty good the
rest of the way in.''
</P>
<P>
   Els, who won the Nissan Open two weeks ago at Riviera before
bowing out of the match-play competition in the opening round, had
an erratic round that included four bogeys and six birdies. The
birdies on the 16th and 18th brought him into contention for his
second win of the year in just his second medal-play event.
</P>
<P>
   Day, who has earned the nickname ``All'' because of his slow
play, had birdies on the fifth (wedge, 7 feet), seventh (8-iron, 15
feet), and eighth (wedge, 20 feet) on the front side. He proceeded
to birdie the 10th with two putts from 40 feet and the 15th
(8-iron, 3 feet) to put him in position to win his first tournament
since joining the Tour in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every tournament I tee up is a ripe opportunity,'' said Day.
``I am trying to win, so I don't care what it is or where it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've practiced every day, and I usually don't hit balls after
I finish. I think I found something in my swing. I can't put a
finger on it. I just played smart and made some putts today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean, who turns 46 Saturday and who hasn't won since the Byron
Nelson in 1986, is the gallery favorite and delighted the crowd at
18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the better shots and maybe one of the more
questionable shots I have ever hit,'' he said. ``I hit to the right
and hit the cart path. I had a lie that there was really no way I
could pitch it out to the fairway. Luckily my ball never left the
flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrade shot himself into contention with a bogey-free round. He
started with a two-putt birdie and added birdies on the ninth
(6-iron, 5 feet), 15th (8-iron, 5 feet), and 16th (sand wedge, 5
feet).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
