A0375 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE07-     03-06 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Change of luck aim for some
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In a city that's certainly not short on luck,
today's Las Vegas 400 offers several NASCAR drivers an opportunity
to change their fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner and Michael Waltrip are both seeking an elusive
first career victory, while unknown driver Tom Hubert hopes to
parlay his fourth Winston Cup race into a full-time ride on the
circuit. Ricky Craven, who has battled injuries the past three
seasons, is looking to revive his career.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who has a tenuous 29-point lead in the Cup standings
after two races, is searching for his first victory in 79 career
starts. He'll start inside the third row today and could have his
best shot at becoming NASCAR's newest first-time winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the odds are better on the guys who win every week,
but I think this team is going to win a race,'' said Skinner, one
of only two drivers to post consecutive top-10 finishes this year.
``I would never bet on me because I think it's bad luck, but I
don't think I would be a guy who would bet against it, either. It
might be the place where we can get our first points victory.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who will drive the No. 31 Chevrolet he used to win last
year's exhibition in Japan, is one of four drivers in General
Motors cars that will start in the top five starting positions.
Bobby Labonte is on the pole in the No. 18 Pontiac, with Waltrip
and Joe Nemecheck starting second and third in Chevys.
</P>
<P>
   The only Ford driver in the top five is Hubert, a road-course
specialist from California. Hubert, 34, usually spends his Sundays
as a rear-tire changer in the pits, but today he'll be starting
fourth in his first start on an oval track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The road racing has gotten me rides, but we need to get that
off our backs and show we can do it everywhere,'' Hubert said.
``We're hoping this will get it rolling into a full deal. I haven't
run but a handful of races, so it would be interesting to get in a
weekly situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford dominated last year's inaugural Cup event at Las Vegas
Motor Speedway, placing 13 cars in the top 14 finishers. Before the
season-finale at Atlanta last year, NASCAR officials changed the
spoiler and front-valence heights of the new Tauruses to curb their
apparent aerodynamic advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Fords led 413 of 593 laps this year, however, and placed six
cars in the top 10 starting positions for today's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fords still have a little bit of an advantage, and the
Pontiacs looked real good, too,'' said two-time defending Cup
champion Jeff Gordon, who will start 11th. ``When I look at it, our
odds aren't that great here. I certainly wouldn't be putting money
on me.... I just know I'm not the best one.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who won the season-opening Daytona 500 and then fell to
a 39th-place finish at Rockingham after engine failure, still is in
a better position than Dale Earnhardt and Rusty Wallace, who both
needed provisionals to qualify and will start in the 19th row.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
