<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Breakout: Jones earns first start
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ After a forgettable start to his Winston Cup career,
rookie Buckshot Jones of Tucker finally has something to smile
about.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a University of Georgia grad, qualified for today's Las
Vegas 400 after failing to make the 43-car field for the season's
first two events.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 28, stood on Friday's first-round qualifying speed of
167.297 mph, which was 35th-fastest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great feeling to make the race,'' Jones said. ``My dad
(Buckshot Racing owner Billy Jones) is all pumped up. You miss the
first two races and you come down hard. I wouldn't care if I was
starting dead last. It doesn't matter where you start, you're in
the show.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones' team struggled with aerodynamics and suspension on the
No. 00 Pontiac at Daytona and Rockingham. They've been getting
advice on setups from various teams, including Hendrick
Motorsports, which fields Jeff Gordon's Winston Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to run every lap and finish the race,'' Jones said.
``It's not going to pay to go out there and and try to go to the
front right off the bat. There's going to be some good cars back
there with me. I'll be doing a lot of learning.''
</P>
<P>
   GOLDBERG AT ATLANTA
</P>
<P>
   Pro wrestling star Bill Goldberg will be the grand marshal for
next week's Cracker Barrel Old Country Store 500 at Atlanta Motor
Speedway. Goldberg, a former defensive lineman for the Atlanta
Falcons, apparently is an avid NASCAR fan.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILIAR NAMES OUT
</P>
<P>
   There were some familiar names on the DNQ list for today's race,
including Kyle Petty and Ted Musgrave. Petty qualified for all 33
races last year, and Musgrave made the field for the 32 events he
entered. But both drivers were left out at Las Vegas after veterans
Rusty Wallace and Dale Earnhardt used provisionals to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a first for me,'' Musgrave said. ``It's very
disgusting. I just messed up on the qualifying. Who would ever
think that Rusty and Dale and all them guys would have to take
provisionals and kind of scarf them away from the guys down here?''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Stanton Barrett, making his first start in the No. 90
Ford, made the field on owner Junie Donlavey's provisional.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
