A0378 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-MEN07-COX     03-06 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MEN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ACC's plea: No way it's 3
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Tradition means a lot in college basketball,
but will it be enough to get four ACC teams into the 1999 NCAA
Tournament? That's just one of the major questions that will be
answered today when the 64-team field is officially announced (6:30
p.m., CBS).
</P>
<P>
   The other major conferences appear to be in pretty good shape
heading into Selection Sunday. If Ole Miss (19-12) gets in, the SEC
will have six teams for the first time in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Ten, the nation's highest-rated conference, definitely
will get six and probably will get seven, with Minnesota (17-10)
and its power rating of 18 screaming to be included.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East will have a good day with a No.1 seed (UConn) and
two No. 2s (St. John's, Miami).
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 (five teams) and Pac-10 (four) should also be
satisfied at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But the ACC, which has been top-heavy with the likes of No. 1
Duke (31-1), No. 5 Maryland (26-5), and North Carolina (24-8), No.
9 in the power ratings and a winner over Maryland Saturday, has
been making its case all week that it deserves to get more than
three teams in the field. Every year since 1980, when more than two
teams from a conference could be invited, the ACC has had four or
more teams in the NCAA Tournament. Wake Forest (16-13) and N.C.
State (18-13) are the league's best hopes for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up trying to outguess those guys (selection committee)
after last year but playing in this conference has got to stand for
something,'' said Wake Forest coach Dave Odom, whose team lost to
N.C. State in Friday's second round of the ACC Tournament. ``If
we're the No. 2-rated conference in the country, how can we get
only get three teams in?''
</P>
<P>
   That, it appears, has been the ACC's strongest argument to the
NCAA Selection Committee this week. The Big Ten, the top-rated
conference, could get as many as seven teams if Minnesota slips in.
So how, the ACC asks, can there be such a big drop-off to second
place?
</P>
<P>
   As it does every year, the ACC compiled a wealth of information
to make its case for multiple bids and sent it to the committee,
which is meeting in Kansas City. A copy of that document was
obtained by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Some of its points
include:
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACC is the No. 2 conference in five computer rankings and
three schedule rankings.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACC's top three teams are responsible for 33 losses among
the other six. Since a team's Division I winning percentage is 25
percent of the Ratings Percentage Index (RPI), one of the major
factors used by the committee, those losses figure significantly
into the RPIs of the other teams.
</P>
<P>
   _ The ACC, at 8-8, is the only conference to have a .500 or
better record against non-conference ranked teams. The Big East is
10-12, the Big Ten 9-11.
</P>
<P>
   _ At 94-23, the ACC has the nation's top winning percentage
(.803) against non-conference competition.
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky athletics director C.M. Newton, the chair of the
selection committee, said last week that once the 30 automatic bids
are awarded, conference affiliation is not a factor in the process
of selecting at-large teams. Every team, Newton suggested, is
judged independently based on strength of schedule, power rating,
and how it finished the season.
</P>
<P>
   That argument is not flying here in ACC country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the object of the process is to pick the best 64 teams in
the country, you have to consider the caliber of competition inside
the conference,'' Maryland coach Gary Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA MEN'S PROJECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   PROJECTED TOP SEEDS
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Tournament selection committee will reveal its 64-team
field at 6:30 p.m. today. Staff writer Tony Barnhart projects the
top 16 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   EAST: 1. Duke, 2. Miami, 3. Ohio State, 4. Arizona
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH: 1. Auburn, 2. Maryland, 3. Cincinnati, 4. Wisconsin
</P>
<P>
   MIDWEST: 1. Michigan State, 2. St. John's, 3. Kentucky, 4. UCLA
</P>
<P>
   WEST: 1. UConn, 2. Stanford, 3. Utah, 4. North Carolina
</P>
<P>
   BY CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   ACC (3): Duke, Maryland, North Carolina; SEC (6): Auburn,
Kentucky, Tennessee, Arkansas, Florida, Ole Miss; Big Ten (7):
Michigan State, Ohio State, Wisconsin, Indiana, Purdue, Iowa,
Minnesota; Pac-10 (5): Arizona, UCLA, Stanford, California,
Washington; Big East (5): UConn, St. John's, Miami, Syracuse,
Villanova; Big 12 (5): Texas, Oklahoma State, Missouri, Kansas,
Oklahoma; Atlantic 10 (4): George Washington, Xavier, Temple, Rhode
Island; Conference USA (3): Cincinnati, UNC Charlotte, Louisville;
WAC (3): Utah, Tulsa, New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   _Wake Forest (16-13) and N.C. State (18-13) are on the bubble.
</P>
<P>
   _Rhode Island (19-12) needed to beat Temple in A-10 championship
game on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _Alabama-Birmingham (20-10) is on the bubble.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
