<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NCAA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WON'T PLAY SPECULATION GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ UCLA's goal on this Selection Sunday is to avoid
Princeton _ not the team, the mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Bruins won the Pac-10 title by three games
and expected a seed in the West Regional. Instead, Arizona stayed
West and the Bruins were shipped to the Southeast Region, where
they faced Princeton in Indianapolis. Unable to shake the
disappointment, they played like a team deflated.
</P>
<P>
   This year, with a young team and an uncertain seed, the Bruins
are again vulnerable to the whims of the nine-man NCAA selection
committee, which has been sequestered in a Kansas City hotel room
since Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so difficult to know what the committee will do,'' UCLA
coach Steve Lavin said. ``We can't allow ourselves to speculate and
get our expectations set on one thing and then face disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to expend a lot of energy giving it much
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   They're leaving the speculation to others, so let's go.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the primary ingredients _ power rating, record in the
last 10 games, performance against top-rated teams, strength of
nonconference schedule, road performance _ the Bruins probably will
be a No. 4 or 5 seed.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's loss at Arizona, the Bruins were No. 17 in the
Sagarin poll, which is more accurate than the RPI but not identical
to the NCAA's ratings formula. That correlates to a No. 5 seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say that's fairly accurate,'' a selection committee member
said earlier this week. ``They're a young team that's made a lot of
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins and Wildcats thought Saturday's winner would be a No.
3 seed. Although possible _ betting on the selection committee is
the quickest path to bankruptcy _ that seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats may have secured a No. 4 seed with the victory, but
they seemingly lack the power rating (18), road wins and
nonconference schedule to displace Utah, Ohio State, Kentucky,
Cincinnati, Stanford, Maryland, St. John's and Miami _ teams
fighting for No. 2 and 3 seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the Bruins go? As the Pac-10 champ, Stanford probably
will remain in the West, and the NCAA loathes placing two highly
seeded teams from the same conference in the same region.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's seed should narrow its potential destination. Because No.
4s and 5s are paired with the No. 1 seed in each region, UCLA could
be shipped to Charlotte with No. 1 Duke, or to Milwaukee with No. 1
Michigan State, or to Indianapolis with likely-No. 1 Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to go East,'' guard Baron Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins should be more concerned with opponent than locale.
They have greater flexibility than last season, when they had no
bench and no size, but they often struggle against physical,
disciplined teams that force them to execute their half-court
offense: Princeton in 1996, Iowa State in 1997, and Miami last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Add center Dan Gadzuric's season-ending knee injury, and the
Bruins are also susceptible to size.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the ability to match up with any opponent other than a
real strong frontline,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA could face any of a dozen teams that fill the 12-14 seed
model, including Murray State, Penn, Kent, Southwest Missouri
State, Creighton, Alabama-Birmingham, Oklahoma, Delaware and, yes,
perhaps Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton, which failed to win the Ivy League title, is one team
the Bruins won't face _ at least on the court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
