<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-CLEMENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COMMENTARY: SPRING STARTS WITH A SILENT STEINBRENNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAINES CITY, Fla. _ At another time, in an earlier season,
George Steinbrenner would have fumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy won how many Cy Young awards?'' the Yankees'
impatient owner might have blurted. ``Who did he pay off? We gave
up my good buddy David Wells for him? You know that was the general
manager's trade. I'm going to have to talk to that young man. He
might be a bright young executive, but he got snookered on this
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner was not at Baseball City Stadium to watch Clemens
pitch his first game for the Yankees Saturday. He was not here to
see the Kansas City Royals pepper Clemens for three runs and six
hits in the first two innings. Even if he had been, though, the
owner most likely would not have expressed outrage that Brian
Cashman (acting strictly on his own, of course, wink, wink) had
traded Wells, the perfect-game pitcher and New York cult hero, for
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Steinbrenner has mellowed, but he has learned that
spring training is not a mandatory time for pitching perfectly and
winning daily. In his past, he had legendary blowups with Billy
Martin over that subject, and Martin was never able to get
Steinbrenner to understand that spring training, especially the
early exhibition games, is a time for players to get into pitching
and hitting shape for the season.
</P>
<P>
   On one March day years ago, Steinbrenner sat in the stands at
Pompano Beach, Fla., and watched Dennis Rasmussen give up three
home runs in the first two innings as the Texas Rangers hit routine
fly balls that the gusty wind carried over the fences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbus, here we come,'' Steinbrenner said as he watched the
third home run, suggesting that the left-handed Rasmussen had
earned a ticket to the minor leagues. When that season ended,
Rasmussen, who never was exiled to Columbus, had been the team's
No. 1 pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens did not give up any home runs. Most of the seven hits
the Royals got against him in his three-inning outing weren't even
produced by hard-hit balls. Nevertheless Clemens said he had to
resist the temptation to turn it up a notch or two when he needed
outs with Royals on base.
</P>
<P>
   He has a tendency, Clemens said, to try to do too much too soon
when he ``a little anxious or the adrenaline is pumping a little
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would the ardrenalin be pumping in his first exhibition
game?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the excitement and the first time being out there again,
just being in a new environment,'' he said. ``I'm always excited
about those situations each time I go out and I have a tendency to
want to do more and overthrow. It was good that Mel reminded me on
two or three occasions that today less is more. It doesn't matter
what happens, guys get on base or whatever. Don't try to turn it
loose just yet.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a mere exhibition game (the NFL arrogantly calls theirs
preseason games), but it offered an intriguingly symbolic matchup:
Clemens pitching for the Yankees for the first time and Kevin
Appier pitching for perhaps one of the last times for the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   It was the money game that was in play.
</P>
<P>
   In acquiring Clemens from the Toronto Blue Jays Feb. 18, the
Yankees expressed willingness _ eagerness _ to take on another big
salary that will grow much bigger when they give the superstar
pitcher a contract extension that will catapult him into the Kevin
Brown stratosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals, on the other hand, are looking to trade Appier for
young players because they want to reduce their $26 million payroll
and Appier, with a $4.8 million salary, is their highest-paid
player. The Yankees' payroll is nearly three-and-a-half times the
sum the Royals are committed to paying at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   The teams epitomize the difference between baseball's haves and
have nots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we can get a player or two back for Appier and we
can take some of the money we save and put it into prospects,''
Herk Robinson, the Royals' general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   The stands were filled with fans, but 20 or more scouts were
here also. Those from the Cleveland Indians, the Boston Red Sox and
the Rangers were probably the most attentive because their teams
have been the ones that have expressed the most interest in dealing
for Appier if he shows he has made a complete comeback from
shoulder surgery.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Royals would like to retain some semblance of
respectability that Appier gives them, economic reality takes
precedence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' Robinson said, ``we cranked our payroll from $25
million to $37 million. We finished third and won five more games
than the year before. We never realistically were competitive with
Cleveland, but it cost us about $2{ million a game. We can't afford
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ``old days,'' Robinson said, the Royals' owner, Ewing
Kauffman, ``could write a check at the end of the season for 1, 2,
3, 4 million, which he unwillingly did. He didn't like it; he
considered it waste. But it put us on a pretty good par with
Toronto or the Yankees or whoever. Now you put another zero on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 70s and the start of the 80s, the Yankees and the
Royals seemed to play each other every October for the right to go
to the World Series. They haven't had any of those games recently
and aren't expected to in the future. Times change.
</P>
<P>
   But they also change for impetuous owners. That's why
Steinbrenner didn't call the press box at Baseball City Stadium
Friday screaming for scalps, Clemens' and Cashman's. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
