<HEADER>
A0387 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC--ROBERTSONCOLUMN-     03-06 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC--ROBERTSON </SLUG>
 COLUMN -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Longhorns might have won for losing
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the spectrum of possible scenarios, Texas'
losing to Oklahoma State on Saturday might have been the Longhorns'
safest, smartest option. Besides making them angry and therefore,
in theory, inspired for the Big Dance, it also bought them an extra
day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   Although some extra shooting practice might be in order, too.
And ball-handling drills. Definitely lots of those.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns, their entire season a transition game, had
overachieved to a level sufficient to claim the regular-season Big
12 title, winning 13 of 16 starts. Their quarterfinal victory over
Colorado here in the postseason just-for-profits classic had
secured, beyond any smidgeon of doubt, their participation in the
NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   To stick around KC for another day given how their legs were
dragging would have been for aesthetics only, not pragmatic gain.
The Longhorns weren't going to beat Kansas in this arena anyway,
certainly not with their feet mired in cement.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, how many steaks can you eat?
</P>
<P>
   ``If going out now,'' coach Rick Barnes said, ``gives us a
better chance to win next weekend, then I'd much rather go out
now.''
</P>
<P>
   It does. With an eight-man depth chart and, in Barnes, a new
taskmaster who asks that defense be played on more than an optional
basis _ a fresh approach for the post-Penders Burnt Orange _ Texas
is flat-out tired. The Longhorns are also hurting, none more so
than Kris Clack, whose badly bruised buttocks Saturday made him
grimace with practically every step. At one point in the first
half, he took to riding an exercise bicycle behind the Longhorns
band to loosen up.
</P>
<P>
   Backcourt monkey business
</P>
<P>
   Barnes wore a pained look as well. No, his fanny felt fine. It
was his guards who were killing him. Although he bragged on
Oklahoma State's defense, which featured liberal use of a zone _
somewhere, Henry Iba was scowling _ he couldn't have been pleased
with DeJuan ``Chico'' Vazquez, Ivan Wagner and William Clay, his
Marx Brothers backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   They shot 4-for-19. They lost nine turnovers. They dished a mere
four assists. Each committed at least one glaring gaffe late that
cost UT a chance to tie the score or lead in a game the Longhorns
would barely lose 59-57.
</P>
<P>
   They've been the weak link all season, these guys. Texas' burly
front line can duke it out with anyone, even Duke. But the guard
corps, minus offseason defectors Luke Axtell (Kansas) and Bernard
Smith (Houston), is thin, thin, thin. On afternoons like
Saturday's, their names should be Chico, Groucho and Harpo.
</P>
<P>
   Coupled with poor Kris Clank's 3-for-11 misfiring, the Longhorns
finished a dreary .333 from the field. Which, by the way, was what
the Cowboys shot. Oklahoma State missed 15 of its first 17 salvos
of the second half, yet amazingly never surrendered the precarious
six-point edge to which it had clung at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Ten times in the last 14 minutes UT had a possession on which it
could have tied the score or regained the upper hand. Ten times the
Longhorns failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities, plenty of them,'' Barnes said. ``We
just didn't capitalize.''
</P>
<P>
   Right down to the final scrum under the basket, Texas was trying
to kick open the door, to no avail. Adrian Peterson's bricking the
second of two free throws with nine seconds left afforded Wagner,
the recipient of Chris Mihm's crisp outlet pass, a long moment to
make amends for his failings, particularly a horrid cross-court
pass just a second earlier that forced Vazquez to foul Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   A scramble to the end
</P>
<P>
   It was a two-point game, and the basketball was Ivan's to do
with as he saw fit. Wagner had gone 1-for-5 from 3-point range and
accounted for five of the Longhorns' 19 turnovers. Nonetheless, all
would have been forgiven with a tying bucket at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate to avoid being referred to by clever sportswriters in
today's editions as Ivan the Terrible, Wagner forged a relatively
clear lane to the hole, but his layup didn't come close to
dropping. It angled straight down off the rim, leaving Gabe
Muoneke, who had muscled into position for the rebound, with an
off-balance putback that had only a dumb-luck chance of going in.
</P>
<P>
   The clock died with Gabe flat on his back, his face contorted in
despair while the Cowboys danced in circles around him.
</P>
<P>
   But, again, it's better this way. OSU profited by winning,
securing its stutter-stepping NCAA Tournament quest, which helps
the Big 12 and thus Texas indirectly. Eddie Sutton, having not
forgotten how his team had been tabbed as the conference's
preseason favorite, was so thankful to be alive he heaped praise on
everyone, even calling the Longhorns good bets to make the Sweet
16.
</P>
<P>
   With an extra 24 hours at home to relax, reflect and recuperate,
perhaps they are. But Groucho, Harpo and Chico must first step
things up a bit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
