<SLUG> BC-HKO-MINOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HAVEN'S HALFNIGHT MAKING SWEET MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAGUE NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY VAN HANDLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Ashlin Halfnight may play hockey for a living, but he
also proves two points: that music does not soothe the savage
beast, and that a musician can be a Beast.
</P>
<P>
   Halfnight is in his second professional season with the Beast of
New Haven in the American Hockey League, though as his 30 penalty
minutes in 50 games indicate, he is far from savage. But as his
teammates and fans at New Haven Coliseum have discovered, the
defenseman is quite adept at performing with a guitar as well as a
hockey stick.
</P>
<P>
   The former Harvard captain and current property of the Carolina
Hurricanes has released a compact disc titled ``Loose Ends,'' and
the original five-song CD has become minor league hockey's version
of a hit record, selling out its first 2,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey plus music usually stirs up thoughts of ``We Are the
Champions,'' the theme song from Hockey Night In Canada, or the
``Chicken Dance,'' which makes the popularity of Halfnight's CD a
bit unexpected, given its acoustic guitar base and plaintive titles
such as ``Next To Nothing'' and ``Blue Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfnight, who wrote and sings each song, had no expectations
that he would ever sell more than a handful of recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was a vanity thing,'' said Halfnight, who recorded
several of the songs last offseason near his Toronto home and
concluded the project in a West Haven, Conn., studio. ``I just
wanted to get it finished before Christmas and give it to my
friends and family as a present.''
</P>
<P>
   He had only 50 copies made originally, but after they were
dispersed, he decided to try to market the disc, with $6 from each
$10 sale going to Saint Francis Home For Children, one of his
charities in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Sales took off at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really kind of weird,'' said Halfnight, whose only formal
music training came in the form of piano lessons as a youth. ``What
I thought was a little thing has really snowballed. It's beyond my
wildest dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Does Major League Soccer star Alexi Lalas, who takes his music
very seriously, have some competition down the road? Halfnight
doesn't think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played a lot in college, but nothing public,'' he said. ``It
was a private thing, a tension release. It was with roommates and
friends, very informal. It's really just a hobby and something I
enjoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Halfnight's younger brothers Drew (a contributor to the CD) and
Chris are also involved in music, but he assures: ``It's not going
to be the Partridge Family or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much hand-wringing (by purists) and fanfare (by the leagues)
accompanied the AHL's decision _ as strongly suggested by the NHL _
to adopt an experimental four-on-four format during its five-minute
overtime periods. The test was designed to see if opening up the
ice would lead to more scoring, and therefore fewer ties. After the
first week and a half, the NHL is getting what it was looking for.
While only 33 percent of games were decided prior to the
four-on-four system, a healthy 64 percent have been recorded as a
win or loss under it. Shots are up by more than 50 percent, and the
average length of overtime has been shaved by a minute and a half
to 2:49 . . . Scoring certainly wasn't a problem for Lars
Pettersen, who netted five goals in a third-period span of 16:01
for Augusta of the East Coast Hockey League last month. However,
Pettersen's splurge began when the Lynx trailed, 7-1, and they
wound up losing, 7-6, to Birmingham. Sam Ftorek, the son of Devils
coach Robbie and a former St. Anselm player, drew assists on four
of Pettersen's goals . . . Pat Egan, a former Bruins defenseman and
color announcer, heads up the list of four new inductees to the
Springfield Hockey Hall of Fame next Saturday at the Civic Center.
Former Indians Bruce Cline, Gerry Foley, and Keith Allen (the
latter of whom helped build the Philadelphia Flyers into a power in
the 1970s) are the other honorees. Gerry Cheevers will deliver the
dinner speech; for more information call 413-739-3344.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Providence's wondrous season threatened to hit a pothole last
week when the Bruins bought goalie Jim Carey out of his contract,
but the Baby B's have stayed on course. It helps to have a John
Grahame handy; the second-year pro, who was splitting time with
Carey, set a franchise record for wins in a season with his 26th
early last week, and when he beat New Haven Friday, it was his 18th
consecutive victory, an AHL record. Grahame's new partner, Joaquin
Gage, whom the Baby B's signed after he was released from a tryout
deal with Portland, debuted with 36 saves in a 3-1 loss to Lowell
last weekend . . . The Lock Monsters and their wives are holding a
dinner to benefit the Angel Fund, which aids in research for Lou
Gehrig's Disease. Bernice Rowe, the wife of general manager Tom
Rowe, and Carrie Jackson are co-chairs of the event, to be held
March 17 at the Andover Marriott. Call 978-458-7825 for details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Injuries and recalls sometimes result in manpower shortages in
the minors, and some teams find what can charitably be termed
``nostalgic ways'' to fill the gaps. It wasn't a ``turn back the
clock'' night, but there was Ron Duguay skating his lane for
Jacksonville in an ECHL game last month. The presence of the
erstwhile New York Ranger did more to hurt than help the Lizard
Kings, who had to forfeit when it was discovered that Duguay's
presence put them one veteran (200 pro games or more) over the
league limit. But maybe they shouldn't have lost the 2 points:
Doesn't a 41-year-old qualify for another category, such as super
veteran? . . . Defenseman Gaston Gingras suited up for a couple of
Chesapeake games this season and is expected to play more to become
eligible for the ECHL playoffs. Gingras, 39, already made a
comeback three years ago in the AHL after six years in Europe; this
time, he's playing for former Montreal teammate Chris Nilan . . .
Dennis Maruk, a 60-goal scorer for Washington in 1981-82, has
signed a five-game tryout deal with Lake Charles (Western Pro
Hockey League). He's a mere 43 . . . Andy Moog is coaching Fort
Worth (WPHL) while its regular coach fills in as a player . . .
Logo of the Week: For six years, The Hockey News's rankings of
logos have been eagerly anticipated by fans and front offices. The
bottom ranking is as coveted as the top spot, since marketing a
team as either worst or first is an easy sell. This time, The
Hockey News judged the ECHL's Mobile Mysticks most egregious. A
dragon wrapped around a hockey stick with blades at both ends?
Judge for yourself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
