<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0391 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HAITIANS07-COX     03-06 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAITIANS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 boats carrying Haitians sink near Florida; 4 dead, others
missing
 &HT;    By Larry Hobbs
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Two smuggling boats crowded with nearly
40 Haitian refugees sank 30 miles east of West Palm Beach early
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After saving three men between 5 a.m. and 8:30 a.m. and
confirming four people dead, the U.S. Coast Guard searched through
Saturday night for other survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard officials believe more than 30 people, who were
being smuggled here from the Bahamas, are unaccounted for.
</P>
<P>
   The three who were rescued by search helicopters were brought to
hospitals in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Border Patrol agents believe all three men are Haitian
refugees, although they had not ruled out the possibility that one
of them may be a smuggler, said William Brett, senior Border Patrol
agent in West Palm Beach. The men are in their 30s, though
officials did not give their names.
</P>
<P>
   Two boats carrying 18 Haitian refugees each set out from the
west end of the Bahamas, the survivors told Border Patrol agents in
West Palm Beach, Coast Guard Petty Officer Jeff Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Both vessels were open boats, one 17 feet long and the other 20
feet long, Hall said. There were no life jackets on board either
boat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first boat had problems, the second boat came over to help
and unfortunately both boats sank,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   A passing freighter called the Coast Guard at about 2 a.m. after
hearing screams in the dark waters, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard helicopter using night vision equipment rescued a
man waving a flashlight and clinging to a propane tank at 5 a.m.,
Lt. Ron Labrec said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing he had the flashlight _ it increased his
chances of being found,'' Labrec said.
</P>
<P>
   Another helicopter plucked the two other survivors out of the
water after a Coast Guard Falcon jet spotted them clinging to a
barrel at 8:30 a.m., Coast Guard officials said.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time, the Coast Guard cutter Matagorda recovered
two bodies in the water and witnessed two more bodies sink near
where the two men were rescued, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the men were released to Border Patrol agents in West
Palm Beach and one man remained at Good Samaritan Medical Center in
stable condition, a nursing supervisor said.
</P>
<P>
   All three men will eventually be taken to Krome Detention Center
in Miami, Border Patrol agents said.
</P>
<P>
   Later Saturday, two Coast Guard helicopters searched north of
where the tragedy occurred, hoping to find survivors clinging to
buoyant debris in the Gulf Stream's swift northerly currents.
Officials planned to re-evaluate at midnight whether to continue or
call off the search.
</P>
<P>
   The search was expected to stretch as far north as Cape
Canaveral by 11 p.m. Saturday, considering the Gulf Stream's 5 mph
currents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We search for survivors,'' Hall said. ``There is a possibility
that someone is alive or we wouldn't be searching.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall said that from ``what the survivors told the Border Patrol,
it was a migrant smuggling operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally that many people don't get on a boat to cross in the
middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Refugees trying to reach U.S. shores with the help of smugglers
risk their lives every time, Labrec said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go in small boats that are overloaded and they don't have
the proper equipment,'' Labrec said. ``It makes for a pretty
dangerous situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of Cubans and Haitians taking to the seas have
increased since 1998, and experts expect the trend to continue in
1999. In 1998, Coast Guard vessels intercepted 1,025 Cubans and
1,206 Haitians at sea, compared with 406 Cubans and 587 Haitians in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 17, a 29-foot boat capsized in 6-foot high seas off
Elliott Key, some 22 miles south of Miami. Nine drowned and another
five passengers were lost at sea and presumed dead. Two of the nine
survivors are the accused smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike earlier refugees who used flimsy rafts, the latest
arrivals often are smuggled across in boats loaded with large gas
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Monika Gonzalez and the Associated Press
contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
