<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PEACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIANS AGREE TO DEAL ON KOSOVO, DOLE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Former senator Bob Dole declared Saturday that ethnic
Albanians will sign an agreement Sunday that would let them run
Kosovo, a development that would put immediate pressure on Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to accept NATO troops to police the
settlement or face possible airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference here at the US Embassy, Dole said he had
promises from all of the leading ethnic Albanian factions
represented at the peace talks near Paris last month that they
would sign the agreement Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Although those talks broke up inconclusively, Secretary of State
Madeleine K. Albright said the ethnic Albanians had agreed to the
settlement in principle but had insisted they could not sign it
until they consulted with supporters in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who has openly favored the ethnic Albanians in their
struggle for independence from the Milosevic regime, said the
Albanian delegation will sign the agreement Sunday in Pristina, the
capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The US point man in Kosovo, Christopher Hill, chief author of
the settlement, will travel to Pristina to preside over the
signing, Dole said. Hill appeared with Dole at the news conference,
but as is his wont was more circumspect, stopping just short of
saying he was sure the Albanians would sign.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even the cautious Hill was optimistic, especially after
Adem Demaci, the uncompromising political leader of the rebel
Kosovo Liberation Army, was pushed aside by Hashim Thaci, the
29-year-old KLA leader who emerged as the Albanian delegation's
leader at the peace talks in Rambouillet. Although he has helped
shape the KLA into a more dangerous insurgency, Thaci is considered
more pragmatic than Demaci.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, however, the KLA sent mixed signals Saturday. The KLA
commander Suleiman ``Commander Sultan'' Selimi told a crowd of
5,000 at a commemoration of a dead Albanian separatist that the
rebels would not accept a settlement without a guarantee of
independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``No half-measures will be acceptable to the KLA nor any
solutions whose goal is not independence,'' said Selimi, who is a
close friend of Thaci, who last week unseated the hard-liner Demaci
as the political leader of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, however, said he was sure the Albanians would sign Sunday.
``I think they'll keep their word. ... That puts the pressure on
the Serbs,'' said Dole, who was dispatched to the Balkans by the
Clinton administration to put pressure on the Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Dole is seen as so partisan toward the Albanians that Serb
authorities refused to give him a visa to enter Kosovo. Instead, he
met with Albanian leaders in neighboring Macedonia, where Hill is
the ambassador, and spoke with others by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said that if the Albanian negotiators sign the agreement
Sunday, he and other diplomats will turn their attention to getting
the Serbs to sign before the talks resume in Paris March 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the Serbs can be brought around,'' said Hill,
sounding uncharacteristically optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   US officials have hinted that special envoy Richard Holbrooke,
who in October got Milosevic to pull back his troops in Kosovo and
avert NATO airstrikes, might be dispatched to Belgrade to try to
persuade Milosevic to drop his opposition to NATO troops in Kosovo.
Last month, Milosevic refused to see Hill, apparently judging him
not important enough.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said he had briefed Albright on the developments Saturday
after she arrived here for talks with British Foreign Minister
Robin Cook. Albright and Cook were supposed to meet for an hour at
his country estate in Kent, but the talks went on for some three
hours, mainly on trade, with officials emerging to say more
detailed negotiations were needed between Washington and the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   American and British officials are locked in a dispute over a
trade war between the United States and the European Union over
bananas. Britain wants the United States to lift sanctions against
European imports, saying that at least 3,000 jobs in the cashmere,
cookie, and car battery industries are at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Dole was dispatched here by the Clinton administration to
pressure the ethnic Albanians to accept the deal, despite their
reservations about its lacking a guarantee of a referendum on
independence. Because some 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people
are ethnic Albanian, such a referendum would virtually guarantee a
vote for independence.
</P>
<P>
   But the six-nation Contact Group on the Balkans _ the United
States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy, and Russia _ does not
favor Kosovo's independence and knows the only way Milosevic will
agree to the deal is if Kosovo remains part of Serbia, which with
Montenegro forms what is left of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs have said they may consider Russian-led troops as part
of a peacekeeping operation in Kosovo. Russia has long been
Milosevic's only staunch ally.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said that while the Contact Group would consider a
diversified peacekeeping force, ``this is a package and a NATO-led
force is part of the package.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Albright, Hill, and Dole met here with NATO's top
official, General Wesley Clark.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
