<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT SEES WINNER'S TENT, BUT IT WILL TAKE SOME MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Greg Kraft showed how determined he is to win. Andy Bean
showed that at age 45, he can still hit terrific shots. Ernie Els
showed how great players remain in contention when they are not at
their best. And Glen Day showed he plans to follow a strong 1998
with an even stronger 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up an intriguing final round, despite some unexpected
names at the top, Kraft shot a resourceful two-under-par 70
Saturday and held a two-stroke lead after the third round of the
Doral-Ryder Open. Kraft stood at 11-under 205 for the tournament,
two strokes ahead of Els and Day and three strokes ahead of Bean
and Scott Dunlap, a rookie on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for a marquee name to emerge as the winner on
Sunday may be disappointed, unless Els or Justin Leonard
(seven-under-par 209) rises to the forefront. But those looking for
an unpredictable finish may get their wish. Kraft showed
resourcefulness, escaping with the two-stroke lead with which he
began the day by dodging trouble on numerous occasions. For Kraft,
who has never won an official event on tour, it was an important
test. But Sunday, the test will be even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious, of course,'' said Kraft, a 34-year-old native of
Clearwater, Fla. ``I have led going into the last round probably
three or four times, so I've had to deal with it. I love being
here. I don't have a sense of urgency. But I want to play well
tomorrow. I didn't play as well as I wanted today, but I'm looking
for a little magic tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Bean, although he hit some magical shots Saturday to keep
his hopes for a storybook victory alive. Bean has won at Doral
three times (1977, '82 and '86), but he has not won on tour since
1986. With a sizable gallery urging him on, he hit two shots that
he will long remember: a 70-foot bunker shot on No. 14 that he made
for a birdie, and, on No. 18, a tremendous 3-iron from 205 yards
away _ after his tee shot had hit the cart path and bounced into a
bunker lining the No. 1 fairway _ that helped him save par. It has
been a long time since Bean has entered a Sunday in contention, and
he was enjoying the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the better shots I have ever hit,'' Bean said
of the bunker shot at No. 18 on the Blue Course at Doral Golf
Resort and Spa, one of the toughest holes in golf. ``I had a lie
such that there was really no way I could pitch it out to the
fairway. I couldn't go straight or sideways, but I could see the
flag. I figured, `Well, I might as well.' I'd rather mess up
playing aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bean's shot landed on the green, the crowd roared, as the
ball skidded by the pin and stopped about 40 feet past. Then Bean
almost made his next putt for birdie, a feat that would have really
rocked the house. After gladly tapping in for par, Bean looked
forward to Sunday, and he was encouraged that the hard work he has
put into his game had begun to pay off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun out there, and it's a long time coming,'' said
Bean, who will turn 46 next month. ``I'm looking forward to teeing
it up tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   So was Els, but for different reasons. Because he is the star
attraction on the leader board, ranked No. 4 in the world and a
two-time U.S. Open winner, many expected Els to mount a charge
Saturday. He instead struggled to a two-under 70, including a 37 on
the front nine. Els went straight from the 18th hole to the driving
range, and he indicated later that he may have corrected a swing
flaw, which might help him Sunday. But he still wished he could
have had a second chance at Saturday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played like a guy who has never won a tournament,'' Els
said. ``I was the guy making mistakes. My experience helped,
scrambling, getting up and down, staying in contention. I didn't
play the way a guy who has won two U.S. Opens should play. But I
get another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Day, another player looking for his first tour victory, hoped to
capitalize on his chance as well. He shot a solid 67 Saturday, and
he looked like the player who had a career year in 1997, winning
more than $1.28 million to finish 26th on the tour's money list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stepped up a level last year, and I have to maintain that,''
Day said. ``I have a legitimate shot at the Ryder Cup team. I think
I need to win a couple of times to do that. It's up to me to show
that last year wasn't a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft knew that the tournament was far from over, and that on
Sunday someone else could emerge as the winner. But he liked his
position. ``I expect a guy like Ernie to make a charge,'' Kraft
said. ``I know someone is going to have a good round tomorrow, so
I'm going to have to have one myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
