<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HOPE PITCHERS SIMPLY DO THEIR JOBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ A Randy Johnson-Roger Clemens duel in late
September would have been something.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, however, barely missed out on signing Johnson, and
the Texas Rangers came within a whisker of trading for Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   So we'll have to settle for Chuck Finley vs. John Burkett, or
Ken Hill vs. Rick Helling with the AL West up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case in the division known for the Mo Vaughns, Juan
Gonzalezes and Ken Griffeys, not the Steve Sparkses or Mark Clarks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Angels won't hesitate to admit their strength is a
lineup that has Vaughn, Darin Erstad, Tim Salmon and Jim Edmonds
among others, they are not exactly whining about lacking quality
arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have choices,'' said new Angels pitching coach Dick Pole.
``We're not in a situation where we have to make a pitching staff
up. We've got guys competing for spots.... We've got people who
will !ital!compete &UR; !off! &LR; , and when you've got people who compete
like that, you have a good chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Pole, who served as pitching coach for the Boston Red Sox in
1998 and was the San Francisco Giants' pitching coach from 1993-97,
was speaking about pitchers like Finley and Tim Belcher. At ages 36
and 37, respectively, both are past their prime. But both are known
for battling deep into the game, keeping their team close and
eating up innings over the course of a season.
</P>
<P>
   Health is always an issue, and when it comes to the Angels, the
most important health question involves Hill's surgically repaired
right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   He missed 2{ months last year after having arthroscopic surgery
to remove bone chips, and wasn't at full strength when he returned
for the final month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Hill's the key,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``If
Ken Hill's arm is healthy, he will give us 200 innings, 200 quality
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why I don't worry about the bullpen. If the starters give
us what we anticipate they'll give us, the bullpen sets itself up.
They don't get overworked and stay in their roles.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case last year, when the starters completed only
three games. It took a toll on the bullpen late in the season.
Shigetoshi Hasegawa, counted on as a key set-up man this year,
pitched 971/3 innings last year, the most by a reliever in the
American League.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have Sparks penciled in as their No.4 starter, with
Omar Olivares, Jarrod Washburn and Jason Dickson in competition for
the fifth spot. Closer Troy Percival anchors the bullpen, and Rich
DeLucia joins Hasegawa as the primary set-up men. Mike Holtz will
be the situational lefty.
</P>
<P>
   Pole has his work cut out for him getting to know his pitchers,
but he has former pitching coach Marcel Lachemann, now the
organization's roving pitching instructor, helping with the
transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lach left a good legacy,'' Pole said. ``We think an awful lot
alike. He's been a big help, especially learning the personalities
of the pitchers. It's a good situation both ways. It's a learning
process from both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, also new to the team after signing a two-year, $10.2
million contract, said he likes what he sees in the Angels
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the old baseball adage says you never have enough
pitching,'' Belcher said. ``But I feel our pitching is as good if
not better than anybody in our division. It's equal to Texas, and I
think we have the edge in experience. They have (closer John)
Wetteland, we have Percival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle's got quality starters, but no Cy Young candidates.
Over the course of 162 games, I'll take our chances.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
