<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS MAKES DEBUT IN HIS FASHION, AND YANKEES LIKE HIS STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBA-COLUMN-CLEMENS) 
(js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Fla. _ Roger Clemens wore a Yankees uniform in a game
for the first time Saturday, and it felt normal to him. Everything
seemed as it should be, the pitcher said. Clemens was on a mound,
staring down hitters, under a scorching spring sun, in a Yankees
cap. ``There was nothing funny about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His final pitching line of this exhibition was a bit funny _ as
in odd. Kansas City scored three runs in three innings on seven
hits, most of them little loopers and slow rollers. But spring
training is for practice, not results, and Clemens felt he mostly
accomplished what he wanted to Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' he said. ``I felt really good. I don't feel
too winded.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, pounded in his first exhibition outing last year before
going on to win the Cy Young award, has had leg problems in spring
training in the past, and he worried that his first-game adrenaline
might push him to strain something. ``But I got through that with
my legs feeling strong,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his outing with the last of his four strikeouts,
whiffing Chad Kreuter with a split-fingered fastball in the dirt
and pumping a fist _ not in celebration, but as a compliment to
catcher Jorge Posada for calling the right pitch. Posada would say
later that Clemens sometimes yelled to him in support: ``That a
baby!''
</P>
<P>
   The traditional relationship between pitcher and catcher is like
that of horse and jockey. The catcher holds the reins, calls the
signals, guides the pitcher through the turns of each game,
hopefully to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens takes full control of each of his starts; the
catcher merely hangs on for the ride. Clemens calls all of his
pitches in the regular season, though how he does this is not
exactly clear _ maybe with a touch of his cap, his thigh, a brush
of his glove against his chest. One signal means he's throwing a
fastball, another a split-fingered fastball.
</P>
<P>
   This is very unusual, and perhaps only the best pitchers are in
a position to ask for that responsibility. Joe Girardi, the
Yankees' catcher, recalled that when he was with the Chicago Cubs,
Greg Maddux used to call his pitches from the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens gathers his intelligence on the Internet, looking for
information in baseball stories. Maybe a hitter will say he's
having trouble with the high fastball, or that he's struggling
against breaking balls. Clemens reads, absorbs, exploits. And he's
leery of counterintelligence: Darrin Fletcher, Toronto's catcher,
would flash three sets of signs at Clemens even when there were no
runners on second base _ just in case an enemy operative happened
to be spying from the bullpen, the stands or the press box in order
to relay information to the hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Even in spring training, Clemens approaches each start like a
military operation (Code name: VICTORY), everything timed to the
minute, always intense, devoted to the role of pitcher. Packing his
bag in the Yankees' Tampa clubhouse Saturday morning, Clemens'
wardrobe belied his Texas roots: black shoes, black shirt, blue
jeans and studded belt.
</P>
<P>
   His arrival at the Royals' complex was delayed slightly, because
Clemens, who drove with his wife rather than ride the team bus,
needed directions once he arrived at the park. He had to check with
the volunteers collecting $3 for parking. ``I'm Roger Clemens _
yeah, the pitcher _ and I need to know how to get to the Yankees'
clubhouse. ''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Powell, the strength and conditioning coordinator who
helped Clemens prepare for his outing Saturday, says he has never
seen anyone go through such a stringent pre-game routine.
``Nonstop,'' Powell said. ``He's a machine.''
</P>
<P>
   A machine, preset. Clemens went to the outfield to stretch at
11:25 a.m. He performed sprints and agility runs, each seemingly
designed to stretch a specific set of muscles, as well as leg lifts
and toe touches in rapid succession. Clemens is not fast, by any
means, but the power in his movement is omnipresent, Girardi
mentioned, like a Clydesdale. (David Cone, who once tried running
alongside Clemens, found the pace never waned and shortly had a
good view of Clemens' substantial backside moving off in the
distance.)
</P>
<P>
   Warming up in the bullpen, Clemens fretted aloud that he would
rush his delivery, perhaps injure himself; the pitching coach Mel
Stottlemyre says he has rarely worked with anyone who knows himself
as well as Clemens does. ``And it's an education for me,''
Stottlemyre said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Royals' Kevin Appier shut the Yankees out in the top
of the first, Clemens strode to the mound, and those fans who made
up the first sellout here in nine years noted his presence
immediately. Most cheered loudly, with some booing. In his 15th
major league season, Clemens is accustomed to playing the villain.
</P>
<P>
   When the Royals' leadoff hitter, Carlos Beltran, bounced
Clemens' second pitch of the game back to the mound, Clemens
barehanded the ball before throwing to first. The umpire Gary
Cederstrom flipped him a new ball, and Clemens barehanded that, as
well.
</P>
<P>
   But the Royals touched him for a run. Joe Randa dumped a bloop
single into short right field, taking second on a wild pitch,
before Jeff King whacked a belly-button-high pitch to left field,
for a clean single and a run batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who had trouble adjusting to the light slope of the
mound, threw strikes with 11 of his first 20 pitches, talking aloud
to himself after making mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   His four-seam fastball, he said later, had unusual movement,
darting away from the right-handed batters five or six inches.
``Jorge said it was running all over the place,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals chipped away for two more runs in the second inning,
the crucial hit an opposite-field blooper that hit the right-field
line. The Yankees trailed by 3-0 when he departed.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, it was the first time since last May that he was
listed as a losing pitcher. ``That was a lot of fun,'' Posada said.
``I was catching the best.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   After losing by 9-1 to the Royals here and by 7-4 to Boston in
Tampa, the Yankees are 1-3 in exhibition games. With the Yankees
splitting their roster for two exhibitions Saturday, the pitching
coach MEL STOTTLEMYRE &UR;  &LR; was the manager in the game here, while JOE
TORRE &UR;  &LR; managed against Boston. Stottlemyre smiled as he approached
reporters after the Kansas City defeat and said, ``What, am I
fired?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
