A0402 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-BELCHER-LA     03-06 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-BELCHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELCHER HAS STAYING POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Tim Belcher is a nice guy. Friendly, outgoing,
talkative, considerate. He's the kind of guy who would offer to do
the dishes after having dinner at your house.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't invite him over after he loses a game. Not if you
still want your china in one piece.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will pay Belcher $10.2 million during the next two
seasons, and hold a $5.1 million option for a third season. They're
not paying for him to break things, though that might happen after
a bad game.
</P>
<P>
   What the Angels are dishing out millions for is what Belcher has
provided six major-league teams over the course of an 11-year
career: innings. Lots of innings.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher is one of only four pitchers to have pitched at least
200 innings in every full season since 1991. Even last season at
age 36, Belcher made 34 starts, pitched 234 innings and went 14-14
for the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Durability, experience _ he's a quality veteran, he'll give
you 230 quality innings,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``In
my opinion, if we score runs like we should score, he's going to
win a lot of games. (begin ital)We'll(end ital) win a lot of
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher prides himself on being the guy who might struggle
early, but you look up in the eighth inning and he's still in the
game. He may not win every game, but at least his team has a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to pick a numbers goal, I don't mess around with
wins, strikeouts or ERA,'' Belcher said. ``I've seen so many guys
have a great year, but it doesn't show up in their record. For me
it's innings, and making my 34 or 35 starts. Pitch deep into games.
Decisions and innings work hand in hand. Pitch a lot of innings and
you'll get a lot of decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Belcher is 136-127 in a career that has had stops with the
Dodgers, Reds, White Sox, Tigers, Mariners and Royals. He's pitched
his innings, 2,0692/3 to be exact, but not all of them have been
good.
</P>
<P>
   That's when his temper might get the best of him.
</P>
<P>
   Once, after giving up a homer to lose a game for the Mariners at
Yankee Stadium, Belcher knocked a television camera out of the
cameraman's hands as he taped Belcher walking in the stadium tunnel
toward the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other incidents, though none of them were caught
on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher doesn't like that about himself, but he realizes it is
part of what makes him the pitcher he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who get to this level don't stay very long if they're
at all passive,'' Belcher said. ``It doesn't mean you have to be a
fly-off-the-handle, type-A personality, although I'm as close to
that as anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing to look at the tape and see what I've done.
I say to myself, `I'm an (expletive). Why'd I do that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   He does it because he hates to lose. And that's why the Angels
got him.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher, though, is not the same pitcher he was 10 years ago. He
doesn't throw as hard as he once did, but that doesn't mean he
can't get outs when he needs them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's less of a physical game for me now and more of a mental
game,'' he said. ``I still consider myself a power pitcher because
I still primarily throw fastballs. Only now I have three or four
variations _ a cut fastball, a two-seamer, up, down. Ten years ago,
I'd grab the ball by four seams, aim for the middle of the plate
and throw the hell out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At 37, Belcher is the graybeard of the pitching staff. His
experience can help younger pitchers, although he's not about to
force his wisdom down anybody's throat. But he might grab someone
by the throat if the situation calls for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel an obligation to be accessible to the guys,'' he said.
``As far as being vocal and grabbing a guy and saying `Come here
son,' I'll do that very rarely. It's gratifying if someone comes to
me and says `What about this?' It's a two-way street. If they want
my input, great.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are times when you take a young guy aside or you
grab him by the throat. Whatever it takes. If he disrespects the
game or our team, I might assert myself. I won't stand for that.
The longer I'm around the game, the more I respect the opportunity
to have played it. It's definitely a privilege.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
