<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTA-ANITA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE HOUSE MAKES CASE TO SUPPLANT SKIP AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KEN GURNICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The shuffling to replace the retired Skip Away
as the top older horse in the United States continued Saturday as
Free House captured the $1 million Santa Anita Handicap, outdueling
Event of the Year and his longtime rival Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think No. 1 is whoever won the last race,'' said Chris
McCarron, his jockey. ``Free House won the last race, so I guess
he's No. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   The California-bred Free House, owned by Trudy McCaffery and
John Toffan, dictated the pace and held on for a half-length
victory over Event of the Year, with Silver Charm another
half-length back. Free House ran the 1\ miles in 2:00 3/5 and paid
$10.20 on a $2 bet to win as the third choice in the six-horse
field. The $600,000 first-place purse gave him just over $3 million
in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero, coming off an impressive victory Jan. 30 over
Silver Charm in the Donn Handicap at Gulfstream Park, was fractious
in the paddock and finished a dull fifth, beaten by 10 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm's second consecutive third-place finish did nothing
to dispel notions that his best races are behind him, two years
after winning the Kentucky Derby and a year after a grueling
victory by a nose in the Dubai World Cup. He is the leading active
money winner, with $6.8 million. The trainer Bob Baffert, who
blamed his horse's outside post position as a factor in the Donn
loss, said this time that his horse was compromised by drawing the
rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The post position got him again,'' Baffert said of the
even-money favorite. ``He was trapped the whole way around.
Everybody expects him to win every time, but these were good horses
he was up against.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm broke alertly but fell back as Free House and Dr.
Fong ran one-two for the first mile. Event of the Year, the
Kentucky Derby favorite last year until fracturing a knee eight
days before the race, moved alongside the two leaders around the
far turn and Silver Charm followed on the outside. Those two were
slowly closing on Free House at the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wouldn't let them pass even when they galloped out,'' said
Paco Gonzalez, Free House's trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stevens, Silver Charm's jockey, offered no excuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's still not the Silver Charm I'm used to riding,'' said
Stevens, who was concerned with Silver Charm's lack of speed in the
Donn. ``Whether he's lost a step or not, I don't know. He's turned
into a bit of a plodder. He doesn't have the acceleration. He was
still coming at the end. Unfortunately, we just couldn't get there
soon enough.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron knew Stevens and Silver Charm were bottled up on the
rail behind him. He did all he could to keep them there.
</P>
<P>
   Although Free House had lost five of the seven previous meetings
with Silver Charm, Free House had beaten him in the 1997 Santa
Anita Derby. Free House's biggest victory was last year's $1
million Pacific Classic at Del Mar, which will be the final race in
this year's inaugural NTRA Champions Series.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
