<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKET ADDS NO FUEL TO FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVENPORT, Fla. _ Boston sports fans are still annoyed about
Roger Clemens wearing a Yankees uniform. As I was leaving the Hub
Friday night, I told the ticket agent I was on my way to see Roger
pitch and the Delta man said, ``Clemens? I hope he gets in a fight
with Latrell Sprewell.''
</P>
<P>
   There should be some glee in New England Sunday because Clemens
made his Yankee debut Saturday and was rocked for seven hits and
three runs in three laborious innings against the hideous Kansas
City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that spring training means nothing, but Bostonians
can get a chuckle from the image of George Steinbrenner back in New
York, listening to Saturday's broadcast and lunging for his red
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   My baseball people wanted to make this deal? What's wrong with
them. Fire Cashman! Fire Costanza!
</P>
<P>
   I am a Boston sportswriter. I no longer have my own stars to
cover. I live vicariously by watching former Boston stars on other
teams. And so while the Red Sox played spring training games in
Sarasota and Tampa, I was at Baseball City Stadium watching Roger
pitch for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Interstate 4, which connects Orlando and Tampa, was backed up
for several miles one hour before the game. Some of the traffic no
doubt was bound for Disney World, but there were many New York
plates in the parking lot at Baseball City. This was the first
Royals spring sellout since 1990, when the Red Sox played KC. Club
officials could not determine whether Clemens was on the mound for
that game.
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket was visible during batting practice, stretching and
hanging out in the left-field area. He stopped to chat with
legendary Kansas City groundskeeper George Toma, then ducked into
the dugout runway. He said he had no time to talk before the game.
Even in the relaxed setting of ``Baseball City,'' Roger has to put
on his game face.
</P>
<P>
   Under the watchful eye of pitching coach (and manager for the
day) Mel Stottlemyre, Clemens warmed up on the bullpen mound
outside the left-field foul line. Fans gathered on the grassy knoll
behind the fence, and no fewer than 15 photographers shot the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees went out in the top of the first (many scouts,
including Boston's Frank Malzone and Lee Thomas, were on hand to
see Kansas City's Kevin Appier and Jeff King), Clemens took the
hill and the phalanx of photographers went to the backstop to
record the moment. Jorge Posada was the Yankee catcher and umpire
Gary Cederstrom was behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Beltran led off and went out on a dribbler in front of
the plate. Joe Randa followed with a bloop single to right. Johnny
Damon flied to shallow center, but Randa took second on a wild
pitch and scored on a single to left by King (who would look good
in a Boston uniform). Jeff Conine reached on an infield single in
the hole, then Jeremy Giambi fanned on a 1-and-2 high heater.
Clemens threw 20 pitches in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Kreuter led off the second with a bloop double to left.
Clemens probably hadn't planned on pitching from the stretch so
much against the faceless, talent-starved Royals. Carlos Febles hit
one off the end of his bat for an RBI double to right. Then Rey
Sanchez hit a seeing-eye single up the middle and it was 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens finally got an out when Beltran grounded into a
fielder's choice. The Rocket got Randa on a fly to right, then
fanned Damon on a breaking ball to stop the bleeding. He was up to
41 pitches after two innings.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the third, Conine drilled a double off the wall
in left-center. Clemens struck out Giambi and Krueter to end his
first Yankee outing. He threw 58 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good,'' he said, before going on his traditional
post-spring-training-outing jog. ``I don't feel too winded. I was
glad to get the first one under way. It was nice. Jorge did a good
job blocking the plate. I had some forkers in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got in a little better focus in the third inning. Being in a
new environment, I have a tendency to want to do more and
overthrow. Mel reminded me, `Don't try and turn it loose yet.' It
was good. I didn't see and hear a whole lot today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rocket is comfortable in such a vacuum. He's at his best
when he tunes out his environment. Was he bothered by the hail of
hits and runs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``My location is what matters. I'd like
to be able to get ahead more. But I wasn't going to try to knock
the bats out of too many guys' hands.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed comfortable wearing that Yankee cap. It still looks to
me like seeing Michael Jordan in a Laker uniform. I asked him about
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty used to it,'' he said. ``Ever since the first
couple of days in camp. It's where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where he is. Roger Clemens is a Yankee now. Every day.
And back in Boston, we'll be watching his every move.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn and the Anaheim Angels open at home against the
Indians on Tuesday, April 6. I'll be in California to see Mo.
Better there than in Kansas City watching the boring Red Sox
against the boring Royals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
