<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' SHIPLEY RETIRES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -- With Gary DiSarcina recovering from a broken bone in
his left forearm, the Angels' shortstop situation took another
couple of twists and turns Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   First, veteran Craig Shipley decided he would retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the desire to play anymore, Shipley said from his
hotel room Saturday afternoon. ``I've been feeling this way for a
while. ... Everybody comes to that point sometime during their
career. It's tough to go out there every day when you don't want to
play.
</P>
<P>
   Shipley, 36, said he spoke with manager Terry Collins about his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understood,'' Shipley said. ``I've known him a long time.
I'm appreciative of everything he and the organization have done
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shipley, who paused several times and spoke softly during the
conversation, said he has no serious health issues and has had no
problems with anyone in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Sydney, Australia, Shipley will return home to Palm
Beach Gardens, Fla. to his wife and two children. He began his
major league career in 1986 with the Dodgers, played in 582 major
league games with five teams (Dodgers, Mets, Padres, Astros and
Angels) and hit .271 with 20 homers and 138 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys play with fire,'' Collins said. ``When the fire
starts to burn out, a lot of times they don't make the right
decision, but this kid did. I tip my hat to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly appreciate Craig's decision,'' general manager
Bill Bavasi said. ``I spoke with him (Saturday) morning about his
feelings and it was obvious he had given this a great deal of
thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels then called up shortstop Chuck Abbott from minor
league camp. Abbott will join the club in Tempe today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby (Fontaine, director of scouting and player personnel)
thought he was a guy we should look at,'' Bavasi said. ``With
DiSarcina getting hurt, I wish we would have brought him in at the
start. But he's in town and he's in shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, a second-round pick in 1996, hit .263 in 132 games last
season for double-A Midland.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels dropped their second Cactus League game in a row to
the Oakland A's, losing 8-7 at Phoenix Municipal Stadium Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had plenty of offense, as Tim Salmon, Phil Nevin and
Todd Greene each homered. But for the second day in a row, the
Angels pitching left something to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Petkovsek, in relief of starter Omar Olivares, gave up
back-to-back-to-back homers in the fifth inning to Ben Grieve, Matt
Stairs and Eric Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Olivares looked good in his first two innings of work, then
allowed three runs in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar threw the ball good until all of a sudden he walked a
couple guys,'' Collins said. ``But his ball had life and
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivares is competing with Jason Dickson and Jarrod Washburn for
the fifth spot in the starting rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Chuck Finley (stiff back) still has not been given the
go-ahead to pitch in a Cactus League game, though he continues to
throw during workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be another week before he's ready to let it loose,''
Collins said. ``I'm not going to let him out there until he's ready
to pitch, because as you know he's a maximum-effort guy. This guy
means too much to us to take a chance with him. One more week and
he'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Stankiewicz, competing for a job as a utility player,
looked good at second base Saturday. Stankiewicz, who also can play
shortstop, is vying for the spot against Jeff Huson and Luis
Rivera. One of them might be the starting shortstop on opening day
if Gary DiSarcina (broken bone in left forearm) is not ready. ...
The Angels play the A's again today (12:05), this time at Tempe
Diablo Stadium. Tim Belcher will start for Anaheim against
Oakland's Gil Heredia.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The SAN GABRIEL VALLEY TRIBUNE, WEST COVINA,
CALIFORNIA  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
