<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, March 7. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) Life is a war in which everyone suffers
losses. For most of us, the enemy is age or illness. Sometimes it's
accident. Sometimes _ too often in a city _ the opposition carries
guns. There are more casualties than there is newspaper space to
write about them, and no real reason to choose Derrek Wheaton's
story over any other _ except maybe for the unusual weather around
his mother's house. Here she is, living in the desert, with no rain
for months and hardly a cloud in the sky, but no sunshine. By E.J.
MONTINI Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
EPA (PHOENIX) It would have been difficult enough for Gov. Hull's
office just to decide how to dispose of more than 800 pounds of
potentially lethal chemicals and explosives left in a shed by a
``gun nut.'' But there was a lot more than explosive chemicals to
worry about. There were also some volatile political forces at
work. There were the New River residents, some concerned by rumors
spread on the Internet, who told Hull they distrusted the federal
government's claims that it could burn up the chemicals without
endangering the community. Less than three miles away there was the
massive 5,856-acre Anthem community, owned by the Del Webb Corp., a
powerful developer and a key Hull campaign contributor, that was
opening its doors for business. And there was a federal agency, the
Environmental Protection Agency, that was proposing to incinerate
the chemicals and evacuate some nearby residents in the very same
month _ March _ that thousands of Anthem buyers were to arrive for
the development's highly publicized grand opening. BY JEFF BARKER .
Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CHARTER package (undated) Flagstaff offers full-day kindergarten.
Mesa now enrolls pupils who turn five late in the year. Queen Creek
tossed aside its superintendent and is pumping more phonics into
the classroom. From the Navajo Nation to Nogales, public school
districts are taking extraordinary _ and some say long-overdue _
measures to keep students from defecting to Arizona's charter
school explosion. No longer are traditional public schools a
monopoly _ their charter-school siblings, who emerged nipping at
their heels in 1995. &QL; 
