<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODMAN HEAD GAMES WORK ON MALONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Karl Malone could willingly bring on repressed memory
syndrome, he'd certainly apply it to the barrage of distasteful
images that comprise his performance in the 1998 NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   If there are images that haunt the onetime NBA MVP, they
resemble a certain 6-foot-6 power forward with strange hair and a
red Bulls jersey. A reasonable facsimile will face Malone and his
Utah Jazz teammates this afternoon at the Delta Center.
</P>
<P>
   The jersey and hair color have changed, but Dennis Rodman's
defense, rebounding an uncanny ability to mess with Malone's head
are the same.
</P>
<P>
   In Games 1 through 4 of the '98 Finals, Rodman helped hold
Malone to 20 points a game _ seven below his average _ and by the
time Malone got untracked in Games 5 and 6 it was too late, and the
Bulls had beaten the Jazz for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman wasn't talking Saturday, but his Lakers teammates are
hopeful the Worm can provide the same voodoo when the teams meet
today. The Lakers, losers of six of their last seven against Utah,
will take whatever edge they can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does an excellent job getting into Karl's head,'' Kobe
Bryant said, ``but I'm sure Karl is getting used to it by now.
Hopefully, he's not. (Rodman's presence) can do nothing but help.''
</P>
<P>
   If not with head, then at least with body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis is able to bump him, be a little bit more physical with
him,'' Bryant said. ``He understands his game a lot more. He has
the footspeed to keep up with Karl and he can contest his shots as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Kurt Rambis said the Lakers' recent strides in defending
the pick-and-roll, Utah's preferred offense, will make more of a
difference than Rodman, who probably won't start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tape of every pick-and-roll they ran in the Finals,
and (Rodman) does do a good job,'' Rambis said. ``But it's not like
I put him on Karl and all my worries are over, because that's not
true. They were very successful in running it, and Chicago defended
it a whole bunch of different ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone will probably start out against Travis Knight and could
be defensed by Rodman, Elden Campbell, Shaquille O'Neal or Robert
Horry at various points in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be afraid to put them all in there,'' Rambis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Horry, who's drawn the assignment for most of the last two years
while playing out of position, said Rodman should be an
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to know you've got somebody who's just as strong as
Malone that can battle him for a significant amount of time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bench time: Horry didn't play Friday night and before that had
averaged just seven minutes a game for the last week because of
Rodman's arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fine. I'm just trying to stay in shape and just wait,''
Horry said. ``If it had been anybody else, I probably would have
been upset. But you got Dennis coming in, you're trying to get him
acclimated to the team, you just gotta be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, usually if I'm sitting on the bench, I'm in a
hurry to get in the game. But now I just wanna watch and learn.
This is a point in my career where I feel like I can learn more
just sitting on the bench. Plus, you know, save some trouble on
these old knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Bryant sprained his right wrist in a tumble to the
floor early in Friday's game against Seattle. He wore tape on the
wrist during Saturday's practice, but Bryant said the injury won't
affect his shooting. He made 8 of 15 shots against the Sonics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
