<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG12-KANSAS-KSTATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Kansas tops Kansas State to make final
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Only one of the top four seeds in the Big 12
tournament survived to reach today's championship game, which is no
big surprise to a league that had only one Top 25 team when the
week began.
</P>
<P>
   But the only top-four seed that remains alive is the team that
was supposed to be vulnerable for the first time since the
conference was formed.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Jayhawks will try to make it a perfect 3-for-3 in Big
12 tournament championship games after defeating Kansas State 69-58
in a semifinal matchup Saturday at Kemper Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Third-seeded Kansas (21-9) will play No. 5 Oklahoma State (22-9)
for the title today at 2 p.m. in a rematch of one of the best games
in the Big 12 regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks won 67-66 in overtime at Lawrence, Kan., two weeks
ago when Cowboys guard Adrian Peterson was whistled for a
controversial foul as Ryan Robertson tried a desperation 3-pointer
at the buzzer. Robertson made his first free-throw attempt to end a
great game on a sour note.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (OSU) game was a big win for us on Senior Night, but we
don't want to win games like that,'' said center Eric Chenowith,
who led the Jayhawks with 20 points and 11 rebounds Saturday. ``I
think they feel like they want to get us back. It will be a big
game for them because they want another shot at us.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Kansas State after losing twice to Kansas in the regular
season. The Wildcats (20-12) made a strong showing in the
conference tournament, but coach Tom Asbury believes their 7-9
conference record will doom their chances of an NCAA Tournament
berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had to win the (Big 12) tournament,'' Asbury said.
``The selection committee probably isn't going to leap-frog us over
a team with a better conference record. So we came here to win the
tournament and came up a little bit short.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 17,000 watched Kansas State battle back from a
eight-point deficit in the second half and take a 57-55 lead with
5:30 to go on a layup off an offensive rebound by Tony Kitt. But
the Jayhawks would outscore the Wildcats 14-1 the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome still was in doubt with 1:53 remaining when Kansas
led 63-58, but freshman point guard Jeff Boschee took control and
scored the last six points with a free throw, a driving turnaround
jumper in the lane and a 3-pointer, his fourth of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boschee made all the plays in the last two minutes,'' Asbury
said. ``It's not a whole lot more complicated than that. It was a
dead-even game and we had a chance to win, but Boschee made some
terrific plays when we lost him a couple of times. He made some
gutty shots.''
</P>
<P>
   A little too gutty as far as Jayhawks coach Roy Williams was
concerned. Williams loves his talented guard who was the Big 12
Freshman of the Year, but Boschee also frustrates Williams at
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is fearless, but he ran the wrong play, so he's also
clueless,'' Williams said. ``The next-to-last play (the driving
jumper), he screwed it up. I called one play and he ran another.
Four guys got it right and he got it wrong, but he ends up making
the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff's never afraid to make a play. He doesn't always make
them, but he isn't afraid to try.''
</P>
<P>
   K-State point guard Chris Griffin was amazed at some of the
running jumpers Boschee made en route to a 19-point effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got the best of me today,'' Griffin said. ``They set a lot
of good picks for him, and it's hard to get back to him because he
has such a quick release.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin and the other Kansas State starters admitted they were a
little tired while playing for the third time in three days. Asbury
used 11 players to try to keep fresh bodies on the floor, but the
Wildcats seemed to fade down the stretch. The team's top scorer,
guard Cortez Groves, came off the bench to score 12 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
