<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0627 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      03-06 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
The weary need rest, but when?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
VIERA, Fla. _ It's the four-letter word no manager wants to say and
no player wants to hear: R-E-S-T.
</P>
<P>
   The players acknowledge needing it but rarely want it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my way, I would never come out,'' said Astros first
baseman Jeff Bagwell, who has played a full 162 games three times
in his eight-year career.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a game, chances are Bagwell's name will be listed on
Larry Dierker's lineup card. Second baseman Craig Biggio will be
there, too. So will third baseman Ken Caminiti and right fielder
Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the foursome missed only 44 games last season, with
Bagwell and Caminiti accounting for 36 of those because of time
spent on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Various factors _ an increase in injuries, cross-country travel
and the non-stop, six-month grind _ make it impossible for players
to go the distance without an occasional day off.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker realizes his job gets tougher when it comes to the
delicate subject of when, and how often, to rest high-profile
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a believer the guys need all kinds of rest, but as you
get older you need some,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking I probably should rest them a little bit more
early in the season. I'll probably have to force myself to do it
because I know I'm going to get into an argument every time I do.''
</P>
<P>
   He's probably right. Do you expect Biggio, who has missed two
games since July 31, 1995, to stroll into the manager's office and
request a day off?
</P>
<P>
   The issue of finding an occasional breather for his regulars
will be one of Dierker's top priorities this season. Special
interest will be paid to Caminiti and Biggio, both at or
approaching their mid-30s.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, even after 1,539 games _ and three years spent
catching _ Biggio has never been on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older you get, you're going to have to take more off days
than normal,'' said Biggio, who in his 10th season hit a
career-high .325 and set a club record with 210 hits last year.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the games Biggio failed to play last season had nothing
to do with injury. His club-record streak of consecutive games
played was halted at 494 _ second at the time to Baltimore's Cal
Ripken Jr. _ when Dierker decided to keep Biggio out of the lineup
Aug. 5 at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Previously when the 33-year-old second baseman wasn't in the
lineup, Dierker had managed to get him into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something you take a lot of pride in,'' Biggio said.
``You still take a lot of pride in wanting to play every day.
You'll always be that way. To me, the goal this year is to start
158 games rather than 162.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's only a couple of games here and there. But it's a
couple of games off and that's a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring marks the first in several years that Caminiti, 35,
is coming back from offseason surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti missed 21 games in 1998 with a strained left quadriceps
and was bothered by a bad shoulder in San Diego's run to the World
Series. Upon arrival at spring training, he proclaimed himself in
the best condition in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already talked about it. If he wants to give me a day
off fine, so be it,'' said Caminiti, who hasn't played more than
146 games since 1991. ``It's his team. I'm just here trying to make
the team better.''
</P>
<P>
   When Caminiti isn't in the lineup, Bill Spiers will play third
base. Spiers also can spell relief for Biggio. Tim Bogar can play
every infield position, with most of his time expected to come at
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   When is the best time to take break? Dierker plans to choose his
spots carefully:
</P>
<P>
   According to most players, leaving a lopsided game a few innings
early is the next best thing to getting an entire day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they keep you in there too late,'' Biggio said. ``If
you can get some guys a few innings off in blowout games, that's
serious relief there. It's always tougher on the infielders than
anybody else, just from the standpoint you're bending over on every
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can get some guys a couple extra innings off here and
there, that's a huge, huge lift. It might not look like a big deal
in the box score, but it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Weekend games are especially tough. Most of the time, a Saturday
night game is followed by a 1:30 p.m. start on Sundays. Sometimes
it's a Friday-Saturday turnaround. Nationally or regionally
televised games start as early as 12:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play 12:35 games (following a night game) that really
beats you up,'' Biggio said.
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many breaks in the schedule. Most players favor
time off when a day game is followed by an off day. There are only
four such opportunities on the Astros' 1999 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Players prefer to find out in advance. Playing regularly becomes
a routine and players arrive at the park early to go through
pre-game batting practice and infield drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to give you a day off during the season, they
should tell you, `Don't come to the ballpark until game time,'''
Bagwell said. ``Guys come, take early hitting, hit batting practice
and take ground balls. They probably do more running around when
they're not playing. They're not getting a day off.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell isn't fond of days off, and with good reason.
</P>
<P>
   From 1993-95, he missed playing time when he fractured his left
hand on three separate occasions, though the 1994 injury happened
just a few days before the strike caused an early end to the
season.
</P>
<P>
   If not for missing 15 games during the second month of 1998 with
a laceration to his right knee, Bagwell would have played in close
to 160 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been injured and I know what it's like not to play,''
said Bagwell, who has two streaks of 300 or more games played. ``I
just want to play as much as I can because I never know when it's
going to end.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue becomes a problem late in the season. Then, it's almost
impossible for a manager whose team is in contention not to go with
his regular lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, with the division title already in hand, the Astros
played a brutal schedule of four games in the three days, including
a doubleheader that followed a series-opening afternoon game that
went 13 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the games in that series with the New York Mets went
extra innings. The Astros lost all but one and finished the season
a sluggish 6-7.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros carried a heavy workload, leading the league with
1,471 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (Mets) series was a backbreaker,'' Biggio said. ``That
just kicked our butt right there. Physically that hurt us, but that
didn't hurt us in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou stayed healthy last season and played 159 games, a
career high. But after a strong and consistent three-fourths of a
season, Alou failed to add to his 38-homer total after Aug. 24 _ a
span of 30 games _ and collected just six of his 124 RBIs during
the final month.
</P>
<P>
   Alou's late-season slowdown lingered into the postseason, where
he went 3-for-16.
</P>
<P>
   The reason?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I am tired,'' Alou said before Game 3 of the divisional
playoffs with San Diego ``That's one of those things that every-day
players find it hard to admit. That's something my dad (Expos
manager Felipe Alou ) was good about when I played for him in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   I used to get mad at him when he gave me a few days, but in the
long run, you're probably better off.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said, ``There are two ways to look at it: You're going
to rest somebody and they don't like to hear that. But the other
guys need some playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   When one of those occasions comes up, don't expect the players
to like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be the opinion around baseball that guys need days
off,'' Bagwell said. ``I don't know. I don't think if you give me a
day off in April or May or June that's going to help me throughout
the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
