<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0628 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS &LR;      03-06 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Kraft leads way, but all eyes on Els
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIAMI _ When people talk about golf greatness, they use adjectives
like ``Tigeresque'' or ``Duvalian.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``Elslike'' will make it into the game's thesaurus by the
end of play today at the Doral-Ryder Open.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Who's No. 1?'' debate between Tiger Woods and David Duval
could be a three-way discussion if Els can hammer out another
victory today, which would be his second in his first three weeks
of PGA Tour action in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be easy for the low-key South African, who trails
leader Greg Kraft by two shots going into the final round.
</P>
<P>
   Els said he dodged a bullet Saturday, playing subpar but not
falling any further behind Kraft than when the day started. Both
players shot 2-under-par 70s, leaving Kraft at 11-under 205 for the
tournament and Els at 207, tied with Glen Day.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Els is lurking, ready to pounce on a leader
board that is slightly less than star-studded. But he added he
didn't play like a man who feels like the one to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I should have felt,'' he said. ``But the way I
was playing, it's like I was the one who's never won a tournament.
I didn't play the way a guy who has won two U.S. Opens should
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was inexperience or simply off days, nobody was able
to put much space between themselves and Els on a day when he could
have been pushed back into the pack if Kraft or Day or somebody
else had gotten hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather conditions in the afternoon were perfect,'' Els
said. ``But nobody made a move and I feel kind of fortunate playing
kind of poorly and hanging in there. I'm still in the tournament.
So I feel I have a good chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft likes his chances, too.
</P>
<P>
   But a history of blown opportunities clearly haunts the Doral
leader. The eighth-year pro from Clearwater, Fla., has never won on
Tour, although he did win the 1993 Deposit Guaranty Classic when it
was an unofficial event in Hattiesburg, Miss. Kraft has led going
into the final day three times on Tour. He had no trouble reciting
when and where he has stumbled at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was '93 at New Orleans, '94 at the Western Open and '96 in
the Deposit Guaranty,'' Kraft said.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost like those moments in history are engraved on his
brain, ready to be fired off in rapid fashion whenever anybody
asks. He rattled them off faster than most people list their kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm anxious, of course,'' he said. ``But it's not the first
time I've had to deal with it (leading with 18 holes left).''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft also said he expects good things today _ from his
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect a guy like Ernie to make a charge,'' Kraft said. ``He
has been playing well all year. And I'm good friends with Andy
(Bean). He's been working very hard on his game, and I hope he has
a great day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean is at 8-under 208 after a 69 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Els who everybody is targeting as the main man today.
He birdied two of the last three holes, including the dreaded 18th
at Doral's Blue Monster, to stay poised for a run during the final
round.
</P>
<P>
   Should a victory come about for Els, it might behoove Woods and
Duval to make a little room for Els in talk about who the sport's
top gun is, if they haven't already. Els won at Los Angeles two
weeks ago, but lost in the first round of the Andersen Consulting
Match Play Championship. He said Saturday if he had gone past the
first round, he probably would not have played Doral.
</P>
<P>
   But now Els is threatening to win for the third time this year.
He captured the South African PGA in January.
</P>
<P>
   Another win might force Els into the same level as Woods and
Duval, although it's a level Els says he hasn't reached yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a better record than I do right now, and that's
the bottom line,'' Els said. ``I know I'm up there pretty high
already. But they (Duval and Woods) will still be the guys people
talk about next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but Els has two major championships and seven Tour
wins. That stacks up nicely against Woods' eight titles and one
major and Duval's nine wins and no majors.
</P>
<P>
   First things first, however.
</P>
<P>
   Els will have to run down Kraft, who has had only one bogey over
the past 27 holes. That came on the par-4 14th Saturday when he
knocked his approach over the green and couldn't get up and down.
He also made a solid par on the 18th to close out his round.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important, I think, to finish out your round strong
because the last thing you want to do is leave a sour taste in your
mouth,'' Kraft said. ``I struggled early in the round, but it was
nice to get it together and hit two quality shots on the last hole
and get out of there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want to do is stumble on No. 18. It's a
hole that I couldn't have won the tournament on today, but I could
have lost it, maybe, if I'd stumbled.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, any stumbling will be done today.
</P>
<P>
   And it might be Els giving him a nudge in the back along the
way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
