<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLES WASTE 3-GOAL LEAD AS FLYERS RALLY FOR TIE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Eric Lindros, the Flyers' hulking center, watched
like a predator as the Islanders' defense weakened in the game's
final minutes. And when the time was right, Lindros saw his chance
and seized it.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders had taken a three-goal lead late into the third
period Saturday. But the Flyers' rally started with 3 minutes 6
seconds left as Philadelphia scored once, then again. And with less
than a minute remaining, Lindros used his enormous body to steal a
point for his team. He barreled over two Islanders on his way to
the goal, where he swatted the puck away from Islanders goalie
Tommy Salo and stuffed it into the net with 51 seconds left,
completing Philadelphia's stunning comeback to earn a 3-3 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros' 37th goal, in front of a sellout of 19,649 at the First
Union Center, was allowed to stand after a video review. The point
snapped the Flyers' five-game losing streak, while the Islanders'
streak without a victory in Philadelphia reached six games, dating
to Nov. 4, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers (30-19-14), who also got goals from Dave Babych and
Valery Zelepukin in the final 3:06, then had several chances to win
before time expired. The best attempt, a backhander by Keith Jones,
trickled just wide of Salo, who faced 28 shots, 15 in the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that Lindros inflicted the damage with the
Islanders' top two defensemen on the bench. Kenny Jonsson missed
most of the game with a headache after getting an elbow to his face
from John LeClair late in the first period. Rich Pilon, a Lindros
nemesis, left the game with about four minutes left with a strained
back, also caused by a run-in with LeClair.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the injuries to Jonsson and Pilon, the Islanders had
the rookie Eric Brewer and the journeyman David Harlock on the ice
when Lindros muscled his way to the net and scored the game-tying
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to take it around the front of the net and slam
it home,'' Lindros said. ``It popped loose while I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   But that was not how Salo saw the play unfold. He complained to
Referee Dennis LaRue that Lindros had violated his crease, and that
he had already frozen the puck between his arm and his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had it right under my arm,'' said Salo, who was taunted by
the cheering fans after the Flyers had tied the score. ``And he
whacked it out. But when you're up, 3-0, with three minutes left,
you shouldn't lose a point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two guys right there,'' Islanders Coach Bill Stewart
said of Sergei Nemchinov and Mark Lawrence, both draped over the
6-foot-4-inch, 238-pound Lindros as he scored the game-tying goal.
``You don't take the body on a guy like that. You take away his
stick.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart added, ``Maybe if we had a $40 million payroll, we
wouldn't be talking right now.'' For the Islanders (19-37-8), it
was one of their most embarrassing collapses of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Islanders played down the injury to Jonsson,
who missed a month earlier this season with post-concussion
syndrome. Jonsson, who left the game after receiving a stiff check
from LeClair behind the goal, will be examined in New York on
Sunday, and his status for that afternoon's home game against the
Devils is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm feeling better,'' Jonsson said after the game. ``I had a
headache right away; they had a little concern about it. They
wanted to be cautious with me. I wanted to go out and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilon's toughness was surely missed. The rugged defenseman had
done a fine job on Lindros and LeClair before twisting his back
trying to hit LeClair and leaving the game. He is also questionable
for the Devils game.
</P>
<P>
   After a scoreless first period, the Islanders took a 1-0 lead on
a power-play goal by Zigmund Palffy at 1:53 of the second period.
It was his third goal in two games. Lawrence scored at 10:02 of the
third period, and Bryan Smolinski scored at 12:58 to stretch the
Islanders' lead to 3-0. It wouldn't last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody on the bench was screaming that we shouldn't die,''
Lindros said. ``We knew that we could get something out of this if
we just kept coming at them.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
