<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA PUTS THE HURT ON UCLA 
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ They did not blame the officials. They did not blame
injuries. The UCLA Bruins blamed no one and nothing but themselves
for this debacle, since the answer was as clear as the desert sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no mystery to this, it was a good, old-fashioned
fanny-whooping,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said after an 87-70 loss
to Arizona on Saturday, before 14,545 at McKale Center. ``They were
tougher. They were smarter. They beat us in every phase of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Always the spin-meister, Lavin then said the Bruins' performance
``could not have come at a better time,'' because it will create a
sense of urgency with the NCAA Tournament beginning this week.
</P>
<P>
   He's right on one count: UCLA (22-8, 12-6) has played some of
its best games immediately following defeats. But a performance
this bad this late in the season could just as easily portend an
early tournament exit, especially with star guard Baron Davis
hobbling on an injured toe.
</P>
<P>
   Davis sprained the middle toe on his right foot in the final
minute of Thursday's victory at Arizona State. On Saturday, with
two minutes left and the Bruins trailing by 20, he aggravated it
and needed help leaving the court. X-rays were negative, and
afterward, Davis seemed resigned to playing in pain in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse,'' said Davis, who scored 21 points and played most
of the second half with four fouls.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bruins had plenty of other problems, beginning with
their half-court offense _ or lack thereof. They shot 38 percent
from the field, set a handful of screens and actually executed
their plan a few times.
</P>
<P>
   Like Arizona State, the Wildcats pressured the perimeter passing
lanes, making it difficult for UCLA to rotate the ball from one
side to the other. The Bruins' structure quickly broke down,
leaving behind the same wild shots and one-on-one play that
dominated their attack two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put up too many 3s,'' forward JaRon Rush said. ``We weren't
patient enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona forward Gene Edgerson's critique was not as kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played scatterball, playground ball,'' Edgerson said.
``You don't win in the tournament with that kind of ball. You'd be
lucky to win the first-round game.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's offensive problems started inside, where skinny forward
Jerome Moiso was helpless against Arizona's big men. They moved him
out of the low post and used well-honed techniques to lure him into
foul trouble. Moiso wanted no part of the rough stuff, scoring four
points and grabbing three rebounds in 21 minutes. Without center
Dan Gadzuric, numbers like that will mean doom in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to deny me everything, and they did it well,''
Moiso said. ``We did not respond to adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso had no help. After playing well in three previous games
without Gadzuric, the trio of Sean Farnham, Travis Reed and Matt
Barnes combined for two baskets and five rebounds. The Bruins had
no low-post presence, no consistent interior attack, and Arizona
feasted _ outrebounding UCLA 46-31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked before the game,'' Lavin said. ``I told them if we
got outrebounded, there was no way we could win.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona guard Jason Terry led all scorers with 26 points in his
final home game. Immaculately prepared, Arizona shot 53 percent in
the first half and built a 52-36 lead, dominating as UCLA did in
the Pauley Pavilion meeting two months ago. Back then, the Wildcats
righted themselves and made a late-game charge.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, the Bruins had no such mettle, wasting several chances
midway through the second half with bad shots and spotty 3-point
defense. The lopsided outcome was reminiscent of UCLA's Senior Day
visit here in 1993, when it lost 99-80.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to regroup and get ready for (the
tournament),'' Reed said. ``If we don't regroup fast, it'll be over
in a heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Guard Ray Young played only a few seconds because of a
hip pointer suffered at Arizona State, but he expects to be ready
for the tournament. Guard Brandon Loyd did not play because of a
bruised right (shooting) hand.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was named to the coaches' All-Conference team but did not
win Player of the Year; that honor went to Terry. JaRon Rush and
Gadzuric were selected to the All-Freshman team. Arizona's Michael
Wright was named Freshman of the Year. Stanford's Mike Montgomery
was selected Coach of the Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 2251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
