r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-06 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM LOSING HIS LUSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ This time, like last time, Silver Charm's problem was
his starting spot, in the spur-of-the-moment opinion of his
trainer. Too far from the rail when he ran third in the Donn
Handicap in Florida, too !ital!close!off! to the rail when he ran
third in Saturday's Santa Anita Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The post position got him again,'' Bob Baffert said down at
trackside moments after the horses crossed the wire. Hemmed in
behind Free House, the eventual winner, and Dr Fong, a 20-1 shot,
``he had no place to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame Baffert if he strains for excuses after Silver
Charm records the worst back-to-back finishes of his career?
</P>
<P>
   It was this colt, by coming within a New York split-second of
sweeping the Triple Crown two years ago, who turned Baffert into
his sport's two-footed star, his prematurely white mop of hair
recognized even beyond the racetrack gates.
</P>
<P>
   In January, when Baffert was in Miami during Super Bowl week,
racing publicists took him to the football press room one day, and
the radio talk-show boys lined up to interview him. A horse
trainer!
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm did that for him, a feat of magic for which the
wise-cracking Baffert is just introspective enough to be grateful.
</P>
<P>
   Given their history, it must be hard for Baffert to admit Silver
Charm's magic is gone.
</P>
<P>
   So instead Baffert said: ``He was trapped all the way around
there. That's why I hate the 1 hole (post position).''
</P>
<P>
   Too far inside? Too far outside? The truth lies somewhere in
between.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that even if the 62nd Santa Anita Handicap didn't
tell us who's the No. 1 older thoroughbred in America, it did tell
us who's not.
</P>
<P>
   After beginning the season as his species' undisputed leader,
Silver Charm has some catching up to do now. The 5-year-old gray
horse ain't what he used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was closing at the end,'' said his jockey, Gary Stevens.
``But he's still not the Silver Charm I'm used to riding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Silver Charm that Stevens is used to riding is the one who
ranks third all-time in earnings with $6.8 million and this month
was listed by a Blood-Horse magazine panel as No. 63 among the
century's hundreds of thousands of racing thoroughbreds.
</P>
<P>
   And mind you, there's not a big difference between greatness and
a third-place finish in the deepest Big 'Cap in memory. Silver
Charm finished only a length behind Free House and half a length
behind runner-up Event of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, in a race that close, drawing a bad post position could
have made the difference. But so could losing a step.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens said during the week that given the strength of the
six-horse field, Silver Charm would ``have to run the best race of
his life to win.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. And you could see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida's Gulfstream Park, Stevens and Silver Charm, breaking
from post 12, had dropped nine lengths behind the leaders to avoid
being swept wide in the clubhouse turn. It proved to be too much
ground to make up and they finished five behind winner Puerto
Madero.
</P>
<P>
   Since Silver Charm had to rally from far back to win his
season-opening race at Santa Anita, handicappers wondered if he'd
simply lost his early speed, a dangerous trend if true.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of fast workouts, designed to drill the speed
back into him, Silver Charm raced close to one of the slowest Big
'Cap paces in decades. With one-quarter mile to go in the 1\-mile
race, he was sitting fourth, tucked in behind Free House, Dr Fong
and inside Event of the Year. Puerto Madero, not himself Saturday,
was safely back in fifth.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the stretch, Silver Charm swung into a clear path
and fixed his sights on the leaders. Stevens went to the whip. But
in the final 440 yards, covered in an ordinary 25.21 seconds, they
made up only a little more than one length. They never looked like
the winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not disappointed by his effort,'' Stevens said. ``I don't
think they can say, `He ran another bad race.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, none of his opponents would say anything so
disrespectful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver Charm has been one of the best horses in North America
for the last couple of years. You can't knock his record,'' said
John Toffan, who, with Trudy McCaffery, owns Free House, a loser of
four in a row to Silver Charm before Saturday. ``If you beat Silver
Charm, you've got a pretty good horse.''
</P>
<P>
   When Silver Charm inched closer in the stretch, Toffan admits he
thought, ``Here we go again.''
</P>
<P>
   He was thinking of the Silver Charm of the Derby, the Preakness
and the Goodwood Handicap last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember,'' McCaffery said, ``Silver Charm's
danced a lot of dances. If he's just got a little tired, I can't
say I blame him. But I don't think we've seen the end of Silver
Charm.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll find out soon enough. Retirement is not in the plans. He
could try to defend his title at the March 28 Dubai World Cup. The
``NTRA Champions on Fox'' series, of which the Big 'Cap was the
second leg, also is laid out before him, even if it's no longer his
for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   What Silver Charm needs is a big victory to restore his
reputation. That or a fresh excuse. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-06-99 2302EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
