u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GARBAGE-DISCRIMINA     03-06 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GARBAGE-DISCRIMINATE-310&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARBAGE TRANSFER STATIONS FACE CIVIL RIGHTS INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The federal government will conduct a broad civil
rights investigation into a Bronx congressman's allegations that
the concentration of dozens of garbage transfer stations in the
South Bronx discriminates against minority residents, federal
officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The formal inquiry is the first of its kind in New York state
and one of a handful of environmental justice investigations the
government has launched nationwide, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It will seek to determine whether dozens of garbage transfer
stations, and the hundreds of trucks that feed them, have spawned
widespread respiratory and other health problems that violate the
civil rights of South Bronx residents, the vast majority of whom
are black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   If the government concludes that the stations are in violation,
it could cost New York City ``tens of millions'' a year in federal
aid, U.S. Environmental Protection Agency officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obviously very serious,'' Jeanne Fox, the EPA regional
administrator for several states including New York, said at a
conference in New York City among federal officials and
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about, `Was a group discriminated against in an
environmental manner?' '' Ms. Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will be led by officials from the EPA and two
investigators from the U.S.Justice Department: Bill Lan Lee, the
agency's chief civil rights investigator, and Lois J. Schiffer, an
assistant attorney general in the environment and natural resources
division.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to launch the investigation follows a monthslong
campaign by U.S. Rep. Jose E. Serrano, a Democrat from the Bronx,
to call attention to the high concentration of garbage transfer
stations in the Hunts Point, Mott Haven and Port Morris
neighborhoods, which form the heart of his 16th Congressional
District.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In December, Serrano filed a formal request with the EPA, asking
the agency to look into whether the approximately 35 garbage
transfer stations in those communities, which have more than 95
percent black or Hispanic residents, have affected the health of
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The 35 transfer stations handle about half of the city's
commercial waste, Serrano said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was announced late Saturday afternoon by
Bradley Campbell, of the White House's Council on Environmental
Quality, after an eight-hour conference among about 100 people,
including officials from several federal agencies and
representatives from city and regional environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the officials toured the South Bronx and parts of
Brooklyn, which have large concentrations of garbage transfer
stations.
</P>
<P>
   After Campbell outlined the scope of the inquiry, a spokesman
for Serrano, Luis Torres, said, ``That's all the congressman
wanted, a serious investigation into the siting of these
facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone late Saturday, Joseph J. Lhota, the deputy
mayor for operations, said that he had not been aware of the
inquiry but added that the city would cooperate with federal
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigation is to begin before the end of
September, Ms. Fox said, and is expected to take a few months to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Though it opens a new chapter of federal efforts to evaluate
environmental justice claims in New York state, Ms. Fox said the
investigation follows similar inquiries in Louisiana, Michigan and
other states.
</P>
<P>
   The South Bronx transfer stations, most of which are privately
owned but licensed by the city and state, serve as temporary
collection bins for a good portion of the 13,000 tons of garbage
that New York City generates and sends to landfills every day.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them operate in residential neighborhoods, EPA officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   To bear out Serrano's civil rights claims, federal investigators
would have to conclude that the stations have an adverse effect on
his constituency's collective health, officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   They also would have to find that the adverse effects, whether
intentional or not, disproportionately affect members of minority
communities.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the federal investigation will be a search for clues
that suggest a causal link between the transfer stations and
asthma, respiratory infections and other illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But measuring the effects of legions of garbage trucks or
polluted runoff from the stations will not be easy, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The waste-transfer issue is difficult because we don't have a
full understanding of their impact,'' Bonnie Bellow, an EPA
spokeswoman, said at Saturday's conference. ``This is kind of new
territory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
