<DOCNO> NYT19990306.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0636 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-AZR &LR;      03-06 2208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARTER SCHOOLS SHOW NO SIGN OF SLOWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY PEARCE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Flagstaff offers full-day kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa now enrolls pupils who turn five late in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Creek tossed aside its superintendent and is pumping more
phonics into the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   From the Navajo Nation to Nogales, public school districts are
taking extraordinary _ and some say long-overdue _ measures to keep
students from defecting to Arizona's charter school explosion.
</P>
<P>
   No longer are traditional public schools a monopoly _ their
charter-school siblings, who emerged nipping at their heels in
1995, charter law passed 94 are now major players in Arizona
education.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one quarter of all the nation's charter schools are in
Arizona, where 270 charters serve about 30,000 students. Four years
ago, some 50 charters in Arizona housed 7,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   Public school districts are still way ahead, enrolling 750,000.
Both charter schools and district schools are free to students and
get an average of $4,800 in state aid for each student in their
desks.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the state, schools superintendents and boards are
changing programs in response to the new competition. In Mesa last
year, the district went so far as to advertise for students and
promote its full plate of educational fare.
</P>
<P>
   Many are spicing up their curricula to try to match the
enticements of charter schools, which often offer a focused diet of
arts, technology or back-to-basics entrees catering to niche
children, a category that includes both gifted kids and academic
strugglers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to survive, we had to quit our whining and do a
better job ourselves,'' said Kent Matheson, former superintendent
of Flagstaff Public Schools, who launched a variety of programs in
his district to dazzle students bent on leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it's too early to tag an ``A'' or an ``F'' on the
charter school revolution. There isn't a lot of information
available to compare _ head-to-head _ the academic performance of
charters and districts.
</P>
<P>
   Only two years of wide-ranging, consistent standardized test
scores are available, and Arizona's Instrument to Measure Standards
won't begin until this spring. Much of the evidence at this point
is anecdotal.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, a growing number of parents are choosing
charters.
</P>
<P>
   And in no other city in the state are charters more concentrated
than in Mesa, home to Arizona's largest school district, with
70,000 students. About 50 charter schools have taken up residence.
</P>
<P>
   At least two national studies have put Mesa under a microscope,
deeming it the perfect place to take a hard look at the impact _
both good and bad _ of charter schools on districts.
</P>
<P>
   Critics rail against the burgeoning charter school system,
saying it is mushrooming out of control without enough
accountability. Most charters aren't accredited, some employ
noncertified teachers, and most inhabit such places as strip malls,
churches and apartment complexes.
</P>
<P>
   Those critics assert that districts do a better job than
charters, offering something for all students, including sports and
other extracurricular activities that most charters don't offer.
And stricter regulations govern districts.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mary Hartley, D-northwest Phoenix, said she hasn't seen any
charters that are doing anything that isn't already being done in
districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not the incubators of education reform that they
promised to be,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates cite a list of pluses: smaller classes, one-on-one
attention, the perception of safer campuses, and more access to
educators and administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charters seem to be more influenced by what we want,'' said
Karla Freeman, who lives next door to a Mesa district school under
construction but sends her boy to Life Elementary School, a charter
in Mesa. ``There's an intimacy here. That in itself would keep me
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Many educators say charters are spurring districts to offer more
specialized programs and to pay closer heed to parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charter schools make us look at ourselves and see what we can
do better,'' said Robert Meko, principal of Mendoza Elementary
School, an arts-based Mesa district school with a new
early-kindergarten program.
</P>
<P>
   Charters have their fair share of problems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, youth at the Arizona Career and Technology High School
in Mesa were left out in the cold when the school folded amid
allegations of financial mismanagement by the operator, who had
once served time in jail on a drug charge. The problems escalated
because the charter holder, the Window Rock Unified School
District, was too far away to keep an eye on the school.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the founder of another charter, Citizen 2000, was
accused of spending more than $100,000 in state money to buy a
Biltmore-area home for her mother and jewelry for herself. The
school closed and went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   One reason charters are gaining popularity is that many burrow
into niches. They may target at-risk students, those who want to
acquire vocational skills, pupils who want to quicken their pace to
college, or those interested in honing artistic talents.
</P>
<P>
   Charter-school director Mike Matwick uses computer-based
learning at the Arizona Career Academy in Mesa to reach the
previously unreachable: teen parents, law breakers, high school
dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Gaddie family has removed the frills from education and
returned to basics to hammer knowledge into students at Noah
Webster Basic School.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Alverson, director of several Mesa charters, hopes to open a
series of neighborhood charter schools that mirror districts'
programs without the overwhelming, overcrowded feel of many
district schools.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the far reaches of the country are taking note
of Arizona's charter school phenomenon. A handful of academic
research projects and national newspaper stories are focused on
Arizona and the dynamic between districts and charters.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the comments are glowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a lot of chaos, a lot of confusion and a lot of
controversy, but I also saw (Arizona) districts that were
responding,'' said Eric Rofes, author of a national study of
charter schools' impact on school districts.
</P>
<P>
   Another still-to-be-published study focused primarily on
Arizona, discovered that although changes are being made within the
traditional system, many are cosmetic and fail to change the core
of public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found cheap, easy-to-do, cute solutions,'' said Rick Hess,
one of the four authors of the federally funded research project by
the nonpartisan Bodman Foundation in New York. ``But what we really
didn't see is the heavy-lifting'' or changes that tried to raise
the academic bar.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of state superintendents by University of Arizona
researchers reflects an even dimmer view of the effect of charters.
</P>
<P>
   About 57.5 percent of administrators polled said charter schools
cannot improve public education, while only 25 percent thought they
could. Fifty percent stated their districts have not been hurt by
or benefited from charter schools. &QL; 
No sharing system &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is no system in place for charters to share creativity
with districts, the superintendents agreed. And charters aren't
clamoring to do it on their own. In fact, some refuse to talk to
districts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many school districts are reacting.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Mulholland, a researcher with Arizona State University's
Morrison Institute for Public Policy, said: ``People rarely like to
admit when something has caused them to change.''
</P>
<P>
   A study she wrote for the state Department of Education
evaluating the progress of charter schools will be released later
this month. She is working with national researchers to look at the
impact charter schools are having on Arizona districts.
</P>
<P>
   Mulholland, like others before her, has keyed in on Mesa to show
that districts are battling with charters to keep students in their
desks.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between public schools and charters in Arizona
has followed an interesting course.
</P>
<P>
   When charters arrived on the scene, districts spread horror
stories about them, asserting that far-out institutions, such as
witchcraft schools, would spring up. They spun tales of doom about
a movement they thought would sputter and choke, several district
educators across the state have said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't, especially in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996-97 school year, about 900 of the Mesa district's
70,000 students transferred to charters. All 70 schools in this
suburban district, already a school-reform leader in the state,
lost at least one student.
</P>
<P>
   The district began listening more closely to parents' wishes.
Coincidentally or not, it opened a third back-to-basics school _
with a fourth slated to open this fall _ and began a
first-of-its-kind enrichment program for home-schoolers. It also
lent several of its teachers to an arts-based charter school and
converted its Montessori program into charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   The district made national headlines when it began advertising
for students. It also started promoting its cutting-edge programs,
including an elementary school transformed into an arts magnet the
year charter schools were written into the law. Mesa's Highland
Elementary School principal uses a glossy brochure and artsy video
to sell his wares.
</P>
<P>
   Teacher Dixie Parrish is convinced she wouldn't enjoy so much
freedom if it weren't for the competitive atmosphere. On one Friday
last fall, students tie-dyed shirts in one classroom and made
candles in another.
</P>
<P>
   By so reacting, it's as if many districts are reminding parents
that they offer good programs too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like looking at your wife and seeing someone
flirt with her. You ask yourself if you've told her you love her
enough times,'' explained Meko of Mendoza Elementary in Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   The effects charter schools are having on traditional public
schools are not unique to Mesa. Take a look.
</P>
<P>
   Queen Creek, a rural district in the east Phoenix area that lost
one-third of its elementary-school students in fall 1996 to the Ben
Franklin Charter School, hired a new superintendent and began
teaching phonics. &QL; 
The `3 C's' &QL; 
In Flagstaff, former superintendent Matheson came up with the
``three C's'': compete, collaborate and be creative. All-day
kindergarten classes were added and several magnet schools opened
in the wake of charter schools. Today, the current superintendent
is trying to entice the award-winning Flagstaff Arts and Leadership
Academy, a charter, to nest under its wing.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Likes, superintendent of the one-school Higley district in
one of the fastest-growing areas in the Phoenix area, also felt the
ripple effect of charters. The east Phoenix-area district is
redoing its teacher evaluation and salary schedule systems after
seeing how charters have done them better.
</P>
<P>
   Likes is in a unique position, though. Realizing he could charge
schools a fee to sponsor their charter, he become the largest
district sponsor of charter schools in the country. He wanted to
use the money to funnel the dollars into his impoverished district.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Likes oversees 260 district students and 3,500 charter
students flung across the state in 28 schools _ none of them within
the boundaries of his district.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new business. It ``is'' a business. Let's not kid
ourselves,'' said Likes, who admitted he was as big a ``crybaby''
as anyone when charters first emerged.
</P>
<P>
   At first, he tiptoed into charterland. Now, he plows through it.
And reaps the monetary rewards.
</P>
<P>
   With the fees he has charged his charters, the district has been
able to gain a business office, a new principal and $25,000 in
computers and other high-tech gadgets.
</P>
<P>
   Other districts are turning to charters, as well. The Florence
district even asked a charter school for at-risk students if it
would take some of the district's struggling students. &QL; 
Not all so positive &QL; 
However, not all districts have reacted so positively to the
charter school movement, according to educational observers.
</P>
<P>
   The Snowflake district said ``no way'' when the Mesa charter
school it sponsors and oversees asked to open a second site in
Pinetop, within the Snowflake district boundary. Too close for
comfort, officials readily admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Call it guerilla warfare. Other districts have refused to accept
charter school credits of students returning to the traditional
system. Mesa officials, who periodically thumb through charter
applications at the Department of Education, have leaked
anti-charter school stories to the media.
</P>
<P>
   Most public educators, however, are realizing that treating
charters as Public Enemy No. 1 won't serve them well in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent election cycle, more than a half-dozen east
Phoenix-area school board candidates said in their platforms that
district schools need to provide more alternatives to compete with
charters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way to improve the entire public system,'' said Lisa
Graham Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would hope the innovations would take hold.'' &QL; 
Kelly Pearce can be reached at 444-7981 or at
kelly.pearce(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
