<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU SEARCHES FOR AN IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Two hours before tipoff Bobby Lazor stood alone
on the arena floor and looked around at 14,000 vacant seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many are gonna be here?'' he wondered.
</P>
<P>
   The ASU senior absently bounced a basketball on the hardwood
floor. The sound in the empty building was hollow, which could
describe how Lazor later felt after he scored 30 points and grabbed
11 rebounds in another losing effort, this one against Southern
Cal, the final game of the Sun Devils season and Lazor's college
career.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance was _ 7,308?
</P>
<P>
   The head count must have included players, coaches, students,
alumni, vendors, Sparky, ASU cheerleaders, the ASU pep band, Ned
Wulk and perhaps a few folks wearing cowboy hats who put down money
at the Wells Fargo Arena window only to discover the tickets they
had purchased weren't for the George Strait concert.
</P>
<P>
   What they saw instead was another tough loss by a team with
limited talent. A team few people identified with. One few
supported.
</P>
<P>
   They saw first-year coach Rob Evans do everything he could to
keep ASU playing hard. And to match ``his'' intensity, his will to
win.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the second half Evans asked for and drew a
technical foul, hoping his display of ire directed toward the
myopic officiating crew would provide his tiring kids an energizing
spark.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils played hard. The team that has lost almost every
close Pac-10 game this season didn't quit. When Lazor who played 39
minutes walked off the court for the last time and his eyes met
those of his father who was waiting for him, Bobby was bone tired,
his gold jersey soaked with sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Evans praised the effort of the team he inherited. But the
Devils suffered another losing season (14-16) and in this town
losing teams go largely ignored _ especially at a school that
hasn't given the public much to cheer about, basketballwise, in a
long time.
</P>
<P>
   Evans understands why ASU sold only 6,000 season tickets. He
isn't surprised that few students attend the games. Only 500 ASU
students at a school with an enrollment of more than 40,000 bought
basketball season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Student cost is $32 for 16 home games. That's $2 a game, less
than what it costs to rent a movie.
</P>
<P>
   One reason students ignore ASU basketball is because the program
hasn't produced many identifiable players in recently. Jake
Plummer, Keith Poole, Pat Tillman and Juan Roque played on winning
football teams. They also competed four years.
</P>
<P>
   ASU basketeers have come and gone, for various reasons. The
school honored three seniors before Saturday's game. Mike Batiste
misssed the first part of two of the last three seasons. Lazor, a
transfer from Syracuse, played only two years here. Ron DuBois is a
former walk-on.
</P>
<P>
   The most recognizable ASU basketball player this decade is
Stevin Smith of point-shaving fame. One ASU fan directed a sign he
made at the USC bench. It read, ``We May Have Hedake (Smith) But At
Least We Don't Have The Juice,'' referring to former Trojan O. J.
Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery why ASU didn't sell out once. Exclude the
Arizona game (13,404) and the Sun Devils averaged 5,450.
</P>
<P>
   ASU hasn't beaten a Top 25 team at home since 1995. The Devils
haven't beaten UA and UCLA in the same season since 1985-86. The
last time the school advanced to the NCAA tournament in
back-to-back years (1979-80/80-81) the head coach was Ned Wulk.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime ASU honored Wulk, now 78, naming the court after
him. ``I hope you come back,`` he told the small enthusiastic
crowd. He could have added, as he did during Friday night's
function in his honor, ``And bring three or four friends with
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans appreciates the former coach's public appeal for support.
What warms his heart even more is the collective talent of ASU's
nationally-ranked recruiting class. Donnell Knight. Tanner Shell.
Tommy Smith. Chris Osborne. Shawn Redhage. ASU may start three
freshmen next year. These are names to remember. Players to get
excited about. Athletes worth paying to see.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in black, Evans looked and sounded like a minister
presiding at a funeral on the day ASU's season died and was laid to
rest. A time to mourn? Yes. ``It was a long road,'' the coach
solemnly intoned.
</P>
<P>
   But friends, glory awaits. There are great rewards in store for
those who do right and keep the faith. Evans envisions the day when
hopes will be lifted up. When ASU basketball will become a hot
ticket. When students will see the light and pack the student
section and Wells Fargo Arena will be transformed into a place as
bountiful and wondrous as heaven itself. ``Evvvvvverybody'' will
want to go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will happen. Absolutely,'' Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   I want to believe. I really do. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
