<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-06 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0638 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-UCLA-AZR &LR;      03-06 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-UCLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLE PLAYERS BUOY CATS' TOURNEY HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ It was Senior Day, an opportunity Saturday for
Arizona's fans to salute point guard Jason Terry and center A.J.
Bramlett, who came up big in their final home appearance.
</P>
<P>
   It proved to be an even bigger day for the little guys _ role
players Ruben Douglas, Traves Wilson, Rick Anderson, Justin Wessel
and Eugene Edgerson _ who carried 13th-ranked Arizona past No. 12
UCLA, 87-70, ending the Bruins' five-game streak.
</P>
<P>
   Those lesser lights will determine how far the Wildcats advance
in the NCAA Tournament. If they play as they did Saturday, it could
be a long run, according to Terry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we play like this I think we can go all the way to the
(Final) Four,'' said the senior point guard, who on Saturday
received his latest accolade, Pac-10 Player of the Year. ``This is
the best game we've played for 40 minutes, despite the 26
turnovers. The freshmen had no fear at all. That's going to be huge
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   In blowing out the Bruins (22-8, 12-6 Pac-10), the Wildcats
(22-6, 13-5) claimed second place in the Pac-10, stretched their
home streak to 32 games, and appeared ready for their 15th straight
NCAA Tournament berth. They find out where they are seeded and
assigned this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Terry scored 26 points and made four steals, making him a close
winner in the point-guard shootout with UCLA's Baron Davis, who
scored 21 and had four steals. Terry's only flaw was losing control
of his emotions. He forced passes (seven turnovers), and received a
first-half technical foul for mouthing off to UCLA's JaRon Rush,
who also received one in the exchange. When the Bruins beat the
Wildcats in the Pac-10 opener in Los Angeles, Rush said the margin
would have been 30 points instead of seven if he had played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to jawing and I usually don't do that,'' Terry said. ``I
did take that comment personally, that's why my emotions were so
high for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Rush conceded that ``J.T. lit us up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bramlett, who joined Terry on the all-conference first team
announced Saturday, posted his 16th double-double of the season,
the most at UA in 22 years and tying Phil Taylor for third on the
UA career list. Bramlett scored 14 points and had 10 rebounds to
lead Arizona's 46-31 board dominance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a physical game,'' Bramlett said. ``Everybody was
scrapping. Maybe they were a little frustrated. You could kind of
see it in their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   And that ultimately is what separated the teams.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona quickly lost power forward Michael Wright, who played
only three minutes in the first half after receiving his second
personal foul. Wright, the Pac-10 Freshman of the Year, is an
inside force, but without him the Wildcats did not panic.
</P>
<P>
   But when Davis got his second foul for the Bruins, just before
center Jerome Moiso got his second, they quickly became flustered.
Arizona broke the full-court press and got good looks at the
basket. Douglas (15 points, three three-pointers), Anderson (eight
points, two three-pointers) and Wilson (a three-point basket on the
only shot he took), along with inside enforcement from Edgerson
helped UA stretch a tie game at the 8:21 mark to a 16-point
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening half, the Wildcats made 7 of 9 three-point shots
(77.8 percent), 13 of 16 foul shots (81.3 percent) and had a
whopping 22-9 rebounding edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anderson gave us a big-time lift, and I'm not just talking
scoring,'' said UA Coach Lute Olson. ``I'm talking four assists and
no turnovers. That is key for us going into the playoffs. Wilson
came off the bench and played with confidence _ three assists and
no turnovers. We extended the lead when they came into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson preached defense hard after California shot just under 52
percent and Stanford 54 percent in two UA road losses the previous
week. The Wildcats got the message, limiting the Bruins to 38.1
percent, that after Southern California shot 43.3 percent as
Arizona blew it away, 88-73, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to go into the tournament too cocky,'' Rush
said. ``This game proves that we're not ready yet.''
</P>
<P>
   And it might have proved that Arizona is. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
