<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-FINLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY DECIDES IT'S OK TO BE LITTLE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ For most of his major-league career, the Diamondbacks'
Steve Finley has made a name for himself with acrobatic catches in
center field, hustling for the extra base and flashing occasional
power.
</P>
<P>
   With his 34th birthday on Friday, Finley believes he has found a
training regimen to enhance his performance by putting less stress
on his body.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always looking for ways to get better,'' Finley said.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of spring training in 1998, he was introduced to a
kinesiologist in Dana Point, Calif., Dr. Edith Heus, who had
developed a training program with longtime personal trainer Marv
Marinovich, father of former NFL quarterback Todd Marinovich.
</P>
<P>
   Because the regular season was just beginning for the San Diego
Padres, Finley couldn't begin the program, but as soon as the club
was swept by the New York Yankees in the World Series, he began.
</P>
<P>
   Its working title is the Pro Sports Tech System. The technical
name is proprioception, ``where the brain knows where the body is
in space.''
</P>
<P>
   In more basic terms, it means to allow the body to maintain
better balance during athletic competition with an exercise program
in which the participant goes through training while off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   It involves resistance training and includes standing and moving
on ``wobble disks'' and large gymnastics balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way I can describe an example of being off-balance is
a big offensive lineman in football who is blocking against an
opponent,'' Finley said. ``The lineman is stronger than anyone, but
it probably wouldn't take much to push him off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``In baseball, you're always making quick movements, reactions.
A lot of the time, you're working off-balance. But by working all
the muscles during this program, you aren't out of balance out
there nearly as often.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think Finley is speaking gibberish, think again. He has a
degree in physiology from Southern Illinois and was accepted to a
chiropractic school in St. Louis before pursuing his baseball
career.
</P>
<P>
   Finley has brought his own equipment to spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the guys might think I'm a little crazy, but
all I care about is the results,'' said the two-time National
League Gold Glove winner.
</P>
<P>
   The workout apparently has the blessing of team strength and
conditioning coach Jeff Forney, who plans to try it, Finley said,
``so he knows what I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   The longer version lasts 90 minutes and the shorter version
about 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not what I would call revolutionary, it's just very
subtle,'' Finley said.
</P>
<P>
   Marinovich has worked with hundreds of college athletes and said
that although there is something to be said for a lot of muscle
mass, ``those guys tend to be worse athletically. They do not seem
to be as productive as some of the other guys who are more
balanced, where the body works together as a unit. This is more of
a total workout, and there's not as much strain on the joints.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a great athlete, you don't need to look like Arnold
(Schwarzenegger). Cosmetics and performance are two different
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Marinovich said his son, who is considering a return to the NFL,
works with the program, as do New York Giants safety Jason Sehorn,
Los Angeles Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown and several ``ultimate
fighting'' participants.
</P>
<P>
   Heus said the workout begins with stretching the muscles at the
core of the spine and then fans out. In addition to the wobble
discs and gymnastics balls, modified weight-training machines are
used and there is some rowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything in the body becomes more efficient,'' Heus said.
``You don't feel wiped out like you do after some workouts, the
body is not broken down. It should help create some endurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your average athlete can benefit by this, too, not just those
in the pros and college. Success from this is not, `You either have
it or you don't.' It's not genetically related.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
