u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DRUG-LAWS-660&AMP;ADD-     03-06 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DRUG-LAWS-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI MUTES CALL FOR CHANGE IN DRUG LAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a significant policy shift, the Pataki
administration has backed away from any major overhaul of the stiff
Rockefeller-era drug laws that have caused New York's prison
population to surge over the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, administration officials say they are considering more
modest changes, like allowing appeals judges to reduce the
sentences of people who have been convicted of low-level drug
offenses when the penalties they receive far outweigh their crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, shortly after taking office, Pataki proposed
overhauling the drug laws, saying that the stiff sentences they
require had packed state prisons with nonviolent drug addicts who
might be better off in drug treatment programs or some other
cheaper alternatives to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic lawmakers had been making similar arguments for
years, though they were derided as soft on crime. But when Pataki,
a Republican, made his comments, the proposal was hailed as a
breakthrough that could result in the first major changes to the
drug laws since they were enacted in 1973 under another Republican
governor, Nelson A. Rockefeller. Pataki has been under mounting
pressure to revamp the laws ever since.
</P>
<P>
   But in a lengthy interview on Friday, Katherine N. Lapp, the
governor's top criminal justice adviser, said the Pataki
administration saw no reason now to overhaul the laws, largely
because the governor had adopted several early-release programs,
including drug treatment, as an alternative to prison for low-level
drug offenders, virtually all of them addicts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lapp said the governor's aggressive use of such programs had
saved the state the expense of building 5,000 more medium-security
cells over the last four years while it kept the most dangerous
drug criminals behind bars. These offenders include people who have
prior records of conviction or were convicted of drug sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say, `Let's repeal the Rockefeller drug laws,''' she
said. ``But that would be contrary to public safety. The
overwhelming majority of drug offenders in our prison system today
have earned their way into the system because of their
background.'' Ms. Lapp added, ``Wholesale changes would be
irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lapp's comments come as a broad coalition of judges,
criminologists and politicians from both parties have begun an
aggressive campaign urging Pataki and the Legislature to scale back
the drug laws drastically, if not repeal them altogether, during
the current legislative session.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks disappointed those advocates, who had been counting
on the governor to lead the fight for overhauling the laws. They
reiterated their concern that the laws have needlessly increased
prison costs without significantly reducing the problem of illegal
drug use and sales.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gangi, the director of the Correctional Association of
New York, a prison watchdog group that supports changing the laws,
said the state was still imprisoning thousands of nonviolent drug
users who were not major dealers but sold drugs or committed other
crimes to support their habits. He said it would be more
cost-efficient and humane to put them in drug treatment programs
rather than prison. ``Their addiction drives their criminal
activity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Pataki's new position drew strong support from prosecutors
and other law-enforcement officials who have sought to block any
wholesale revision of the drug laws. They argue that the laws
enable them to force drug offenders to accept lower charges or even
placement in drug-treatment programs in exchange for lesser
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased to hear this from the governor,'' said
William J. Fitzpatrick, the president of the New York State
District Attorneys Association. ``We use the Rockefeller drug laws
as a weapon to ferret out criminal activity, and I think we are
pretty discreet in its application and in who we try to put in
prison.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The timing of the policy shift may have political ramifications
for the governor. He is currently exploring the possibility of
running for national office, and his desire to avoid overhauling
the drug laws would play well among conservatives who are
influential in the national Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   But some political experts believe it is more likely that his
new position is an opening bid in negotiations with Democrats in
the Assembly who have long sought wholesale revisions to the drug
laws. Indeed, Ms. Lapp said that the administration would only
agree to revise the laws in exchange for the Assembly's support of
the governor's proposal to eliminate parole for all nonviolent
felons. ( Pataki has already pushed through bills eliminating
parole for violent felons.)
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1973 Rockefeller drug laws, judges must abide by rigid
sentencing guidelines that require long prison terms for drug
offenses, even relatively minor ones like possessing a small
quantity of narcotics. Under a similar law passed that same year,
the sentences increase sharply when a person is convicted of a
second felony within 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, nearly 22,000 of the state's 70,000 prisoners were
incarcerated for nonviolent drug crimes, at a cost of about $600
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration contends that more than half of those
had been convicted of other crimes as well. Ms. Lapp said that 29
percent were convicted for illegal use of weapons, 15 percent for
robbery, 9 percent for assault and 6 percent for burglary.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lapp also said that the administration has managed to halt
the rapid growth of the population of nonviolent drug offenders in
the prison system for the first time in nearly two decades. It has
done so, she said, by employing early-release programs on a
case-by-case basis.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
