<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PHXOPEN-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOENIX OPEN MUST PRESERVE ITS IDENTITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - So the elitists will get their way. Their golf
tournament will once again be sanitized, hosed down, cleansed of
the common folk.
</P>
<P>
   So the Phoenix Open will become just another boring stop on the
tour. Another anonymous tea party of knit shirts and coddled
sponsors. Just another perfectly putrid, self-contained corporate
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Just another cash grab to fill time between the majors.
</P>
<P>
   When a sport deems itself sacred, there is no room for fun. But
this isn't about loud mouths or public drunkenness or galleries
that haven't been brainwashed by the politics of polite. This is
about killing an institution, the Mardis Gras of golf. A tournament
championed as a cultural event, embraced for its revelry.
</P>
<P>
   For the very things the Thunderbirds are trying to kill.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, sweeping changes are in the works following a wave
of bad publicity. In the wake of an alcohol ban that didn't work
and a gun found in a fanny pack comes radical reform. Ideas ranging
from weekly passes priced at $150 to limits on alcohol consumption
to artificial measures designed to restrict attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Ever hear of a sporting event so callous? So self-important that
it wants to handpick its following? So stodgy that a proposed price
increase is designed not to make money but to weed out the
undesirables?
</P>
<P>
   So snobbish that it casts judgment on its fan base?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, when a gun-toting, beer-chugging goofball charges a
police officer, there is room for concern. But isn't it ironic how
tournament officials once went out of their way to downplay the
significance of Brian K. Murphy? And now he's the symbol of pending
disaster?
</P>
<P>
   If he is truly an aberration, treat him like one.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, there is some middle ground here. Some way to appease
the golfers and the PGA Tour without ripping the personality out of
the Phoenix Open. A tournament so popular that it has become a part
of our sporting culture, an event so different that it's recognized
across the country. And it's not like the Valley has an excess of
national identity.
</P>
<P>
   This year, more than 40,000 people gathered around the 16th hole
on a Saturday afternoon. Television cameras were everywhere. And
there wasn't a viewer in the nation who didn't watch the
proceedings and wonder, ``Whoa, is that really golf?''
</P>
<P>
   The Thunderbirds don't know how good they had it.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, one of the premier players on tour, called No. 16
the ``most unique hole we'll play all year.'' Do they understand
the significance of such a statement?
</P>
<P>
   It is a testament that should be treasured, trumpeted, marketed,
parlayed into big-time prominence. The Phoenix Open could've been
the most unique non-major on tour. Instead, they are running from
their fears, into the safety of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Magee, a Paradise Valley resident and new match-play
celebrity, told ``The Republic'' on Friday that the Phoenix Open
was ahead of its time. That the rebellious crowds were preparing
golfers for ``the next generation of golf fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Magee recognizes one key factor: If you can't boo, it's
not a sport. And you can't appeal to a new generation with an
antique mindset clinging to country club traditions.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Open should hold firm. Put the emphasis on the fans,
not the golfers. Increase plain-clothed security. Announce severe
penalties to any fan who crosses the line, most notably its new ban
on guns. Promote the tournament as the future of golf, and if a
handful of professionals want no part of it, fine. Fill the field
with guys who do.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, if raucous galleries are really a glimpse of the
future, the TPC will be remembered as ground zero, the origin of
evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they want the silence of etiquette to prevail, the frat
house kicked off campus. They want a nice, quiet tournament. They
want to appease the PGA Tour, appear dignified, disgusted by the
monster they unknowingly created. They want to fill their corporate
tents, sell their identity to sponsors, limit alcohol to a quaint
beer garden, reward the sheep who wouldn't dare boo a shot in the
bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Thunderbirds:
</P>
<P>
   Careful what you wish for. Silence can be deadly. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
