<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH-VEGAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE MORE BORE THAN ROAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Those weren't the throaty roars of engines heard
Friday at Las Vegas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   They were snores.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an impeccable performance by Mark Martin and several
NASCAR Winston Cup buddies, a crowd of 72,500 was forced to endure
more than two hours of a yawning Sam's Town 300.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who with 35 wins is the NASCAR Busch Series all-time
leader, led 150 of 200 laps, including 89 of the final 90.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the car to beat all weekend,'' Martin said. ``The
thing was really hooked up today.''
</P>
<P>
   Cup regulars, of which there were a robust 16 in a starting
field of 43, dominated their Busch counterparts, which may not
necessarily be good news for NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR officials made a preseason marketing pitch to make
certain everyone understood the Busch Series could stand on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not NASCAR's minor league,'' NASCAR official Kevin
Triplett said.
</P>
<P>
   OK, then why allow so many Cup drivers in a Busch race, which,
in turn, sends several Busch regulars home early?
</P>
<P>
   Although many Busch drivers encourage the Cup invasion because
they feel it enables them to gain valuable experience, how much can
be learned when the Cup regulars combine to lead all but 14 laps
and collar the top five finishing positions.
</P>
<P>
   Not much, that's how much.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite, Martin insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Busch regulars) could look at what we did and say it can
be done,'' Martin said. ``All the parts are available to everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we started running so well (in the Busch Series) in the
(1990s), the Busch regulars have really stepped it up. They thought
they were doing all they could, then we sort of raised the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, they went back to work and figured out what to do to
raise the bar for themselves. There's some really great talented
teams and drivers out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But none were able to flex their Busch muscles against the Cup
contingent.
</P>
<P>
   Following Martin across the finish-line were Joe Nemechek, Jeff
Burton, Jeff Gordon and Jimmy Spencer. And Burton now leads the
driver's standings in a series in which he's only a part-time
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Defending series champion Dale Earnhardt Jr. (sixth) was the top
Busch finisher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a problem with the (Cup drivers),'' Dale Jr.,
said. ``But it's a shame because some people that were up in the
points, like Casey Atwood, had to go home and that makes you sick
to your stomach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Busch Series isn't going to thrive off the Winston Cup
drivers. It's going to thrive off the Busch drivers. But, then
again, it's a double-edged sword. Those guys come into our series
and we get a chance to compete against them. There's no feeling
like running with guys like Mark Martin. It's a good
confidence-builder.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's confidence builder was knowing his car wasn't entirely
perfect, but it didn't need to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started off a little too loose and we tightened it up a
little bit too much,'' said Martin, who started from the pole
position and won $87,625 from a $1,053,728 purse. ``On the last
stop, we wound up going half in between.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin could have instructed his pit crew to install a luggage
rack on the roof and he still probably would have had the
aerodynamic sleekness to put away Nemechek and company.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who was making his first Busch start in seven years,
struggled with a nagging handling problem throughout most of the
race. Although he edged Earnhardt Jr., in their initial Busch
showdown, Gordon, believe it or not, was a non-factor.
</P>
<P>
   He never led and never came close to leading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed on the gear and we were way too tight,'' Gordon
said. ``It took us a little while to get it dialed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he started next to Martin on the front row, Gordon
immediately went in another direction. He went backwards, dropping
to fifth by Lap 2.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on Lap 24, Dale Jr., passed Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   The move invoked cheers. And some boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess all the fans want to know how I feel about the first
time me and (Gordon) have run in the Busch Series together,'' Dale
Jr. said. ``I really enjoyed it. To run second to that guy is not a
bad day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best. Everyone wants to be where he's at right now. I
have a lot of admiration for him. He's good at what he does and
that's where we all want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Martin. Martin seems content right where he's at. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
