<HEADLINE>
FORD APPAR ENTLY SLIPS IN VEGAS LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ A year ago, the Las Vegas 400 might as well have
been a New York City fashion stage for the Ford Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   Models dressed as NASCAR Winston Cup drivers paraded the
aerodynamically sleek machinery down the Las Vegas Motor Speedway
runway, capturing 13 of the top 14 finishing positions in a nearly
endless conga line of superiority.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Calvin Klein would have been proud.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford's reign could be over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bobby Labonte put a  &UR; Joe Gibbs-owned Pontiac on the pole
position for today's Las Vegas 400 and has a front-row neighbor in
Chevy's  &UR; Michael
 &UR; Waltrip.
</P>
<P>
   The top Ford qualifier is road-racing specialist  &UR; Tom Hubert,
who will start fourth next to Chevy's  &UR; Joe  &UR; Nemechek.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy's  &UR; Mike Skinner will start fifth, but the next five are in
Fords.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's race also provided little side-by-side racing and
that, too, could change.
</P>
<P>
   Rule changes allowing for larger rear spoilers and smaller front
air dams have drivers believing there will be less
follow-the-leader racing and more door-to-door racing.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying casualties &QL; 
NASCAR waits for no one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kyle Petty and  &UR; Ted Musgrave failed to qualify, and  &UR; Rusty
Wallace,
 &UR; Dale Earnhardt and  &UR; Ernie  &UR; Irvan were forced to rely on
provisionals to make the 43-car starting field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Darrell Waltrip also was forced to use a provisional, but what
else is new? Waltrip needed 20 past champion's provisionals last
season and already has used three in three races this season. &QL; 
Pit stops &QL; 
Rookie  &UR; Buckshot Jones qualified for the first time this season and
will start 35th in today's race.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jeff Burton and brother  &UR; Ward Burton were the fastest drivers
during Happy Hour practice. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
