<SLUG> BC-EPA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL FORCES COMPLICATE DISPOSAL OF CHEMICALS, EXPLOSIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It would have been difficult enough for Gov. Hull's
office just to decide how to dispose of more than 800 pounds of
potentially lethal chemicals and explosives left in a shed by a
``gun nut.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a lot more than explosive chemicals to worry
about. There were also some volatile political forces at work.
</P>
<P>
   There were the New River residents, some concerned by rumors
spread on the Internet, who told Hull they distrusted the federal
government's claims that it could burn up the chemicals without
endangering the community.
</P>
<P>
   Less than three miles away there was the massive 5,856-acre
Anthem community, owned by the Del Webb Corp., a powerful developer
and a key Hull campaign contributor, that was opening its doors for
business.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a federal agency, the Environmental Protection
Agency, that was proposing to incinerate the chemicals and evacuate
some nearby residents in the very same month (March) that thousands
of Anthem buyers were to arrive for the development's highly
publicized grand opening.
</P>
<P>
   So for the governor, it was not just an environmental problem
but a safety issue and a political headache.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 21, Del Webb told the EPA in a letter that to incinerate
the chemicals when thousands of people were visiting Anthem between
Feb. 27 and April 1 ``could be close to disastrous in terms of
traffic, crowd control, media exposure and criticism, availability
of appropriate fire and sheriff's resources, and overall community
relations.'' The EPA had been considering conducting the burn in
March because it wanted to complete it before the beginning of the
fire season.
</P>
<P>
   But after weighing everyone's objections, Hull appeared to go
out of her way to antagonize the EPA _ denouncing its leaders as a
group of ``bumbling bureaucrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA took charge of a property formerly occupied by Charles
``Chuck'' Byers in Sept. 17, 1997, after it was discovered Byers
was storing explosives and chemicals for making munitions there.
The ranch is in the 44800 block of North 27th Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by Hull's critical words on talk radio and her lack of
support for its cleanup plan, the EPA told the state to finish the
job itself and pick up the tab estimated in the hundreds of
thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to proceed and take care of it, but we wanted to do
it with the state's full support,'' EPA Regional Administrator
Felicia Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Also withdrawing was the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms, which had been providing security at the site.
</P>
<P>
   The abrupt federal departure has put the governor in the
position of having to explain why she rebuffed two agencies that
that had already spent more than $1.5 million to clean up and
secure the mess and were prepared to spend more.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's office acknowledges that Del Webb's concerns played a
role in her reluctance to back the EPA's plan, but her spokespeople
deny that the developer's influence outweighed other, equally
serious considerations. To understand the story, the Hull aides
said, you have to appreciate the depth of skepticism held by many
New River residents toward the EPA. Her staff members say local
citizens were always their primary concern.
</P>
<P>
   Del Webb was a significant campaign backer of Hull's. Phil Dion,
Del Webb's chief executive officer, arranged a fund-raising
luncheon for Hull in Las Vegas in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it (Anthem) is a big development, and I know that Del
Webb has communicated their concerns to the governor,'' said Hull
spokeswoman Francie Noyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that they're not part of the reason (to reject
the incineration for now),'' she added. ``But they are by no means
the major consideration here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacque Pappas, community and public relations manager for
Anthem, said the development had communicated its concerns to the
EPA only because it had been advised by the Maricopa County
Sheriffs Office to let the federal government know of any
`significant events'' occurring during the planned incineration.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's office said many of the New River citizens don't believe
the agency's claims that burning the chemicals can be done without
contaminating the ground, water or air.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to know if their kids are going to be playing in
dirt that's contaminated,'' said George Weisz, executive assistant
to Hull.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents think the cache of 800 pounds of chemicals and up
to 100 pounds of explosives should simply be carted away. Most of
the chemicals in the shed _ the non-explosive ones _ already have
been removed by federal cleanup crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state can finish this up without even causing a bang,''
said Byers, now lives in the Ahwatukee Foothills. He pleaded guilty
to munitions-related crimes in January and was put on probation for
five years. The judge called him a ``gun nut.''
</P>
<P>
   Byers has accused the ATF of corruption and alleges that the CIA
has taken part in drug running and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rumors have spread on the Internet that the EPA has
been using its incineration proposal to try to drive down property
rates because the U.S. is secretly planning a federal buyout.
Hostility toward the federal government in New River reached a
point where Marcus believed there was a ``safety concern'' for her
EPA employees.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA, which denies the Internet rumors, believes the
chemicals are too volatile to be transported out of the shed. Many
of the chemicals are unlabeled. All are believed to be precursors
to manufacturing explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't go in with a robot and pick it up, and you can't
send anyone in, or else you might get an unplanned fire and
explosion,'' said Paula Bruin, an EPA spokeswoman. ``A burn is
controlled.''
</P>
<P>
   EPA said it has been prepared to destroy the witches' brew since
October 1997 but that the state needed reassurance. Marcus said the
Department of Defense subsequently endorsed the plan, and an Army
Corps of Engineers contractor ranked on-site burning as the safest
remedy.
</P>
<P>
   But the governor is still not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Hull spokeswoman Noyes said, is that the
EPA has not answered all of the state's questions and has not
communicated well with New River citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that if this thing had been handled a little more
quickly and if they had talked to the people up there, it wouldn't
have gotten to the place it's at,'' Noyes said.
</P>
<P>
   But Marcus said, ``We did engage the community and individuals
for countless hours and put out the best information we had.'' A
timeline released by the EPA shows numerous meetings and other
contacts between the agency and New River citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Noyes said the governor didn't intend to chase the EPA and ATF
off the project, adding that the state was surprised when it was
notified they were pulling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way anybody wanted this to go. It has been
really unfortunate,'' Noyes said. &QL; 
Republic writer Brent Whiting contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
