A0648 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAMBERS-RECRUIT-2ndT     03-06 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAMBERS-RECRUIT-2ndTake-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  LOS ANGELES: said Mayor Dan Kuperberg.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurtz has said if the Agoura-Las Virgenes Chamber of Commerce
doesn't attract more businesses, it may have to merge with
neighboring chambers. That's been another trend of the '90s for
chambers: merging smaller groups to form regional entities that
better reflect the regional nature of business. After all, a
business won't turn away a customer just because she lives five
miles down the freeway in another town.
</P>
<P>
   It's that kind of thinking that brought together the Chatsworth
and Northridge chambers, though merger talks are on hold for now.
</P>
<P>
   If talks are revived, said Chatsworth's Himes, it would be
because the benefits of merging include economies of scale plus
some added clout in lobbying efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're approximately the same size; we'd be speaking with twice
the voice, so to speak,'' Himes said.
</P>
<P>
   And the merged chambers could attract more members _ and more
money. About half the Chatsworth chamber's approximately $100,000
budget comes from membership dues, Himes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some anecdotal evidence that there were people who
were on the fence; that if there was a merger they would be
interested in joining again,'' Himes said. ``Right or wrong, there
is this concept that if you are bigger, you are better.''
</P>
<P>
   Operations have rolled along at the Mid Valley Chamber of
Commerce, which covers the Los Angeles city communities of Van
Nuys, Panorama City and North Hills _ but not without some
difficulty, executive vice president Nancy Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the health of my chamber's improving,'' she said.
``We've struggled, too _ we had some really rough years _ and we're
finally seeing the light at the end of the tunnel, which we thought
would never happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can almost change the light bulb at the end of the
tunnel,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   About 45 percent of the chamber's $330,000 budget comes from
member dues.
</P>
<P>
   Membership has fluctuated over five years for various reasons:
569 in fiscal 1994; 533 in 1995; 559 in 1996, the year of a major
membership drive; 509 in 1997; and 503 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There is a simple explanation for the 1996-97 drop: About 50
percent of members recruited during drives typically drop out after
the first year, Hoffman and other chamber officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just us _ it's a known fact,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber, or its committees, have adopted several measures to
boost or retain membership. In 1997, for example, a Latino Business
Development Committee was formed to increase chamber representation
of Latinos, who constitute a bulk of business owners in the
northeast San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the organization in 1997 appointed a member services
coordinator. In addition, the Mid Valley Chamber of Commerce stays
in regular contact with its members to remind them of events and
other activities of interest.
</P>
<P>
   And it recently brought in a telemarketing volunteer, whose
duties include those simple ``hi'' calls to members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not asking for money; we're not reminding them of
events,'' Hoffman said. ``We're just reminding them that we're here
if they need anything.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be working. Membership in fiscal year 1999, which
ends March 31, was 538, up nearly 7 percent from the prior year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
