<SLUG> BC-CHAMBERS-RECRUIT-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBERS OF COMMERCE TRY DIFFERENT TECHNIQUES TO RECRUIT MEMBERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ed Kurtz would walk a mile _ or more _ to promote
a new business association he hopes will breathe new life into the
struggling Agoura-Las Virgenes Chamber of Commerce in the Agoura
Hills community northwest of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In Van Nuys in Los Angeles' San Fernando Valley, Nancy Hoffman
and her Mid Valley Chamber of Commerce team let their fingers do
the walking, phoning local businesses just to say hi and let them
know the chamber is there for them any time they need.
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz and Hoffman are top people at their chambers _ Kurtz the
new president of the Agoura-Las Virgenes chamber, Hoffman the Mid
Valley's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   They are fighting to boost _ or just hang onto _ their
memberships.
</P>
<P>
   Chambers throughout California are losing members in part
because business people want them to go beyond their traditional
role as networking organizations, said Kathy Fairbanks, a
spokeswoman for the 11,000-member California Chamber of Commerce in
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses aren't just joining chambers for the sake of
joining chambers anymore,'' Fairbanks said. ``They want to get
something out of it such as advocacy at the local level with city
councils and so forth.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many chambers are doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Kurtz and Hoffman _ and executives like them across
the region and across the country _ are canvassing their
communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of chambers are really growing in size, because they're
really active in the community and serving businesses in the
community really well,'' Fairbanks said.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Fernando Valley, many chambers were hit hard by the
1994 Northridge Earthquake, said Les Himes, president of the
260-member Chatsworth/Porter Ranch Chamber of Commerce in north San
Fernando Valley, which until recently had been in merger talks with
the Northridge chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Many businesses were destroyed or damaged, and their owners had
to devote more time and resources to rebuilding them, he said.
Organizational dues were some of the first items cut in their
budgets.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the economic recession of the early 1990s forced some
businesses to close their doors, he said. Meanwhile, many surviving
businesses had to cut their staffs, forcing their owners to devote
more time to managing and operating them.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot of all this was that merchants had less time _ and
money _ for their chambers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general feeling throughout the chamber business that
things were off a little bit,'' Himes said. ``There's also a
feeling that there's an upswell of improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   A more activist role is what Kurtz _ a former Agoura Hills
council member and mayor _ had in mind when he formed the Agoura
Hills Merchants Association, which had its first meeting on Feb.
22.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the prior two weeks beating the pavement, distributing
several hundred fliers announcing the first meeting to every
business in the city.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 merchants, plus some city officials, turned out for the
meeting, a small but promising first step in getting the new
association off the ground, Kurtz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new concept; it's never been done before _ 10 people
could mushroom to 20 people,'' Kurtz said. ``I'm cautiously
optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea that first came to Kurtz some five years ago. But
he put it into action now to reverse the sagging fortunes of the
50-year-old Agoura-Las Virgenes chamber.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly alarmed that about 40 percent of the
chamber's members are from outside Agoura Hills _ an indication, to
Kurtz, that the chamber is becoming too regional.
</P>
<P>
   The Agoura-Las Virgenes chamber has some 365 members, according
to executive director Diana Malmquist.
</P>
<P>
   The new association is intended to boost local membership in the
chamber by demonstrating its benefits to local merchants.
</P>
<P>
   It would do four things: educate merchants about rules and
ordinances affecting them, such as regulations on outdoor displays;
re-establish the ``shop Agoura Hills'' campaign; expand the
chamber's annual business fair; and organize a citywide Midnight
Madness sale during which stores in the city would remain open
through midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that if merchants prosper, so will the city, since
35 percent of the city's $6.6 million general fund is derived from
sales tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city's interests and the businesses' interests coincide
perfectly,'' said Mayor Dan Kuperberg.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
