<SLUG> BC-PUCK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES FANS FLOCK TO RALLY FOR PROPOSED NEW ARENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURA TRUJILLO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ They didn't wait in line for more than an
hour to discuss taxes, traffic, redevelopment or whatever else many
Scottsdale residents think a new hockey arena might bring to their
town.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the families at a Saturday rally for a new arena at Los
Arcos Mall just wanted to see the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   They lined up some 300 deep, many wearing thick maroon-and-green
hockey jerseys in the 79-degree afternoon sun, to get autographs
outside the aging mall.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the crowd don't even live in Scottsdale and are
ineligible to vote in the May election that will decide whether the
new arena is built. But whatever the Coyotes want, fans said, they
want, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm for it if it makes them happy,'' said Kurt May, 12, who
added Coyotes center Daniel Briere's and forward Brad Isbister's
autographs to his jersey. The Peoria sixth-grader already had
Jeremy Roenick's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got him at the Exxon station.''
</P>
<P>
   And Teppo Numminen's _ ``I ran all over the Ice Den for a pen
once I saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of arena supporters staged the rally and autograph
session in hopes of gaining support for the May 18 election, when
Scottsdale residents will vote on the City Council's December
decision to form a stadium district. The district would pay for the
mall's proposed $624 million redevelopment, including a 20,000-seat
arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes now play at America West Arena, where, from about
4,200 of the seats, fans can see only one goal.
</P>
<P>
   They registered voters, played street hockey and raffled off
game tickets as Howlin' Tommy Rox and the Phoenix Coyotes played
classic rock such as ``Mustang Sally'' and songs that evoked the
sounds of a hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   They say the proposed 20,000-seat arena will revive the almost
deserted mall, where the shadow of Sears remains along with only a
handful of stores and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 feet away, pacing the sidewalks surrounding the mall,
arena opponents passed out fliers, waved handmade signs and yelled
into bullhorns, hoping to fight the development at the corner of
McDowell and Scottsdale roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will destroy our neighborhood,'' said Eric Auxier,
36, an America West Airlines pilot who can see the old Sears
building from his driveway.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Auxier bought the home he grew up in, hoping to
return to the quiet, modest neighborhood of block homes he
remembers from childhood. Now, he worries he'll back right up to
the sports arena.
</P>
<P>
   The protest, organized by No Pucks _ Neighborhoods Organized to
Prevent Unwanted Community Killing in Scottsdale _ is all the
protesters feel they can do to sway voters their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need all this congestion here,'' says Scottsdale
resident Theresa Halverson, holding a ``No arena'' sign in one hand
and passing out fliers to passing cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait till the traffic stops,'' her cousin, 72-year-old Nancy
Brown, chimed in.
</P>
<P>
   The two worry the arena will change the pace of their
comfortable south Scottsdale neighborhood. As Halverson, 62,
watched Coyotes sign autographs in the shade, she wondered aloud
why they didn't come talk to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why can't they come over here and ask me what I want?'' asked
the retired office worker. ``This arena won't help them win any
faster.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
