<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE RUMORS ABOUND IN NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case we are being heckled by a special-interest lobby, it
should be noted that no agents were harmed in the production of
this column.
</P>
<P>
   Any violence against agents has been simulated. Actually, we
have made every attempt to avoid the use of agents, because our
topic is this week's NBA trading deadline (Thursday), and seeking
insight about trades from an agent is about as ill-advised as
asking a mugger for directions to the nearest ATM.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the league's new corrective bartering agreement has put
the ``dead'' in trading deadline. Clearing room beneath its nastier
salary cap seems to be at the top of each team's ``to-do'' list.
Well, unless that elbow injury has left his jumper with the
accuracy of a five-day weather forecast, Glen Rice still is
expected to be acquired by the Lakers. But most general managers
are concentrating on dumping salaries, throwing them overboard like
a collection of Boz Skaggs albums cluttering the passenger basket
hanging beneath an endangered hot-air balloon.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? If everyone's doing it, then who's left to do any
trading?
</P>
<P>
   Teams that are one warm body shy of evolving from playoff
pretenders into contenders.
</P>
<P>
   George Karl, stunt double for John Lithgow and coach of the
playoff-sniffing Milwaukee Bucks, knows his frontcourt has less
depth than a half-hour of ``Friends.'' Last week, George accused
the Clippers of having ``get-able'' frontcourt players, but
wondered who in his right mind would want players from a winless
team.
</P>
<P>
   If one of those players is second-year power forward Maurice
Taylor, the answer is ``everybody.'' For the last several days,
trade talks with the Clippers begin and end, quickly, with Taylor,
who - rest assured, Clipper fans - is as untouchable as your wife's
meatloaf. The Philadelphia 76ers, who recently won six games in a
row for the first time since Coach Larry Brown began talking to and
answering himself, reportedly discussed a deal involving talented
Tim Thomas, but Taylor isn't moving.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas? He's making $1.8 million in the second of his three-year
deal. Nobody else in that price neighborhood (and the cap dictates
that salaries conform in these deals) is near his level of talent.
So for the Sixers to acquire anyone capable of helping them advance
in the playoffs, the other team probably would have to toss in
another player to achieve a salary match; that would leave the
other team with an extra body and, perhaps, an extra contract to
eat.
</P>
<P>
   OK, as the start of March Madness approaches (savvy NBA timing,
eh?), a deal should be swung here and there. Don't be stunned if
the struggling New Jersey Nets - who have a few big-ticket players
playing the same positions - ship somebody somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But simply clearing cap room is no guaranteed solution, so help
us Jerry Krause. Since the new contract allows only a potential
free agent's team to pony up the maximum scoots, many in the
eagerly awaited talent avalanche have re-enlisted with their
current teams.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the deadline for teams to re-sign players they don't
mind having around is Saturday. After Saturday comes and goes,
contract chat is to be forbidden until July 1, and signing a free
agent from another team isn't legal until Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   sub UF5 Worm 2000
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman, the Krazy Glue threatening to hold the Lakers
together, may be Laker enough to join the team in its move to the
Staples Center. But Dennis, who signed for the $1 million exception
(which sounds like the plot line from the movie ``Indecent
Proposal''), would be limited to just a 10 percent raise.
</P>
<P>
   After two Laker seasons, he'd be eligible for big money ... at
age 39.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Rodman could make up the difference by going
Hollywood, which now is within walking distance. Remember, with
Rodman and Rick Fox, the Laker bench has more film experience than
its starting lineup (sorry, Shaq).
</P>
<P>
   Fox had a nice role in ``He Got Game,'' leading Jesus
(Shuttlesworth) into temptation.
</P>
<P>
   As the co-star of ``Double Team,'' Rodman led Jean-Claude Van
Damme into early video rental.
</P>
<P>
   sub UF5 Clip and save department
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, as you may know, are owned by Donald T. Sterling.
Wouldn't it be nice if the ``T'' stood for Terrell, as in Brandon?
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Brandon plays point guard very well for Milwaukee. He
will be a free agent at the end of this season, because he is not
wild about a bratwurst-case scenario and refuses to re-sign with
the Bucks until testing the free-agent market. Brandon has said he
will sign with the team that really wants him, and money may not be
the lead variable (uh-huh).
</P>
<P>
   His agent is Bill Duffy, who also represents Clipper rookie
center Michael Olowokandi and may not mind steering Brandon to L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have eight players in the last year of their
contracts; by not re-signing all of them (except Tyrone Nesby),
they could clear, oh, $15 million or so in cap room and still have
eight bodies under contract.
</P>
<P>
   With two more rookies (the Clips should be hell in lottery
Ping-Pong), and two free agents (including Brandon for a hard pinch
or two over $10 million per year), the Clippers could be in
business.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is convincing Sterling to pay one player more then 10
large ones. Here's a hint: giving the loot to a great player just
before moving into a new arena with the Lakers beats dividing it
among three medicore players.
</P>
<P>
   sub UF5 Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Olden Polynice was fined last week for making an obscene gesture
for the benefit of his old fans in Sacramento. Actually, Olden was
using a finger to signal how many times he will have appeared in an
All-Star Game the next time he's chosen for that honor. ... Further
evidence that the only Nelson who belongs in Texas is Willie, not
Don: With Paul Pierce, Jason Williams and Larry Hughes still on the
draft board last year, Nellie selected Robert ``Tractor'' Traylor,
then shipped him to the Bucks for Dirk ``Apocalypse'' Nowitzki. He
also sent this year's No. 1 pick (a lottery likelihood) to Phoenix
in exchange for its backup point guard, Steve Nash. ... According
to rumor, No. 1 Clipper fan Billy Crystal is writing the screenplay
for a film about the coach of his favorite team. The working title
is ``Analyze Chris.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
