<SLUG> BC-ANTHEM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND OPENING OF `ANTHEM' PLANNED COMMUNITY IN PHOENIX DRAWS
THOUSANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Take a retired Marine Corps colonel, a family of four
and a golf fanatic, throw in some snowbirds and a couple of
nudists, and you get a good idea of who showed up to see the newest
development in the north Phoenix- area:
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's grand opening of Anthem _ a widely-hyped
master-planned community that spans 6,000 acres _ drew home buyers
and curiosity seekers from as close as neighboring New River and as
far as Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees walked alongside young couples. Self-described country
folk mixed with city dwellers. The country club set inspected wine
cellars while families checked out kitchen space.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking for four years,'' said James Laseter, 70, a
retired colonel with the U.S. Marine Corp. who lives in Hawaii. ``I
haven't found anything I like as much as this.''
</P>
<P>
   The skeptics came out too on Saturday, scratching their heads at
the thought of this large community rising from the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't stop development,'' said Charlie Gross, 65, who
lives on an acre-lot in nearby Black Canyon City. ``But I couldn't
stand anyone living that close to me. I don't want to hear my
neighbors. All I hear now is dogs occassionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob and Min Lussier got dressed and bicycled over from the
nearby nudist colony in New River. Residents drive on dirt roads
and rely on wells and septic tanks in rural community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just wondering what it's going to do to the water
supply, and the impact it will have on the desert,'' said Bob
Lussier.
</P>
<P>
   By Anthem estimates, over 6,000 people showed up Saturday. That
almost matched the number who decended on the development last
weekend during a frenzied pre-grand opening sale.
</P>
<P>
   People with invitations and gate crashers quickly snatched up
lots _ leaving Anthem security and sales reps overwhelmed and
prospective homebuyers irked when they couldn't buy a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Anthem officials then released another 200 lots for this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Developer Del Webb Corp., planned on selling 1,000 lots over 12
months, starting this month. Several hundred have been sold so far,
exceeding expectations, said Anne Mariucci, a senior vice president
with Del Webb. She declined to give an exact number of home sales.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the buying frenzy last weekend, people entered
drawings for appointments with sales reps on Saturday. Drawings
will also be held from 10 a.m. to 6 p.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   Laseter, who was visiting from Hawaii, grabbed a lot in the
country club community. For him, Anthem's location is ideal for
visiting his children in both Gilbert and Sedona, but also offers
the ammenities he wants like golf.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Winerkoorn , 77, was also drawn by the links.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play three or four times a week,'' he said. ``I will buy
right away.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone touring Anthem jumped at the chance to sign on
the dotted line.
</P>
<P>
   At a drawing in the lesser-expensive Parkside community, the
first two potential buyers for 10 lots decided to pass _ one
changed his mind and the other wanted a better pick of lots.
</P>
<P>
   And Al McLeod, who toured the property with his wife Martha via
shuttle bus, ``just wanted to check out the options. We're just
kicking the tires.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bob and Jean Moody, who live in the Deer Valley area, came
with checkbook in hand. They want their three kids to grow up
outside the city, and said the the development's price range and
ammenties won them over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a good investment and a good place to
live,'' said Bob Moody. &QL; 
Susie Steckner can be reached at 444-7129, or at
susie.steckner(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
