<HEADLINE>
ODOM IS HOT SHOT IN LIFTING URI 
</HEADLINE>
 10 FINAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ It was a huge gamble from the beginning. The
university enrolled him as a non-scholarship, non-matriculating
student, never guaranteeing him full admission. He went nearly two
years without playing organized basketball, including one at his
third and final high school. Twice he bolted from the university,
including one time after the exam period, only to return and start
anew.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Lamar Odom became eligible to play at the University
of Rhode Island, many wondered how long he would stay before
vaulting to the NBA. Questions persisted as to whether he was worth
the effort, the risk and the criticism URI absorbed for opening its
doors to him.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was worth it.
</P>
<P>
   With 6.1 seconds left in Saturday's Atlantic 10 tournament
championship game, the sophomore sensation from New York firmly
etched his place in URI and A-10 basketball lore. He dribbled to
the left wing, and with Temple forward Keaton Sanders guarding
heavily, he drilled a 24-foot trey at the buzzer to give the Rams a
thrilling 62-59 tourney victory over Temple and the league's
automatic bid to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, the A-10 rookie of the year, finished with 21 points and
10 rebounds for URI (20-12), which won its first title game in
three finals appearances. He also became the league's first rookie
to win tournament outstanding player honor since freshman Alex
Bradley of Villanova in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Odom initially signed a national letter of intent to attend
Nevada-Las Vegas out of high school but a Sports Illustrated
article questioning the validity of his admissions test scores
prompted the school to release him from the letter.
</P>
<P>
   He reacquainted himself with URI coach Jim Harrick, who had
recruited Odom when he was mentor at UCLA. And after a lengthy
process to obtain eligibility, Odom began his much-anticipated
career this season.
</P>
<P>
   His winning shot Saturday sent the URI faithful among a crowd of
10,167 into bedlam, and left a partisan-Temple crowd of 10,167
stunned.
</P>
<P>
   It also prompted Odom to weep openly moments after the feat and
in the postgame press conference 15 minutes later. ``I dreamed
about it all my life, but I can't even explain how I feels,'' said
Odom. ``I didn't know it was in until it went in. I guess it was a
lucky shot. I tried to jump over him and shoot him and I got a good
look, I just let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how he felt at the moment considering all he had been
through, Odom began, ``It's like heaven,'' then he broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord works in mysterious ways,'' interjected Harrick,
while patting Odom on the back. ``He's made this young guy go
through a lot of adversity and the rewards are tremendous,
certainly at the end of the rainbow.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick added that the shot conjured up memories of Odom's first
collegiate game, when he slipped past Texas Christian's Vladimir
Jacksic on a crossover dribble, drove into the paint, and scored on
a finger roll with 5.7 seconds left to lead the Rams to a
season-opening 87-85 win over TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got in the huddle, I said, `Hey, he hit the first shot
against Texas Christian on a layup. We're going to go from the
first game to the last game on the same play.' (URI guard Preston)
Murphy spotted up and so did (URI guard Tip) Vinson. But I saw in
his eyes that he was going to take the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple coach John Chaney said the Owls defended Odom to the
sideline to give him a bad angle to shoot. ``And he finished it,
like he's supposed to finish,'' said Chaney, whose team (21-10) is
a virtual lock for the NCAA Tournament. ``He's a pure shooter and
there's nobody in the country better than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments before Odom's heroics, Temple had a chance to take the
lead, but guard Pepe Sanchez (8 points), who all but ceased
shooting after a horrid game from the floor (3 of 16, including 1
of 11 from 3-point range) misfired again, and Odom got the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that when you're open and you stop
shooting, you put pressure on your other teammates,'' said Chaney,
whose players struggled from the perimeter throughout the game and
blew a chance to pull away after leading, 36-27, with 19:04 left in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Lamont Barnes led Temple with 19 points and nine rebounds but
took only four shots in the second half. Sharp-shooting forward
Mark Karcher added 16, including a trey with 1:26 left to put
Temple ahead, 59-57, but even he struggled, going 2 for 9 from the
floor in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   URI forward Antonio Reynolds-Dean (7 points) scored with 48
seconds left to tie the game at 59.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful basketball game between two wonderful
clubs,'' said Harrick. ``It was bad someone had to lose, but we
needed it more than Temple.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
