<HEADLINE>
UCONN CAPTURES BIG EAST CROWN 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST FINAL-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now it's on to Phase 3.
</P>
<P>
   After completing the first phase of its season by winning the
conference regular-season championship for an unprecedented fifth
time in the last six years, the top-seeded University of
Connecticut men's basketball team achieved its objective of Phase 2
by winning the Big East tournament championship _ with astonishing
ease _ in Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's 82-63 romp over No. 3 seed St. John's
before a sellout crowd of 19,548 at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   For the seventh time in the league's 20-year history, the
tournament championship was decided by a pair of finalists ranked
in the Top 10. But the No. 3 Huskies (28-2) demonstrated their
championship mettle with a sustained and savage beating of
10th-ranked St. John's (25-8) to enter the third phase of their
season, the NCAA Tournament, as a likely No. 1 seed in the South
Region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of energy we brought out in the first half and at the
start of the second half is the kind of energy we're going to need
next week,'' said UConn coach Jim Calhoun, whose team won its
fourth tourney title in the last five years to become the second
team behind Georgetown (6) to win back-to-back titles.
</P>
<P>
   Junior swingman Richard Hamilton, who shared conference player
of the year honors with Miami's Tim James, led the Huskies with 23
points on 8-for-11 shooting and grabbed 7 rebounds while sophomore
guard Khalid El-Amin scored 15 and Rashamel Jones had 11 points off
the bench, all in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can now say that in 32 of 33 games we played, we had a
chance to win,'' said St. John's coach Mike Jarvis, who was
accompanied by the team chaplain to his postgame press conference.
``Tonight was the first one, I guess in a way you can say, that we
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, having conserved much of their energy after
breezing to a 71-50 romp over Syracuse in the semifinals, came out
of the box looking very much like a band of whippets in streaking
to a 13-0 lead. Hamilton set the frenetic pace by scoring UConn's
first 7 points in a row _ on a layup, a 3-pointer and a baseline
jumper _ after the first 1:29 had elapsed.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin followed with a top-of-the-key trey and then found Kevin
Freeman with a pretty alley-oop feed that turned into a
crowd-igniting dunk for an 11-0 lead, prompting St. John's coach
Mike Jarvis to signal for a 20-second time out. It was of little
use, however, as UConn extended it to 13-0 when Hamilton let fly of
a stop-and-pop jumper at the 16:50 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Erick Barkley, who led St. John's with 18 points before fouling
out with 33.7 seconds left, got the Red Storm on the board when he
hit a pair of free throws with 16:20 to go. The Huskies threatened
to bury St. John's in the first half when they led by 17 four
times, but the Storm refused to cave and finally made their stand
in the final 5:02 by going on a 10-0 run to rally from a 34-17
deficit to within 7, 34-27, on a 3-pointer by Marvis ``Bootsy''
Thornton (17 points) with 55 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Just when it appeared St. John's had finally gained some
momentum by drawing within 37-29 on Artest's low-post move with
eight seconds to go before intermission, UConn quickly wrested it
away. With five seconds left, Ricky Moore took an inbounds pass and
relayed a midcourt bounce pass to El-Amin. With the clock ticking
toward zero, El-Amin took the ball, spun away from a double-team
trap, and let heave of a 40-footer that found its mark at the
buzzer, giving the Huskies a 40-29 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good play,'' El-Amin said. ``Just the way coach drew
it up on the sideline, and we just executed it the way he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The second half began much like the first after the Huskies
scored 11 unanswered points to build a 51-29 lead with 15:50 to go.
Freeman, who was snubbed by the league's coaches when the
all-conference teams were released last Monday but was voted the
tourney's most outstanding player, expanded it to 25 points, 61-36,
when he stepped to the line to the chants of ``MVP! MVP! MVP!'' and
sank a free throw with 10:11 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not making one of the teams really hurt me,'' Freeman said.
``But this is probably the best thing that could've happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Artest sparked and capped a 12-6 run with a driving layup and a
3-point strike that cut UConn's lead to 66-50. Thornton hit a free
throw with 3:17 to go that drew St. John's within 15, 68-53, but
that was as close as the Storm got to putting a damper on UConn's
banner night and season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
