</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN SENDS A MESSAGE? 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The message the University of Connecticut seemed to
be sending Saturday &UR;  &LR; night was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to trash us?'' the Huskies seemed to be saying.
``Talk about how we had `run out of gas'? Suggest that this will be
another season ending in the frustration of not making the Final
Four? Concede the national championship to Duke?''
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, fire away. But be careful. Underestimating this team
might be a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly no one in the sellout crowd of 19,548 who came to
Madison Square Garden to watch the Huskies and St. John's joust for
the Big East tournament title should have any doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Not after the way the No. 3-ranked Huskies took apart the
Johnnies, 82-63, in what was more a scrimmage than a contest. The
Huskies took a 13-0 lead and never stopped running, playing
defense, or hustling.
</P>
<P>
   It was fine preparation for the NCAA Tournament, which will
begin this week with the Huskies as a No. 1 seed in some region
other than the East, which will belong to Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, that's the way UConn coach Jim Calhoun wanted
it. Winning this tournament in the 20th anniversary of the Big East
was a nice fringe benefit, but it wasn't essential. Calhoun didn't
treat it that way, as he mixed and matched lineups, defenses, and
offensive styles, getting a look at such seldom-used players as
Souleymane Wane.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, once the game started, Calhoun had his ``A'' game face on,
chewing on the officials and his players the way he always does.
Calhoun is of the old school that says if you are going to keep
school, you might as well try and win.
</P>
<P>
   But the tension that will be present when the one-and-done
tourney begins was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have to win this tournament,'' said Calhoun. ``We
proved ourselves during the 18 games (of the Big East regular
season). But we're getting back to where I want us to be.''
</P>
<P>
   The place that Calhoun and his team want to be at the end of the
month is in St. Petersburg at the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   As every Husky fan from Norwalk to Storrs will be happy to tell
you, that is a place that no UConn team has been.
</P>
<P>
   With that comes inherant pressure, since the Huskies have
accomplished all they can at their current level.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get there (Final Four),'' said Calhoun, with a smile,
``I won't be a better coach. If we don't, I won't be a worse coach,
you can be sure of that.''
</P>
<P>
   The players say that if there is pressure, it is a kind they
like. ``A fun kind of pressure,'' said forward Richard Hamilton,
who scored a game-high 23 points and is getting healthier each game
after a month-long recovery from a thigh contusion. ``Our goals at
the start of the season were to win the Big East regular season, to
win the Big East tournament, and to win the NCAAs. But we want to
win for ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have done that in reaching their first two goals.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun began preparing the Huskies for their third goal after
they won a rematch with Syracuse in the Carrier Dome on Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   His game plans started to include a more liberal use of his
bench and experimentation with different defenses, different
lineups. He also tried to get his team healthier _ Hamilton and
center Jake Voskuhl (foot) had been the primary patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did get healthier,'' he said. ``That was the biggest key.''
</P>
<P>
   Being healthier has made the Huskies happier.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone understands that this week will bring new pressures.
The 28 games the Huskies have won will mean nothing. They will be
0-0, along with 63 other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun says it doesn't matter to which regional his team is
sent as much as who is waiting for the Huskies when they get there.
``I'm a bracket guy, much more than a geography guy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, the final line of the Big East championship
bracket had the Huskies on top.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time for satisfaction but not celebration. The Huskies
didn't cut down the nets. They didn't go wild in their postgame
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the thousands of fans who at times had made the Garden
sound like Gampel Pavillion sent the true message on which all
Husky fans are now focusing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Duke,'' they started chanting with 3:06 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   If UConn can continue to play the way they did Saturday &UR;  &LR; night,
they might indeed get an opportunity to dance with the Devils.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
