<SLUG> BC-RAC-BIGCAP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE HOUSE DAZZLES IN BIG 'CAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- Chris McCarron is a little new to this Silver
Charm-Free House rivalry, but it didn't take the jockey long to
know the score after winning Saturday's Grade I $1 million Santa
Anita Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 5-3 now,'' McCarron said in the jockeys' room after
guiding Free House to a half-length victory over Event of the Year
in a much-anticipated race that lived up to its hype.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, the even-money favorite, had a rough trip from the
No.1 post position and finished third. Silver Charm and jockey Gary
Stevens encountered traffic problems around the clubhouse turn and
near the five-eighths pole before unleashing a closing surge in the
final eighth of a mile that fell one length short.
</P>
<P>
   It was Free House's second victory in a $1 million race in the
past seven months -- he also won the Pacific Classic at Del Mar in
August -- and it ended a four-race losing streak to Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to beat Silver Charm again,'' co-owner John Toffan
said. ``I was beginning to think it wouldn't happen, although I
still feel we should have won the (1997) Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Free House's last victory against Silver Charm before Saturday
came in the 1997 Santa Anita Derby. Silver Charm got the best of
the 5-year-old California-bred in all three Triple Crown races that
year, and he continued his dominance with a 2 1/2-length victory in
the Goodwood Breeders' Cup Handicap at Oak Tree in October.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm still holds the overall edge, but Free House is
beginning to stamp himself as a horse you don't want to let have
the lead. The son of Smokester went gate to wire in winning the San
Antonio Handicap last month, and he duplicated the feat Saturday to
give trainer Paco Gonzalez his first Big 'Cap victory and McCarron
his second.
</P>
<P>
   Once McCarron overcame a rough start, it was clear sailing. Free
House hopped in the air a bit at the beginning, but he was in front
by a head the first time past the grandstand and kept the lead
while posting fractions of :23.56, :47.40 and 1:11.46 en route to a
final clocking of 2:00.67 for the 1 1/4 miles on the main track.
</P>
<P>
   Longshot Dr Fong pressed Free House early, and Event of the Year
and Silver Charm took turns with late bids. But Free House, the 4-1
third choice, found another gear to record his ninth victory in 21
starts.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron said he knew Free House was going to be tough to catch
when he chirped to him on the far turn and could feel he had a lot
of horse left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked down at the fuel gauge and saw the needle still on
full and I thought, `Man, this is awesome,''' McCarron said. ``I
went ahead and tapped him on the shoulder and he just jumped
forward, sort of like Alysheba did when he won the (1988) Santa
Anita Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that same feeling of acceleration. It's fun when you get
that feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Nakatani, who rode Event of the Year: ``Free House just ran
a great race. There's not many horses who could have beaten my
horse today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Free House was the best horse on the track today because he
took the track early, and he didn't relinquish it,'' McCarron said.
``They took shots at him all the way around there ... Dr Fong,
Event of the Year from the three-eighths pole, and Silver Charm
very late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all had a chance to run by him, but the best horse won
the race today.''
</P>
<P>
   Free House returned $10.20, $5.20 and $2.80 and spoiled Richard
Mandella's bid to become the first trainer to saddle three
consecutive Big 'Cap winners. Mandella saddled Event of the Year
and 5-2 second choice Puerto Madero, who finished a disappointing
fifth in the six-horse field.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Madero was coming off a huge score in the Donn Handicap
on Jan.31, but the Chilean-bred never resembled the horse that
romped by 2 3/4 lengths in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what happened to him,'' Mandella said. ``It
didn't look like he had his mind on his job early. He just looked
like the first eighth of a mile he didn't have his heart in it.''
</P>
<P>
   For McCarron, it was his 17th mount in the Santa Anita Handicap
and continued a run of good luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventeen is my lucky number,'' he said. ``I got married on
the 17th, (wife) Judy was born on the 17th and I beat Sandy
Hawley's record of 515 winners on Dec.17, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of good things have happened to me on the 17th.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron has won four times in six attempts as the rider of Free
House, who tied Puerto Madero atop the NTRA's ``Champions on Fox''
series standings with his latest victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
