<SLUG> BC-RAC-BIGCAP-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIMLICO SPECIAL NEXT?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA -- John Toffan, co-owner of Free House with Trudy
McCaffery, said Saturday's winner of the $1 million Santa Anita
Handicap may run next in the Pimlico Special in May.
</P>
<P>
   The horse's connections are pointing the horse toward the next
stop on the NTRA's ``Champions on Fox'' series -- the Hollywood
Gold Cup in June -- and Toffan said they would like to give Free
House a race between now and then.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spacing (between races) is there, and he likes the
track,'' Toffan said of the Pimlico Special.
</P>
<P>
   Free House ran second to Silver Charm, losing by a head, in the
1997 Preakness Stakes at Pimlico.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Smith, ridden by Garrett Gomez, lost the lead to 3-2
favorite Hawksley Hill in midstretch but rallied back along the
rail to win Saturday's Grade II Arcadia Handicap by a head.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Smith, trained by Bruce Jackson, ran the mile on the turf
in 1:34.53 and returned $16, $6 and $3.
</P>
<P>
   Hawksley Hill, who ran a similar race in the Breeders' Cup Mile
in November when Da Hoss re-rallied to win by a head, won last
year's Arcadia Handicap with Pat Day aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Jose Valdivia, Jr. guided 5-2 second choice Big Jag to a
half-length victory in the seven-furlong Grade II San Carlos
Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Big Jag overcame a stewards' inquiry and paid $7.80, $3 and
$2.20 while beating even-money favorite Kona Gold. The final time
was 1:21.18.
</P>
<P>
   Kona Gold also ran in last November's Breeders' Cup, finishing
third at 16-1 in the Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita offered a $1 million guaranteed Pick Six pool
Saturday, and there were 29 winning tickets.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect ticket, which was made difficult by 12-1 longshot Jack
The Bull's victory in the eighth race, paid $28,065.80.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
