<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GORE-SUPPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY AND GORE COMPETE FOR DONORS IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the contest for votes in next year's New Jersey
presidential primary, even Vice President Al Gore's supporters
agree that former Sen. Bill Bradley is likely to win his home state
going away.
</P>
<P>
   But in a battle of nearly equal importance _ for New Jersey
money _ Gore's team is not yielding an inch, and politicians from
both camps say the vice president will probably reap as much
campaign cash from the state as the favorite son, and perhaps more.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Jersey has always been very rich in terms of giving to
politicians on the national level,'' said state Sen. Richard J.
Codey, the minority leader who is helping run Bradley's New Jersey
campaign. ``I'm sure they'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is of more than academic interest. To many
politicians, the presidential campaign season starts not in Iowa or
New Hampshire next year, but with the filing of the first campaign
finance reports with the Federal Election Commission next month.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, having run in three presidential campaigns since 1988 and
served as vice president for six years, has assembled a loyal
network of supporters capable of raising large amounts of money in
just about every state.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who represented New Jersey in the Senate for 18 years,
has many wealthy supporters in New York, Illinois and California,
but nothing to rival Gore's fund-raising apparatus. To a large
extent, Bradley is counting on New Jersey to be his base of
financial support. So how well he does in the Garden State's money
sweepstakes will be used as a barometer of his strength nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In another way, New Jersey money may prove more important than
New Jersey primary votes. The state's primary is scheduled for June
2000, potentially too late to help Bradley offset Gore's strength
elsewhere. Although Bradley's supporters are pushing to move the
primary to March, the effort has stalled in the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   In the first test of his local money-raising prowess, Bradley
garnered $1.5 million at an event in East Brunswick on Thursday.
Bradley aides contend the take was particularly impressive because
Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., held a major event in Newark
featuring President Clinton just the night before, raising more
than $2 million for the senator's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore supporters are questioning how much of Bradley's $1.5
million came from New Jersey. ``We know a lot of that money came
from throughout the country,'' said Alfred C. DeCotiis, a Teaneck
lawyer who is one of Gore's major fund-raisers in the state.
``Bradley has to go nationwide to raise $1.5 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Hauser, a spokesman for the Bradley campaign, said the
``vast bulk'' of the money came from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is so strong in New Jersey, and other states, because
essentially the same people who raised money so successfully for
Bill Clinton in 1992 and 1996 are working for him. In New Jersey,
that team consists principally of David Steiner, a real estate
developer; Orin S. Kramer, an investment banker; state Sen. Raymond
J. Lesniak of Elizabeth; DeCotiis, and Charles Kushner, a major
fund-raiser for Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   The group raised more than $9 million for Clinton in the last
two elections, its members said, and hopes to bring in $6 million
for Gore in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the New Jersey fund-raisers are supporting Gore,''
Lesniak said. ``On the political side, most people are holding back
because they know that politically it is not wise to go against
your own senator. And there is no need to.''
</P>
<P>
   After running three successful statewide campaigns, Bradley has
his own extensive list of affluent bankers, lawyers and businessmen
to draw upon, but much of it overlaps Gore's. And for the time
being, many Democrats are giving to both men, or neither.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does present a dilemma for New Jersey Democrats,'' said
Thomas P. Giblin, the state Democratic chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Spicuzzo, chairman of the Middlesex County Democratic
Committee, expressed the conflict many New Jersey Democrats feel,
saying that although he supported Bradley, he still planned to
attend Gore's first New Jersey fund-raiser in May. He will go, he
said, ``out of respect to the person and the office.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley acknowledges that he will be unable to match Gore's
fund-raising prowess. He has said he wants to raise $20 million to
$25 million from around the country for the primaries, about half
the $40 million to $55 million Gore's advisers say they plan to
raise.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley, who has long contended that the high cost of
campaigning has distorted the political process, says his campaign
will be more efficient than Gore's, relying more heavily on
volunteers and person-to-person contact than on expensive
television commercials. He also says he expects to attract
contributions from people who have not given to politicians in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are going to run the kind of campaign that reaches
out to the broadest kind of constituency, and encourages people who
have not been involved in the political process to get involved as
volunteers and contributors,'' he said Friday at a news conference
in West Orange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's particularly important to me to have New Jersey
supporters who came forward with their $1,000 contributions,'' he
continued. ``We think that we will be able to surprise a lot of
people. But, no, I don't think we'll get to $55 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Gore's advisers say they think Bradley will reach his
goal of $20 million to $25 million in contributions, and that that
will be enough to make him a credible candidate. But they also
asserted that Gore would be able to raise money almost at will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard not to raise money when you are the incumbent
going around the horn for the fourth time,'' DeCotiis said. ``With
only one competitor, a man not currently in office, it's hard to
believe Vice President Gore won't be able to raise what he wants to
raise.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's supporters agree, but say Gore's organizational
strength will not necessarily make him a winner. ``My fear, and I
think many Gore supporters might say this privately, is that he
could be another Walter Mondale,'' Codey said, referring to the
former vice president and Democratic presidential candidate who was
trounced by Ronald Reagan in 1984. ``He had a lot of the
establishment, but not the public.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
